<HEADLINE>Witches, whores and other women</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIA LANGDON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635009</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECT BEFORE HER: A History of Women in Western Europe. Volume One, 1500
- 1800
Olwen Hufton
HarperCollins, #25
IN Northanger Abbey which Jane Austen had just begun at the close of the
eighteenth century, and of the period covered by this book, Catherine Morland
remarks to Mr Tilney that she reads history a little as a duty but it tells her
nothing that does not either vex or weary her. She explains: ``The quarrels of
popes and kings, with wars and pestilences in every page; the men all so good
for nothing, and hardly any women at all, it is very tiresome; and yet I often
think it odd that it should be so dull, for a great deal of it must be
invention.''
It is a wonderfully apt and well-chosen quotation with which Olwen Hufton opens
her remarkable book telling a different sort of history. It is a bold choice,
too, for it sets the author the considerable target of ensuring the story she
has to tell is neither vexing, nor wearying, nor tiresome, nor dull and yet at
the same time fulfils the obligations of a serious historian dealing with a
huge subject over an immensely lengthy span of years during which there was
inevitably much change. Even for an immensely experienced prize-winning
historian, who was able, as she explains, to draw upon the intellectual baggage
of her lifetime's work in comparative European social history, the project was
of daunting proportions.
She has succeeded magnificently. This is no dull history book. There is nothing
dry or dusty about the narrative, despite the fact that it is a work of
scholarship intended as much for the historian in the library as for the
``lay'' reader, the working woman on the bus. It is interesting and
informative, filled with delicious nuggets of social history and it is
readable. The last 150 pages are notes and bibliography which I left to the
history students, but despite the somewhat fearsome size of the book - it is
such that you could probably kill a man with a well-aimed throw - it is an easy
read.
While the cautious man should rightly steer clear of any aggrieved women of his
acquaintance who are engaged in reading this book - at least until it is in
paperback - he should not fear opening it himself. It is a considerable work of
obvious feminist importance, but another of the author's significant
achievements is that it does not read like a work of vengeance on behalf of the
neglected women of history; it is not in any sense a one-sided dogmatic tract.
It is the story of women and men during this period, explaining their lives as
one affected the other in different countries and social conditions.
It is an economic and social analysis of the role of women in the
pre-industrial societies of western Europe. She concentrates mostly on France
and Britain, but there is much incidental intelligence from elsewhere woven
into the historical tapestry. It is set in the context of the questions about
women that are relevant to the history of the period. To paraphrase the author:
What did women do? How did change affect their lives and those of their
families? What were the consequences of the Reformation and its attendant
guilts on everyone's sex lives? What do we really know about motherhood? Who
acquired literacy and what did they do with it? Who rebelled and why? Who lived
and who died?
The first several chapters take the lives of girls and women through the
various stages of womanhood, and this is followed by an examination of the
unusual: witches and whores and writers and women in the French Revolution. It
is all put in the perspective of the traditional society and the extent of
change in the period. The bad news is, or was, that while some were beginning
to question the continuing dependence of women at every level, there was really
no agenda for improving their lot even by the end of her 300 years.
She pictures young girls seeking employment in order to establish the dowry and
thus the husband; their marriage; their motherhood and their widowhood. None of
it makes for very cheery reading - apart from the constant personal reminder of
the extent to which one might be very grateful to be living now and not then.
Their lives, at whatever social strata, appear to constitute a catalogue of
misery ranging from, at worst, a struggle to survive at all to a position
which, at best, seems always to have been lacking in dignity. It is,
apparently, a tenet of much feminist analysis since the 1960s that the progress
of women's lives has throughout history represented a ``descent from paradise''
to the horrors of the twentieth century. Olwen Hufton would seem to have her
doubts about this which, on the basis of her own work, I would wholly share.
That doesn't mean, though, that I wasn't riveted by much of the social detail
she records: about the dangers and difficulties of survival, for example. In
the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, 25 women in every thousand in Britain
and 40 per thousand in Paris died in childbirth (compared to 0.12 per thousand
today). The babies were carried off at an even greater rate, and if they made
it to weaning they were lucky if they didn't then fall victim to summer
diarrhoea caused by the filthy conditions in which everyone lived. It was only
if they got to the age of five that they were reckoned to have a good chance on
living to a middle-age, motherhood notwithstanding.
They all had lice and worms and never washed and they thought that cradle cap
was meant to protect the cranium and it wasn't picked off (after a gentle
rubbing with butter) until the infant was several years old. It is all
absolutely disgusting and utterly compelling to read about.
It is the best sort of history book because it is filled with the trivial
detail which illuminates. The author tells the tale of a classic case of a
witch trial in Scotland in the late seventeeth century brought against one
Janet MacMurdoch, a sub-tenant of the laird of Broughtone, who spent years
causing people's husbands and cattle and children to suffer and die for
crossing her.
``Poverty,'' writes Olwen Hufton, ``perhaps also bred its own kind of defiance
- known in Scotland as `smeddum', the propensity to answer back, the refusal of
deference.'' She did not defend herself when she was brought to trial as an old
woman. She was aggressive and defiant - and convicted (although we can only
assume her fate). Even smeddum didn't get you far 400 years ago.
</TEXT>
