<HEADLINE>Fear of the silent spring</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Peter Evans</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the midst of the dark days of winter, when storms blow and rain lashes the
windows, it's something to look forward to - that verdant renewal of life that
is the spring. Lighter days, the first leaves on the trees, and the birdsong;
above all, the birdsong.
There are few who would disagree that without it life would be intolerable. So
what of the unthinkable prospect of a silent spring? Ridiculous, you might say;
but you'd be wrong. Far-fetched as it may seem, ornithologists believe changes
in farming practices in the last few decades make the silent spring a real
possibility.
Studies have shown a dramatic drop in the populations of some of Britain's
best-loved birds, and unless measures are taken to improve the situation, they
will decline even further.
Take Shelley's blithe spirit, the skylark, for example. ``The situation is
becoming desperate with some three million fewer breeding skylarks singing in
the British countryside,'' says Dr Jeremy Greenwood, director of the British
Trust for Ornithology.
Following the production of a report highlighting the problem, the trust has
launched an appeal to help pay for research into the specific reasons for the
decline in farmland bird populations, and to find ways of boosting numbers.
The trust is not the only body to have shown concern. The Royal Society for the
Protection of Birds reports skylark numbers have diminished by more than 50% on
farmland over the past 20 years. In Scotland, as well as other parts of the UK,
it is joined by the tree sparrow, grey partridge, lapwing, and reed bunting,
among others.
``We view the situation regarding farmland birds as very alarming, and across
the society's work, the plight of farmland birds is one of our biggest
priorities,'' says Steve Sankey, head of policy and advice at the RSPB's
Edinburgh headquarters. ``It's easy to recognise the problems, it's much less
easy to resolve them.''
Changes in farming methods brought about by the Common Agricultural Policy are
to blame. In order to thrive, birds need a food source and they need a breeding
habitat. The CAP has encouraged farm units to merge and become bigger, and
rewarded farmers for intensifying production and bringing non-productive land
into use.
In the process, farmland birds have lost what they need to survive. Pests have
no place on high-yield farms, so pesticides have been employed to prevent them
attacking crops. Consequently, insects and invertebrates - vital sources of
food for insect eaters such as the skylark - have been drastically reduced.
Farmland weeds, whose seeds are another food source for birds, have been
suppressed with herbicides. Their food in short supply, birds have had to cope
with fewer hedgerows and rough ground cover for breeding, reducing their
chances of survival still further.
Berwickshire, the Lothians, and parts of Aberdeenshire are the worst affected
areas in Scotland, but even in the less intensively farmed areas, says Sankey,
there is still an increased use of chemicals and mechanisation.
Another group of birds threatened is farmland waders, affected by the increased
drainage of wet areas to bring them into production. The lapwing, already
mentioned, together with oystercatchers, snipe, curlew, and redshank come into
this category.
``None of us in the RSPB blames the farmers,'' stresses Sankey, ``because we
recognise that it's hard making a living, particularly in the remoter areas of
the country. It's the system that's at fault, and it's the system we need to
change.''
This may sound like a Marxist analysis of the political economy, but it has
been shown that careful management and a sympathetic approach to production
which takes into account environmental requirements, can make a difference.
Biodiversity is the current conversational buzzword for it, and in the case of
one bird in particular, it has proved crucial to its survival on a worldwide
scale.
The secretive corncrake, with its grating, vocal call, is a rare and threatened
species which requires very specific conditions for breeding. Once widespread
and common, it has undergone a dramatic and continuing decline. Now nearly all
the remaining corncrakes in Britain are confined to the Outer Hebrides and the
Argyll islands.
Drastic action was needed to deal with the problem and three years ago the
RSPB, in conjunction with Scottish Natural Heritage and the Scottish Crofters'
Union, initiated a scheme to save the bird.
``We paid crofters to delay the cutting of their hay until the beginning of
August and we paid them a little more money to cut their corn in a particular
way,'' explains Sankey. Corncrakes like the cover of long grass and crops, and
other tall plants, where their eggs are laid. By August, adults and young
migrate to Africa for the winter, and the initiative was designed to safeguard
breeding and rearing. Numbers have shown a modest increase in the past two
years.
``What's good for corncrakes is also good for many other species,'' says
Sankey. ``We know exactly what corncrakes need because of all the research we
have done, but we have so far failed to get the Scottish Office to include that
in an agri-environment programme.''
Over the past three years #10.5m in the Scottish Office budget earmarked for
environmentally sensitive areas, which could have been paid to farmers and
crofters to help wildlife, has returned to Treasury coffers, claims the RSPB.
The Government is in the process of publishing a biodiversity plan and rural
White Paper, both of which Sankey hopes will help farmland birds.
If the lilting, liquid sound of Shelley's skylark is to be part of British
countryside, and the silent spring is not to become a reality, the warning
signs must be heeded; the message not dismissed as exaggerated, and the people
bringing it not labelled as alarmist cranks.
</TEXT>
