<HEADLINE>Army finds it ill belongs to Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635011</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Michael Fry, in his latest missive, recounts a frosty festive reception for the
Prince and his followers.
GLASGOW, December 30 - After nearly a week in this Presbyterian stronghold,
Prince Charles Edward Stuart is preparing with relief to march on to the north.
He has had a frosty reception from Glaswegians, and a response in kind from the
Jacobites has made the festive season miserable for both sides.
The only revelry took place before the prince's arrival, a fortnight ago, when
false reports that the Duke of Cumberland had defeated him near Lancaster
brought the people on to the streets to celebrate. As soon as the Jacobites'
advance guard entered the undefended city late on Christmas Day, Glasgow left
no doubt that they were unwelcome.
Reports had arrived of outrages as they advanced down the River Clyde. They
pillaged and burned Lesmahagow, in revenge for the villagers' action two months
ago, when they happened to capture a Highland chieftain, Donald Macdonald of
Kinlochmoidart, and turned him in to the royal authorities. In Hamilton,
officers were accused of losing control as their men got drunk, looted, and
threatened civilians.
Scouts were sent on to Glasgow while Charles enjoyed a short break at Hamilton
Palace, seat of the absent Duke of Hamilton. The prince went hunting in the
park, and shot a brace each of pheasant, woodcock, and hare, as well as a young
buck. For Christmas, he dined in public at Chatelherault off a turkey which
cost three shillings.
The next day, a big crowd of Glaswegians turned out to watch his arrival, but
nobody cheered and the men all kept their hats jammed on their heads. The only
commotion came as he rode up the Saltmarket when, according to unconfirmed
reports, someone aimed a pistol at him. After parading along the main streets,
the Jacobites marshalled at the Cross, where King James VIII was proclaimed
with Prince Charles as his Regent. Onlookers again remained silent.
Some clansmen have been billeted, without incident, on private homes. The rest
are encamped round the half-built St Andrew's church, beside the Molendinar
Burn in between London Road and Glasgow Green, where they are drilled daily.
During one review the prince was heard to remark that this was a fine town but
he found he had no friends here.
He is staying at Shawfield Mansion, on Trongate at the head of Stockwell
Street. The citizens are free to enter twice a day to watch him dine with his
staff, though few do so. He cannot quite believe they are so impervious to his
charm, and walks the streets in his elegant French suits. Still, when he held a
ball, the Glaswegian ladies refused to attend.
The reason may lie in the fact that Charles has hit their husbands where it
hurts, in the pocket. While occupying Edinburgh during the autumn, he sent an
armed detachment to collect taxes from Glasgow. The city gave him only #5000 of
the #15,000 asked for. Now, with his soldiers ragged and often barefoot after
the invasion of England, the prince has ordered the town council to hand over
6000 coats, waistcoats, blue bonnets, and pairs of shoes and stockings, with
12,000 linen shirts.
The Lord Provost, George Murdoch, has been fined #500 for the previous
unfriendly act of raising two battalions to fight the Jacobites. The total cost
to the city will be #10,000, and may exhaust the Common Good Fund. Similar
punishment, on a lesser scale, has been meted out to Paisley.
The open hostility so angered some chieftains that they urged Charles to sack
and burn the city. Luckily another of them, Donald Cameron of Lochiel, has
strong links with it. His brother, John Cameron of Fassifern, is a merchant and
burgess of Glasgow. His aunt, Mrs John Campbell, lives at Shawfield Mansion and
is Charles's unwilling hostess. Lochiel persuaded him to stick to his policy of
avoiding needless suffering to civilians.
The West of Scotland has been unable to mount any organised resistance. But
since the Jacobites left and crossed the Border two months ago, the general
situation in the country has changed in the British Government's favour. Its
troops have retaken Inverness. The Royal Navy is setting up a blockade in such
depth as to make it impossible for the prince to get the French supplies he
needs to tighten his grip on Scotland.
All this has yet to be taken into account in Jacobite strategy. Since the
retreat from Derby, the prince's first aim has been to make contact with the
fresh troops recruited while he is away in England. In the North-east, Lord
Lewis Gordon has raised two regiments which, in a skirmish at Inverurie, have
just repulsed units sent to attack them by Loudoun. They can now combine with
the French force under Lord John Drummond which landed a month ago at Montrose,
and with reinforcements of Frasers, Mackintoshes, and Mackenzies.
After a planned rendezvous with Charles at Perth, they could bring total
Jacobite strength up to 7000. He will then have several options. One would be
to attack Stirling Castle, still held for the Government, and secure the lines
of supply from the Highlands. Another would be to attempt the recapture of
Edinburgh. The prince himself has not abandoned the scheme of turning about to
invade England again.
However, the scheme suffered a setback today with the surrender to Cumberland
of the Jacobite garrison left behind in Carlisle. Mostly Englishmen recruited
in Lancashire, they had the job of keeping open the route to the south. As the
duke approached, they did their best to strengthen the town's crumbling
defences with earthworks and sandbags. But he brought up heavy cannon, and
after three days of bombardment further resistance was useless.
Cumberland would grant the soldiers no terms, only ``that they should not be
put to the sword, but reserved for the King's pleasure''. He added in a message
to London that ``they have no sort of claim to the King's mercy and I sincerely
hope they will meet with none''.
n Another dispatch next week
</TEXT>
