<HEADLINE>Don't worry, the  gang's all here</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE, DAVID BELCHER, ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ping!, The Happy Gang (Happy Gang)
As the Singing Kettle go more and more showbiz, blythely annexing the panto
tradition for the under-eights down at the SECC in Glasgow, the new pretenders
move smartly into early SK territory with their second cassette, featuring
versions of the likes of Aitken Drum and The Wee Kirkcudbright Centipede.
Modern keyboard instruments rather than the traditional instruments that
distinguished the Kettle's earliest (and best work), but still just the thing
for those long car journeys this time of the year necessitates.Enter the
Hardbag, various (A&amp;M)
Just what your Uncle Adam and his flatmate Steve would like to have found in
their stocking. This 2-CD set is the perfect gift for foxy chaps who like
nothing better of an evening than waxing their chests, piercing their nipples
and then bouncing around to some cheesecore Nu-NRG music: high-speed handbag
music for high-speed he-man hedonists.
Nowhere is the hardbag philosophy better summed up than on Fee Fi Fo Fum by the
Candy Girls, an urgent demand for sexual congress with a large man of
Afro-Caribbean lineage.
Other highlights? Son Of A Gun by JX; Mrs Wood's Joanna, and Fluke's Bullet.
Listen to Enter The Hardbag and know that God made you to go for it, Adam and
Steve!
Rockabilly Filly, Rosie Flores (Hightone)
Neat twang'n'torch inspired by the Blessed St Patsy of Cline as well as a
host of primal rockabilly legends, including Johnny Burnette, whose son, Rocky,
turns up as one of Ms Flores guests. Super covers - Lefty Frizzell's Stranger,
Cliff Gallup's Bop Street, Butch Hancock's Boxcars, Crazy Mixed Emotions by
Russell Scott - and some corking originals. Yup, yup, yes indeedy; accompany
Rosie to her Poor Girl's Town for some good rockin' tonight.
A Sense of Direction, various (BGP)
``The in sound from way out: 12 positive jazz gems from the left side of jazz
culture'' it says on the cover, telling you most of what you need to know about
this collection's tastefully-swinging cool-bop delights, recorded between 1961
and 1987.
Vibe up with Walt Dickerson, providing a helpful Sense Of Direction. Abbey
Lincoln offers sinuous scat philosophies on Long As You're Living. Stanley
Cowell's I'm Trying To Find A Way is a swaying slice of chamber-orchestral
salsa. Soul legends Mel and Tim offer the best advice of all: Keep The Faith.
Tony McManus, Tony McManus (Greentrax)
McManus is one of the most exciting talents to have emerged on the Scottish
folk scene for years. An acoustic guitarist with a harpist's breadth of vision,
a piper's grace note-dotted phrasing and a twinkling-eyed wit (check his
version of Louis Armstrong's Wonderful World), he renders his occasional
accompanists almost superfluous on this remarkable debut. His slow airs are
clear and poignant and his reels are a spiky tribute to the benefits of being
born with 18 fingers on each hand.
Tone Poems II, David Grisman &amp; Martin Taylor (Acoustic Disc)
Anyone predicting back in January that one of my favourite tracks of 1995
would be a version of Swanee played with the last dance at a snail's soiree in
mind, would have had their temperature taken.
But here we are: track one of an intimate and reverent yet reinvigorating
breeze through the well-worn (Anything Goes, Unforgettable et al) and a few
newer choons, all beautifully played on a variety of vintage guitars and
mandolin family members which the accompanying booklet illustrates in life
savings-threatening detail.
Valpariaso, Rita Connolly (Tara)
The second album from the woman who gave cool, clear voice to Shaun Davey's
brilliant folk-rock opera Granuaille and Relief of Derry Symphony follows a
similar formula to the first: majestic singing, sumptuous accompaniments.
Connolly sails dangerously close to tweeness at times but her ability to
convince on songs as diverse as Irving Berlin's vaudevillian Shakin' the Blues
Away and Mike Nesmith's enigmatic Rio plus her commanding way with a narrative
swing the balance in her favour.A New Way of Listening - Book Competition
Winners
THE six winners of copies of Alexander Waugh's new guide to listening to
music are: Mr IM Connell of Glasgow, EJ Fairley of Bishopbriggs, Bill Hamilton
of Prestwick, GM Clark of Glespin, Alexander Leggate of Glasgow, and S
Livingstone of Bonnybridge. Beethoven, in answer to the question, wrote nine
symphonies. Copies of the book, which includes a CD, are in the post.
</TEXT>
