<HEADLINE>Benny's on the way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOOD jazz news for the New Year came this week from the United States where
veteran alto saxophonist Benny Carter has announced he is ready to visit
Glasgow to front an all-star group.
Talks have begun to have Carter - who will be 89 this coming year - headline
the Glasgow Jazz Festival in July. It will be the tenth year of the Festival
and Carter featured heavily at the launch as composer in residence and
instrumentalist.
I still remember the altoist fronting a big band which included trumpeter Tommy
McQuater who had worked with the American fifty years before when Carter had
first come to Britain as staff arranger for Henry Hall's BBC Dance Orchestra.
This time round, Carter will be teamed with younger musicians, some of whom he
will hand pick. One has already been chosen, cornettist Warren Vache, who was
in Glasgow a few weeks back. Vache recently recorded an album of Carter songs
with the saxophonist which is set for release in February.
Vache says: ``It was a great experience. The idea was to get a whole gang of
singers to record some of Benny's numbers, some old favourites and some which
were unpublished until now.''
On this latest CD, entitled The Benny Carter Songbook, the singers involved
include Peggy Lee, Carmen Bradford, Ruth Brown, enjoying a New York revival
right now at Rainbow and Stars, Shirley Horn, Jon Hendricks, Bobby Shot and the
former count Basie vocal star Joe Williams.
Carter's career has been unlike that of any other major musician of his
generation. There have been few instances of the man being forced to scuffle
for a living though that might just have happened in his earlier days with the
Fletcher Henderson Orchestra.
He had an enormous influence on the British music scene during his stint with
the BBC, even though that was interrupted every few months because of work
permit restrictions. Still, at his creative peak, Carter was providing six new
arrangements a week for Henry Hall.
His playing too, was echoed by every Palais band altoist in the land. For long
enough these bad imitations which you could hear all around Scotland, and
England, made me chary of Carter's elegant, studied playing.
Eventually, however, I listened and I learned the breadth of the man's talents.
I doubt if, Louis Armstrong apart, any other black musician has been more
respected by his peers.
I can remember one time when the late Red Allen told me of Carter revisiting
his old Harlem haunts and how the musicians paid homage to him. Said Allen:``It
was like royalty visiting, all these guys who used to play with Benny in the
old days were there just wantin' to shake his hand. You see, Benny made it more
than any of us did.''
Allen was not only talking of Carter's superb musicianship, he was also talking
about the way the urbane and sophisticated saxophonist had broken down the
racial prejudices which long existed in the studios.
Carter wrote the sound track music for the film Stormy Weather in l943 and
followed up with other major Hollywood film successes and TV show themes. He
was the first black musician to break into that market and for many years he
hung up his horn to concentrate mainly on writing, though his Further
Definitions' reunion album with Coleman Hawkins was a notable return to the
recording scene.
Since he stopped writing movie scores he has returned to playing as often as he
can. Eighteen months ago I saw him at the Blue Note in New York in front of an
SRO audience and he played with an effortless lyricism. He is still doing it
and hopefully he will be demonstrating his mastery one more in Glasgow. It's a
nice thought to have around at Hogmanay!
</TEXT>
