<HEADLINE>An affair too far</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARL MacDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARRIAGE
Gloria Nagy
Little Brown, #16.99
MICKEY and Annie Wilder met, both aged six, when her family moved into the
converted brownstone on MacDougal Street, Greenwich Village, where his family
lived. They shared childhood and adolescence and married when Annie's mother
died. A year later their first child was born, ``and Annie moved aside and let
Mickey pass through. Mickey had the aura of success about him. He had
presence''.
Annie's move allowed Mickey to become a moderately successful actor, while she
did a little journalism.
Other couples found them special because of their endurance. ``Through the
seventies and eighties, when relationships were crashing like cheap pottery at
a Greek wedding - human beings smashing and breaking apart; infecting one
another with terrifying diseases; betraying, lying, incesting, child abusing,
deserting one another as if an epidemic of antihumanity had consumed the planet
- they endured. They were the envy of everyone.''
The Wilders transplanted to California when Mickey was chosen to star in a hit
television series. Especially in the spiritual home of active consumerism, such
a couple make dull fiction, so in their 45th year each has an affair and their
marriage looks like coming apart. The rifts remain, revealing sacrifices and
resentments each had kept hidden for the sake of their life together. Will they
make up, separate, stay together for the sake of the kids or make sufficiently
meaningful sacrifices for the sake of their relationship, if not each other?
Gloria Nagy has an irritating style. She is sloppily informative, layering the
narrative with nuggets of dross, so that she appears to be dispensing
information, but in fact is either telling nothing or is relating the sort of
detail one could either guess or manage perfectly well without.
When she does tell us something, it is almost immediately discounted or
contradicted. ``Having always been together, they could not even imagine being
apart,'' she says early on. Yet most of the novel is spent actively discussing,
contemplating, analysing and at one point even embarking on this proposition.
Apart from the affairs, we do not know how or why this happens. Too much has to
be taken at face value and while these impressions are generally disguised by
the mellifluous pace, there are occasions when cracks appear in more than the
marriage. Gloria Nagy assumes we will take her word for it. She tells what is
going on, and makes empirical statements with little or no evidence to support
them.
Neither of the Wilders' respective lovers are ever more than ciphers. Mickey's
mistress could be taken for Annie's alter ego, but if this is so, what are we
to make of Oliver, an Englishman in the Hollywood mould, who spoils an illusion
of silent manliness by opening his mouth?
Mickey's affair is with an opinionated, athletic sculptress who earns his
daughter's antipathy by wearing cheap underwear. The attraction seems to be
that she is younger than Annie, who wastes no time small-talking Oliver,
flaring into passion with something more than a need for revenge.
All of which seems to suggest their long-term commitment was based on nothing
more than a lack of opportunity, though we are assured this is not so. Yet to
underline the message, and with typical Californian excess, their accountant
makes off with the loot. Annie gives chase, thinking: ``No-one would ever
believe this.''
There are moments when Gloria Nagy approaches the heart of the matter, when the
Wilders' dilemma is both complicated and convincing. There are times when she
seems to have her eye on the tensions and compromises of family life, and
provides a final twist which increases Annie's dilemma and adds to her feeling
of desperate resignation.
CARL MacDOUGALL
</TEXT>
