<TEXT>
TELEVISION: ALLAN LAING
PETER MULLEN. This actor and director, if there is any justice, is surely going
to follow in the footsteps of Peter Capaldi and win the Oscar for best short
film with his bleak and uncompromising Tartan Short, Fridge. Also likely to
make a full-length film this coming year.
PAULINE QUIRK. The comedy actress best known for Birds of a Feather will make a
sensational impact in the coming year when she appears as an ugly, obese,
murderess in the BBC
adaptation of Minette Walters' seering crime novel, The Sculptress.
JOHN HANNAH. The Scots actor of Four Weddings and a Funeral fame will be given
his first lead role on telly if and when the network gives Scottish Television
the go-ahead to turn MacCallum, a thriller about a London-based pathologist,
into a series in the New Year. He will also be seen in bad-guy mode in a new
feature-length thriller by BBC Scotland, Bait.
EWAN McGREGOR. Like Hannah one of the new breed of young Scots actors, he will
be acclaimed for his rivetting performance in Trainspotting, the controversial
follow-up from the Shallow Grave team.
CLIVE RUSSELL. He seems to have been in just about everything this year
(Cracker, Ruffian Hearts, Roughnecks, Atletico Partick . . ). He must be in
line for a major lead role in TV. One of the best actors in Scotland, he'll be
seen later in the year in The Flowers of the Forest, a disturbing one-off drama
from Michael Eaton about ritual child abuse allegations.
KATE MURPHY. She made an impression in Donna Franceschild's last award-winning
drama, Takin' Over The Asylum, and will make an even bigger impression in the
same writer's next series, A Mug's Game, to be shown on BBC2 early in the New
Year.
EDUCATION: BARCLAY McBAIN
FRANK PIGNATELLI. Strathclyde region's director of education will quit local
government in April rather than take up a much less prestigious post - with
#94,500 salary conserved and access to a substantial pension - to which he is
entitled with cash-strapped Glasgow City Council. Can you keep a good, and a
driven, man down? 1996 will tell.
DOUGLAS OSLER. The man who had to sell the initially highly-unpopular version
of national testing - and suffered much parental ire in the process - has got
his reward by being appointed HM senior chief inspector of schools. What kind
of fist will he make of Higher Still, the forthcoming reform of upper secondary
schooling?
RAYMOND ROBERTSON. The Scottish Office Minister for Education wants more
schools to opt out and more families to take advantage of the expanded assisted
places scheme for the private sector. 1996 will tell if a significant number of
schools move to self-governing status, or if the vision continues to be a
pipedream.
HELEN LIDDELL. How much of the Tories' education clothing will Scottish Labour
steal? We shall find out early in the New Year when the Monklands East MP
produces Labour's blueprint for Scottish education.
Prof JOHN MacBEATH. The value schools add to their pupils' experience is
recognised as the key pointer to their effectiveness. Professor MacBeath and
his team at Strathclyde University are chasing that Holy Grail. Their report on
effective schools is eagerly awaited.
BRIAN MacKINNON. Where will the manchild turn up next in Scottish education,
and in what guise? Not in one of our medical faculties and certainly not as one
of their students. Of course, in 1996 the Government will run pilots to test
nursery vouchers.
MEDICINE: ALAN MacDERMID
NEIL WILSON and ALAN HOUSTON are consultant cardiologists who have pioneered
the use of catheter intervention to treat heart defects at the Royal Hospital
for Sick Children in Glasgow. A new, state-of-the-art catheter lab is planned
at Yorkhill.
Dr CAROLINE BLACKWELL is an expert on the factors which increase some people's
susceptibility to disease, in particular the way in which viruses, genetic
factors, or cigarette smoke make the cells in our mouths ``stickier'' and more
hospitable to bacteria.
Dr MOIRA BROWN, a scientist at the MRC Institute of Virology in Partick,
Glasgow, has played a leading role in disarming the herpes simplex virus of the
protein through which it causes damage to the cells in the brain and other
parts of the nervous system.
Dr DONNIE BLACK, from Stornoway, has been involved in Scotland, England and
America with the hunt for the gene mutations responsible for familial breast
cancer, the first of which, BRCA1, was identified last year.
Prof DAVID LANE heads a top-flight team of scientists in the Cancer Research
Laboratories at Dundee University. His discovery of the tumour suppressor gene
p53 could point the way to a new generation of cancer drugs. With his
colleagues - including wife, Dr Birgitte Lane, and Professor David Glover - he
has helped to justify Dundee's City of Discovery title.
LITERATURE: HARRY REID
NICOLA BARKER. Regarded by many as the best young short story writer around,
the acerbic Barker used to work in the kitchen of a children's hospital and has
more of a grip on the realities of life than many of her more precious
contemporaries in literary London. Watch out for her second collection of
stories, Heading Inland, from Faber in the spring.
AJAY CLOSE. Close is, well, closer to home. The Scottish journalist must be
delighted at the advance publicity for her first novel, Officialand Doubtful.
Secker &amp; Warburg publish it in February.
CARL MacDOUGALL. Carl needs little introduction to Herald readers; he is our
chief fiction reviewer and a regular contributor to many parts of the
newspaper. The Casanova Papers, set in Paris and Glasgow - always a potent
combination - is his best yet. This powerful novel comes out in May, again from
Secker.
NIALL DUTHIE. Less well known than MacDougall is this older, expat writer. He
is returning from Spain early in 1996 to launch his second novel, Natterjack,
which is partly set in Edinburgh and for which his publishers, Faber, have high
hopes.
ALAN FURST. If there is one author who deserves to achieve widespread acclaim
in 1996, it is Furst. His new novel, The World at Night, is published by
HarperCollins in October. Meanwhile, the paperback of his last, The Polish
Officer, is out in January.
FRANK KUPPNER. Finally, we have Glasgow's own Mr Kuppner, whose unexpected
success in the McVitie's will raise his profile. The small but enterprising
Edinburgh house of Polygon bring out his latest novel, Life on a Dead Planet,
in February.
CINEMA: WILLIAM RUSSELL
SANDRA BULLOCK. In the last year her roles as the bus driver in Speed, the
computer expert in The Net and the girl in love with a stranger in While You
Were Sleeping confirmed her as a star in the making.
NICOLE KIDMAN. Until her homicidal weather girl in To Die For this talented
Australian actress was best known as Mrs Tom Cruise.
RICHARD LA GRAVENESE. Without a script there is no film, and La Gravense has
over the last year established himself as among the best there are at turning
novels into celluloid gold with The Bridges of Madison County, the enchanting
tale of a waif amid thieves. A Little Princess, and Diane Keaton's debut as a
director, Unstrung Heroes.
MARTIN CAMBELL. Although his TV career as a director is distinguished, a veil
is best drawn over his cinema past, but Goldeneye has shown he knows how to
make genuinely exciting action adventure films.
HUGH O'CONNOR. This Irish actor's beguiling performance as the mass poisoner,
Graham Young, in The Young Poisoner's Handbook was brilliantly concieved, and
with luck - because it all depends on the parts that turn up -he should go far.
GEORGINA CATES. Her Stella, the repertory theatre trainee whose innocence
causes havoc in the lives of all around in Mike Newell's An Awfully Big
Adventure was amazing. She stole the film from Alan Rickman and Hugh Grant.
SPORT: JAMES TRAYNOR
STEPHEN GLASS. Aberdeen's emerging young fullback. In the modern game he is
described as a wingback, a player who starts wide of the defence but spends as
much time as possible lending support to his midfield and attack.
DAVID COULTHARD. Perhaps the Formula 1 driver from Twinholm in the Borders
should have started his Grand Prix career in 1995 in a team which wasn't
expected to win the championship, but by moving to from Williams Renault to
McLaren Mercedes, who are developing a new car which they hope will take them
back to the No 1 position, Coulthard can concentrate on his own development.
COLIN McRAE. He ought to be worth following. Only recently he became the first
British rally driver to win the world championship and he is young and bold
enough to secure back-to-back titles.
PRINCE NASSEEM HAMED. We should really keep our eyes on this man who is the
most exciting fighter to appear in the boxing ring in decades.
ALAN MACKIN. This teenager from Paisley has been making sterling progress
through the ranks and is a member of the Lawn Tennis Association's Rover team.
THE TARTAN ARMY. I suggest we all watch the Man in Threadbare Kilt and
Old-fashioned Football top with Scotland's finest gearing up for a march south
of the Border in the summer for the European Championship finals.
CLASSICAL: MICHAEL TUMELTY
SALLY BEAMISH. Since moving to Scotland around five years ago, the composer has
gone from strength to strength. The new year sees her order books full.
JOSEPH SWENSEN. Taking up his new post as principal conductor of the Scottish
Chamber Orchestra in 1996, American Swensen is exciting news; so far,
everything he has touched has turned to musical dynamite.
TAN DUN. More musical dynamite for Scotland with the appointment of Chinese
composer Tan Dun to the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra.
HE WHO CANNOT BE NAMED. The BBC  SSO is on the verge of announcing the
appointment of a new principal conductor.
ANGELA WHELAN. Starry young trumpeter, still a student at the RSAMD, and
already making a name and reputation for herself. Definitely a classy musician
to watch out for. Appearing in February with the Scottish Bach Consort in a
tribute concert to Sir Alexander Gibson.
BRYAN ALLEN. Just in the door, Allen, leader of the Fine Arts Brass ensemble
and newly appointed head of brass at the RSAMD, has launched a big band at the
academy within his first term.
BUSINESS: ALF YOUNG
FRED GOODWIN. Less time under the bonnet restoring old cars when this intense
37-year-old accountant finally takes the executive reins at Clydesdale Bank
from departing Aussie, Frank Cicutto. One of the tough new breed of non-banking
bankers taking a traditional industry by the scruff of the neck and giving it a
good shake.
BRIAN STEWART. Courage is in the bag and chairman Sir Alick Rankin departs to
chair General Accident from early 1977, so the soft-spoken chief executive of
Scottish &amp; Newcastle, now the UK's biggest brewer, has his chance to step into
centre stage. The rave reviews should multiply.
ROBERT SMITH. The local profile has slipped a bit since the sharpest accountant
ever to emerge from Maryhill left the Royal Bank's investment banking offshoot
for Deutsche Morgan Grenfell. Still a grandmaster of buy-outs in Europe, he
becomes president of the Scottish chartered accountants institute in April.
TOM HUNTER. With the deal to purchase the Olympus sportswear chain from Sears
complete, the boy from New Cumnock who started selling shoes from his father's
lock-up is poised to become a really serious UK retailer.
BRIAN SOUTER. Love him or hate him, the co-founder of the UK's largest bus
fleet, Stagecoach, now has his chance to prove the Perth-based group can weave
the same spell with trains in south-west England.
JIM FAULDS. Nice man, running successful ad agency. Having cheekily poached the
hugely creative Jim Downie from arch rival The Leith Agency, Faulds now has to
prove a Scottish success story can rival anything to be found in London's
ad-land.
</TEXT>
