<TEXT>
n.SOMETHING about wrens has always got to humans. The midwinter ``wren hunt''
is one of the widest pre-Christian rituals in Europe. Sometimes it is killed,
sometimes caged, sometimes made a king. Maybe it is to do with its size, or
maybe to do with sex: ``The wren goes to it and the gilded fly does lecher in
my sight.'' But the wren would not die for adultery. It is one of the 20% of
common songbirds for which polygamy is a natural way of life. Males mate with
several females, but females with only one male.
This raises some interesting questions. Why do they do it? Why do the females
put up with it? Polygamy is thought to be the fundamental mating system for
animals; females must choose mates carefully as they invest more in their
limited number of young than the carefree and unchoosy male does in his sperm.
Most birds are monogamous because they need both partners to raise young and so
leave any genes to posterity. Not so the wren?
It may be that polygyamy is likely when there is a vast disparity between the
quality of the male's territories. Females find it more productive to be the
second mate of a rich wren than the only mate of a poor one. The male builds a
number of nests and sings loudly outside each. The female chooses the nest for
its safe inconspicuousness; she chooses the male for his conspicuous energy in
defending a large area of good feeding for her nestlings.
So now we begin to understand wrens: that mouse-like scurrying flight, those
domed nests tucked into crevices (no wonder the Latin name, troglodytes, means
cave-dweller) and above all that incredibly loud, vibrant, piercing song.
</TEXT>
