<FLAG>weekend extra scotching myths</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jim Hewitson argues that to map out the future we should listen to echoes of
the past
.
DID you notice the bewitching advertisement in The Herald a few weeks ago
seeking experienced psychics, clairvoyants, and fortune-tellers, and another
offering training in the secret arts? This is a bit scary and not just because
we're dabbling in the occult.
Why such a shortage of seers? Is business booming or is there a more sinister
story to be told? Perhaps the now widely trumpeted prediction of the world's
end in 1999 is gaining credence and the gazers into crystal balls and chicken
livers, quite literally, see no future in the trade or in anything else for
that matter.
Over the years I've given a lot of thought to this business of peering into the
future - reading teacups, scanning tarot cards, or interpreting cloud
formations (amazing what you can see up there after a jar or two). You name it
and someone, somewhere, will have used the medium to indulge in a bit of
soothsaying.
In this column, however, one theme consistently spins into view and that is the
cyclical nature of Scottish history, world history, and presumably existence
itself.
Despite the apparent linear progression of our lives, a succession of days,
months, and years speeding by in a dizzy blur, there is an underlying whirlpool
effect, a circling of events not just in individual lives but in society at
large. The big wheel keeps on turning.
It ill behoves a feckless gowk like myself, coming as I do from Covenanting
stock, to advocate some dwamie Buddhist concept of the nature of existence when
predestination should be my bag. But I can only say I have found life thus, and
in any case I don't regard the two ideas as mutually exclusive.
So, what I offer on the precipice of a new year is a pocket soothsaying kit - a
chance to impress your friends and family with predictions for the coming year
simply based on happenings in the 96th year of previous centuries. I'm willing
to bet we're not far off the mark.
First look for interesting developments in the cinema and in politics. Among
the big events of 1896 was the first public screening of a film and the first
screen kiss, while the Scots took a drubbing at the first battle of Dunbar
(1296). Cinema and politics: in 1996 will the SNP ride to victory on the broad
shoulders and brave heart of Mel Gibson?
In health and medicine watch out for new hospitals and/or some stunning
technological innovations. In 1196 the St Nicholas Leper Hospital in St Andrews
was in the midst of a development programme and in 1896 Glasgow Royal Infirmary
became the first hospital in the United Kingdom to operate an X-ray unit.
In the sporting arena, much as I'd like to predict a glory year for the
Bankies, it is to the Fair City of Perth we must look. In 1996 we will mark the
600th anniversary of the famous formal and bloody clan battle on the North
Inch. St Johnstone for the Cup? I wonder. Whatever, let's hope there are more
survivors on the park this time at game's end.
How will our big neighbour south of the Border treat us in '96? Well, in 1296
Edward I nicked the Stone of Destiny and in 1696 English support for our Darien
scheme was withdrawn. Not encouraging portents, I fear.
So remember, as you peer over the edge into a new year, there probably is
indeed a route map through this confusing life, but many roads to your
destination and more than a few roundabouts to negotiate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000009</DOCNO>
