<HEADLINE>On a mission to  delight the senses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Clare Henry talks to a talented furniture maker
whose mother still hopes she'll get a `proper job' .
A WOMAN furniture maker is rare, but from her name, Michaela Huber was
obviously expected to be a boy. When, on leaving school, she took a three-year
apprenticeship as an artist cabinetmaker or ``kunstschreiner' in a Bavarian
workshop in her native Germany, her mother was not impressed. ``Yes, she's
still hoping I'll get a proper job and a husband!''
In fact, Huber has done well with ``proper jobs'', the latest being the
furniture for Reidvale Housing Association's new phase IV sheltered housing in
Dennistoun, which was opened with great success at the end of September.
Huber's furniture is just part of several craft commissions for the building,
including lovely etched glass panels on the stairway by Reinhard Behrens and a
disappointing clock from Gordon Burnett.
Huber's furniture was no disappointment. A curved love seat plus two very solid
oak and iron benches - too heavy to be pinched - sitting outside in the central
garden courtyard, were much enjoyed in the unique warm weather. Hopefully, they
will continue to provide a perch for residents in summers to come.
I first saw Huber's love seat in an exhibition at Greywalls put on by
Edinburgh's Scottish Gallery but wasn't familiar with her work. A visit to her
studio in Gogar Old Church, near Corstorphine, was revealing. Sited on the
outskirts of Edinburgh, hidden up a track off the busy Glasgow Road in an
idyllic pastoral setting, it accomodates three furniture makers: Huber, Chris
Holmes, and Chris Scotland.
``I couldn't work alone!'' says Huber. ``I get inspiration from the others as
we all do different things in different ways.''
Holmes found the tiny atmospheric but derelict church in 1982 and restored it
to make a workshop. It dates from 1890, although one of its crowstepped gables
is part of the chancel of a former bit from the 16th century, while the
original chapel dated from the 12th century. Squat, with stained glass, a
northwest tower, (the spire was never built,) it has a small kirkyard right out
of Samuel Palmer, the cows lowing over the hedge.
All three artists prefer to work on one-off commissioned pieces, (costing
between #200-#8000) with Holmes currently making a dresser for a private
commission and Scotland creating ``an amazing balcony/deck'' for a house in
Edinburgh.
Huber likes hills and walking, (last weekend she was busy protesting with the
Ramblers' Association about the Scottish Office closure of a public right of
way in parkland at Middleton Hall near her home) and came to Scotland because
of its landscape.
In 1982, on a visit to the dentist in Munich, she saw some photographs of the
Scottish Highlands in a magazine. She liked what she saw, left Bavaria behind
for travels round Europe - but never got further than Lochaber.
She moved to Edinburgh in 1983, working at Whytock and Reid, the well-known
Scottish cabinetmakers established in 1807. She was the first woman ever to
have worked there. ``It was interesting for a while but I felt it was a little
like being in a zoo - there were lots of VIP visitors and I found it
off-putting. I was expert at restoring German traditional furniture, so I did a
lot of their restoration: church chairs, Penicuik chairs.
``It's sad that Scotland has no tradition of apprenticeships because there is a
need for training. Most young furniture makers here have been at art colleges
studying art and design. But I believe they are too academic, not enough hands
on. Few of them can use materials to their best advantage - the quality of
craftsmanship is just not there. Students don't get enough cabinet making.
There's still a lot to be said for the apprenticeship system.''
In 1984 she moved to Ben Dawson Furniture in Musselburgh, making modern office
and board room furniture, but in 1987 decided to go freelance, ``a leap in the
dark'', taking space in the sawdust strewn Gogar Church.
``We share big machinery and equiptment like the dehumidifier but have our own
hand tools. You get really attached to your tools. We get our own logs, native
woods, saw them up: yew, elm, holly, apple, sycamore from fallen trees at
Linlithgow and elsewhere. It's a nice thing to do. Just think, making furniture
out of a log, it extends the life of a tree by 300 years.''
The church has really thick walls and they have a sawdust burner stove, so it's
not too cold in winter. The dog, called Sprocket, likes the stove. The scent of
new wood being worked adds to the homely workshop. The dehumidifier, a big
walk-in box, sits to the side of where the alter used to be, taking up one
whole corner. ``It reduces the wood by 10%. If you don't do that, when you put
a piece of furnitre in a house with central heating, it starts to jump about
and split.''
Huber describes her philosophy or design approach as ``menschlich'' or
``putting people at the centre, emphasising comfort, a feeling of wellbeing and
at the same time delighting the senses''. She works with clients over a period
of months, making drawings and scale models till both are satisfied. ``I don't
have a particular style. I'm not interested in that. I'm strictly a
craftswoman. I don't consider myself an artist.''
Julia Radcliffe, who managed the Reidvale Annbank Street art project, thinks
otherwise. She's keen to get artists involved in new urban buildings in
Glasgow, and was commissioned to report on the potential importance of
including art in the housing sector. Reidvale's architect, Murray Design Group,
aimed to put art in its buildings from the initial design stage.
Radcliffe advertised for craftsmen for Reidvale, then presented a ``long list'
of 20 artists. ``The committee chose three, including Huber, who they believed
could contribute to this user-friendly building for elderly people. The client
did not want `decoration,' rather strong, simple, pared back solutions.''
Molendinar Park, Reidvale's sister organisation, is also commissioning artists
to work on its new building at Bellgrove Street. Meanwhile, Huber has just
completed three new Celtic Benches for East Kilbride town centre, again working
with blacksmith Phil Johnson, of Ratho, who makes the curved ironwork for all
the seats. One bench has just won the 1000 Premier One prize at Edinburgh's
SAAC exhibition at the RSA and several more are destined for Leith and
Edinburgh's Elm Row.
Huber will make you a solid kitchen table in elm, oak or beech from #300 to
#600; a coffee table from around #200; a board room table for #4,500. A rocking
chair, made to measure, takes three weeks. ``I like my customers to come to the
workshop while I'm working on the piece.'' Well, it may become an heirloom
after all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
