<HEADLINE>Streamlined thrills</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BATMAN FOREVER (retail, #14.99; also available to rent; certificate PG). This
is easily the best of three comic-strip action adventures released this month -
though up against Judge Dredd and Tank Girl (see below) that might sound like
praising with faint damns.
Batman Forever rings a few changes on the personnel of the previous two films
in the series. Val Kilmer takes over the cape and mask from Michael Keaton; Tim
Burton moves upstairs to the producer's office and leaves the director's chair
to Joel Schumacher; and Robin the Boy Wonder finally makes an appearance in the
person of Chris O'Donnell.
Most of these changes are positive - Kilmer delivers a darkness and duality
that Keaton could never manage, and O'Donnell makes a useful foil for Kilmer to
bounce his personality off of.
However, Schumacher's direction lacks Burton's wild flights of fancy, and when
it comes to narrative drive he's no more coherent than his famously plot-hating
predecessor.
Batman Forever actually kicks off with a strong plot idea - the invention by
Wayne Corporation electronics geek Jim Carrey of a virtual-reality
entertainment gizmo that not only turns its users into zombies but can steal or
manipulate their thoughts.
Having established this notion, however, he throws it away and scarcely
mentions it again. In lieu of a story, we get two enjoyably over-the-top
performances from Tommy Lee Jones, as the facially and psychically scarred
villain Two-Face, and Carrey as a high-camp Riddler.
Batman Forever is a show - a couple of hours of streamlined thrills and
throwaway laughs. As Barry Humphries might say, it's a nice night's
entertainment.
nJUDGE DREDD (rental, cert 15).
Let's cut to the chase: the best thing about Judge Dredd is that when you rent
it you get a free copy of 2000 AD, the comic in which the grim lawman began and
continues his career of meting out instant justice to the creeps, crims, and
perps of Mega-City One. The strip is fast, funny, and stylish; the film is a
slow, dull mess.
Everything you heard about the Judge's troubled movie gestation is right up
there to see on the screen: star Sylvester Stallone and director Danny Cannon
obviously had two different films in mind, and the compromise combo is less
that the sum of its parts.
One problem is that, in America, irony is a word that describes the taste of
Perrier.
Another problem is that it looks as though it was edited the way Willaim
Burroughs edits his books: somebody threw all the footage in the air and
stitched together whatever bits came first to hand. A honker, a howling dog, a
stinker in 48 different keys.
nTANK GIRL (rental, cert 15).
Like Judge Dredd, Tank Girl has its roots in the British comics scene, being
the adventures of a feisty, beer-swilling punkette who lives in the
post-apocalypse Australian outback, drives a tank, and bides in with a mutant
kangaroo called Booga.
Also like Judge Dredd, it's lousy; in fact, it's even worse than Judge Dredd.
At least that film didn't make the mistake of incorporating montage sequences
of the original comic strip just to remind how much better that was than the
witless, charmless, style-free fiasco you're watching. Lori Petty stars, for
her sins.
</TEXT>
