<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Future is growing concern</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q My wife and I have Tessas maturing in January and would appreciate your
comments on re-investing in Tessas up to the maximum allowed and the balance in
investment trusts. We have retired early, both in our fifties, and have
index-linked pensions which cover our day-to-day needs comfortably. We are both
basic rate taxpayers and are homeowners with no mortgage or other commitments.
We seek to invest with minimum risk and primarily for growth. Our current
investments are: 4357 Sun Life distribution bond, 900 BT, 2500 Edinburgh
Investment Trust PEP, 650 Dunedin Income &amp; Growth PEP, 3070 Schroder UK Growth
PEP, 2340 Foreign &amp; Colonial, 1420 Scottish Mortgage, 116 Alliance Trust, and
700 KEPIT. We also have #23,000 in Tessas and #7000 on deposit.
n Your strategy - including investment in Tessas - is a sound mix of risk-free
and equity investment which should yield good results over the long term. It
might, however, be worth switching more of your existing investment/unit trust
holdings into PEPs in the new tax year, not so much for the benefit now but in
case you need more income in the future.
q I am likely to be over the capital gains tax limit this year and my wife not
at all. I believe I can transfer some shares to her before April 6 and make use
of her allowance for 1995-96. I also think she would have the full benefit of
all indexation allowances due from the original purchase dates of the shares.
Can you confirm this?
n Transfers of assets between spouses are regarded as made on a no-gain,
no-loss basis, so there is no tax payable when the gift is made. Your wife will
be treated as having acquired the shares at your original cost at date of
purchase and this, together with the full indexation allowance from that date,
will be available against the proceeds of sale next year. Her annual exemption
of #6000 will be available against the disposal.
q It has been suggested that for future income I put #15,000 in a life
assurance distribution bond from which up to 5% can be taken each year tax
free. In what way, apart from the small tax advantage, will this be better than
opting for unit or investment trusts and taking 5% each year?
n It would probably be preferable to do the latter because bonds of this sort
can carry higher charges and have performed less well on balance. The more you
can put into PEPs the better as these will be much the more profitable
investment.
q I have 500 shares in Thorntons which have done nothing much over the seven
years I have held them. I would be prepared to be speculative with the proceeds
of these and was considering transferring into an investment trust such as
Dunedin Enterprise. However, the recent upheaval at Dunedin has made me wonder
if it would be a suitable fund to invest in at present.
n The venture capital side of Dunedin which runs the Enterprise Trust has not
been greatly affected by the upheavals in the company and you can invest in it
with some confidence, so long as you are aware of the riskier nature of its
investment strategy. The trust has a good track record among its peers and the
management team is generally well regarded.
q We have a Royal Life Homestyle unit-linked policy which we started in April
1990 and is due to run until 2014. The level of cover is #15,000. We have since
reduced the mortgage capital sum by more than this amount so we do not need the
life cover. We are thinking of stopping the policy and putting the monthly #39
premium in an investment trust savings plan. Is this a wise?
n The disadvantage is that you are unlikely to get back even half of what you
have put into the Royal Life policy if you stop it. The question is which will
give you the better return, keeping the existing policy or changing to an
investment trust savings scheme. Given that part of the current premiums go
towards providing the life cover, the latter will probably give a superior
return over the long term.
q Any articles and adverts I have seen regarding investment trusts and unit
trusts that invest mainly in Preference shares or bonds seem to focus on their
high yields and relative degree of security but do no comment on future value
of capital.
I am looking for investments that provide a combination of high income and
capital values that keep pace with inflation in the medium to long term, so
could you please comment on this and offer any advice about alternative
investments that meet the above criteria.
n You are looking for the holy grail - an investment which offers high income
combined with capital values which are maintained in real terms. There is no
investment which can guarantee such an outcome. However, over the long term
equities have more than kept pace with inflation and provided a rising return,
which is also important for those dependent on investment income. You have to
be prepared for short-term fluctuations in capital values though.
Ten years ago the average equity income unit trust yielded 6.6% gross, against
8.5% for building society seven-day notice accounts. Within a couple of years
the income exceeded that from societies and by 1992 the gross yield on sums
invested in 1985 had risen to 12.4% before dropping back to 10.7% currently. So
they have delivered a rising income.
On the capital front, #1000 invested has become about #2300 in 10 years, though
between 1987 and 1993 they moved nowhere. Also there were two periods when
there were falls of about 25%, one of 20% and another of 15%. So it is
essential the long-term view is taken. While the future may not repeat the
past, the overall positive trend can be traced further back so there is a good
chance it will carry on.
q I propose to give a young relative a few shares. As he will not be a taxpayer
for some time, I presume he will be able to claim back the tax on dividends.
How does he go about this?
n If the child is under 16, it is necessary for the parents or guardian to make
a claim for repayment of income tax deducted. The child cannot apply personally
for a repayment unless he is 16 or over and the investment producing the income
in his own name. In addition, where he is under 18 and the income arises on
gifts from parents, it is not possible to claim repayment of the tax deducted
if that income amounts to more than #100 a year.
Where a claim for repayment is being made for the first time you must complete
Inland Revenue form R95D which you can obtain from any tax office. This
requests details of the child's name, address, date of birth and so on, and
also the name and address of the parent or guardian.
This should be sent to your local tax office which will issue a repayment claim
form. This is a simplified version of a tax return where details of the income
received and tax deducted can be entered. It should be submitted to the tax
office with the dividend vouchers which the Inspector will require before the
repayment is made. Further details are given in the booklet IR112 also
available from any tax office.
q I have an endowment policy which has another six years to run. Before that
time I would like to make it over to my son so he will have the benefit of the
sum assured. I have been told, however, that this will not prevent the capital
sum becoming liable to inheritance tax. Surely if the policy is in my son's
name when it matures there can be no question of a gift being made.
n The advice you have been given is partially correct - there is a transfer of
value for inheritance tax purposes where the benefits of a policy are
transferred or assigned as a gift or for less than full value. The value of the
gift is the value of the policy or, if greater, the value of the total premiums
paid by you to date, less any partial surrenders received on the policy.
Like most other transfers during lifetime, the assignation of the policy will
not be taxable if you survive seven years after the date of gift to your son.
It should, however, be noted that if you continue to pay the premiums on this
policy these are also gifts and, to the extent not covered by exemptions, each
one will also be subject to the seven-year rule.
Provided you retain no benefits under the policy and it is properly assigned to
your son, there is no reason why the capital should be liable to inheritance
tax if you survive the required seven years.
Caledonian Newspapers Limited and the editor of The Herald accept no legal
responsibility for the answers given in these columns. Readers are invited to
submit concise questions for answer in the paper. No correspondence can be
entered into.
</TEXT>
