<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why Tessa is the name on everyone's lips</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HELEN PRIDHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635023</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DURING the first half of 1996, the name Tessa will be on many savers' lips.
Existing investors in this type of tax-free bank and building society account
may soon have to decide what they are going to do with their money when it
matures. New savers may be tempted to open up an account.
Tessas were first introduced in January 1991. Many people took the plunge
immediately. Of more than four million who have opened accounts, two thirds did
so in the first year. These are now coming to the end of their five-year term.
Savers were permitted to invest up to #9000 over these five years. Tax-free
interest was added to their accounts. Final returns are set to range from
#11,300 to #14,000. The best results will come from those which offered
fixed-interest rates at the outset, with Bristol &amp; West's Capital Maker topping
the list.
But there were only a handful of these Tessas on offer initially, and
relatively few investors chose them because the rates they offered looked so
much less attractive than those whose rates could change once you were
invested. Fixed-rate accounts at the time were paying around 11.5%, while the
variable versions were offering up to 15%.
Since 1991 as general interest rates have fallen so too have the returns on the
variable Tessas. But some came down further and faster than others. The better
performances have come from smaller building societies and banks.
The Dunfermline Building Society produced one of the best results. More than
7000 investors who put in the maximum deposits over the period have benefited
from the society's competitive rates and maturity bonus. Spokesman Gordon Swan
explains: ``We wanted to encourage and reward longer term savers. We still
believe in maintaining a healthy Tessa rate.''
The most disappointing performances have been produced by the banks. Even the
TSB, which has been advertising itself as ``The bank that came first - top of
the bank Tessa performance table'', has produced a below average return
compared to all providers, though it has given better results than other banks.
The maturity value of the Clydesdale's Tessa is nearly #1000 less than the
Dunfermline's and nearly #500 less than that of the TSB, but a spokesman for
the bank was unrepentant, describing these differences as ``not significant''.
One wonders whether the customers would agree.
Savers with the Bank of Scotland got even less. Initially it refused to
disclose its returns, saying they might be ``misinterpreted''. A spokesman
says: ``Unlike a number of other Tessa accounts, ours did not require the
maximum amount to be invested or a feeder account to be opened.''
If you have a maturing Tessa, you have a number of options. You could spend the
money, of course, but if you want to go on saving you need to think carefully
about your choices. The rules allow you to roll over your capital, but not the
added interest, into a new account. If you have saved less than the maximum
over the past five years, you will be able to roll over your capital in the
first year and then top it up in future years to the full #9000.
It makes sense to roll over your savings into a new Tessa if it is money you
would keep on deposit anyway. There are some attractive roll-over products on
offer which run for another five years. But look carefully at the cash-in
penalties in case you need access to your money earlier.
There are more fixed-rate Tessas available this time round. The Clydesdale
appears to be trying to redeem its poor performance in the first round by
offering one of the highest fixed rates of 8% to existing customers who have
accumulated the maximum in their original account. The Dunfermline is also
offering an attractive 7.7% to previous investors. But cash-in penalties on
fixed-rate products tend to be higher than on variable rate accounts.
Also there is the question of whether interest rates generally will rise or
fall over the next five years. Nobody has a crystal ball but Graham Cooper of
financial adviser Chase de Vere says: ``With a General Election coming up and a
possible change of government, interest rates could well increase again, if
only temporarily. That is why I would opt for a variable rate Tessa.''
THE range of variable rate products is wide. If past form is anything to go by,
investors are likely to get a better long-term deal from a building society
than a bank. If you have a maturing bank Tessa, there is nothing to stop you
transferring. The Dunfermline is offering a variable rate account currently
paying 7.2% for transferred deposits of #3000 or more, and 6.2% on smaller sums.
You cannot reinvest the interest from your first Tessa in a new one, so
consider an alternative investment that is equally tax efficient. If you are
risk averse, you could put it into National Savings Certificates. But for
something more exciting, how about a personal equity plan?
Helen Pridham
</TEXT>
