<HEADLINE>Misanthrope with morbid obssessions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Frank McLynn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974635024</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEWIS CARROLL:
A Biography
Morton N Cohen
MacMillan, #25
AUTHORS write under pseudonyms for a variety of reasons, some as banal as the
attempt to baffle the taxman. But when the Oxford mathematics don Charles
Lutwidge Dodgson claimed not to know Lewis Carroll, author of the Alice books
and The Hunting of the Snark, he surely alerted us that the two aspects of his
personality were as dissimilar as Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde. Morton Cohen, an
American professor, sets himself the task of making sense of the divided
Dodgson/Carroll in a book whose erudition and scholarship is betrayed by the
thinness of its psychological insights.
Dodgson was a deeply unpleasant man, and in two very different senses. The very
worst sort of Oxbridge dons, he was desiccated, supercilious, sardonic, fussy,
spiteful, pedantic, obdurate, self-satisfied, reactionary, misanthropic, and
small-minded - the sort of man who cannot imagine the esoterica of Oxford and
the minutiae of Hebdomadal Council politics are of interest to anyone but a
handful of inverted pedants.
In fact, the entire panoply of ``effortless superiority'' of Victorian Oxford
rested on a risible foundation of religious belief that the average Hottentot
would have found puerile. Nobody can understand Dodgson/Carroll who does not
understand this deadly academic milieu, and Cohen sketches it very effectively.
Yet the second aspect of Dodgson's unpleasantness is less easily dealt with. As
is fairly well-known by now, Dodgson was a man of repressed and disturbed
sexuality - ``confirmed bachelor'' was the euphemism at the time - for whom
paedophiliac is not too strong an epithet.
Any doubt on this score will not survive a reading of Cohen's text and still
less a study of Dodgson's photographs here lavishly reproduced, which reveal a
genuine obsession with pre-pubescent girls; the four nude studies are
especially rebarbative. Alice in Wonderland, however one interprets it - and
the ``readings'' are legion - is a classic example of sublimation through
creativity.
Interestingly, Cohen reveals that Alice Liddell, daughter of the dean of Christ
Church who was co-author of the famous Greek lexicon, was herself a nasty piece
of work - a snobbish, domineering, class-obsessed, money-grubbing martinet and
domestic tyrant, the terror of ``below stairs''. Cohen convincingly argues that
Dodgson discerned her deep character during the famous ``endless summer'' of
1862, when he first told nine-year-old Alice Liddell the Alice stories, and
that this accounts for Alice's temper tantrums during the adventures in
Wonderland.
This book is full of fascinating stories, asides, and titbits, but suffers from
two main faults. Hostile as he is to psychological interpretations of his
subject, Cohen finds himself manoeuvred into banality, occasional philistinism,
and sometimes the downright absurd. Having scouted all psychoanalytical
readings of the man and his work, Cohen argues that Carroll, far from being a
pathological case, found children interesting because he had read Blake,
Wordsworth, and Dickens. According to this argument, all reputable teachers of
English literature, who have read these authors, should be morbidly obsessed
with very young girls!
The second fault with the book lies in the structure. A biography, of all
artefacts, ought to be relied on to follow a clear chronological sequence, yet
for the most part Cohen organises his material thematically, on relations with
publishers, etc. One feels that one has read a book of essays rather than a
life. The ultimate absurdity comes when Morton devotes a chapter to Dodgson's
parents two-thirds of the way through the book; clearly the proper place for
such a discussion is in Chapter One.
There is a lot of pure gold in this book but it is hidden among the iron
pyrites of lengthy quotes, legions of proper names, and a veritable Who's Who
of Victorian England. Specialists will doubtless be fascinated, but this
reviewer found all the doubling back on its own tracks and the failure of the
book to develop chronologically or, ultimately, to evince any real structure or
craftsmanship as wearying as watching a Godard movie.
FRANK McLYNN
</TEXT>
</DOC>
