<HEADLINE>All aboard for a journey into a darker world</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Artist Douglas Gordon tells Ann Donald about his night time reading.
n I WAS travelling recently and decided to buy all three of Irving Welsh's
novels and read them within the week, starting off with Trainspotting. I liked
it a lot because the vocabulary invaded your mentality, which for me was quite
funny because I'm not an east coaster. The dialect was relentless and strangely
I could relate more to Welsh's language than when I read James Kelman. Maybe
it's a generation thing. I didn't find it such a horrible or bleak novel;
rather he dealt with the whole thing of drugs and casuals quite humorously and
didn't sanitise anything but dealt with it all very honestly.
I thought Acid House was good but didn't enjoy the short stories as much as
Trainspotting where the narrative was so chaotic. The characters flowed in and
out of each other like an extended family, which reminded me of Brett Easton
Ellis' style. Marabou Stork Nightmares I thought was just incredible. It was
really heavy but I enjoyed the whole deep, dark aspect. Maybe it was because I
was reading them all in succession but by the time I got to Marabou I was
crushed. The rape scene was one of the worst things I've ever read. And as for
the ending - and this probably says more about me than him - I just don't
believe in this idea of redemption. I think the main character should have died
suffering spiritually rather than physically. I thought Welsh let him off a wee
bit in the end.
I think Welsh is a great storyteller. The metaphors of abuse, recycled abuse
and then redemption in Marabou were quite simplistic but that's not necessarily
bad. At the risk of sounding totally pretentious I'd say that it was like a
Calvino book. He treads the same story again and again. But for me that's fine.
A young writer needs to get to know his territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Live fast, die young</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenneth Wright</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974635026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n A Good-Looking Corpse, by Mike Nicol, Minerva, #7.99.
It's a pleasant change to read a book about black life in South Africa that
isn't either painfully pious or devoutly PC, and Mike Nicol's recreation of the
musical and social scene of the townships in the 1950s, centred on the
pioneering black magazine Drum, is a delight from beginning to end.
While never ignoring the miseries of apartheid, he reveals a raucous and
raffish subculture, based on dancing, jazz, zoot suits, and home-grown hashish,
whose inhabitants refused to be victims and defied their oppression by not
letting the Boers stop them having fun. Live fast, die young, and leave.
n Stigmata, by Padraig Standun, Brandon, #5.95.
The latest example of Ireland's thriving literary cottage industry of whimsical
comedies that take a poke at sanctity and sanctimoniousness in the 26 Counties,
Stigmata is a real inside job in that its author was ordained as a priest in
1971 - and for all I know, may still be one.
We're deep in the heart of what Dubliners call culchie country here, a
piety-ridden village in the West where bad language gets you barred from the
pub, the parish priest is suspected of communist leanings, a mad old woman
spends her time rebuffing the social services, and the odd miracle is
considered not all that remarkable. Droll and kindly humour with an edge -
great fun for all folks of Irish descent and those who wish they were.
n Clint Eastwood: Actor and Director, by Edward Gallafent, Cassell, #12.99.
Not so much a star biography as an attempt to give Clint Eastwood the place he
deserves in the history of the American movie, Edward Gallafent's book makes a
convincing case for the star of Dirty Harry as an auteur whose austere cultural
and historical vision has been denied serious recognition because his films
actually bring people in to see them.
Grouping his pictures within the genres and cycles to which they belong, and
relating them to broader movements inside and outside the cinema, current the
author diligently analyses the themes and attitudes of Eastwood's work and
creates a coherent critical portrait. Feeling lucky, punks?
n A Working Mother, by Agnes Owens, Abacus, #5.99.
One of the best but also the most underrated of the informal 1980s Glasgow
school of novelists that includes Alastair Gray (who drew this edition's front
cover) and James Kelman, Agnes Owens here adds a delightful touch of wry and
dry humour to the painstaking anatomies of working-class women's lives in which
she specialises.
It's still as dark a brew as ever - madness, adultery, fortune-telling, and
hard drinking are among its ingredients - but her spoonful of sugar helps the
medicine go down. Now if James Kelman would just discover a sense of humour too
. . .
n Hollywood People, by Douglas Thompson, Pan, #4.99.
Film fans with a taste for gossip and scandal - ie all film fans - will find
plenty of guilty pleasures in the book of Douglas Thompson's 1995 TV series
about life at the top and bottom (there is no middle to speak of) of the
capital of the movie industry.
This is the place Marilyn Monroe summed up as ``where they pay you $1 million
for a kiss and 50 cents for your soul'', where every waiter has a script in
development, and where only the most deprived 12-year-old on Sunset Boulevard
still has the nose she was born with. Sounds like heaven to me.
KENNETH WRIGHT
</TEXT>
</DOC>
