<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rich rewards for the baroness of crime Margaret Rigillo</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Margaret Rigillo bumps into P D James at the Spanish Steps and hears how her
disappointments are outweighed
by satisfaction
BATHSHEBA Abse, curator of the Keats-Shelley Memorial House in Rome, has a
favourite anecdote concerning P.D James. ``When the BBC Breakaway team were
over here preparing a feature on the Romantics, they were with me in the house
looking for a likely visitor to interview,'' she told me. ``Nobody they asked
seemed to speak good enough English, and they were about to give up - when who
should happen to come toiling up three flights of stairs but Lady James!''
P.D James was, of course, the answer to a producer's prayer - a famous author,
an eminent public figure, and a good off-the-cuff talker. She is also a genuine
Keats fan and she makes a pilgrimage to the little room where the poet died
every time she is in the Eternal City.
``I love his odes,'' she tells me, as we sit over a cappuccino in her hotel at
the top of the Spanish Steps. ``And I have immense respect for him as a human
being. I'm not a poet, but I think I understand something of the poetic
imagination. Maybe that's why I made Dalgliesh a detective poet. Great poetry
gives you solace in these moments of darkness, of grief and distress.''
Phyllis James's early life was not easy. She married young, at the outbreak of
the Second World War, and subsequently she had to shoulder the responsibility
of supporting her husband, who came home incapacitated, and two small
daughters. Widowed when she was 44, she never remarried.
``You don't forget...... Funnily enough, as you get older, you miss them more.
You see your grandchildren growing up and you think: Oh, why isn't he here to
see them, to enjoy things with me, to do things together...?''
In a moment, the shadow is gone. P.D James is the last person to indulge in
self-pity. She is an optimist, projected towards the future. At 75 years young,
the last thing she is thinking about is retiring. Indeed, she is already hard
at work on her next crime novel: ``Plot planning takes me almost as along as
the actual writing. I end up with enormous notebooks of ideas and information.''
After her incursion into a different genre with Children of Men in 1992 - ``It
was very much a one-off event. I found it a very painful book to write, but I'm
glad I did it'' - she returned to her poet-detective Dalgliesh with Original
Sin.
P.D James seems to have featured on our bookshelves for so long that it is
difficult to believe she was over 40 before she published her first novel,
Cover Her Face.
``I always knew I wanted to write books, but it just never seemed possible. I
always just had to concentrate on what I considered was a safe job with a
cheque at the end of the month.
``One day - I can remember it quite clearly - I thought: there's no point in
going on like this waiting for a good time to write my first book, because
there never was going to be a good time. I was already attending evening
classes to try to get qualifications in hospital administration so I started to
get up early in the mornings to write, before I went to work.
``I thought the crime-fiction genre would be a wonderful apprenticeship. I
loved the structure and I found it very supportive. But at the time I don't
think I believed that I was going to necessarily stay with it.''
Her eyes still sparkle when she recalls the day, 30 years ago, that she got the
news that her first novel had been accepted. ``When I learned I was going to be
a published author! That was a great moment!''
Other fondly remembered high points in her career are the two honorary degrees
conferred on her, by Buckingham University in 1992 (``I never got the
opportunity to go to university myself. My family couldn't afford it. I started
work at 16, and I've been working ever since'') and Glasgow last year. ``I had
a really lovely time - they had a piper piping me in!''
Although she enjoys all the accolades and adulation, they have not gone to her
head. A candid and straightforward writer, who has been going quietly and
unostentatiously about her craft for the past 30 years, she was astonished to
find herself, some months back, the object of an apparent denigratory campaign
when she was accused first, of snobbery and political incorrectness, and then
of snubbing the Crime Writers' Conference.
These allegations she publicly refuted, but the wound has not healed. Her voice
rings with indignation when she talks about it: ``It was a disgraceful business
really. It's the first time I've ever been attacked like that, on a personal
level. And all completely untrue. The journalists involved should have checked
their facts.
``I realised that if you are very successful, sooner or later you are going to
attract spite. I suppose I'm lucky that I haven't attracted it before this.''
And she laughs a little, shrugging it off: ``Fortunately, they can't take the
goodies away from me!''
The ``goodies'' include an OBE, a life peerage, and a string of crime-writing
awards, as well as stints chairing the prestigious institutions like the Booker
Prize Committee and Literature Advisory Panel of the British Arts Council, a
governorship in the BBC, and a seat on the British Council Board.
They also include her two daughters, to whom she is very close. ``They both
helped me with the research in Children of Men and I dedicated the book to
them.''
She told me of the new honour which is about to be bestowed upon her: ``The
National Portrait Gallery has commissioned my portrait. I believe that this is
the first time this has been done for a crime-fiction writer. They do have, I
believe, a portrait of Dorothy L Sayers hanging up, but they acquired that - it
wasn't commissioned.
``They asked me if I'd prefer to be painted by one of their famous
old-established artists, or by an up-and-comer. I said: `Oh, I'd rather have
someone up-and-coming'. A young man called Michael Taylor is doing it.''
During this latest trip to Rome, she has a busy schedule. She is to star in a
couple of literary events, and she will be wined and dined by the British
Ambassador.
``But I do have one day off,'' she says. ``I'm going to take a taxi and nip
down to see the Sistine Chapel.''
And this is the picture of her which has remained in my mind: Baroness James of
Holland Park standing unobtrusively in the queue, among the Japanese and German
tourists at the doors of the Vatican Museum.
</TEXT>
