<HEADLINE>Hard facts in good measure CELLARMAN</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW MacKAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra cellarman</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635028</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO a large extent, especially in my maturing years, it is still better to have
received Christmas presents that are hard. Soft generally means clothes and
after a few pokes and prods it's a safe bet the parcel will soon produce an M &amp;
S jersey or cardigan. Occasionally there's been the odd red herring; but the
boxed shirt is betrayed by its lightness and the jigsaw when shaken gives a
crinkly rumble instead of that pleasing murmur of settling liquid.
The Ultimate World Encyclopedia of Beer (#16.99) comes into the hard category,
and although you can't drink a book, if you could this one would be a classic.
If it were liquid it might be described as having full colour, being aromatic
as well as robust, with a subtle flavour that satisfies to the finish, leaving
a pleasant hoppy aftertaste. A probable ABV might be around 6.6%. Clearly one
to be respected but which on occasion may be lifted and laid during a session.
Beer is certainly a subject that lends itself to some extravagant treatment and
author Roger Protz has not missed the opportunity to bring out its colourful
characters with bottles, beermats and breweries swirling amid a spray of facts,
figures and fonts to bring cheerful animation to each page.
Credentials don't escape Protz either. He was one of the earlier driving forces
behind CAMRA and editor of its Good Beer Guide and is currently editor of its
monthly What's Brewing newspaper. His beer blethers have earned him leading
honours and he now sips his ale from a golden tankard.
Within the 224 pages, Protz goes on a global pub crawl and from Flanders to the
Far East visits leading breweries, sampling products and profiling each
company. He seems to have landed the ideal job, although he does return with a
few tales to tell. Behind many of those well-known beer labels some
entertaining and interesting facts emerge.
For instance, did you know that Heineken was so appalled by the depravity and
drunkenness caused by gin drinking he told his mother he would brew healthy
beer for the people if she bought the Haystack Brewery?
Chapters cover the making of beer and the beer business, beer and food, the
history of beer and the culture of beer drinking. For about the price of a
night at the pub or a reasonable carry-out The Ultimate Encyclopedia of Beer is
a good reference book for the enthusiast beer drinker or anyone interested in
this fascinating subject. It is certain to have a lengthy shelf-life.
Another gift that came in hard format, although this time towards the soft end
of the spectrum, was the World Beer Guide (#9.99). Written by Andrea Gillies,
who like Protz was editor of the Good Beer Guide, it is dominated by sections
dealing with tasting notes of bottled and canned beers that are available in
this country.
Over a six-month period she and her fellow tasting companion sampled more than
4000 beers - which seems to be nice work if you can get it. But everything in
the garden wasn't rosy. Despite their huge popularity, it is certainly true
canned beers are in a third division of taste leagues when compared with their
bottled cousins. In her tasting notes Gillies does not miss this point.
An unmentionable (and undrinkable?) has been thus described: ``Must be a joke.
Dark, plummy-brown beer with a caramel, roast-barley nose, and a sugar syrup,
corny, vaguely roasted, sweet and sticky palate. One of the crudest and most
unpleasant of British beers, and certainly not a pale ale, by even the most
imaginative definition.'' Ouch.
Occasionally Gillies' tongue unfurls around a beer and language more associated
with the wine taster streams out. A bottled blue-eyed boy was depicted as being
``rich brown coloured, with even richer, malty-fruity, butterscotch aromas. A
good, dry, prickly hop character, introducing a wonderfully soft, buttery (rich
dark toffee), fruity sweetness, with a little baked apple and the tiniest hint
of prune. Dark malts, succulent yeast fruits, vividly hoppy: this is an
admirably made ale, at once deeply mellow and arrestingly clean-edged.''
Clearly Gillies' tongue reaches tastes that others do not. Yes, nice beer if
you can get it.
n Making its baptism, albeit in minute quantity, is Red Cuillin from the Isle
of Skye. Available at Blackfriars, Brewery Tap, State Bar and Station Bar,
Glasgow; Coane's in Johnstone and the Bow Bar, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
