<TEXT>
THERE is nothing like a happy ending. When Elizabeth married Darcy and Jane
married Bingley, more than 10 million viewers, who tuned in to the final
episode of Pride and Prejudice for the double wedding, basked in the glow.
The married couples aside, no one is happier than Auntie Beeb herself. Pride
and Prejudice has been a huge commercial and critical success for the
corporation and, following on from Middlemarch and Martin Chuzzlewit, the
adaptation has helped ensure the classic serial is now an integral part of the
BBC's drama output, after a long period during the mid to late eighties when
whiskers and morning coats dropped out of fashion.
``They are now an essential plank of public broadcasting in our society,''
explains Michael Wearing, head of BBC's drama serials. ``With a literary
history as long as our own, you can't say we shouldn't do them.''
Already adaptations of George Eliot's Daniel Deronda, Daniel Defoe's Moll
Flanders, and Anne Bronte's Tenant of Wildfell Hall are all at various stages
of production, while Joseph Conrad's Nostromo, a novel that defeated the best
efforts of film-maker David Lean, has already been completed and will be shown
next year.
This Christmas, the boy's own adventure The Prisoner of Zenda graced our screen
for the umpteenth time.
Even ITV is planning a version of Jane Austen's Emma, its first costume drama
since Jewel in the Crown back in 1984.
``The BBC have proved there is a market for them,'' explains Wearing, the man
responsible for commissioning these adaptations. ``Oddly enough, they are now
more successful than when the BBC were doing two or three a year as a matter of
absolute course.
``There is no doubt that they are great stories and they seem to connect, which
I don't pretend to fully understand, but every time we've done one they've
caused a splash.''
However, as producers rush to the local library to see what other old
favourites can be rescued from the cobwebs, it's notable that the recent
revival seems to be drawing on the same small band of literary sources.
True, Middlemarch had not been adapted before last year, but the cameras have
turned on the works of George Eliot before. Dickens is a hardy perennial on
television and Andrew Davies's version of Pride and Prejudice comes just over a
decade after Fay Weldon's attempt in the early eighties, which itself was not
the first time the BBC tackled Jane Austen's novel.
Yet, with the much praised BBC Scotland's adaptation of A Scots Quair now
little more than a distant memory, the question arises, where are the Scottish
classics? Is the BBC only interested in serials for and about middle-brow,
middle-England?
``I hope if we do Middlemarch it does speak to people in Scotland, Ireland and
Wales as well as England,'' Michael Wearing says. ``There is a sense in which
writing in the English language, as written by Oscar Wilde or Walter Scott or
Jane Austen or anybody else has to belong to all of us.''
However, Wearing is aware of criticisms that the canon of great works upon
which the BBC draws does seem a little restricted. Unfortunately, he suggests,
the problem is money. ``These things aren't cheap. That's the biggest problem.
We can never entirely fund them ourselves. We can't actually do more than two
or three a year.''
He suggests that, as a result, there can be limitations on what the BBC can
afford to adapt. ``It's fair to say that more esoteric classics are not what
American producers want to invest in.''
It's a problem that BBC Scotland's own Head of Drama, Andrea Calderwood, is
well aware of.
``The problem with classics is that they're massively expensive to do and
normally they have to be co-produced. The Jane Austens are the ones everyone
has heard of and that American co-producers are familiar with, so that's a
reason why we in Scotland are at a slight disadvantage.
``In Scotland, we have less of the books everybody has heard of and that are on
everybody's school curriculum. There is a danger, however, of just doing the
curriculum classics. The same classics have been done over and over again.''
A few Scottish classics might help combat that danger and Calderwood is
certainly not averse to the idea.
``The way I look at our output, we should be doing things right across the
whole range. So at the moment, we're doing original serials like A Mugs's Game,
the popular series like Hamish MacBeth and there are hard-hitting serials like
Cardiac Arrest and I think the classics are something we should look at as well.
``I firmly believe if there's a good strong accessible story and if it's well
adapted and the scrip works on its own terms then there's no reason why we
shouldn't do it.''
At the moment, nothing has progressed further than the development stage, but
BBC Scotland is hopeful that its plans for adapting Walter Scott's Old
Mortality will come to fruition.
``What interests me is that we should try to find an original approach to the
classics,'' says Calderwood. ``And the reason we're doing Old Mortality is that
the writer Chris Hannan came to us just full of enthusiasm for what he saw as
the contemporary resonance of the book and because it's an accessible, strong
adventure story,'' Calderwood explains.
``A very few people have read it, but he felt it had something to say - it's
about the Covenanters, about sectarian divisions within Scotland and those are
the same problems we still have today.''
BBC Scotland is also hoping to adapt Irish novelist Patrick McGill's Children
of the Dead End, with a script by Bernard MacLavety.
``It's a story about Irish migrant workers coming to work in Scotland,''
Calderwood explains. ``I think it will have particular relevance here because
we tend to see ourselves as the people who tend to migrate and are treated as
underdogs. This is a story which turns the tables and says, `Well, this is how
Scots behaved as landowners and how they treated migrant workers at the turn of
the century'.''
An adaptation of Children of the Dead End would certainly combat the nagging
notion that it is only novels firmly couched in a bourgeois setting, with
plenty of opportunities to show off posh frocks, that get the nod when it comes
to television adaptations. There's no guarantee, however, that either of these
programmes will actually appear on the screen, as Calderwood admits.
``You have to ask is it a strong story and will it work for a television
audience and can it have a cast which people will have heard of? And, as the
projects we have are now in development, that's what I'm about to find out.''
Coincidentally, Michael Wearing is also looking to Scott for source material.
He is planning an adaptation of Ivanhoe for 1997.
``Ivanhoe trades on romance and action. Like Rob Roy or Braveheart, we're
talking about archetypal, semi-mythic characters which carry across
generations. It touches the fact that at that time society excluded the Jews,
or other elements of society, which is not so unfamiliar a story now.''
As the classic serial returns to television's centre stage, the opportunities
for adaptations that reflect life outside middle England will grow. And though
they have to survive in the Darwinian universe of television drama, short of
money and the recognition that attracts it, it would appear Scottish literature
will not be neglected. That's certainly what Andrea Calderwood is hoping for.
``Obviously, they've got to compete with other classics being developed in
England and in Ireland, but it's certainly possible.''
Time to put a kilt on costume drama
</TEXT>
