<HEADLINE>Family faces identity crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bertie Denham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974635030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRIME
n Dead Ringer, by John Francome, Headline, #14.99.
David Tredington returns unexpectedly to his home and family, having
disappeared at the age of 12. His father, Sir Mark, has no doubts about his
identity but his two sisters are less certain although prepared to give him the
benefit of the doubt - as is cousin, George, the next heir.
It is the beautiful Susan Buckley, his father's secretary, for whom David has
fallen, who is the only one to remain totally suspicious. The book opens in
October with David winning a race on one his father's horses, a success marred
by the death in a motor accident of a promising lad from Sir Mark's stables to
whom he was giving a lift home. Next follow two flashbacks - to September, when
he returned home, and to August, when he was first located and persuaded to
return by Sir Mark's godson - before moving on again to November where the
story moves towards its conclusion. Is he really David Tredington and, if not,
who? This is John Francome's best book so far.
n THE ISLAND OF THE DEAD, by Philip Hook, Hodder &amp; Stoughton, #15.99.
This is also the name of a picture by Arnold Brocklin - a cliff rising from the
sea, steps leading to a darkened doorway, a boat rowed by an ancient oarsman, a
sinister passenger swathed in white. A fictional second version of the picture
forms the focal point of the book. This oil-painting hanging in a gallery in
London is vandalised and the irrefutable perpetrator is Thomas Donat, a wartime
Hungarian refugee to the US, who is visiting this country.
At about the same time, a memorial service takes place in St James's,
Piccadilly, for Alexander Courtney, a leading art dealer, which Dominic
Maitland, an art journalist who has been commissioned to do an in-depth study
of Courtney, attends. He is also commissioned by his paper to do an article on
the vandalisation of The Island of the Dead, thereby bringing the two threads
of the tale together. The relationship between Thomas and Greta Kassak in
wartime Budapest and the present day are dovetailed skilfully together to make
a coherent whole. Philip Hook, a director of first Christie's and then
Sotheby's, contrives to make the world in which he lives and works a vividly
clear background for a suspense story.
n BETRAYAL, by Clare Francis, Heinemann, #12.99.
This is another first-class thriller. Written in the first person, hero Hugh
Wellesley's business has been taken over, his marriage seems doomed, his
mistress has been found dead and, by the end of the first chapter, the reader
is suffering every ounce of his despair coupled with apprehension.
The ``betrayal'' of the title runs throughout: in the business, which may just
be recovered by a management takeover; in the marriage, where his wife has
taken to hosting charity fund-raising events as a compensation for his frequent
absences on business; and with the mistress, Sylvia, a girlfriend from some 16
years earlier who has accidentally returned to his life and with whom he has
almost involuntarily begun an affair. This affair is complicated by the
revelation that her recent life has been one of drugs and promiscuity.
n TEN LORDS A-LEAPING, by Ruth Dudley Edwards, HarperCollins, #14.99.
This is in a far lighter vein than the other three, but no less enjoyable. Jack
Troutbeck, the Mistress of St Martha's College, Cambridge, has become a life
Baroness. A Bill to abolish foxhunting is being taken through the House of
Lords and Lady Troutbeck, with the aid of Bertie, Duke of Stormerod, and
others, has taken upon herself the task of blocking it. Nothing very unusual so
far, you may say. But the methods employed by both the supporters and opponents
of the Bill to achieve their ends, including among other things, mass murder,
add a distinctly Tom Sharpeian atmosphere.
BERTIE DENHAM
</TEXT>
