<HEADLINE>The bounty of a small country</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Doreen Taylor-Wilkie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635031</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER the release of the film Braveheart, the newly restored Wallace Monument,
perched high outside Stirling, trebled its figures in September to 30,000
people. There is no doubt movies like Braveheart and Rob Roy raise interest in
Scottish holidays.
There are more films to come too, with a new family story set at Loch Ness, to
be released in February. In addition to the monster, it stars Ted Danson as a
sceptical American scientist, and Joely Richardson, with a local lass as the
junior lead. The special effects for the monster are spectacular and should
send hundreds more to the area.
The Wallace Monument restoration was one of the benefits brought about by the
injection of public money under the Stirling Initiative, which has benefited
tourism along with other industries. Historic Scotland has already done much in
that most castle-like of castles, Stirling Castle, and this year saw the
completion of the Medieval Kitchens, which portray food and tableaux from the
past, and the opening of Marplace House, not far away, as the Cornerstone
Gallery.
In the spring, the Old Town Jail, once a detention barracks, will reopen its
ground floor as a Museum of Punishment and Crime. Following the principle of
keeping the Old Town as a place where local people live and work, the upper
storeys will be offices.
The Stirling Initiative has also made possible the re-cobbling of the Old
Town's Broad Street, and freed lower areas from cars, with a Heritage Tour Bus
in the season. This historic town, above the River Forth, is very popular for
weekend (or longer) breaks. Examples are: Stirling Castle Hotel, #55 per person
per night, D/B&amp;B; Forth Guest House: #24 person/night D/B&amp;B: two nights per
D/B&amp;B #75, plus Sunday free as long as dinner is taken. There are many more.
Information: Stirling Tourist Centre: 01786 475019.
Quite apart from the new film, Loch Ness and its monster and the area around
Inverness are always popular. Inverness Castle, above the River Ness that
divides the city, is the successor of many more militant fortresses. When it
closed its gates against Mary Queen of Scots in 1562, she recaptured it and
hanged the governor, whose ghost can still be seen in the vaults. The castle
esplanade holds a statue of Flora Macdonald.
It is only six miles or so to the start of Loch Ness, with the Loch Ness
Monster Exhibition Centre, at Drumnadrochit (01456 450 573). It is refreshingly
different from the usual ``themed'' centre in that it tells the history of the
search for the monster with some interesting scientific pictures. A very
popular spring and summer way to see the loch is by Jacobite Cruises, which
also sail into the Caledonian Canal (01463 241730).
As the Highland ``capital'', Inverness is the centre of a huge area, stretching
from John o' Groats to Cape Wrath and south to Fort Augustus. The Inverness
area alone offers Macbeth's Cawdor Castle (and gardens), said to be the place
where King Duncan met his end. Fort George, built against the Jacobites, now
holds the Regimental Museum of the Queen's Own Highlanders. Information: 0131
244 3101. Moniack Castle, along the inner firth, is home to a winery which
makes country wines from local sources, such as rowans and birch bark. Good
licensed restaurant. Information: 01463 831 283.
Again in 1996, the most celebrated place near Inverness will be Culloden, in
commemoration of the 250th anniversary of Bonnie Prince Charlie's ill-fated
attempt at the throne, which died on April 16, 1746, on this battlefield. The
great grave mounds show Culloden for the disaster it was and, despite a modern
audio-visual programme and a restaurant, there is always a sense of sorrow
about this peaceful place. Information: 01463 790 607.
In addition to this Jacobite anniversary, Scotland has several more in 1996.
One that should bring people from all over the world, as well as native Scots,
is the Burns International Festival to mark the bicentenary of the death of
Robert Burns, on July 21, 1796. The Festival was opened last September by the
Princess Royal, who unveiled a new statue of Burns by Alexander Stoddart, at
Kilmarnock Cross.
There will be hundreds of events - in places from Ayrshire's Alloway Kirk and
Souter Johnnie's Cottage to the Burns House and Monument in Dumfries, and much
wider. A National Burns Exhibition starts in Edinburgh, and Glasgow's Royal
Concert Hall will host the Burns Federation Concert, with a 500-strong Scottish
male-voice choir. A Tam O'Shanter summer spectacular will tour the country,
telling of Burns through song and dance, and include Son et Lumire.
Information: Burns Festival: 01292 288080. Accommodation: Ayrshire: 01292 2988
688; Dumfries: 01387 53862.
As usual, Glasgow will hold its annual Mayfest, the international arts festival
which has gone from strength to strength. There is also the Jazz Festival in
June. But Glasgow's main event for 1996 is the Glasgow Festival of Visual Arts
which, among other events, makes a feature of the work of Charles Rennie
Mackintosh. Starting in Glasgow (May 25 to September 30) it will move on to
three American cities: New York, Chicago, and Los Angeles. The Festival of
Visual Arts will have many other components, including a Festival of Design,
and a Visual Art Fair in George Square.
Glasgow regularly runs ``breaks packages'', including a series of Extra Special
Breaks for 1996, which covers accommodation, travel, and tickets to a major
festival. Information: Greater Glasgow Information Centre: 0141 221 0049.
In 1996, the Edinburgh International Festival reaches its 50th year, and this
will be a momentous occasion, with the Edinburgh Festival Theatre adding
greatly to the quality of the venues. The Tattoo continues to flourish and
attract many overseas visitors but I have always believed all Scots should make
a point of being on the Castle Esplanade every few years. In 1995, Edinburgh
opened a new Conference Centre, close to the five-star Sheraton Grand Hotel and
the Usher Hall.
In addition to a plethora of hotels and guest-houses, the city has long made a
feature of first-class bed and breakfast accommodation. One group, Welcome
Homes, had its birth in the Festival some 15 years ago, by matching guests to
carefully chosen host families, and has continued to grow. Almost all hotels
and guest-houses in Edinburgh have special Festival packages and Welcome Homes'
1996 Festival packages include tickets for festival events, plus a Tattoo
ticket. Information: Edinburgh International Festival: 0131 226 4001. Full
brochure ready end-March, preliminary now. Edinburgh Information Centre: 0131
557 1700. Welcome Homes: 0131 332 0410.
Scotland is synonymous with climbing and hill walking, Munros and mountains.
The great walking routes, the West Highland Way and the Southern Upland Way,
which often follow the old drove and hill roads, have added another dimension
to long-distance walking, with overnights in the small communities en route, or
mountain huts.
In addition to the various mountaineering clubs, several companies offer group
walking, often with leaders for the less experienced. H.F Holidays is a good
example. Started earlier this century in the North of England to get industrial
workers away from their dark satanic mills, the company has built up a series
of houses all over Britain (and overseas), and has some 600 leaders who, among
other places, walk and climb in many parts of Scotland.
Walks are usually graded into Low, Middle, and High Level, indicating
standards. One of the attractions is the social life of H.F evenings - very
much a house party. There are houses on Arran, and at Loch Leven and Pitlochry,
with transport to walks that range widely. More challenging routes are tackled
on summer weeks such as Ridges and Scrambles of Arran and the same for Glen
Coe, and Munro Bagging, and in winter, in hill-walking and mountaineering
weeks. Prices for seven nights are reasonable, from around #250-#300 depending
on the season, and there are shorter breaks. Brochure: 0181 905 9388. Sales:
0181 905 9558.
Golf rides even higher on the Scottish outdoor list, though wildlife and
watersports run it close. Two or three places immediately come to mind. St
Andrews claims to be ``the home of golf'', though East Lothian would certainly
dispute that. St Andrews' Old Course Hotel, which looks over the famous Old
Course, now also has its own Duke's Course, in a lovely parkland setting
overlooking the links.
The Duke's Course is championship standard, and the hotel offers packages and
golf holidays. From spring 1996, for golf fanatics there is a basic package for
#160, per person per night which includes table d'hote dinner, a course guide,
and a round of golf per day on the Duke's Course. The minimum is two nights
with two people sharing. For golfers and non-golfers, the Leisure Break starts
from #125 per night for Dinner B&amp;B, and guests use the hotel as a base for any
for St Andrews' famous courses, while non-golfers explore old St Andrews,
Scotland's oldest university, the thriving Byre Theatre, and other places in
Fife. Both can luxuriate in the hotel's excellent health spa. St Andrews has
many other hotels, inns and guest-houses with course tee-times. Information:
Old Course Hotel: 01334 47427. St Andrews Tourist Information Centre: 01334
72021, April-September. Tourist Board: 01334 74609.
Also world famous are courses from Ayrshire and the South-west such as Royal
Troon, founded in 1878, and Turnberry, a familiar sight on many a television
screen, to Royal Dornoch in the north (rated one of the world's top 10) and
Caithness, which claims to provide some of Europe's cheapest golf. Grampian
also boasts some of the best. The Royal Aberdeen has a club going back to the
eighteenth century. It is a links course only a few minutes from the cobbled
streets of Old Aberdeen.
One of Aberdeen's newest ``old'' hotels, the Marcliffe at Pitfodels, run by
Stewart and Sheila Spence, well known for their time in Deeside, now has strong
ties with Royal Aberdeen, with special tee-times and so on, and there are
several more courses within close range. The Marcliffe is just as popular for
fine cuisine, served in the Conservatory Restaurant which, weather permitting,
also has a patio. Grampian's famous hills, valleys, and coastline have a range
of accommodation at all prices. Information: Marcliffe: 01224 861 000. Aberdeen
Information Centre: 01224 632 727.
East Lothian boasts some 18 golf courses, including Muirfield, Gullane,
Aberlady, and North Berwick, which also has a new course above Tantallon
Castle. A good base is the town's Marine Hotel, where the manager, Alistair
Risk, is a keen golfer and can often be seen encouraging his younger guests on
the Children's Course just outside. The hotel organises its own competitions
and weeks, with a special golf holiday at the end of June each year, which
tries to cover as many East Lothian courses as possible, ending with a
competition. Throughout the year the hotel has many golfers, but for less
interested folk it is also right in North Berwick. The town is a great place
for sailing, and has exciting boat trips out to the Bass Rock to see the great
white patch, growing larger each year, that is thousands of breeding gannets.
