There is a curious part of the Scottish psyche that seems to think ``north''
when going on holiday in Scotland. This often means that the Borders, or
Galloway in the South-west, are not as well-known as they should be. Not many
of the Braveheart devotees, for example, realise that there is a huge Wallace
statue high above St Boswells, very close to Dryburgh Abbey, and within walking
distance of Dryburgh Abbey Hotel. It is an impressive piece but well-hidden by
tall trees. Both these regions make excellent walking areas, with the Southern
Upland Way striding some 220 miles from Portpatrick in the west and Eyemouth in
the east. Galloway has the south of Scotland's highest mountain, the Merrick,
only a few feet below Munro status. Mountain-biking is also popular in these
uplands.
Another curiously similar area much further north, the Grampian uplands,
north-west of Aberdeen, stretching up to the south side of the Moray Firth, is
also excellent for horse-riding and trekking, with some 10 centres in
communities such as Grantown, Tomintoul, and Lossiemouth. Elgin Tourist
Information Centre: 01345 542 666.
The Borders are full of history, and strife between England and Scotland, with
the warring Border families deep into cattle reiving. The colourful Border
Common Riding ceremonies of today were then a necessity. In those warring days,
Border burghs such as Selkirk, Hawick, and Lauder had to ride their marches to
ensure that no thieving landowner or marauding English band had annexed any of
the town lands. The tradition of horse-riding has continued today for pleasure,
and Kelso Racecourse, and the many point-to-point meetings, are well
patronised. Thirlestane Castle at Lauder also hosts the BHS Scottish
Championships over an August weekend, with dozens of horses tackling the
terrifying cross-country jumps.
The Borderland has some fine mansion houses, beside the Tweed near Kelso,
Mellerstain House, Border peel towers like Smaillholm. There are famous houses
such as Abbotsford, built by Sir Walter Scott, also by the Tweed, where his
descendants, Mrs Patricia and Miss Jean Maxwell-Scott, are frequently on hand
to welcome visitors.
The mild south-western climate makes Galloway's great gardens bloom abundantly,
from the wonderful display of rhododendrons at Castle Kennedy, close to
Stranraer, to the lovingly-tended gardens of Ardwell House on the Rhins
Peninsula, and nearby Logan Gardens, now in the care of Edinburgh's Royal
Botanic Garden, and many more. Both regions have the sea - the dramatic eastern
Berwickshire coast, great cliffs at St Abb's Head, and the gentler Solway
coast, which leads to Scotland's southernmost point, the Mull of Galloway, with
its towering lighthouse. Both regions offer many holiday packages in hotels and
guest houses, caravan and camping sites, and bed and breakfast accommodation is
first-class. Information: Borders Tourist Centre: 01835 863 435, Dumfries &amp;
Galloway: 01387 253862.
If Sir Hugh Fraser, who built the Aviemore Centre in the 1960s, could see the
Spey Valley now, he would be amazed at the transformation and the numbers of
visitors who come to Speyside all year round. So too would the pioneers of the
Cairngorm chairlift, who introduced many to skiing. Today they would see the
chairlift used year-round, the summer lifts packed with walkers, or visitors
going up to the restaurant and to admire the glorious view. From Dalwhinnie,
through Newtonmore, Boat of Garten Aviemore, Coylumbridge, Carrbridge, and the
rest, then on up to Inverness, the area is packed with things to do.
Many are connected with the outdoors - climbing, walking, fishing, mountain
biking, and pony trekking for a start. There are places such as Rothiemurchus
Highland Estate with falconry, ranger forest walks, fishing, and more. At the
Highland Wildlife Park at Kingussie, my pride of place goes to the wild cats
but, there are herds of deer and bison and also foxes and the rest. There is
energetic or easy walking and climbing (skiing in winter) in the peace of
Glenmore Forest Park, which takes in part of the Cairngorms, Glenmore Lodge and
Camping Park, and the Reindeer Centre is dedicated to Britain's only reindeer
herd, free-ranging out on the mountains, which can be visited with a guide.
Landmark, one of the earliest forest parks, today also has an emphasis on
Highland history, shared by the Highland Folk Museum at Kingussie. A
fascinating Heather Centre at Dalnain Bridge grows some 300 varieties, with
plants for sale and an interesting exhibition.
All these are only a taste, and in the Aviemore Centre itself, many of the
younger guests spend a lot of time go-karting. Between Aviemore and Boat of
Garten, the Strathspey Steam Railway makes an interesting contrast to the car,
with a lot of special trips. Information and accommodation: Aviemore &amp; Spey
Valley Information Centre 01479 810363.
I try to visit at least one Scottish island every year, sometimes a new one,
sometimes an old friend. This year I went to Coll and Tiree. Fascinating
islands, well out into the Atlantic yet relatively easy to reach by ferry from
Oban, or air from Glasgow. Tiree's long low stretches and its beaches are ideal
for birds and botany, cycling and golf.
But it is most interesting for the Skerryvore Lighthouse built by R L
Stevenson's uncle, Alan. Today the lighthouse's landward storehouse at Hynish,
plus the small harbour from which the builders travelled to the site, have all
been restored. It is now an ideal place to stay. Close by is Skerryvore Museum,
in the old signal tower.
Coll, only a few miles away by boat or ferry, is unusual in that its population
is growing. Here there are seals and Breadach Castle, the ancient seat of the
Coll Macleans, restored by Nicholas MacLean-Bristol and his wife, who founded
and run the Project Trust. In a specially-built house, the trust trains young
volunteers for work all over the world, a bit like VSO. At other times, the
house is available for paying visitors, and there are a couple of small hotels
and guest-houses. Coll's great asset is the corncrake, which owes its survival
to traditional agriculture, and croaks its way through the night. This may
produce a love-hate relationship with the locals but it brings birders galore
to the RSPB reserve, and there are seals and expeditions to smaller islands by
boat.
All along this western coast, with its inlets and peninsulas, islands and sea,
one is never far from water. Roads wind and have wonderful views and every
island is different. Arran has northern, mountain scenery in a southern
location. Islay has a famous golf course and hotel and six - or is it seven? -
distilleries. Every visitor is sure to want to try out Skye's new bridge in
1996; Gigha has great gardens; and Mull, with two castles and the Mull Little
Theatre, is close enough to Oban (an excellent base for Argyll too) to be busy
and bustling. It is also on the way to the Holy Isle of Iona with its abbey and
community.
Mull gave me my first sighting of an otter, sitting up on a rock eating a fish,
though that would have been a more likely first in Orkney or Shetland to the
north. For these are magnificent wildlife island groups, with many unexpected
offerings. But though I first went for birds and wildlife, I soon discovered
archaeology too, for both, perhaps Orkney in particular, have magnificent
sites, some 4000 years old such as Orkney's standing stones, the Ring of
Brodgar, and Maes Howetom. Jarlshof in Shetland stretches between the Bronze
Age and Viking times.
The Outer Hebrides are another world, but that does not mean a town like
Stornoway lacks a golf course or a swimming-pool and a busy social life. But in
Lewis, Harris, the Uists, Barra (where the thrill is landing on the beach by
air) and the rest, there is always a sense of being far north-west on the very
edge of Scotland and in a land of the Gaels.
No-one specialises more in Scottish islands than D A Study Tours, of Culross in
Fife. The tours are mostly led by a specialist in the area or subject, but
there are a few programmes for independent travellers. In 1996, D A Study Tours
will visit Lewis, Harris, Barra, and Vatersay in the Western Isles, Islay,
Jura, Colonsay, Gigha, Coll, and Tiree, and more further south. The holidays
usually last five or six days, travelling by coach and ferry, staying in hotels
and cost from around #230-#390 per person. The company also visits Orkney and
Shetland, as does the specialist firm, Island Holidays, whose 1996 programme
includes Natural History in Orkney, and a similar 10-day programme in Shetland.
Both are led by specialists. Prices range from around #645-#680, by air/coach.
Information: D A Tours: 01383 882 200. Island Holidays: 01764 670 107.
But many like their active holidays to be productive too, and want to work hard
when away whether it be digging or diking, roofing or raking.
Aching muscles, this school of thought claims, give a great sense of
achievement! Various organisations offer working holidays. The National Trust
for Scotland (NTS) runs Thistle Camps, working on restoration and environmental
projects throughout Scotland. For some 38 years, one very special NTS trip has
been to St Kilda, where volunteers are restoring many of the old cottages that
were deserted so long ago. Scottish Conservation Projects (SCP) is also busy
spring, summer and autumn, drystane diking in East Lothian and Orkney, tree
planting on Rum, controlling erosion on a Roman fort, and much more, Historic
Scotland's similar Action Breaks are also run by SCP, and all these
organisations ask visitors for a small sum towards their keep, very small in
the case of SCP - #5 a day. Information: SCP (also Historic Scotland work)
01786 479 697. NTS: 0131 226 5922.
Historic Scotland has a long list of properties in its charge, many of which
hold special events such as battle re-creations, next year strongly featuring
the 1745/6 Jacobite Rising. Historic Scotland offers seven and 14-day Scottish
Explorer tickets with free entry to 60 properties, including Edinburgh and
Stirling Castles and Fort George (#12 adult, with some concessions), which can
be bought at Historic Scotland Properties, and many tourists centres. Historic
Scotland events list: 0141 668 8686.
Quite apart from its numerous properties, (NTS members free entry) the National
Trust for Scotland has a selection of apartments and cottages in more than 30
places all over Scotland, from a small flat sleeping two in Gladstone's Land in
Edinburgh's Lawnmarket to Thrums Cottage at Kirriemuir, elegant castle flats in
Culzean and Brodick Castles and Castle Fraser to cottages in Threave Estate in
Galloway where the NTS runs beautiful gardens. This is self-catering and many
sleep four or six, while a house on the Isle of Canna can take 10. Prices are
reasonable. Brochure/Bookings, NTS: 0131 243 9331.
Though travel by car is essential for some places, anyone who has seen the
number of summer coaches on the Scottish roads is well aware that this is an
easy, comfortable option, and there are many tours within Scotland, often
starting in Edinburgh or Glasgow. For individual travel, ScotRail has a Freedom
of Scotland travel pass which gives unlimited travel on all scheduled ScotRail
and Strathclyde PTE trains, Glasgow's Underground, scheduled Caledonian
MacBrayne ferries on the Firth of Clyde and the Western Isles (except Raasay
and Scalpay), with Strathclyde PTE included and discounts on other ferry
services, bus and postbus. It even includes discount on entry fees to some
places to visit.
The Freedom of Scotland pass costs #99 for eight consecutive days, #110 for
eight from any 15 consecutive days, and #139 for 15 consecutive days. The more
limited ScotRail Rover (no ferry or bus concessions, some restriction on times)
costs #60 for four out of eight consecutive days, #88 for eight consecutive
days, and #115 for 12 out of 15 consecutive days. There are also Short Breaks
packages and Days Out by Rail. Information Sales: staffed ScotRail stations or
from rail-appointed travel agents, British Travel Centre, Regent Street,
London. Credit card sales and packages: 0800 450 450.
