I ONCE spent many rewarding hours in the company of a man whom I regarded as a
true West Coast Scot. His preferred mode of dress was a dark pea jacket, navy
wool rollneck sweater, and a flat cap to thwart the perpetual rain. The
nautical look was a backwash from his years in the Merchant Marine and in rich
men's yachts.
He lived in one of those organic, whitewashed crofts with which mid-Argyll is
dotted and which appear to be growing out of the rock. He could handle a small
boat in a gale as sweetly as a shepherd controls his dog.
Once, after a black night drift-netting in the Kilbrannan Sound, he took a
mackerel from the net, filleted it with a few deft flicks of his seaman's knife
and fried it with butter and salt and pepper before it had properly stopped
twitching. Served in a warm foc'sle with a mug of tea, it tasted heavenly.
I wonder what this courteous, contented, and unostentatiously knowledgeable man
would have made of the recent inhabitants of another whitewashed house on the
West Coast who have announced their presence with a glossy book of Vegan
recipes entitled Rainbows and Wellies, the Taigh Na Mara Cookbook.
Their bubbling enthusiasm is such that they must surely be incomers to the
small guest-house near Ullapool on Loch Broom, from whose menus they take the
evangelically anti-meat recipes.
Certainly one of them arrived, ``a casualty of the stressed-out 90s'', just
last year and it is difficult not to suspect a marketing background, given the
``Och Aye the Noo'' flavour of the names of their dishes.
Bonnie Prince Pudding, Sushi MacHoochie, Ceilidh Cassoulet, MacFungus
Croustard, Hector's Haggis Boats and Culloden Hearts . . . the list goes on,
excruciatingly.
They would doubtless be greeted with thigh-slapping glee by a southern English
coach party, as would the injuction in the first few pages to use the Orgasmic
Chocolate Mousse for sexual purposes.
I am sure the colonial tone of the text - ``the local boys are so good at
keeping our roads clear'' - is unintended. However, the laddish image on the
front cover - a picture of one of the owners standing in Loch Broom naked
except for a bunch of bananas - is straight from the culture of Men Behaving
Badly.
A ceilidh, we are informed, is ``generally perceived to mean a dance or
party''. In the book, ``lassies from Lewis'' ask for the porridge recipes. The
guest-house address is given as ``near Ullapool, Scottish Highlands''.
Many of the meals circumvent the limitations of vegan cooking with imagination
and flair and I can accept that they feel obliged to import tofu, oyster
mushrooms, and Japanese seaweed in favour of the traditional fare of the
district. However, it is difficult to ignore the feeling that they are just
delighted with themselves for indulging in a lifestyle adventure in such an
outlandish place.
Burton Anderson is a writer who has no qualms about exploring a different
culinary culture, in Pleasures of the Italian Table. He has lived in the
country for more than 20 years, writing about wine, food, and travel and has
approached his subject with respect, not to say reverence.
In this discreet and unillustrated volume, he dwells in depth on familiar foods
such a pizza napoletana, witnesses the ritual of pasta being shaped and cut
and, on a foggy morning in Alba, goes in search of the legendary white truffle
in the company of an experienced trifolau and his five dogs.
His style reminds me of the incomparable Margaret Visser and her great culinary
polemic Much Depends on Dinner. He talks in fascinating and informed detail,
adding dashes of history, economics, and politics to the mix, and listening
carefully to the wisdom of the ordinary people who have created extraordinary
food from the bounty of their immediate surroundings.
Junior Masterchef is a book designed to irretrievably dispirit parents with
couch-potato children whose most rigorous activity is changing the computer
game disk.
A spin-off from the highly successful Loyd Grossman TV series, it features
recipes from gifted adolescents who can not only produce dishes such as timbale
of trout and sole in a champagne sauce, but would no doubt dominate the
dinner-table conversation with unanswerable bons mots.
From the Scottish section, for instance, 14-year-old Ross Spence, from
Banchory, not only offers a recipe for chargrilled pave of gravadlax salmon but
lists his hobbies as fishing the Dee, collecting wine labels, and playing
croquet. One can only assume he will grow into burgers on the barbie like the
rest of us.
It was Shirley Conran who observed that ``life's too short to stuff a
mushroom'', and only the most relaxed of the leisured classes would spend their
afternoons creating the recipes in A Passion for Caviare, such as the spinach
parcels stuffed with lemon sole and Sevruga.
However, this beautifully produced and lovingly illustrated book is worth its
price for the little gems scattered throughout. Did you know - and buy yourself
a bottle of champagne if you did - that the Queens's Grill on the QE2 serves
15% of the world's consumption of Beluga? Or that in 1927 Cartier had in their
brochure a small gold ball on a chain for use as a caviare tester? Whenever
caviare was served you dropped the ball into it. If it sank, it was judged
acceptable, but if it stuck in the middle you sent it back.
Along with A Passion for Oysters from the same stable, which is lavish in its
praise of the famously creamy Islay oyster, these would make entertaining
birthday gifts, or simply treat yourself.
n Rainbows and Wellies, by Jackie Redding and Tony Weston (Findhorn Press,
#14.95).
n Pleasures of the Italian Table, by Burton Anderson (Penguin, #9.99).
n Junior Masterchef, foreword by Loyd Grossman (Vermillion #8.99).
n A Passion for Caviare, by Susie Boeckman and Natalie Rebeiz Nielsen (Mitchell
Beazley, #9.99).
n A Passion for Oysters, by Shirly Line (Mitchell Beazley, #9.99).
</TEXT>
