<HEADLINE>The Olympic Hopefull The Dolphin, ready to go to any lengths</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE word ``talent'' infers a volcano of ability, but it needs a support group.
The structure of the life of 14-year-old swimmer Steven Kidd is geared towards
allowing him the chance to reach his goal of Olympic Gold Medallist in the year
2000. His is a story of parental love versus the establishment.
Scotstoun Leisure Centre, run by Glasgow City Council, where Steven is coached,
where he does circuit training, boxercise, step aerobics, weights, and uses the
400m track, doesn't really merit a mention, because it didn't let our
photographer in to snap Steven in their pool for this article. The Herald is
not being churlish. We have it on authority that the Sunday Mail was once let
in, after all.
The fact that a young boy - while some others of his age all over the world are
staring at a computer screen, sniffing glue, drinking, taking their first
ecstasy tablet, or watching nine daily hours of TV - turns up to train in their
pool so that one day he will represent Scotland and Scottish sport, in a major,
international competition, seems to elude council officialdom.
It is commonsense that Steven needs all the publicity he can get. But while
phone-calls inquiring about centre facilities are answered, wires are crossed.
Boys and girls anxious for heros troop in and out the swish complex, already
converted to the benefits of health and competition, already familar with Nike
trainers, Linford Christie and McCoist.
But for Daniel and Isobel Kidd there would be more money to invest in Steven's
future if they stayed outside in their car. For Scotstoun Leisure Centre
contributes to the isolation the Kidds already feel by regularly charging them
admission money. The price of watching Steven in the pool is not much, around
35p per person, but it mounts up, day after day, year after year, decade after
decade.
``But there's no-one else to drive him,'' Isobel explains. The Kidds have no
choice but to be there. If Steven ever wins a Gold Olympic Medal, it will be a
credit to him and his family, not his country.
Steven, a member of the Scottish Junior Swimming Team, swims eight times a
week. He travels from the family home in Bo'ness to Scotstoun, 44 miles there,
and 44 miles back. During a normal day, Steven trains twice, getting up at
4.30am and arriving at the leisure centre at 5.30am. He trains until 7am, then
he's driven home to Bo'ness for 8am, gets his breakfast, and is at school for
9am. At 3.45pm he leaves straight from school to travel once again to Glasgow
for a training session which starts at 5pm and finishes at 7pm. His dad does
the driving, although his Grandpa helps out nights. Aren't you permanently
knackered? I ask Steven.
``It's me that's permanently knackered,'' says his dad. Daniel and Isobel Kidd
turn up at 5am in the morning, and hang around at the pool side for up to three
hours until their son has been coached. As taxpayers the Kidds feel that they
are already paying for the use of the leisure centre, but the council still
feel at liberty to make money from their support. What can you say? This
ignorance and parsimony is an example of a mediocre and lazy Scottish
mentality. A sports centre in Scotland thinks that it's OK to penalise the
parents of a boy who could, one day, be their worldwide and respected
representative.
But Steven is a fighter, and the more he has to face down the better he
becomes. He knows his parents are struggling to put him through his training.
He knows they have to find thousands of pounds per year, and they don't have
high-flying jobs; Isobel works in a hospital and Daniel is a contracts
supervisor.
``I've got an ambition to go the Olympics,'' he tells me. ``Your family have
got to pay for you, and it costs a lot of money to get there. It's hard for
them. They've got a life as well. I just know that it all pays off when you go
into a competition, when you win.''
Indeed. I counted 26 gold medals on Steven's CV, and seven new records. A rough
estimate of expenditure, based on information gleaned from Mr Kidd - ``#62 for
Darlington, #108 for Norway plus spending money, #12 per month coaching fees,
#3.50 a swim, #22 entry fees for each race, #67 for Dunoon training camp, daily
petrol . . .'' - comes to about five, six grand per year.
``Sponsorship in swimming is non-existent,'' he states. ``Steven got a couple
of hundred quid from a guy in Bo'ness who doesn't even know him. I got a phone
call last night from the coach, Steven's got to go to Lanzarote to a
warm-weather training camp, and needs #240 to go, just like that.''
Steven left Grangemouth and Cumbernauld for Scotstoun to be trained by an
Englishman and a New Zealander, because his dad believes that here the coaches
are the best. Coaches are only looking for someone who can do the business, who
can perform.
``There is no doubt that Steven will become a Scottish Senior
Internationalist.'' There aren't any swimmers in the family. Daniel raises his
eyes, mystified to where it has all come from. All he knows is that your
children are bound to you forever, that Steven has to continue training and
that he has to look out for him.
As a child, Steven was wildly energetic, but never a waterbasher, like other
swimmers. He has a liquid technique, he's a dolphin, but without his swimming
he has nothing. Daniel is determined for his son, but he's not the driving
force. You can't have starstruck parents when swimming champions are largely
ignored by the media. Steven knows that winning might bring him anonymity.
``Fraser Walker was second in the world championships. Ask anyone in the street
who Fraser Walker was and they wouldn't know.''
``We've got to pay it and get on with it,'' says Daniel. ``He's come too far
for us to say you'll need to stop swimming, we can't afford it. He can't just
stop. If they've got the talent you've got to give them the chance to do it.''
It really depends on your own state of grace, whether you feel a sense of
patriotism or disdain for a wee worker like Steven Kidd. His current best event
is the 200m backstroke. When I interviewed him, his time was 2.13.13, but it
will now be down to 2.10, if not better. Steven's times are consistent. It's
the only way to progress. Each new level is a platform to knock more seconds
off, and he knows how much time he must lose each year to earn a chance of
winning an Olympic Gold. He worked it out one night, when he was 12-years-old,
allowing for new and better records.
``You need a positive approach,'' says Daniel Kidd. ``If you do 2.13 and your
coach says I want 2.10 next week and you go, `I can't do that,' it's wrong.''
The problem with nature is that it takes its own course. Steven has a technique
which complements his bodyweight and five feet 10 inches of height. But he is
still growing, on a high-fibre diet of pasta, bread, and rice. He can only hope
that his comprehensive training outside the pool has indoctrinated his muscles,
and that he will ``bulk out'' in a beneficial way.
``My coach at Bo'ness said it was a natural technique that I had. Just now,
there are other boys in my age group who are much bigger and stronger than I am
and they are using strength. I haven't got as much strength, so I use technique
- that's what's getting me there.''
``Probably this year and the year after are going to be the most difficult time
for him,'' says his dad, ``to keep his interest in swimming, although he's
never lost any of that interest, and to progress to senior stage by fifteen or
sixteen, and the women, ken . . . ''. At this point Steven's dad bursts into
giggles.
Steven hasn't graduated yet to that male nadir where he begins to take girls
seriously. He is not yet at the mercy of women's hormones. His dad tells me he
thinks Steven's got a girlfriend. ``Ah huvnae!'' Steven insists, getting red
and annoyed. He thinks having a date is an insult, proof that he doesn't have
anything more important to do.
``What about that wee lassie who keeps following you about?'' his dad nudges.
Steven sighs deeply. ``We were at Darlington last week,'' Daniel continues,
``and he was at the hotel. I went down to see him and there were four girls in
the room with him.'' Well, the girls seem to think he's a safe bet. Young,
talented, fit. Yes, the boy's got a tribe of groupies already.
I don't think, however, that he'll go off on a wild spree. Steven's focused.
He's calm. He was the fastest in the junior championships in Leeds this year,
but not without some immediate trouble. A fellow competitor, the boy
representing England, took an emotional crisis on his block. Steven just turned
his back to him and beat him. He has sessions with a sports psychologist, but
he learned this tactic from watching Linford Christie.
``In his race in the Olympics, in the 100m, he usually looks down the track, he
was under pressure, and the guy next to him was looking at him. He just turned
and concentrated on his own race. The guy next to him was destroyed.'' Can
somebody throw you, Steven? ``They can't really, it just makes me more
determined.''
The use of a psychologist sounds ominous. Prodigies feel pressure. It's true.
``According to the coaches, this is him getting groomed for six or seven years'
time, when it comes to a major championship, so that his bottle doesn't go.''
Then, all the nurturing would be wasted.
But Steven believes that the hassle, the expense, and the time will pay off,
because he'll make sure it does. In the Olympic Year 2000, Steven will be 19,
but in 2004 he should be at his peak at 23. He doesn't yet know what his best
stroke will be then. It is unbearable for either Steven, his mum or dad or even
his little sister to think about what might happen if Daniel lost his job, or
Steven was permanently injured. When your whole existence revolves around one
purpose, you have a tenuous link with the idea of failure.
``David Wilkie hit the nail on the head. He said that money from the lottery is
being pumped into building fancy new pools. Glasgow will get three: Tollcross,
Bridgeton, and the Gorbals,'' says Daniel Kidd. ``But, as he reckoned, that's
not how you get Olympic swimmers, you need the sponsorship to take them
through. And companies only sponsor the finished article, the guy who's made
it, that's where the problem is.''
Linford Christie gets #50,000 for turning up for a race. Sponsors pay for their
logo to be paraded on the back of the man or woman to which the TV camera
always turns. Sponsors, unlike parents, will not take a chance on anyone's
future; even though, unlike parents, all they have to do is sign a cheque. But
Steven Kidd will prove the cynics and the fat cats wrong. I think he'll make
it, I think he'll get what he wants.
``You need self-motivation,'' he says, frankly. ``You have to want to do it, to
have that goal.'' But like Wilkie, he won't forget that he had to achieve on
behalf of his country, without its help.
``I'm hoping that when I'm older, I can help somebody else who's younger than
me, and share my experiences'' he says. Ironically, Scotland will not lose its
chance of stardom, because if Steven Kidd doesn't make it, he'll make sure
another Scottish talent does.
n If you or your company are interested in sponsoring Steven Kidd, or you would
like to make a donation, please call Mr Daniel Kidd on 01506 822766.
</TEXT>
