<HEADLINE>Fine and ban for ex-owner of castle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former owner of a haunted Scottish castle now relies on family and friends
to keep him going financially, a court heard yesterday.
Yorkshireman Ian McMillan, 51, used to own the 600-year-old Hallgreen Castle,
near Inverbervie, Kincardineshire, and held the title Baron of Brigfoord.
He and his wife spent thousands of pounds renovating the clifftop fortress and
he had planned to develop a #1.5m theme park there.
However, he ran into money difficulties earlier this year, was declared
bankrupt, and had his assets sequestrated.
Stonehaven Sheriff Court heard yesterday that McMillan now lived in Hull and
was reliant on friends to keep him going.
He admitted a charge of driving a hired car without proper insurance.
The court was told he had not realised the insurance was only in his wife's
name.
The offence happened in May this year, near the entrance to his former castle
home.
His defence solicitor, Mr Dennis Daun, said McMillan had asked his wife if he
was covered to drive the car and she had told him he was.
Mr Daun added: ``He was sequestrated in this court earlier this year and his
financial circumstances are fairly strained, to say the least.
``He now lives in Hull and is relying entirely on friends and family for
assistance and support.
``He is endeavouring to seek work and his best efforts to find employment may
lie abroad,'' said Mr Daun.
Sheriff Robert McCallum fined McMillan, of Ferry Lane, Hull, #150 and banned
him from driving for six months.
Hallgreen Castle is home to a series of ghosts, including green ladies,
mediaeval serving-wenches, and murdered children.
It was put on the market earlier this year for #250,000 pounds - the same as a
traditional granite house in Aberdeen, 25 miles away, would be expected to
fetch.
</TEXT>
