<HEADLINE>Mikki  Doyle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIKKI DOYLE, the fiesty former women's editor of the Morning Star, communist
and fighter for women's liberation, died this month aged 79, after a long
illness.
At a ceremony at Putney Crematorium attended by the Marchioness of Lothian and
Ken Gill, former general secretary of MSF, her friends recalled the memory of
an extraordinary woman. Although she was only ``5ft-nothing'' in her stockinged
feet she had a hea
rt as big as her native New York where she met and married her Glasgow-born
soulmate Charlie Doyle who passed away in 1983.
Always refreshingly candid with a wicked sense of humour the chain-smoking
Mikki could hold court for hours over drinks with such amazing tales, they
could have provided the stuff of novels.
Born Miriam Levental to East European parents in the lower east side of
Manhattan in 1916, her communist politics were forged at an early age -
initially by her first husband, an English communist sailor, but essentially by
her experiences surviving the d
epression.
She was renowned for taking her two children on the campaign trail,
demonstrating her support for the Spanish Republic and fighting the judicial
murder of the Rosenbergs.
She met Charlie in 1949 after a second failed marriage. It was just months
after she had lost an eye at a Paul Robeson concert in Peekskill, New York,
when a gang of drunken racists pelted the crowd with stones.
Mikki was forced to marry Charlie by proxy as he was detained awaiting
deportation to Britain during the McCarthyite purges. He was a vice-president
of the Gas, Coke and Chemical Workers Union and member of the US Communist
Party.
Mikki's account of their exile sounds like a scene from Casablanca. Separated
by the full length of the ship and two burly FBI agents, wee Charlie was only
freed from his handcuffs when they reached international waters.
Typical of her mischievous sense of humour was her response to the strange
request by the US Communist Party for all members to record a list of their
personal relationships.
Rumoured to have been initiated by covert FBI agents, who many believed
outnumbered the real membership of the CPUSA during the cold war, Charlie
adamantly refused to comply.
Not so Mikki. ``I wrote down the name of every male I knew and then some. If I
was to be painted a red harlot, they might as well put me down for f****** them
all.''
In another spectacular confrontation, this time on British television, the
normally trouser-wearing Mikki upstaged the usually ostentatious Barbara
Cartland by tarting herself up in a shocking pink outfit.
On her arrival in Britain in 1953 Mikki became a factory worker and then a
successful copywriter in advertising before spending a short time working for
the Cuban Embassy and then going on to join the Morning Star in 1967.
Charlie went on to become shop stewart in the electricians union and was dubbed
by the Daily Mirror during a strike as the ``most dangerous man in Britain''.
Always ready to put the cat among the pigeons Mikki helped to transform the
Morning Star's women's page into a lively feminist forum and was instrumental
in shaping the emerging women's movement of the 1970s.
She was a founder member of Women in Media, was an active anti-racist
campaigner and was the only Morning Star journalist ever to be invited to
appear on What The Papers Say.
Affectionately dubbed Lady Doyle because of her friendship with the Marchioness
of Lothian, Mikki first met her when she was asked to address a Woman of the
Year luncheon to raise money for the Greater London Fund for the Blind.
When she retired from the Morning Star in 1985, the former editor Tony Chater
praised her contribution to working class politics, saying: ``Mikki is not
retiring, she's just slowing down.''
Mikki never let the side down. Despite having countless operations against
cancer she continued to inspire many younger comrades with her revolutionary
enthusiasm.
</TEXT>
