<HEADLINE>Shura Cherkassky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cherkassky: showy and often deliberately wayward.
Shura Cherkassky, pianist; born Odessa, October 7, 1911, died London, December
27, 1995
WITH the death of Ukranian-born pianist Shura Cherkassky at the age of 84, one
of the final links with a great romantic tradition is severed.
Utterly wilful, completely eccentric, and frequently bizarre in his playing
style, Cherkassky sustained his career into old age, celebrating his eightieth
birthday with an international tour. Audiences loved him, purists detested his
waywardness, and crit
ics wandered away from his concerts shell-shocked by his indifference to
convention.
In an age when pianists are churned out by conservatoires, schooled in the
disciplines of absolute correctness and the sublimation of individual whim,
Cherkassky was almost a direct link with an earlier age, when
personality-pianism ruled, high-velocity v
irtuosity triumphed, and the pianistic pyrotechnician was the first genuine
international superstar.
Born in Odessa, and trained initially by his mother, a piano teacher,
Cherkassky emigrated to the United States with his family in 1922. A child
prodigy, he made his debut that year, aged 11, in Baltimore.
His first real contact with the great nineteenth-century tradition came when he
played for the pianist-composer Rachmaninov, who saw the young Cherkassky's
potential, but said he would teach him only if he agreed not to play in public
for two years.
Cherkassky, impatient for the limelight, instead went directly to the Polish
pianist Josef Hofmann, one of the lions of late nineteenth-century pianism,
then teaching at the Curtis Institute at Philadelphia. Hoffman took the
opposite view to Rachmaninov,
saying that Cherkassky must give recitals immediately, accepted him as a
student, and began indoctrinating the youngster into the great romantic
tradition.
By the age of 16, Cherkassky had embarked on his first international tour, a
practice that was to become the habit and passion of a lifetime. From 1945,
when he made his first, extensive, and acclaimed tour of Europe he began a
ceaseless circuit of intern
ational touring that he attacked with a rare relish and that was to last almost
half a century until his death.
He became famed for his exuberant performances of the great romantic piano
concertos of Tchaikovsky, Rachmaninov, Chopin, Liszt, and Schumann. Unlike many
others, he never eschewed new developments, tirelessly absorbing new
compositions by composers as av
ant-garde as Berio and Stockhausen.
The dapper little pianist was famed - and notorious - for his complex and
ambiguous behaviour. In his preparation and practice he was meticulous and
prissy. But only to a degree - four hours a day precisely he practised; not a
minute more or less.
Every year he abandoned his strict regime for two months, when he would travel
somewhere hot and, in his own words: ``Lie in the blazing sun doing nothing
until my fingers are stiff like iron.''
His eccentric inflexibility and obsessiveness with detail spilled into his
personal life. He would insist on two copies of the programme for each of his
concerts being placed on the table in the artist's dressing room. And, at
another extreme, he would sp
ecify the number of sheets of toilet paper to be made available in the
dressing-room lavatory.
Not surprisingly, with such bizarre behaviour, his one marriage was
short-lived. He admitted himself that the reason for his wife divorcing him was
``mental cruelty''.
Following the break-up of his marriage, he lived with his mother in Nice, until
her death in 1961. Thereafter, he moved to London and - for the last 17 years
of his life - lived in a cluttered hotel room at The White House in Regent's
Park, surrounded by
his books, clothes, and CDs and the airline timetable which was, he said, his
bible.
Despite all of Cherkassky
's obsessiveness with precision - and he confessed freely that he was extremely
difficult to tolerate - when he played, he would be showy and often
deliberately wayward. ``I must admit,'' he once said, ``that I will always play
how I feel on the spur of t
he moment.''
He drove conductors and orchestras mad by rehearsing a work in a particular
way, then, without warning, going off in a completely different direction
during the performance. Though many found this an endearing and rather romantic
trait, it could be comple
tely ruinous to a performance.
At his last appearances in Scotland, three years ago, when he toured with the
BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, Cherkassky, as neat and dapper a figure as
ever, went totally off the rails.
Playing Gershwin's Piano Concerto he introduced an unwritten rhythm section by
stamping his feet throughout, and in a completely unpredictable version of
Beethoven's Emperor Concerto, defying any known convention of style, he at once
reinvented the piece
and repeatedly charged ahead, leaving the conductor and orchestra miles behind
and racing to catch up.
As ever, despite leaving a technical shambles in his wake, the charming little
shocker secured a rapturous reception from his audiences. More anarchist than
romantic, Cherkassky left his mark wherever he played.
</TEXT>
