<HEADLINE>Briton dies before sex abuse trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels, Friday
A BRITISH former church minister accused of publishing international guides for
child molesters has died before standing trial in Belgium.
John Stamford, 56, was scheduled to answer charges brought by children's rights
groups alleging that he provided information on child prostitutes to
paedophiles around the world.
Belgian media and sources involved in the case said Stamford died on Wednesday
of a heart attack in hospital near his home in northern Belgium.
``His death will probably mean the end of all judicial action. We regret it
because we wanted to make an example of him,'' said Bernard Boeton of Land of
Mankind, one of the groups pressing charges.
Stamford, a former Sunday school teacher from St Helens on Merseyside, denied
child sex charges and claimed to be the victim of an anti-homosexual campaign.
News reports claim that the former policeman's son ran an organisation that
dispatched paedophile information to more than 25,000 customers.
He allegedly recommended that clients visit Third World countries where
children could be ``hired'' for a can of Coke.
Prosecutors say Stamford used a homosexual travel guide called Spartacus as a
front for a mailing service offering information on child prostitution in
Thailand, Brazil, the Philippines, and other nations. In April, a court in
Turnhout ruled that he shoul
d face a jury on charges of offending public morals and publicising sexual
exploitation.-AP.
</TEXT>
