<TEXT>
THE final steps on the road to Superbowl XXX will be initiated this weekend as
the NFL's post-season play-offs get under way with the first round of the
knock-out stages.
Wild-card teams Miami Dolphins, Indianapolis Colts, San Diego Chargers, Detroit
Lions, Atlanta Falcons, NFC Central champions Green Bay Packers and AFC East
conquerors Buffalo Bills will battle to fill four berths among the last eight
in next weekend's di
visional play-off games.
Up for grabs for the AFC teams is a divisional play-off visit to either
Pittsburgh Steelers or Kansas City Chiefs, while the NFC survivors will face a
trip to either Dallas Cowboys or San Francisco 49ers, who all received byes to
the divisional stage due
to their superior regular season records.
The Dolphins, more used to the tropical climes of sunny Florida, travel to
freezing Buffalo today to take on the Bills in a rivalry as bitter as the
weather in up-State New York.
Led by record-breaking quarterback Dan Marino, Miami are playing for more than
a trip to the Superbowl in Arizona. Unbelievably, after 25 years in charge,
head coach Don Shula's previously unassailable position is under threat.
In the NFC a battle of running backs will ensue when Philadelphia Eagles and
their ground attack specialist Ricky Watters host resurgent Detroit Lions, who
boast one of the NFL's most potent rushing threats in Barry Sanders.
NFL play-offs round 1 fixtures;
Today: AFC - Miami Dolphins at Buffalo Bills (KO 5pm GMT); NFC - Detroit Lions
at Philadelphia Eagles (9pm GMT).
Tomorrow: NFC - Atlanta Falcons at Green Bay Packers (5pm GMT); AFC -
Indianapolis Colts at San Diego Chargers (9pm GMT).
STEVE LIVINGSTONE
</TEXT>
