<HEADLINE>Archibald Gillespie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Archibald Gillespie, director of finance, Strathclyde Regional Council; born
September 4, 1935, died December 25, 1995
WITH the death of Archie Gillespie on Christmas Day, I have lost a trusted
friend as well as a director of finance. The relationship between a committee
chair and director has to be special, with respect and trust on both sides. I
worked closely with Arch
ie for the past eight years, and we certainly had that kind of relationship.
He was a wise counsellor, always there to give a considered response whenever
it was asked for. When he felt strongly about something he would stick to his
own view, as the Scottish Office and Secretary of State - and members of his
own council - have fou
nd to their cost.
He was never an easy touch, and was noted for his tenacity and his integrity.
Last year, when discussing the problems of capping with Ian Lang and Allan
Stewart, he pointed out that the only way to make savings was redundancies -
``and that won't save mon
ey, but cost us more''.
A big man in every way, Archie had worked his way up from Greenock Corporation
through Bute County Council to Strathclyde, where he controlled a budget of
over #3bn, more than that of many independent states.
Although he served his apprenticeship in the private sector (with Ritchie and
Holmes in Greenock), he was one of the old-style council officials who firmly
believed in public services and their need to be funded properly.
As the director responsible for the collection of local taxes, he had no doubt
about the duty of citizens to pay their way. He was constantly concerned about
collection of rates, and the effect the Poll Tax had on public attitudes to the
payment of local
taxes.
He had, however, the knack of switching off when he left the office, and
enjoying life with his family, or on the golf course. One of his great passions
was Greenock Morton: just a few days ago he was discussing the team's progress
with me, and expressing
his doubts about how the Dutch-style football they were playing could
withstand the Scottish weather. He loved football, and enjoyed nothing more
than going to Cappielow, watching the game, then heading to the golf club with
friends.
He was quite a wit. When we had to take some difficult decisions on collection
of poll tax by arresting student grants, he ended a stormy meeting with the
remark: ``That's it gone, my chance of being elected rector of one of our
universities!''
I'd known Archie since I came to the council in 1982. At that time I lived in
Gourock, where he was an elder of the Kirk and a well known figure in
Inverclyde district. He very much enjoyed his appointments as a commissioner
for the Public Works Loans Boa
rd, and treasurer for Loch Lomond Park.
We had all hoped that he would enter retirement and have the chance to give
more of his special talents to the wider community. This was not to be, and our
hearts go out to his widow, Alice, and the children, Linda, Christina, Duncan
and Kenny.
n.Appreciation by Councillor JOHN MULLIN, chair, finance committee, Strathclyde
Regional Council.
</TEXT>
