<HEADLINE>Resolutions to boost your family's financial health</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gillian Barton</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635117</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILLIONS of us are busy making resolutions at this time of the year, but how
many of us ever turn words into actions? Well, that all depends on whether
you're a shaker, a breaker, a maker or a faker, according to some New Year
research by IFA Promotion.
Shakers make really bold decisions, but the proposed changes are so dramatic
they fail to do anything at all. The solution? Set realistic goals - the more
manageable your New Year resolutions the better your chances of achieving them.
Breakers believe that if one bad habit vanishes, the rest will soon follow -
but they tend to give up after a few days or weeks. The solution? Try to break
only one bad habit at a time - and note when and where you slip back into your
old ways.
Makers are most likely to stick to their guns. They plan well and focus on
greater personal, professional and financial achievements - don't you just hate
them!
Fakers, meanwhile, produce the longest list of resolutions, but keep them for
the shortest time. The solution? Make just one realistic resolution that will
improve your life or help those around you.
In the aftermath of Christmas many people will be looking for ways to increase
their income, cut back on expenditure or simply make financial life easier for
themselves and their families. So here are a handful of ideas that may help to
make your 1996 mor
e prosperous.
n Switching your bank account could save you as much as #100 a year and give
you a better level of service. Top accolades in a recent Which? magazine survey
of customer satisfaction went to the Royal Bank of Scotland and First Direct.
Many of us don't switch banks because we think they are all the same - not true
- and that there's a lot of work involved. But many banks have special
switchers' packs to ease the move, so get cracking.
n Thousands of people move home each year, leaving millions of pounds behind -
not hidden under the floorboards, but left in savings accounts, premium bonds,
insurance companies and other investments.
Without an up-to-date address dividends cannot be sent, Ernie cannot pay out
premium bond prizes and the proceeds of insurance policies remain in the
companies' coffers. Building society savers who don't pass on their new address
can't be told about impen
ding takeovers either and may miss out on valuable free shares or cash bonuses.
So it's time to sort through all your policies, passbooks and investment papers
and make sure every organisation which has some of your money knows where you
are.
n Could there be a long lost pension waiting for you somewhere? If you worked
for an employer many years ago and left behind benefits in a scheme now is the
time to track them down. The company may have changed its name, moved or been
taken over, but the
Pension Schemes Registry can help to find where your benefits are now.
Write to the Registry at PO Box 1NN, Newcastle upon Tyne, NE99 1NN. You'll be
sent a form to fill in and asked to give as much information as possible about
your old scheme and employer. With luck it will be able to come up with an
address where you can w
rite to collect your pension from long ago.
n More pension cash could be waiting for anyone who has been employed in the
construction industry since 1982. If you were directly employed in the industry
and received ``holiday stamps'', get in touch with the Building and Civil
Engineering Benefit Sche
mes (B&amp;CE). You could be in line for the tax-free lump sum paid out to workers
when they retire at age 65. To be eligible you need to have had 80 weeks of
service between April 1982 and your retirement date.
To find out if you might qualify phone B&amp;CE for the cost of a local call on
0345 414142 - the lines re-open for claims on Wednesday, January 3.
n If you took out term insurance in 1990-91, you could cut your premiums by a
third by switching to another company. Premiums for term life insurance peaked
in 1991 as the insurance industry agonised over the potential effects of Aids.
But premiums have c
ome down again in recent months and you can benefit from cuts by cancelling
your old policy and starting a new one.
A word of warning - don't opt out of your existing policy until you've been
accepted by a new company. Also, make sure the new one gives as good or better
cover.
Term insurance simply guarantees to pay a fixed amount if you die within the
term of the policy - say, between five and 25 years. There is no surrender
value, which is why you may have nothing to lose by cashing in and starting
another plan. Don't try the
same trick with investment-type policies such as endowments though as there
are big financial penalties if you stop these early.
n Consider using the savings you make to add critical illness cover to your
range of insurance. Traditional policies pay up when you die. But you might not
have heard of the newer critical illness cover. This gives you and your family
a lump sum as soon a
s a serious medical problem is diagnosed. This could be used to pay off a
mortgage, provide specialist nursing care - or even to fund a round-the-world
trip if, like thousands of people each year, you recover.
Serious illnesses covered include most cancers, heart attacks, strokes,
multiple sclerosis, Alzheimers, kidney failure and heart bypass surgery. The
typical cost for a 40-year-old man of buying #50,000 of critical illness cover
would be just in excess of
#20 a month. But before you take out a policy, always seek expert advice from
an independent financial adviser.
</TEXT>
