<HEADLINE>Border moves to replace Bragg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BORDER Television chief executive James Graham will also assume the role of
chairman, following the decision by South Bank Show producer and editor Melvyn
Bragg to relinquish the position.
When it was announced at the beginning of this month that Mr Bragg was to step
down as chairman at Easter but remain a non-executive director, finance
director Peter Brownlow did not anticipate that the appointment of a new
chairman would be considered un
til the Carlisle-based company's next board meeting in early February.
However, Border has obviously decided to move swiftly to appoint a successor to
Mr Bragg from within. No-one at the company was available for comment yesterday.
Concrete sale
CONSTRUCTION firm Costain has sold its concrete products business to Tarmac for
#3.6m. Under the terms of the sale, Costain will retain the company and a small
number of projects which are completed or near completion. It will also retain
and recover the
book debts of the business. Work in progress and debtors retained are estimated
to be worth #8.5m. Tarmac will assume the trade creditors of the business which
amount to around #6.9m.
Name change
NORTH West Water is changing its name to United Utilities from January 1,
following its recent takeover of the Norweb regional electricity company.
Timber profits
TIMBER manufacturer Allan Brothers of Berwick has announced record profits for
the past year of #1m, compared with a #750,000 surplus the previous year and a
deficit in 1993 of #250,000, before being taken over by the John Carr Group.
Cash flows
ROYAL Bank of Scotland experienced its busiest day for cash withdrawals on the
Friday before Christmas, with more than #26m taken out by customers. It
believes its Cashline network will notch up a new monthly record during
December, with withdrawals expec
ted to exceed #400m.
</TEXT>
