<DOCNO>GH951230-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>English even steal our wind-ups</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I SEE Dean Richards got a wee award in the honours list. Well done, Dean, and
shiver my fibrillating left ventricle, but you deserve it old boy.
You know, it's about now that I should enter into my hate-the-English mode and
start to slag them off and call them all manner of things, but entirely in
keeping with the spirit of Christmas and forgiveness, ever in touch with the
sentiments of a New Year
, I just can't do it. Not this year any how.
The English wear a white jersey, which is a sure-fire sign of the purity of
their lovely country. Their system of law and order has been copied all over
the world for its fairness and simplicity.
Gary Lineker is English, as is Frank Bruno. I actually like the English as a
race. As a wee boy in Malaya, I was surrounded by lots of little English lads
and I quickly learned that beating them on the rugby pitch was a good way to
annoy them, and it didn
't matter that these rugby games were the only way to let rubber planters' boys
living in a boarding school on the top of an island off the coast of Penang let
off steam, because we all loved it. What the heck, these were my friends.
Take Brian Moore, for instance. The only reason he has a pathological hatred of
Scots is that he has an even bigger inferiority complex than us north of the
Border. The boy acts like a Scotsman in that he is so flaming blinkered and
one-eyed that we are i
nsanely jealous that he's capable of doing unto us what we have done to the
English for decades now - wind us up.
What a cheek he has to use our tactics, which often include talking utter
nonsense to inflame a situation, to annoy us. Take it from me that we have no
viable historical reason to despise them so, because it's years since they came
over the hills in John
Jeffrey's neck of the woods and took all the sheep for their own purposes.
You must have that hate of a neighbour to make it really work, of course, and
it suits us fine, doesn't it? Not only is their dammed country bigger but
they're richer and healthier as a race. Their rugby team is better.
So's the football side, which is miles better, actually. The Queen lives there
and only rarely visits Holyrood Palace.
So you have to pity the English. There they sit, in the sunnier bit of our
island system, looking wearily north at a bunch of miscreants. Yes, we Scots,
who are out to cause trouble and complain until the world ends. We mump if they
beat us, we gloat like
ignorant little children if we duff them, and we talk all the time about
wanting to be a separate country.
Perhaps it's got to a stage in our relationship with our big cousins south of
the Border for us to re-think what we do. The off-field battle is as important,
remember, as the on-field one.
Could it be that our years of niggling away at the English, calling them this
name and then that, have turned events full circle so that the pressure is now
on us? Is Brian Moore and his hate of the Scots a sign that we have lost the
tactical high ground?
Is it a coincidence that Dean Richards gets a wee award and no Scotsman does?
Is it now time to try to understand our persecuted neighbours?
Look at it from their point of view. No-one in the world likes the English, and
therefore, what must it be like for them to have their nearest neighbours
against them instead of acting in support?
I have a novel solution. Let us make it our New Year's resolution to like the
English, and admire them. For they are indeed admirable. Look, I'm only joking.
I hate them too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
