<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The eighties' hangover that's bound to cheer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS you await the bells to ring in the new year tomorrow night and you reflect
on what 1996 might bring, just consider this. We are officially living in the
country with the most dynamic economy in Europe. I am not going to predict the
creation of more job
s, continuing strong exports, higher disposable incomes, rising capital
expenditure, lower interest rates and higher growth. The independent
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development has done that already.
However, you might ponder the fact that of Europe's elite top ten companies,
four are British. This is more than any other country, the Swiss being next
with three, poor old Germany with only two, and the Netherlands with one.
If you think that is a quirk how about this? Of the 25 best-performing shares
in Europe, an astonishing 15 are for British companies. (The French,
incidentally, don't figure in either grouping although they do have five major
firms with the worst performi
ng shares in Europe.)
Okay, but what does that mean in translation? Well, if Pierre, Jose or Hans
want to salt away some cash in anticipation of the proverbial rainy day, they
will be looking no further than UK stocks. And as many of the high performers
are in the financial se
ctor this is splendid news for Scotland.
If that's the case, you may ask, then why don't you feel good? You will. All
these indicators point in that direction. Your job should be safer. The housing
market should finally pick up. And you should certainly have more cash in your
pocket. After one o
f the worst recessions in modern times this will be some achievement.
The reason why Britain has emerged as leader of the pack is thanks to that most
remarkable of decades, the eighties, which is to be the subject of a major
documentary series on the BBC beginning next month.
I feel it is still too soon to stand back and fully appreciate what happened in
these years and what the long-term effects will be, but the period has been so
traduced a pre-emptive strike is needed.
There have been attempts to dismiss it as the ``me'' or the ``greedy'' decade.
In fact, the eighties was the most important decade for Britain this century.
It represented a watershed when Britain finally shrugged off a near century of
decline, buried the
``British disease'' of the sixties and seventies which had made us the Sick
Man of Europe, and instilled a self-confidence not seen since the days of
Victoria. So revolutionary was it that it radically transformed the political
landscape and, ironically,
the biggest beneficiaries have been Tony Blair and New Labour.
Mrs Thatcher stirred up so many extreme emotions, idolatry or hatred, that the
message of the eighties has often been confused with the messenger. It has
always amused me that socialists speak highly of Lord Home, the product of a
privileged class which p
resided so long over the genteel decay of Britain, but disparagingly of a
clever grocer's daughter who strove to reverse it. Yet it was Mrs Thatcher who
attempted to create a classless Britain by assaulting the cosy Oxbridge liberal
establishment and the
closed shops in medicine, law and the civil service.
The ``yuppy'' in the City and Essex Man in the gentrified villages of southern
England was indeed vulgar with ostentatious spending habits, flashy cars and
brash attitudes, but these were invariably the aspirational sons and daughters
of working class fam
ilies, the very people Labour used to tell us were the salt of the earth.
Mrs Thatcher failed to permanently change attitudes - it was not possible to do
so in the space of only 10 years. What she did achieve, however, was the
systematic burial of the trade unions and the birth of privatisation, both have
invigorated the econom
y. The tradeunions had been living on borrowed time. One of the best books this
year was Correlli Barnett's The Lost Victory, which examined why Britain
underperformed economically after the war. Among the fascinating wealth of
detail are the passages con
cerning the trades unions who put themselves first even when the nation was
fighting for its survival. ``The particular symptoms of the British disease
which was to become so notorious are bluntly documented in the war years of the
1940s by field investig
ations into various industries and tabulated in strike charts kept by the
Ministry of Labour and National Service,'' he writes.
``More working days were lost through strikes every year from 1942 to 1945 than
in 1938, the last full year of peacetime. Coal was far and away the worst
offender with no fewer than 1.2m man-days and 2m tons of coal lost in the first
quarter of 1944 alone
. Usually a coal strike was about wages which really meant a miner's place in
the industrial pecking order. But one local strike during the Normandy invasion
year of 1944, costing 1000 tons of production, took place simply because the
miners wanted to get
rid of the canteen lady.''
Mr Barnett also records how ``who does what'' disputes and stoppages abounded
in the shipyards at the very time Britian stood in desperate danger of losing
the Battle of the Atlantic for want of new warships and merchant vessels to
replace those sunk by t
he U-boats. He notes that the ``unrelenting pursuit of such absurdities were
worthy of the weird land of nonsense visited by Gulliver.''
Politicians of both parties tolerated this for 30 more years before Mrs
Thatcher in the eighties swept away the Lilliputian fantasy and at the same
time severed the cords of nationalisation which bound so much of British
industry. Apart from the error of
joining the ERM, which aggravated the effects of the recession, this new-found
industrial and labour flexibility set the pattern for Europe and catapulted
former state firms like BT into the forefront of private European companies.
It is for these reasons, rather than the ephemera of the ``loadsamoney''
culture that Britain is now in pole position. Happy new year.
</TEXT>
