<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French teenager's naked body is found in lay-by</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MISSING French teenager Celine Figard has been found dead in a lay-by.
Police confirmed last night that a naked body found by a motorist near
Worcester at lunchtime was that of the 19-year-old student, who vanished 10
days ago from a motorway service area near the M4 at Chieveley in Berkshire.
She was formally identified by her 24-year-old cousin Jean-Marc Figard, who had
travelled from a hotel in the New Forest where he works as head waiter.
Celine had been on her way to spend Christmas with him when she disappeared.
Home Office pathologist Dr Peter Ackland carried out a post-mortem examination
in Worcester yesterday afternoon but the cause of death has not been released.
It is understood there were no major injuries on the body of teenager.
Police forces throughout Britain had been on the alert for Celine, who was last
seen apparently getting a lift from the ginger-haired driver of a white
Mercedes lorry cab at the Granada Service Station on the A34, near Newbury.
She hitched her way from her home on a farm in the village of
Ferrieres-Les-Scey, south east of Paris, by lorry as travel was difficult in
France because of numerous strikes.
A nationwide manhunt is under way in a bid to track down the mystery driver,
who is said to be aged 30 to 35 and with a ginger chin-strap beard.
Celine's body was discovered at lunchtime yesterday when a motorist stopped to
examine a faulty windscreen wiper near the hamlet of Hadley.
As he stepped from his car he looked over the fence of the lay-by and spotted
the naked body lying in a dip of land close to the fence, but sheltered by a
small copse.
Officers from Hampshire Police drove Celine's cousin to the West Mercia Police
headquarters at Hindlip Hall, near Worcester.
Earlier this week her farmer father Bernard made an emotional appeal on British
television for the safe return of his daughter.
.q.THE 19-year-old victim of a savage attack vowed yesterday that it would not
ruin her life.
Ms Louise Laight was set upon after becoming separated from friends during a
Christmas Eve night out in Chester-le-Street, County Durham.
Her dress was torn off, she was dragged through a garden, suffering deep
scratches from thorn bushes, and punches to her face left her with two black
eyes and a cut lip.
As detectives hunted her attacker, Louise said: ``I wanted to come forward in
public to show that I have nothing to be ashamed of and that I will not let
this incident ruin my life.
``The attack has not just left me physically hurt, but has left me with mental
scars as well.
``I had been looking forward to Christmas and never dreamed anything like this
could happen to me in a place I knew so well.
Louise, who urged anyone who could help police catch the man responsible to
contact them, said she could remember very little about the incident.
``It has made me very nervous about going out, and I know for sure it will take
me a long time to put this fully behind me.''
Detective Inspector Neil Redhead, leading the inquiry, said: ``This assault
left me sickened and was one of the worst of its kind I've come across.
``Obviously, with New Year's Eve coming up, I am concerned that the man who did
this remains at large.
``The last thing I want to do is to scare people, but it is a fact there will
be lots of young people out and about in Chester-le-Street trying to have a
good time just as Louise was last Sunday.''
He urged the man's friends, particularly those with him outside the Red Lion
pub last Sunday night, ``to examine their consciences''.
</TEXT>
