<HEADLINE>Apologist for troubled times</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN BOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A USER'S GUIDE TO THE MILLENNIUM: Essays and Reviews
J G Ballard
HarperCollins, #18
THE 1984 novel by J G Ballard, Empire of the Sun - the book of the film by
Steven Spielberg - has an obvious pun in the title. Empire of the Sun depicts
the world as seen by Jim, son of English immigrants to Shanghai.
A son with Anglo-Saxon attitudes to the Chinese inhabitants of Shanghai is
forever altered by the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941 as he ends up in
a civilian prison camp. Sunny Jim is transformed into a son of several empires
- English, American,
Japanese, Chinese. He has sympathy for them all.
He honours the English, hopes for help from the Americans, admires the audacity
of the Japanese, sadly stares at the bodies of dead Chinese soldiers: ``In the
trenches between the burial mounds hundreds of dead soldiers sat side by side
with their heads a
gainst the torn earth, as if they had fallen asleep together in a deep dream of
war.''
As a writer of fiction - including the science fiction that first made his name
as a writer - Ballard spreads his sympathies like Jim. In this collection of
his essays and reviews, Ballard is as sunny as Jim. Sympathetic to one and all.
Born in Shanghai G
eneral Hospital in 1930, Jim Ballard was impressed when Japanese forces invaded
China in 1937. As he explains in an essay in autobiography: ``As I moved
through the checkpoints I was even more drawn to the Japanese soldiers.
``Many were ruthlessly brutal to the Chinese farmers and rickshaw coolies (yet)
I knew that the Japanese soldiers were brave, and I hoped the British tommies
would never have to fight them. But the Japanese had a strain of melancholy
that I admired, a qua
lity not much in evidence among the party-going Europeans and Americans whom my
parents knew.''
After Pearl Harbor he was placed in Lunghua Camp, to the south of Shanghai, and
(astonishingly) enjoyed the experience: ``Once the 2000 internees had settled
in, life in Lunghua was dominated by the overheated summers and freezing
winters, by stench, nois
e, and boredom. I was enthralled.''
He played games with Japanese prison guards, and continued to look on Lunghua
as his real home when liberated and sent back to Shanghai. As a famous writer
he returned to Lunghua in 1992 and knew ``this was where I had been happiest
and most at home, desp
ite being a prisoner living under the threat of an early death''. Being nice is
second nature to Ballard.
As a reviewer he manages to be nice even when he is inclined to be nasty.
Discussing Richard Schickel's biography of Marlon Brando (1991), Ballard begins
by ridiculing the actor as one who trivialised his talent by agreeing to appear
in poor films for ric
h fees. Then he pays tribute to Brando on account of his performance in Last
Tango in Paris - ``in no sense a pornographic film, but a stunning portrait of
male middle-aged despair, in which he wrote a large part of his own dialogue''.
So, after all, Bran
do is a great actor for Ballard who is, above all, a fan.
A fan of Elvis, despite the great entertainer's decline into overeating and
drug-addiction. Reviewing Albert Goldman's autobiography
character-assassination of Elvis in 1981, Ballard begins by repeating all the
vicious rumours about a man who allegedly be
came a maniac. Yet, Ballard observes, Elvis was ``an enormous talent, and an
influence on popular culture greater than that of any other musical performer
of this century''. Ballard believes a man should be judged on his best work,
not his worst.
He has a good word for Mao as one who enabled millions of Chinese to express
emotion. A good word for Hirohito as an emperor determined to save what was
left of Japan after the dropping of the A-bombs. A good word for Hitler as a
man at the mercy of his o
wn ignorance: ``Hitler was one of the rightful inheritors of the twentieth
century - the epitome of the half-educated man''. Similarly, Charles Manson and
Gary Gilmore are observed as fascinating figures, given ``the remarkable
talents these rootless and
half-educated men (manifested) for manipulating the mass media''. So much
nonsense in the name of entertaining copy.
The title essay of this collection has Ballard waxing lyrical on his favourite
sci-fi films, again making the nasty sound nice. Alien (1979), a truly
repulsive and gratuitously violent movie, is enthusiastically admired as ``an
extremely elegant s-f film'
'. How anyone can see this stomach-churning spectacle as elegant is beyond
belief unless you believe, with Ballard, in moral relativism.
Ballard mentions moral relativism in a review of 1993 of two books on Einstein.
Rejecting criticisms of Einstein as a genius who also managed to be a jerk -
rumours of a visit to a Berlin brothel, speculation that he had sired a number
of illegitimate chi
ldren - Ballard writes that ``none of these revelations lessens one's
respect''. In a world of moral relativism, behaving badly means nothing
compared to the fame of the name noticed by Ballard.
As Ballard, for all his fame as a name in the world of science fiction,
confesses he has never understood what Einstein was on about intellectually,
let me enlighten him by boldly breaking into verse on the subject of Einstein's
Special Theory of Relativity:
According to Einstein
There's no still centre of the
universe:
Everything is moving
Relative to something else.
My love, I move myself towards you,
Measure my motion
In relation to yours.
According to Einstein
The mass of a moving body
Exceeds its mass
When standing still.
My love, in moving
Through you
I feel my mass increase.
According to Einstein
The length of a moving body
Diminishes
As speed increases.
My love, after accelerating
Inside you
I spectacularly shrink.
According to Einstein
Time slows down
As we approach
The speed of light.
My love, as we approach
The speed of light
Time is standing still.
I prefer the moving relativity of Einstein to the moral relativism of Ballard
but appreciate the latter as a fine aphorist (``the great appeal of alcoholism
. . . is that it provides an opportunity for honourable and even heroic
failure'') and one of the
finest apologists for his troubled time. Relatively speaking.
</TEXT>
