<HEADLINE>Saving the world More and more investors are putting their money where their conscience is</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Clay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ETHICAL investment may sound a bit dull. And the concept of ``going green'' was
dismissed by some fund managers as irrelevant to investing when it emerged in
the UK 11 years ago. But ethically run investment funds are now reckoned to add
up to an impressi
ve #1000m or thereabouts.
Clearly the concept has caught the imagination of a sizeable number of
investors, even if #1000m is only a tiny fraction of total investment values
and an even smaller percentage of overall funds than in the US.
Conscience and money, which have seldom been obvious partners, have managed to
produce some pretty good results. The 1995 stock market year, for instance,
ended with an impressive flourish for shares in a number of the ``baby bio''
companies working to di
scover cures for a range of problems from cancer downwards as investors placed
bets on hopes of profitable breakthroughs.
Savers can now choose from 30 funds concentrating on the broad field of social,
health or environmentally friendly concepts. One of the most successful at the
moment is the Framlington Health Unit Trust. This has been run by Antony
Milford since it was st
arted in 1987 and in the last five years has quadrupled investors' capital.
The fund is still a small one, adding up to approximately #15m. Much of the
growth came this year - its 1994 low point was 114.5p but it ended 1995 more
than 100p higher.
Although run within ethical guidelines, it is more specialised than most funds
of this type, which can mean it can be more volatile. Its stated aim is to seek
capital growth through investment in health care and medical services and
product companies worl
dwide. Investment includes pharmaceutical and biotechnology firms, which are in
great favour with investors at the moment, and more than three-quarters of its
money is invested in the US with the UK coming second.
Friends Provident, which was the first to launch an ethical fund - its
Stewardship Unit Trust - in the UK back in 1984, claims around half of the UK
funds under management. But it is now mounting a campaign to convert more
investors.
``Investment in the care market is increasing and we think there is great
potential,'' a spokesman says. ``People are becoming much more aware. This was
shown when people sold Shell shares when the company refused to pull out of
Nigeria after the executio
ns there. But we do need to sell the concept and show that investment does give
long-term performance. Ethical investment is a success story waiting to be
discovered.''
The Stewardship life and pension funds have, in fact, out-performed a fair
number of non-ethical rivals. The company says that a recent survey showed that
four out of five people had not heard about ethical investment but ``millions
would consider investi
ng in such funds if they knew about them''. As many as 60% of those questioned
said that they would prefer to invest in a unit trust that was run on ethical
lines.
The company maintains financial advisors should ask people about their ethical
concerns when discussing their financial needs. Otherwise pacifists might find
themselves investing in companies involved in the arms trade, non-smokers in
tobacco companies, a
nd vegetarians in factory farming.
When ethical investment started it was mainly based on negatives - the funds
avoided companies involved in certain activities and also shunned countries
such as South Africa during the apartheid regime.
Now the ethical funds are increasingly adopting positive criteria and looking
for companies making a helpful contribution to the environment, involved in
medical research or aiding development of the Third World. Funds which once
banned South Africa might
now be keen on supporting it.
The CIS Environ Trust run by a subsidiary of the Co-operative Insurance
Society, for example, says it ``aims to provide capital growth by investing in
the shares of companies which are active in improving the environment, human
health and safety''.
Launched in 1990 it has more than doubled investors' money in five years and in
one performance table using Micropal figures features as second after
Framlington Health. Others with gains of more than 80% in the five years
include Eagle Star Environmental
, Credit Swisse Fellowship, Abbey Ethical, Friends Provident Stewardship and
TSB Environmental.
A large number of companies in the FTSE-100 share index would fail for one
reason or another to qualify for inclusion in an ethical fund. They are usually
so big and diverse that a subsidiary somewhere could well be doing something
that breaches the ``rul
es''.
Looking further, it is estimated that some 60% of the companies in the
All-Share index would also be ruled out. When it launched its first fund
Friends Provident argued that this could be a good thing for investors as it
meant fund managers, having a much
more restricted list of approved investments, would have to research each
company more thoroughly than might otherwise be the case.
This may or may not be a valid point, but it is clear most of the companies
qualifying for consideration are medium or small ones. That usually means their
share prices will be more volatile than those of the giants, but as a trade off
for that they can g
row a lot faster than the really big ones.
Deciding whether a company is ``ethical'' or not is often carried out with the
help of research from EIRIS - the Ethical Investment Research Service. Each
fund has its own criteria and many use EIRIS research to decide whether or not
a company meets them.
EIRIS (0171 735 1351) does not itself give investment advice but individual
investors can buy research material from it to do their own screening. It will
also supply a list of independent financial advisors able to give specialist
advice on ethical inves
ting.
December has seen the Mid-250 index of ``second line'' companies hit a new
record, and with many pundits predicting that 1996 will be another positive
year, ``going green'' should be good for the pocket as well as the conscience -
at least for a while.
</TEXT>
