<HEADLINE>`Top ten' decide on a softly, softly approach.  Wrangle over Europe remains informal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S top 10 are seeking a special meeting of all clubs in membership of
the Scottish Rugby Union so that the issue of clubs or districts in next
season's European Cup tournament can be more fully aired.
The request, which was due to be discussed at the SRU general committee last
night, follows a meeting of the clubs on Thursday in Edinburgh. The SRU
declared that a decision on whether or not to accede would be made within the
next few days.
It also emerged at yesterday's Murrayfield press briefing that the union's
preferred route is for European participation by three recognised district
sides and not by ``hybrid'' teams - a concept which has also been under
discussion. Which sides will be d
ecided soon, with performances over the past four or five seasons taken into
account.
``The Top Ten,'' as this latest grouping of clubs is now known, had the option
to call for an extraordinary meeting of the union, at which the six in favour
of club participation in Europe - Melrose, Stirling County, Boroughmuir,
Watsonians, Edinburgh Aca
demicals and Currie - could have put their case, but it has been decided to
request a more informal meeting of all clubs.
Top ten spokesman Ronnie Smith, vice-president of Boroughmuir, said yesterday:
``We have the six clubs necessary for an extraordinary meeting but feel this
way is less confrontational. We are trying to keep it informal rather than
become involved in the l
egal niceties that an extraordinary general meeting would entail.''
The pro-clubs lobby envisage a meeting which would hear presentations from the
SRU which would put the case for districts, and from those in favour of clubs.
There would then be a three-week truce during which club representatives would
return to their co
mmittees for further discussion before returning to a second meeting at which a
vote could be taken.
The Top Ten representatives have also asked the SRU to provide details of the
European Cup rules of participation so that they are in a better position to
fine-tune their counter proposals.
Yesterday, SRU senior vice-president Fred McLeod said that this latest round of
talks had been conducted in a positive manner, and he had been able to say that
players and the clubs which supplied them to the district sides which the SRU
want to compete w
ould receive around 70 per cent of the European Cup revenue.
``We have endeavoured to provide a sensible package with a view to keeping the
best players in Scotland,'' he said.
The position regarding participation of the Exiles was still unresolved, he
added, largely because of potential problems with club contracts but this was a
matter for ongoing discussion.
q GLASGOW make three changes to the side which lost 23-5 to the South last
weekend for tomorrow's inter-district championship game against Edinburgh at
Murrayfield.
Kenny Logan, Stewart MacGregor, and Gordon Doran come into the side for Gus
Turner, John Gibson, and Brian Robertson. Logan, chosen to play against the
South, withdrew because of flu. Gibson and Robertson are unavailable, allowing
district debuts for MacG
regor and Doran.
The only change to the Edinburgh side which defeated the South 31-30 is in the
pack where Edinburgh Academicals' Scott Murray is unavailable because of
gastro-enteritis. He is replaced by clubmate Malcolm McVie.
Tomorrow's game is scheduled to take place on the international pitch at
Murrayfield thanks to the under-soil heating, but because of the severity of
the weather, inspections will be held today and tomorrow morning. The
Murrayfield switchboard (0131 346 5
000) will be manned tomorrow between 10am and 1pm. Teams:
Glasgow - G Breckenridge (GHK); T Mathewson (Glasgow Acads), A Garry
(Watsonians), I C Jardine, K M Logan (Stirling County); C MacGregor (Glasgow
Acads), C Little (GHK); S MacGregor (Glasgow Acads), G Bulloch (West of
Scotland), G Doran (Glasgow Acads), G
Perrett (West of Scotland), M Norval (Stirling County), F D Wallace
(Boroughmuir), G Mackay (Stirling County), I Sinclair (Watsonians).
Replacements - A Turner, C Sangster (Stirling County), F Stott (West of
Scotland), D McVey (Ayr), D Jamieson (West of Scotland), C Docherty (GHK).
Edinburgh - C Simmers (Edinburgh Academicals); F Henderson, S Hastings (both
Watsonians), D Wyllie, N Penny (Stewart's-Melville); A Donaldson (Currie), G
Burns (Stewart's-Melville); G Wilson (Boroughmuir), G McKelvie (Watsonians), P
Wright, D Burns (both
Boroughmuir), M McVie (Edinburgh Acads), B Ward (Currie), S Reid (Boroughmuir),
R Hoole (Edinburgh Acads).
Replacements - R McNulty (Stewart's-Melville), G Ellis (Currie), C Mather
(Watsonians), G Beveridge, D Laird (both Boroughmuir), S Lang (Heriot's FP).
