<HEADLINE>Women get cab priority</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAB drivers in Clydebank have introduced a fast response scheme to help make
the streets safer for female passengers.
Companies will give priority to women walking alone and others considered to be
in a vulnerable situation. The scheme is a joint initiative involving the
district council.
Open order
THE Army has done an about turn on plans to close a recruitment office in
Dumbarton. It will remain open for a trial period to help with the Army's
efforts to fill thousands of posts.
Ringing changes
THE service by switchboard operators at Dumbarton District Council offices is
to be extended for an extra 45 minutes every day in a bid to be more user
friendly.
Not playing fair
YOUNG soccer fan Ben Sutton saw red when his team turned up all white on the
night. When 11-year-old Ben opened up Sega's top-selling FIFA '96 computer
game, something seemed wrong. Then he realised that star black players like
John Barnes and Les Ferdina
nd had been turned white overnight. A spokesman for makers, Electronic Arts,
said: ``We are limited on the number of colours we can use for this one, so
teams have to be entirely white or black.
Rape charge
GLENROTHES men Robert McDowall, 29, of Marmion Drive, and David Gibb, 29, of
Alyth Court, yesterday were accused of rape. During a brief private appearance
at Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court, they made no plea or declaration and were released
on bail.
Chime and again
DISC jockey Ronnie Barbour is going to be sick of Auld Lang Syne by next week .
. . for his Talk Radio UK show is going to tune in to New Year celebrations
eight times around the world. Ronnie, from Ayrshire, will hear the midnight
chimes from eight diffe
rent countries across the time zones on Sunday night and Monday morning.
Thief detained
CAR thief Andrew Murphy, 19, was sentenced to two years detention yesterday
when he appeared at Edinburgh Sheriff Court. He had earlier admitted stealing
nine cars in Edinburgh in August and September. Murphy also admitted driving
while disqualified and w
ithout insurance and committing all the offences while on bail. He was also
banned from driving for 10 years.
His number's up
FLAMBOYANT hotelier Ian Ashton will be buried in Howden-le-Wear, County Durham,
next week - with the personal number plates from his Jaguar screwed to his
coffin. Ian Ashton's family is determined his passing will not end the humour
and goodwill for which
he was noted during his life.
</TEXT>
