<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stand on drugs attacked.  Legal action `excessive'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635128</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S senior judge and a chief constable have been accused of being
infected by a ``frenzy'' over drugs cases.
SCOLAG, the magazine of the Scottish Legal Action Group, has lambasted the
approach of ``hammering'' otherwise law-abiding people with the criminal law.
An editorial in the latest edition of the magazine describes the 18-month
sentence recently imposed on advocate's wife Rosalind Henderson for cultivating
cannabis as ``plainly excessive''.
SCOLAG says: ``We seem to be in the midst of another flare-up in the `war
against drugs' which has been waged with varying degrees of ferocity for nearly
30 years. It is a war which all experience shows cannot be won . . .
``Yet otherwise clever and rational people seem to be gripped with a kind of
frenzy.
``Thus Chief Constable (Ian) Oliver of Grampian region confesses his police
force alone cannot win the local war and he tries to have employers co-opted by
law to fight it for him.
``He wants health and safety law amended to force employers to impose random
urine tests for forbidden substances so as to provide evidence for their
dismissal.''
SCOLAG argues that employers are already familiar with the problem of employees
turning up unfit for work because of the abuse of alcohol and need no extra
powers to discipline or sack such people.
It adds: ``Clare Short, the Shadow Transport Secretary, is made, ignominiously,
to recant by her outraged party leader, after merely suggesting that
consideration be given to the legalisation of cannabis.
``Regrettably, the Scottish law system's leader, Lord Hope, who has been
responsible for several enlightened legal reforms, seems to have been infected
by this frenzy.''
SCOLAG refers to the Henderson case in which Lord Hope, Lord Justice General,
upheld an 18-month sentence for ``cultivating 13 cannabis plants in a locked
room in her remote farmhouse''.
In that case, Lord Hope said: ``Whatever views others may take about the
purpose and nature of the production of cannabis, the fact remains that it is
an offence which has been laid down by Parliament as punishable by a sentence
of imprisonment.''
SCOLAG argues, however, that with the exception of the mandatory life sentence
for murder, Parliament does not insist on judges imposing any particular
sentence but relies on them to select a sentence appropriate to the unique
circumstances of the case.
It points to a case in which the High Court decided that a sentence of 12
months was excessive where a first offender had cultivated cannabis for his own
use. The court substituted a sentence of six months.
``Not only is the 18-month sentence of Rosalind Henderson plainly excessive in
relation to that one, it looks positively oppressive when compared with the
three years imposed by the High Court in Aberdeen on two young men who stamped
and kicked a father t
o death.''
SCOLAG sees a ``minor ray of hope'' in the approach taken by Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth to deaths at raves caused by taking ecstasy.
``He proposes to make it a condition of licensing the premises that water and
cooling facilities be available.
``A better approach than hammering otherwise law-abiding people with the
criminal law is to ask what exactly are the harms that we seek to avert when we
control certain substances and frame measures that focus on removing these
harms.''
</TEXT>
