<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tighter electricity controls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OFFER, the electricity industry regulator, has published proposals for the
financial ring-fencing of electricity businesses within enlarged groups after a
spate of takeovers in the industry. This will provide reassurance for consumers
worried about the po
ssibility of higher bills following the change of ownership.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, director-general of Offer, said he proposed to
modify the licences of South Western Electricity (SWEB) and Eastern Group. This
follows their takeover by the US utility firm Southern Electric International
and the Anglo-Ameri
can conglomerate Hanson, respectively. The regulator first issued proposed
amendments to electricity firms' licences in July after Southern Company's bid
for SWEB.
Southern and Hanson have already agreed to Offer's proposals which deal with
financial ring-fencing of the electricity businesses, restrictions on
activities, availability of resources and disposal of assets.
Offer's statement said that the modifications will be applied to other merged
companies in due course. Chester-based Manweb was taken over by ScottishPower
in October and North West Water has acquired Norweb.
During the bid North West Water said that the regulated water and wastewater
businesses of North West Water and the regulated electricity businesses of
Norweb would remain separate subsidiaries of the enlarged group.
Two other bids, Powergen's for Midlands Electricity and National Power's for
Southern Electric, have been referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
by president of the Board of Trade Ian Lang.
``The merged companies will continue to have to meet their existing obligations
under the Electricity Act and licences,'' said Professor Littlechild. He added
that the additional licence modifications would allow him to regulate
effectively and to ensure
that customers continue to be fully protected.
Offer's announcement may deter other potential bidders such as the Texan
utility company Houston Industries.
</TEXT>
