<HEADLINE>Second `fat gene' found</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635131</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS in the US say they are a step closer to developing a drug for fat
people after discovering the second half of the signalling system that tells
the brain when the body has had enough to eat.
In today's issue of the journal Cell, scientists said finding a receptor on the
surface of brain cells could lead to medication that would alter how the
signals of no longer being hungry are received.
The researchers from Millenium Pharmaceuticals, based in Cambridge,
Massachusetts, in collaboration with other pharmaceutical laboratories and
academic centres, have been seeking the receptor gene since the discovery last
year of the first important obesi
ty gene, called OB, and the leptin protein it produces.
Dr Robert Tepper, author of the paper published today, said a drug to treat
obesity was probably years away but that the new finding ``will jump-start
research at Millennium and elsewhere''.
The scientists say that while leptin is what sends the satiety message to the
brain, it is not a lack of the hormone that causes obesity. On the contrary,
most obese humans have higher levels of leptin.
The problem, the Millennium team theorises, may be that obese people are
resistant to the message because of a deficiency in the leptin receptors or in
the pathway leptin takes to the brain, Dr Tepper said.
Scientists hope to bypass that resistance via drugs.
``It's of course an important breakthrough and it's exciting when specific
genes in a certain trait are identified,'' said cell biologist Dr Jeanne
Lawrence. ``People who have problems with weight are often looked down upon by
people who don't, but they'r
e struggling under a different set of conditions that nature has handed
out.''-AP.
</TEXT>
