<HEADLINE>Challenge mounted to feudal law.  Absentee landlord thwarts property sale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHALLENGE is to be mounted in Parliament against a ``ludicrous anachronism''
in feudal Scottish property law.
The move by Ross, Cromarty, and Skye MP Charles Kennedy was prompted when an
absentee landlord based in Kent pre-empted the sale of a cottage to a local
villager in Cromarty.
Ferro Cottage, on an estate belonging to retired investment adviser Michael
Nightingale, 68, had been on the market for almost three years.
Mr Nightingale stepped in and bought the cottage only after forester John
McIver, 56, struck a cut-price deal with the vendor, the local baker.
To exercise his right of pre-emption which goes with the Black Isle estate, Mr
Nightingale simply matched the agreed price.
Landlords used to be able to exercise this right whenever they chose but under
a reform introduced by the Heath Government in the early 1970s, the right
expires if it is not used once a property comes on the market.
Mr Kennedy now wants such ``archaic privileges swept away completely''.
``I have already written to Lord James Douglas Hamilton on this question of
pre-emption because another landlord in my constituency was doing much the same
as seems to have happened in Cromarty,'' Mr Kennedy said.
``He didn't give me much hope of reform. But following the news from the Black
Isle, I will be pressing him on this matter and I will be raising it with the
Law Commission. It also strikes me that our beefed-up Grand Committee would be
an excellent place
to discuss this.
``Such rights have more to do with the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries than
they do with trying to keep people in our rural communities in the last decade
of the twentieth century. Quite simply, they have no place in a modern
democratic society.''
Mr McIver said last night: ``It is all so very unfair but I understand that is
the way he works. The property was on the market for almost three years and he
never showed the slightest interest until my deal was under way.
``I am just waiting to see how much I will lose out on legal fees. It is a
bargain buy for Mr Nightingale. He must have saved almost #20,000 on the
original sale price.''
Speaking from his Kent home last night, Mr Nightingale said he was unwilling to
comment.
``I have had no contact from the community council as yet, so I cannot talk
about something I don't know about,'' Mr Nightingale said.
It is not the first time Mr Nightingale has caused controversy in the village
by exercising his feudal rights. About seven years ago, he acquired Cromarty
Lighthouse from Northern Lighthouse Board, although several local families were
interested.
Cromarty Community Council chairman Gordon Hogg now warns that an ambitious
project to seek Millenium Foundation funding for development of the harbour
area may be prejudiced because of Mr Nightingale's actions.
The project, Cromarty 2000, was to have included Aberdeen University's Dolphin
Research Laboratory, which is situated in the lighthouse. However, Mr Hogg and
the council decided it would be unwise to include the lighthouse given the
level of local discont
ent.
As a result, Aberdeen University will have to make a separate application.
Mr Hogg said: ``There is no doubt the Cromarty 2000 plans would have been much
stronger as a package of three proposals: the harbour, the visitor centre, and
Cromarty Lighthouse. The package as a whole could total more than #3m, and it
would be a tragedy
if this ruined our chances of securing such a major boost for the village's
economy.
``We have no argument with Aberdeen University. They will be able to apply
separately. But public opinion bars us from including their scheme. There is no
way we could justify our part in securing a quarter of a million pounds for a
property on Mr Nightin
gale's estate after what he has done.''
</TEXT>
