<HEADLINE>Charles Fletcher</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635133</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Charles Fletcher, physician and TV personality; born June 5, l9ll; died
December l5, l995
IT is difficult today to comprehend how much consternation and opposition there
was among members of the medical profession when Charles Fletcher presented the
television series Your Life In Their Hands, a step in opening up the closed
door of medicine to
the public and patients. Perhaps only a physician as distinguished as Fletcher
could have made such a success of this courageous venture.
Fletcher, who has died aged 84, was educated at Eton and Trinity College,
Cambridge, and studied medicine at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London. He was
involved in the early investigation of penicillin and gave the first injection
to a patient, at the Ra
dcliffe Infirmary in Oxford.
He had knowledge of medicine on both sides of the profession, having been
diagnosed as a diabetic, which rendered him ineligible for military service.
This in itself may well have shaped his subsequent career and his interest in
bringing medicine and trea
tment into people's homes.
Fletcher, whose subject for his doctorate was gastroenteritis, switched
direction, being appointed by the Medical Research Council to the directorship
of its Pneumoconiosis Unit in South Wales, an inspired choice for a dedicated
physician. With an equally
dedicated team, the work on lung disease in coal miners became internationally
recognised.
In l952 Fletcher returned to London, to the Department of Medicine at the Royal
Postgraduate Medical School in Hammersmith, to continue his research into
respiratory disease. Again with MRC support he built up a team to study chronic
bronchitis, with the
emphasis on the risks of smoking, air pollution, and respiratory infections.
Fletcher received many honours in his life of medical research, including being
appointed CBE, but probably his lasting memorial will be the TV series which
ensured medicine would never again be a book almost closed to all but a
privileged profession.
</TEXT>
