<DOCNO>GH951230-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Addict mother faces baby bar</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635134</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SALINAS: A judge in California has ordered a mother convicted of manslaughter
in the deaths of three children to have no more babies while still a drug
addict or face 11 years in prison. Gelenda Bosley, 25, slept in a drug stupor
while seven children in h
er care played with matches and set fire to a dry Christmas tree. Her
five-year-old son died in the blaze.
Judge John Phillips jailed Bosley for one year and enrolled her in a drug
programme, but said he would impose the maximum 11 years if she had another
baby while still an addict.
Colonel blamed
BRUSSELS: A Belgian inquiry has blamed a senior Belgian military officer for
the deaths of 10 men under his command while part of a UN peacekeeping force in
Rwanda last year. Colonel Luc Marchal is to be charged with homicide by default
in the deaths of 1
0 paratroopers, who were taken prisoner and shot after being tortured. Marchal
said he welcomed the chance to prove his innocence.
Stowaways row
PARIS: The fate of five Moroccan stowaways found aboard a container ship hung
in the balance last night. French authorities refuse to let them off the ship,
while its Dutch captain refuses to leave the port of Brest as long as they
remain aboard.
Rockets fired
MARJAYOUN: Hizbollah guerrillas fired Katyusha rockets into northern Israel
yesterday after Israeli shelling killed a civilian in south Lebanon. No-one was
hurt in the reprisal attack. Seventeen people have died in Israeli shelling of
south Lebanon villag
es this year.
Wife quizzed
BERLIN: The German wife of international guerrilla ``Carlos the Jackal'' has
returned home from Venezuela and has been questioned by prosecutors. Der
Spiegel magazine reported that Magdalena Kopp, who has a nine-year-old daughter
by Carlos, was ready to t
estify against her notorious husband.
14 wiped out
MANILA: Fourteen people, mostly children, were killed when gunmen attacked
their home in the northern Philippines. Police said the victims, members of two
families, were watching television when a house was strafed by gunfire. Three
were later beheaded. O
nly a six-year-old boy survived the massacre which may have resulted from a
land dispute.
Space toast
MOSCOW: Two Russian cosmonauts and a German will see in the New Year on the Mir
space station with brandy - because it is hard to sip champagne in zero
gravity. Yuri Gidzenko, Sergei Avdeyev, and Thomas Reiter, who have been in
space since September 3, wi
ll toast 1996 while watching pictures broadcast from Earth of a clock in the
Kremlin striking midnight.
Executions rise
WASHINGTON: Fifty-six convicted killers were executed in the United States this
year, the highest total since 1957. The figure looks set to rise again next
year with more than 3000 men and women on death row. Texas, with 19, had the
most executions among
the 16 states which carried them out.
Santa mellows
ROME: Italy's leading civil rights campaigner, wearing a yellow Santa Claus
suit, was arrested yesterday for throwing bags of hashish to passers-by in
central Rome. Marco Pannella, 65, leader of the Reformist movement that seeks
the legalisation of soft d
rugs, staged another bold stunt when he gave a TV presenter a bag of hashish
during a prime-time programme.
Oops, sorry
VIENNA: A cat lover watched in horror as firefighters ran over her new kitten,
just after they rescued it from the roof of her house in Goettingen, Germany.
</TEXT>
