<TEXT>
Forte lifts profit forecast
FORTE has inched up its forecast for profit before tax and exceptional items
for the year ending January 31. It now expects to make not less than #190m
compared with earlier expectations of a #185m profit. This increased forecast
represents a 50% rise on
last year's #127m.
Earnings per share before exceptional items are forecast to be not less than
14.5p, an increase of 44%.
The new projection follows strong trading in December. Highlights were said to
be a 25% increase in the sale of London hotel rooms through a 6% rise in
occupancy and 17% growth in achieved room rate.
Forward bookings are also said to be strong. Business contracted in the UK with
tour operators and other groups for 1996-97 is projected to show revenue growth
of 13% compared with the same period last year.
Forte is the subject of a hostile #3300m bid from Granada which promptly
dismissed the hotel group's latest prediction, citing the fact that it was #10m
less than Forte's own broker's forecast last April. ``In real terms, it is
still lower than five years
ago. The earnings per share forecast is 16% less than five years ago,'' said a
Granada spokesman.
Granada remains convinced that it can improve Forte's profits by #100m in the
first financial year after takeover. Forte has attacked these claims as
``unsubstantiated''. Granada's share price has out-performed the All-Share
index by more than 150% over t
he last five years while Forte's has under-performed by 40%.
</TEXT>
