<HEADLINE>Car dealer is jailed for mileage `clocking' fraud</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635136</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAR dealer was jailed for 15 months yesterday after admitting he sold 47
``clocked'' cars with three million miles taken off their speedometers.
Glasgow Sheriff Court heard that Mark Fox, 33, bought high-mileage fleet cars
at auctions in Manchester and shipped them north on transporters to sell at
auctions in Glasgow.
Some cars had between 40,000 and 50,000 miles taken off their speedometers
before they were sold. This netted Fox an average extra profit of #800 on every
car he sold.
The case prompted immediate calls for a change in the law by Shadow consumer
affairs spokesman Nigel Griffiths, who has previously sponsored a Bill to
tackle ``clocking''.
He now intends to introduce a new measure to force motorists to declare the
mileage on their vehicles each time they renew the road tax certificate.
The Edinburgh South MP said this would mean that every vehicle's declared
mileage would be logged at Swansea and prospective purchasers could then check
its accuracy with a premium rate phone call.
Mr Griffiths said yesterday: ``This latest case is the worst I have ever come
across.
``Second-hand car buyers are being cheated of an estimated #100m every year.''
Fox went on trial earlier this month but changed his plea midway through the
case. Sheriff Brian Lockhart called for social inquiry and community service
reports and continued the case for sentence until yesterday.
Fox's defence counsel, Mr Frank Pieri, asked the sheriff not to jail him but to
allow him to do community service.
He claimed that only half a million miles had been taken from the 47 car
speedos and that the difference in profits was not in fact a great deal.
However, Sheriff Lockhart rejected this and said: ``I have considered closely
what has been said and I also have regard to the evidence led in this case.
``In my view, the minimum sentence I can impose is one of 15 months.''
Earlier this month, the court heard how the car dealer was arrested after a
nine-month undercover investigation by Strathclyde Trading Standards officers.
Yesterday, it was revealed that the team used video and still cameras in a van
with its windows blacked out.
The special car fraud investigation squad also had sophisticated satellite
eavesdropping equipment.
They discovered Fox used various aliases to cover his tracks, including the
names of well-known football players and managers.
A Trading Standards spokesman said yesterday: ``We are delighted with the
sentence - it will send shock waves through the crooked car business.
``What we uncovered in this case, which was one of the biggest investigations
of its type in the UK, is just the tip of the iceberg.
``There are other motor dealers still involved in this fraudulent trade and,
hopefully, the knowledge that the courts are treating the matter seriously will
deter them.
``We have a number of other cases in the pipeline.''
</TEXT>
