<HEADLINE>Council investigates why pensioner froze to death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN investigation was launched yesterday into the death of an 88-year-old war
veteran whose frozen body was found outside his home in a council-run sheltered
housing complex in Edinburgh.
Mr Nick Gould, a widower, was found by neighbours in the courtyard development
in Coillesdene Avenue, Joppa, around 8.30am, when temperatures were around
-14C. He may have lain for several hours.
Edinburgh District Council which runs the home said it had launched an urgent
inquiry into the circumstances surrounding his death.
The alarm was raised by neighbours who saw Mr Gould's body lying near his door.
Locals believe the former Royal Navy seaman slipped on an icy pavement after
spending the evening out with friends.
They believe the frail pensioner, who needed a walking stick to help him move
around, would probably have been unable to get himself off the ground.
Neighbour Jess Young, 88, said she was shocked to learn of the death of her
friend.
She said: ``I knocked on his door on Thursday night to ask him in for a
Christmas drink but because I didn't get an answer I assumed he was in bed.
``I couldn't believe it when I opened my curtains in the morning and saw him
lying outside. In this cold weather, he wouldn't have a chance of surviving out
there all night. He was such a good man.''
Friend George Wilkes, who had been out drinking with Mr Gould before the
tragedy, said: ``When he left me on Thursday night, he was in great spirits.
What has happened hasn't really sunk in yet.''
Police investigating Mr Gould's death said there were no suspicious
circumstances.
An Edinburgh District Council spokeswoman said: ``The council will take a close
look and see if there are any ways we could, if needed, tighten up
proceedures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP hits out at `appalling' gas supply shut-down</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635138</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN MP made an outspoken attack on British Gas last night after the supply to
15,000 people in nearly 5000 homes in his constituency was cut off.
East Lothian MP John Home Robertson said it was ``appalling'' that thousands of
people faced, in some cases, a further 48 hours of freezing conditions with no
heating in their homes after the gas supplies crashed.
Mr Home Robertson said he was ``horrified'' to find out it could take until
tomorrow evening to restore the gas supply to all the affected houses. He said
he was deeply concerned for the plight of the elderly and disabled people in
the area.
Hundreds of people from Cockenzie, Port Seton, and Prestonpans affected by the
gas shut-down sought refuge yesterday in community centres, where they received
a warm meal.
The problem arose as British Gas revealed that, over a 24-hour period up until
yesterday morning, 29 million cubic metres of gas was transported to customers
in Scotland. That is the highest amount of gas yet recorded and 12% higher than
the previous peak
demand.
Mr Home Robertson said he would be demanding compensation for all the people
whose gas supply had been turned off.
In a letter to gas board officials, he said: ``There is a widespread belief,
which I share, that the generation of profits is the only priority in the
privatised gas industry . . .
``The present crisis has apparently been triggered by a 12% surge in demand in
very cold weather, which suggests that the margin for security in the system is
woefully inadequate.''
A spokeswoman for British Gas TransCo, the company's pipeline franchise, said
last night it had people working 24 hours a day all over Scotland to maintain
its supply. It said that in many of the 5000 homes in parts of East Lothian
affected by the gas shu
t-down, hundreds of electric heaters were being distributed to vulnerable
residents.
British Gas engineers working for the pipeline franchise company, TransCo,
spotted levels of gas in its pipes dropping dangerously on Thursday evening.
Five thousand customers were immediately asked to switch off all their gas
appliances while the cause of the problem was identified.
A British Gas TransCo spokesman said last night: ``Teams of engineers are now
working in the area to restore supplies as quickly as possible. Twenty-five
people are currently going from house to house, isolating the individual
services.
``Once this work has been completed, we hope to restore gas supplies to groups
of up to 500 people at a time. We hope to restore supplies to everyone, all
being well, over the weekend.''
Last night, Lothian regional councillor John Russell said an emergency plan to
cope with the problem had been launched.
Councillor Russell said: ``This is a very severe and difficult situation. We
got the first indications around eight o'clock on Thursday night that the gas
might have to be cut off.
``The local authorities are issuing advice to people in the area of what to do
and whom to contact for help.''
Local residents said having their gas supply shut down was causing them worry.
Mr John Merritt, 60, of Prestonpans, said: ``Many people are worried about what
they will do. In my case, I will be bringing in an oil-fired heater to my house.
``I've heard of other people going walks in the cold to keep warm, rather than
sit in their freezing homes.''
A spokeswoman for Lothian Regional Council, outlining the council's emergency
plans, said: ``People should remain in their homes whenever possible.
``Those who are completely reliant on gas for cooking, heating, and food and
particularly those who are either frail, elderly or who have young children are
urged to phone a helpline set up by Scottish Gas for assistance.''
The helpline number for people in East Lothian is 0131 559 4885.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Daughter of heiress settles claim for #43m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635139</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE adopted daughter of a late tobacco heiress has dropped her claims against
Doris Duke's estate in exchange for a #43m settlement.
The financial settlement to Chandi Duke Heffner, 42, was approved by a
Manhattan judge, the New York Daily News reported.
Duke, who died in 1993 at age 80, left an #800m fortune, one of the largest
private fortunes in US history. It has been the subject of complicated legal
wrangling ever since.
Duke adopted Heffner in 1988, but they later became estranged and Duke left the
younger woman out of her will. The twice-divorced heiress had no other
children.
Duke left most of her money to charity and named her butler, Bernard Lafferty,
as co-executor of the estate.
Heffner also dropped a breach-of-contract suit in which she claimed her adopted
mother reneged on a promise to support her for life, the newspaper said.
Heffner contested the will and also attempted to make a claim upon a #120m
trust established in 1917 by Duke's father, James Buchanan Duke, who founded
the American Tobacco Company.
According to the settlement, Heffner will receive #40.5m from the trust and
#3.3m from Duke's estate.
Duke's will is still subject to a separate legal fight by her former physican,
Dr Harry Demopoulos, who sought to have the butler removed as co-executor.
Earlier this year, a judge removed Lafferty from that position for allegedly
squandering the estate's assets on a lavish lifestyle. The former butler is now
fighting to resume managing Duke's fortune.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Honour bound</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Interviews: JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635144</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Some of the names are unlikely to appear on the official list, but the
selectors believe they should be our nominations for New Year honours
n Elizabeth Blackadder, artist, nominates:
Penelope Beaton. She was a very good painter, and also taught for many years in
Edinburgh College of Art, guiding people such as Robin Philipson and John
Maxwell. She was my tutor, and a lot of people, I'm sure, owe a lot to her.
n Shirley Robertson, dinghy champion who is tipped for gold in the next
Olympics:
Princess Anne, because she's deeply involved in sailing, is president of our
federation, and is always supportive of the sailors and of sailing in this
country, and of the Olympic movement. She's a great fan of Scotland, too.
n Primrose McCabe, chartered accountant, Scottish businesswoman and MD of
Primrose McCabe &amp; Co:
Anne Gloag, founder of Stagecoach, because she's a good example to the rest of
the women in business of someone who can make a success of it. She has also
done a lot to improve the economic structure of the country in terms of
creating jobs and wealth. Dr
Elizabeth Scott for her services to medicine, not just as a GP, but as a
researcher into sleeping problems. I think she's quite a character. Also
Catherine Duthie, for 20 years director in Scotland of the Macmillan Nurses.
Basically, she's done an awful
lot to make the Macmillan services in Scotland second to none.
n Roseanna Cunningham, MP:
I think we definitely need to give an honour to Princess Diana for her sterling
contribution to the campaign for an elected head of state! And can I give one
to my mum, who will be 84 in January, for all her patience and her lifetime of
unshakeable faith
in me.
n Professor Rona MacKie, Scottish skin cancer specialist, professor of
dermatology, Glasgow University:
Cicely Saunders, who introduced palliative care into the hospice movement - but
she's already a Dame, so somebody else thought it was a good idea. One to Jane
Glover, the female conductor - she's super, she brings a lot of pleasure to a
lot of people. The
next one is Dame Margaret Turner Warwick, the first woman president of the
Royal College of Physicians of London, which is a male bastion. Unfortunately,
somebody got there first with the honour!
n Vera Weisfeld, founder of What Every Woman Wants, top Scottish businesswoman,
and owner of Glasgow department store Weisfelds:
The women who stand out most in my mind are the wives of assassinated
presidents - for example, Yitzhak Rabin's wife - for the way they face life
afterwards, particularly when their husbands were canvassing for peace.
n Ray Michie, MP:
I would vote for Yitzhak Rabin's widow, and for the wife of Philip Lawrence,
the headmaster who was knifed. I think everybody admired the way she conducted
herself and the way she has held the family together. I think her views on what
we should be doing
about violence and knives are admirable. She appeared to be a very courageous
woman.
n Maria Fyfe, MP:
Princess Diana for doing more to upset the establishment than anyone I can
think of.
n Winnie Ewing, MEP:
Mrs Pankhurst. After all, she was the main voice for votes for women, and very
courageous, very eloquent and good looking and everything else, and she had the
ability to inspire a movement, which is not an easy thing to do.
</TEXT>
