<HEADLINE>`Benjamin' can storm to success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BENJAMINS Law has been in particularly fine form since being campaigned on the
all-weather and can win the first division of the Snowstorm Handicap, the
opening race of Wolverhampton's afternoon fixture.
The four-year-old gelding, who shares top weight with Beauman, has made the
frame in each of his last four outings, including two wins.
He was getting off the mark for his career when winning a handicap over course
and distance in November, landing the spoils by a neck from Rood Music.
Following two creditable efforts, he was back in the winner's enclosure, after
another course-and-distance suc-cess. Starting the 4-1 favourite, he was taken
to the front by Jimmy Quinn with over a quarter of a mile remaining and had
three-quarters of a l
ength to spare over Pine Ridge Lad at the line.
Quinn once again takes the mount and, despite his hefty burden, Benjamins Law
is taken to win his third race over this course and distance.
David Evans does very well with the string he trains at his Welshpool base and
his Little Ibnr looks a sound bet to take the first race of the evening
meeting, the `Farewell 1995' Handicap.
Although he, too, has to carry top weight of 10st, he showed he is in fine
fettle by lifting a claimer, again over course and distance, earlier in the
month, beating Cretan Gift by a neck.
q ANY punter wishing to have a placepot bet on Wolverhampton's even-ing fixture
will get a ticket for Epsom instead.
The unusual arrangement has arisen because the computer system cannot
accomodate two placepot meetings of the same name on the same day.
The Jackpot - with a #20,968 carry over - will be on the afternoon card at the
midlands track, but both that meeting and the evening fixture have a placepot
bet available on the first six races.
</TEXT>
