<HEADLINE>Revellers warned of the risks of hypothermia.  Doctors highlight deadly combination of drink and cold weather as death toll continues to rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STARRS and CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635146</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW YEAR revellers and elderly people will add to the growing hypothermia death
toll if they fail to take proper precautions against the record low
temperatures, Scottish doctors warned last night.
The stark message came as the number of recent deaths from hypothermia rose to
at least five following the discovery of another man killed by extreme
temperatures in Joppa, near Edinburgh.
One hypothermia victim has already died and two more were being treated last
night by doctors at Southern General Hospital, in Glasgow.
The freeze has also claimed the lives of Renfrewshire pensioner Elizabeth
Donaldson, 77, Mr John Murphy, 55, who had been sleeping rough in Bathgate,
West Lothian, and 16-year-old John Colquhoun, from Ayrshire, who froze to death
on Christmas Day after tr
ying to walk home in the early hours of the morning.
Glasgow has recorded its lowest temperature yet (-20C) for the past three days.
In East Lothian, 15,000 people in nearly 5000 homes were without a gas supply.
British Gas said the problem was caused by an all-time record demand for gas in
the area.
Dr Brian Potter, Scottish secretary of the British Medical Association, warned
that more lives would be put at risk over New Year if people did not take
commonsense precautions.
He said: ``There are going to be some people who die over the festive season
primarily because of alcohol but also because of the combination of the effects
of record low temperatures on people who have been drinking.
``Alcohol increases susceptibility to serious dangers from the cold, especially
the elderly and ill. Young people can be particularly at risk at this time of
year because they are tempted to drink more than they should.''
Dr Malcolm Gordon, accident and emergency consultant at the Southern General,
repeated the warnings and told people to take commonsense precautions. He urged
people to stay indoors or remain sober while celebrating the New Year.
Doctors fought for around 10 hours to save  a 67-year-old man who was brought
into the Southern General on December 21. He had a core body temperature 12
degrees below the normal level of 37C - hypothermia sets in at temperatures
below 35C. The man, who
had been found in his own house, did not regained consciousness and died later
that night.
A 70-year-old man was in a critical condition in the hospital's intensive care
unit yesterday after being found frozen just yards from his home in the
south-west of the city. An elderly woman was also brought into the hospital
yesterday morning after her
home help found her suffering from hypothermia in her house.
Two people have been treated for hypothermia at Glasgow Royal Infirmary, six at
Edinburgh Royal Infirmary, and two more victims are recovering in hospitals in
Dundee.
Weathermen yesterday predicted the nights will get comparatively warmer but
still remain below zero. Snow is expected over the weekend and winds of up to
30mph will make it feel as cold as before.
Shetland's snow emergency was drawing to a close last night but the islands are
still severely affected by snow and ice. The temperature dropped below zero
again yesterday afternoon after a slow thaw through the day.
Mr Malcolm Green, chief executive of Shetland Islands Council, said military
help offered by the Government would not be needed meantime, although the
council was grateful for the offer.
``I think the worst is definitely over,'' Mr Green said. ``We've got all the
power back and virtually all the roads are now open.
``As long as we don't get hit again by another heavy fall of snow, I think
we'll be OK. But the weather can change at any moment so we can't be
complacent,'' he said.
Council roads staff and Hydro-Electric crews who had worked on through the
worst of the snows were being told to stand down last night.
Shetland police said last night that Shetland's roads were ``like a 500-mile
skating rink'' after melting snow refroze at dusk.
Coastguards said they had ``almost lost count'' of the medical evacuations
carried out by their rescue helicopter in Shetland since Christmas Eve.
Yesterday, they made two more mercy flights.
Two climbers who had become trapped on Aonach Eagach Ridge in Glencoe were
rescued uninjured last night. Members of the Glencoe mountain rescue team and
an RAF rescue helicopter from Lossiemouth had been involved in the search.
Hydro-Electric said 22 houses were still without electricity on Harris, but
engineers were confident of fixing the problem last night.
Cold weather payments are to be made to people who qualify in the Western Isles.
A Department of Social Security spokeman in Edinburgh said Stornoway Weather
Centre triggered the payments for the Western Isles for the period December
22-28. This will mean #8.50 per week for those who qualify.
</TEXT>
