<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Internet blocks off porn for fear of prosecution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From WILLIAM BOSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bonn, Friday
GERMAN authorities have launched a investigation into the US-based online
service CompuServe on suspicion that members sent child pornography over its
world-wide Internet computer network.
The inquiry prompted the service to block access to 200 sexually-explicit
Internet discussion groups and sites where pornographic pictures are available.
Prosecutors denied that other groups were under investigation but industry
officials feared it could set an international precedent in the battle against
cyberporn and affect other on-line services and companies offering access to
the Internet.
``Our investigation is directed against CompuServe,'' said Manfred Wick, the
Munich prosecutor leading the inquiry. ``It deals with distribution of child
pornography and there is concrete evidence of a crime that leads back to
CompuServe.''
CompuServe members inundated the service's discussion forums with sometimes
abusive criticism of the decision to block access to any part of the anarchic
Internet.
Several American members denounced the German authorities for taking what they
saw as a unilateral swipe against freedom of speech in cyberspace.
``This is how Nazi Germany and Communist Russia started out by taking away
basic freedoms of the people,'' wrote one Midwesterner who said he had
``old-time family values''.
CompuServe provides online information, electronic mail, and Internet access to
more than four million subscribers in 140 countries, including 500,000 in
Europe.
Prosecutors were tipped off last month that child pornography, which is illegal
in Germany, had been exchanged over the CompuServe network. Police searched the
company's Munich offices on November 22.
Marielle Bureick, spokeswoman for CompuServe in Germany, said the company could
do little to censor the Internet and complained that laws concerning online
services were vague.
``We simply transfer data. If someone sends a letter bomb in the mail, do you
file charges against the post office?'' she asked. ``We need more clarity
regarding the legal framework.''
There is pressure on new online services in Europe because media laws are more
restrictive than in the United States.
Germany, for example, bans all neo-Nazi literature and officials are frustrated
that racist propaganda is available on the Internet from World Wide Web sites
in the United States.
Europe Online, which has just launched its service, said it chose to avoid
conflicts by blocking access to pornographic material online. ``We take the
issue of pornographic areas on the Internet very seriously indeed,'' said chief
executive Juergen Becker
.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
