<HEADLINE>Italy arrives at crossroads  as caretaker premier quits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PAUL HOLMES Rome, Friday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIME Minister Lamberto Dini said that he would offer his resignation tomorrow,
clearing the decks for Parliament to decide on Italy's political future.
Dini, appointed last January to head an unelected Cabinet of technocrats, told
a news conference that he would tell President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro that the
work of his government, Italy's 54th since the Second World War, was done.
``The government will offer its resignation, having completed its duty, its
mandate, and its programme,'' said the former central banker.
He spoke after the Cabinet's final decision, approval of a 5.29 trillion lire
(#2213m) package of revenue-raising measures and spending cuts. The package
completed Italy's deficit-cutting budget for 1996.
Scalfaro has already made clear that he will not accept Dini's offer until
Parliament has had its say on whether to rise for an early General Election or
to try to agree on an ambitious, long-term programme of constitutional reforms.
The Parliament, elected in March 1994, has been bitterly fractured since media
magnate Silvio Berlusconi was forced to resign as Prime Minister a year ago
after the collapse of his stormy conservative coalition just seven months into
office.
However signs were growing today that the opposing centre-right and centre-left
blocs were giving serious consideration to a possible cross-party government
with a two-year mandate to enact the reforms needed to give Italy the stability
it lacks.
The Democratic Party of the Left (PDS), the main force on the centre-left and
Dini's biggest backer, proposed giving Dini a fresh mandate for a further six
months, a formula it said would safeguard Italy's European Union presidency
starting on January 1 a
nd still leave time to hold a June General Election if the exploratory talks
failed.
The proposal responded to an initiative announced by Berlusconi yesterday for a
cross-party government of the ``best minds'' in the various parties with two
years to work on constitutional and electoral reform before going to the
polls.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
