<DOCID>GH951230-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Celebrating `a very happy Goodyear' Coronation leads to MBE</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635150</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JULIE GOODYEAR, former Coronation Street landlady Bet Gilroy, celebrated her
MBE with pink champagne, saying she was ``thrilled and delighted'' with the
award which came weeks after she quit the top ITV soap after 25 years and 2002
episodes.
``This is one of the most memorable and proudest moments of my life,'' she
said. ``I am a very happy Goodyear.''
Julie was one of 1036 people honoured.
One third of award-winners were women, including Stella Rimington, the head of
Britain's security services, who becomes a dame, and agony aunt Claire Rayner,
who is celebrating her OBE in hospital.
``It's like getting a tick from teacher,'' she said.
The list contains stars from the pop scene, TV, and the stage.
Elton John, reputedly a regular guest of the royals at Windsor, is made a CBE.
Cameron Mackintosh, the stage impresario, becomes a knight.
The man behind Les Miserables and a host of other international hits kept his
award a ``dark secret'' from his friends.
``We can't even ring to congratulate him,'' said Nick Allott, his executive
producer.
Meanwhile, actress Peggy Mount, 78, gets an OBE. She excelled in the role of
formidable battleaxe.
Elsewhere, Nicolas Roeg, who becomes a CBE, found distinction as a film
director even though he ploughed a lone furrow with controversial productions,
including Don't Look Now.
There is an OBE for Ken Adam, who won an Oscar for the best art direction in
The Madness of King George.
There are also a host of Britain's sporting stars in the list. Jonathan
Edwards, the world champion triple-jumper becomes an MBE, as does Ian Rush,
Liverpool's Welsh striker.
There are MBEs too for Robert Jones, the Swansea, Wales, and British Lions
scrum half, and for Dean Richards, the Leicester and England player, the most
capped back-row forward in the world.
There is also an OBE for Dermot Reeve, captain of the successful Warwickshire
cricket team.
Elsewhere in sport, there is an MBE for Karen Dixon, an Olympic equestrienne
and Britain's leading events rider.
Ted Lowe, the whispering voice of snooker TV commentary, becomes an MBE.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
