<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Widow praises husband's heroic attempt to rescue girl from lake</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE widow of firefighter Michael Mee, who sacrificed his life in a bid to save
two people from drowning in an icy lake, yesterday paid tribute to her
husband's courage.
Mr Mee, 48, plunged through ice at Hemsworth Water Park in West Yorkshire as he
tried to save Tracey Pattison, 11, and Mr Jack Crawshaw, 51.
All three died despite five hours of resuscitation attempts in hospital.
As Mr Mee's wife, Elizabeth, spoke of her husband's bravery, council officials
disclosed that even as the bodies were being dragged from the freezing water on
Thursday, reckless youngsters refused to leave the ice on an adjoining lake.
A distraught Mrs Mee, of South Hiendley, said: ``He was a wonderful, brave man
who devoted his life to helping others. We have lived in this village for 22
years and there is no-one here who doesn't respect or like him.''
She had watched helplessly with her daughter, Katy, 19, as Mr Mee rushed to
save Tracey as she struggled in the water.
She said: ``He sprinted round the lake, telling me and Katy to dial 999. The
next thing I knew, Mike was on the ice trying to reach the little girl.''
Bachelor Jack Crawshaw, 51, plunged into the lake about the same time.
Mrs Mee, 46, said she and her daughter shouted to try to give her husband moral
support in his rescue attempt.
``Katy and I ran up and just kept shouting to him to try and support him but he
didn't have a chance. He had nothing to get hold of,'' said Mrs Mee, who also
has a son, Christopher, 17.
``The girl and the other man went underneath first, and then Mike disappeared.
After that, everything seems blurred.
``They were all gone by the time the firemen arrived.''
The second rescuer, Mr Crawshaw, lived with his brother Ian at Wrenthorpe. They
once operated a corner shop which adjoined their house but it has since closed.
Jack and Ian, whose other brother Chris lives nearby, lost their mother and
father a few years ago.
Yesterday, Mr Ian Crawshaw said: ``I'm terribly upset. I've been up all night -
I just can't believe it. Nobody knows how this feels, nobody.''
Mr Donald Andrassy, who runs a garage opposite Mr Crawshaw's home, said: ``Jack
was a quiet man who kept himself to himself. Nobody round here can believe this
has happened to him. It was a very brave thing to do.''
Council officials yesterday revealed that, as the tragedy unfolded, children
continued playing on a frozen lake just yards away.
Council staff pleaded with them to get off the dangerously thin ice but they
refused.
Hemsworth town clerk, Mr Chris Geeson, said: ``While they were dragging bodies
out of the big lake, kids were on the ice on the smaller lake.
``They must have known what had happened but, when they were asked to keep off
the ice, we just got abuse from them.''
He said lifebelts around the park, which attracts 75,000 visitors a year, were
constantly vandalised. One was thrown into the middle of the lake as a frisbee
not long before the tragedy.
As the council yesterday reviewed safety measures at the park, Mr Geeson said
the authority ``deeply regretted'' the accident but pointed out it was very
difficult to stop people going on to the ice.
``Commonsense needs to prevail,'' he said. ``The park is open 24 hours a day
and we cannot close it.
``There are already plenty of signs up with lots of `Don'ts' on them and, quite
frankly, while the majority of people adhere to them, a small minority don't.
It's very difficult to stop that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New unitary authority faces jobs inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE inquiry ordered by the Government into complaints about staff appointments
made by the new unitary North Lanarkshire Council will open on January 8, when
it will begin taking evidence from witnesses in public.
The new authority, whose area will take in Monklands District Council - itself
the subject of a number of inquiries over allegations of bias in employment
practices - has been criticised for the methods it used in appointing staff.
The hearing, to be held by Mr Ian MacLeod in the Council Chamber of
Motherwell's Civic Centre, is expected to hear evidence from around 80 people.
Mr MacLeod was appointed to investigate allegations that North Lanarkshire
Council had failed to comply with the statutory obligation on them under the
Local Government and Housing Act 1989 to appoint staff on merit.
Earlier this month, Mr William Nimmo Smith QC, appointed by the Government to
hold an independent inquiry into Monklands District Council, produced an
83-page report in which he said he had found no evidence to support allegations
of religious bias or nep
otism within the council.
His inquiry followed another, commissioned by the district council itself,
chaired by Professor Robert Black. His findings failed to eliminate public
concerns of a ``Monklands Mafia''.
The Black Report coincided with the entire Monklands ruling group being
suspended by the Labour Party pending its own investigations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J P Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT ever you do, I thought, don't write about Christmas. For months now, every
newspaper has been banging on about shopping ideas, overeating, and parties. A
festive season grump would be the easy option, and you won't catch me following
the crowd.
So last weekend, as I sat at the computer, I was determined to strike out and
be different. I had three attempts: one was about aeroplanes (got bored after
50 words), one about snow (everyone else doing it, abandoned halfway through),
and a rant about pet
ty nationalism and the England game in June (not topical enough: two weeks too
late). No matter that it was hard work, I was determined to avoid writing
anything about Christmas.
Christmas had largely passed me by. Like most men, I had avoided Christmas
shopping by invoking the ``I've got a Y-chromosome so it's your job to buy mum
a christmas present'' principle. So no problems there.
Even going to the carol service was relatively traumatic. One of our kids is
going through yet another ``phase''. Doctors are obviously taught that any
socially unacceptable behaviour should be dismissed as a ``phase''. To GPs,
this means ``He does whaaaa
t? Jeez, that kid is wierd!'' Our three-year-old has lately developed a case of
Premature Adolescent Behaviour Syndrome, as shown by a delight in shouting rude
words. The word `botty', for him, is the pinnacle of smut, and he uses this
word loudly, in pub
lic, whenever possible. No matter how much we feign disinterest, he knows it's
embarrassing.
On the way to the playgroup carol concert in the local presbyterian church, he
delightedly told us how he was going to sing Away In A Manger, but spiced up
with his favourite word. Matthew's singing voice is as bad as his mother's, but
what he lacks in me
lody, he makes up for in volume. We were, to say the least, a tad anxious that
he would be onstage shouting ``Away in a botty, no crib for a botty'' in his
usual tuneless yelp. It says a lot that we were relieved when he only stood
with his arms folded, f
ace scowling, making intermittent ``Harrumph'' noises. So, no problems there,
and we were still all go for a Christmas-free column.
On Christmas eve, we took the kids to Julia's birthday party. With the kids
having to sing songs about something other than snow and babies in straw, this
helped diffuse some of the yuletide mania. Despite having to do the Hokey Cokey
twice, the party wen
t well. Having known the other parents for years, I wasn't at all embarrassed
about being seen putting my whole bulky self in and shaking it all about. It's
at least less demeaning than dancing to neuromantic records which is what we
used to do for entert
ainment when we first met.
In fact, the Hokey Cokey is probably laden with meaning compared to most of
Duran Duran's rubbish. I'd probably rather be remembered hokeying, or indeed
cokeying, than poncing around to A Flock of Seagulls or Soft Cell as a gawky
adolescent.
Come C-day, I remained untroubled. The innocent wonder with which children
greet their heist is always quite special. It might be basically greed, but if
so, it's greed dressed up cutely, which makes it quite palatable. At first,
after the parcels were op
ened, I thought that we had avoided that phenomenon, The Present From Hell.
Unfortunately, it was only hiding.
You would find it hard to believe there's a thin line between love and hate
when you see the gulf between the affection that Jack held for our PFH and the
loathing it inspired in me. Some vindictive person had given the kids an
instrument of torture disgu
ised as a toy CD player. It didn't seem to be particularly sophisticated, it
just murdered the first two lines of selected Christmas songs in a loud beeping
sort of way, when you insert a small fake CD.
Initially, this was not too bad. As the day drew on, it became apparent the PFH
had been cunningly programmed to develop an Attention Deficit Disorder. It
began to play short snatches of each carol, with no breaks in between, sounding
like some wild music
al maelstrom. The PFH had evolved from a mild irritant into an unstoppable
crazed random note generator. The kids loved it. I was waiting patiently until
bedtime, hammer at the ready.
So why have I written about Christmas? Just to say that if you're out there,
PFH donor, I'll find you. I'll rebuild the PFH, and next year I'll make sure
your kid gets it. And I'll fit long-life batteries. In fact, if I'm still this
mad, I'll programme it
to sing Away In A Botty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leeson drops appeal against jail sentence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From CHRIS JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Barings trader Nick Leeson will not pursue an appeal against a six-year
jail sentence for cheating Singapore's financial futures exchange.
Leeson, whose disastrous deals brought down Britain's oldest bank, Barings, in
February under debts of #860m, was sentenced to six-and-a-half years in jail on
December 2 after pleading guilty to two charges of cheating.
The 28-year-old former whizz-kid trader gave notice of appeal against one of
the charges, for which he received a six-year sentence, on December 12.
He had until 5am tomorrow to present his formal petition in Singapore's
subordinate courts.
However a spokesman for his lawyers said that no petition would now be
presented on Leeson's behalf.
A court spokeswoman said yesterday that Leeson's appeal would be considered as
dropped if nothing was heard from him by the Saturday deadline.
Any appeal by Leeson would have been a gamble. Under Singapore law, even though
the defence brings an appeal seeking a lighter punishment, a court can increase
the sentence and has done so in some past appeals.
Leeson's sentence was backdated to March 2 when he was arrested in Germany, so
the nine months he served in a German jail pending extradition will be deducted
from his time.
He is now likely to serve only three-and-a-half to four years if he gets
reduction for good behaviour.
His sentence came after nine other charges of fraud and forgery were set aside,
following his co-operation with Singapore's Commercial Affairs Department.
In another development today, a Singapore court has authorised the liquidators
of Baring Futures to investigate the assets of six executives in a bid to
recover the company's losses, according to a report in the Straits Times
newspaper.
The High Court order was granted on Wednesday to liquidators Price Waterhouse.
The company will investigate officials Simon Jones, Peter Norris, Michael
Kilian, Roy Johnson, James Bax and Fu Ya Yin, said the usually reliable Times.
Jones, former Baring Futures finance director, Norris, former Barings chief
executive, and Bax, former Asia Pacific managing director, were blamed earlier
this year by a Singapore government-commissioned investigation for failing to
stop Leeson's activiti
es, and even covering them up.
Norris and Bax have denied the allegations. No formal charges have been filed,
but Singapore's fraud squad has said that it will prosecute anyone who broke
the law.-Reuter/AP.
