<HEADLINE>Going, going, no gong</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenny Logan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NO more gongs for Gavin in the New Year's honours list, but it's about the only
thing he has not won this year. Player of the Year, and Scotsman of the Year
from this newspaper and that. A book, a film, This Is Your Life, and now BBC
Scotland's Sportscene
Personality of the Year.
He even kept a jumbo jet waiting on the tarmac this week as he and Diane flew
out to Colorado for a week on the piste.
Strange, though, that the BBC blew their own gaffe by arranging pictures of
Gavin with the trophy before he left, and especially when the awards programme
will not be screened until Ne'erday. It kind of kills the surprise element. I
might give it a miss.
It's been a big year for Scottish rugby, and Gavin has been a big part of it.
We'll all miss him now that he's gone. We turned the corner in January against
Canada after nine games without a win. Then we were into the Five Nations'
Championship, which cer
tainly went much better than the Doubting Thomases thought it would.
Personally, I enjoyed the game against Wales best of all and especially the run
which led to Eric Peters' fantastic try. Paris was something else when we won
for the first time since 1969. Hopefully it won't be another 26 years before we
win on French soi
l again, by which time video footage of that Hastings try would be looking as
grainy as that black-and-white footage of the Jim Telfer try which the BBC show
religiously every year since.
The World Cup was special. It was a great experience in a country which was in
the throes of great change. Who knows how far we could have gone if Emile
N'Tamack had not scored that try in the dying seconds which lined us up against
New Zealand.
For Stirling County, too, 1995 was special. It was the year in which we won and
lost the championship title and because of league reconstruction, that's the
first time that's happened.
Nevertheless, we came second and equalled Melrose on points, thus cementing our
place as one of the top sides in Scotland. It's not bad going for a club that
was looked upon as one of the country cousins of Scottish rugby not so long ago.
Weather, and Murrayfield's undersoil heating permitting, I get my first run of
the season with Glasgow tomorrow. It's been frustrating to sit on the sidelines
injured while the district championship was going on, and we just have to end
on a winning note
against Edinburgh.
Then, next weekend, we swop Murrayfield for the, hopefully, sunnier climes of
Italy. It's an A side in name only. This is a full metal jacket squad and
although the Italians - named the most improved side in the World Cup - will be
no pushovers, a good wi
n would set us up nicely for the start of the Five Nations a couple of weeks
later.
This weather is a real bind for us farmers. At a Murrayfield squad session on
Tuesday night, I was just remarking to fellow farmer, Doddie Weir, that it was
so cold the milk was freezing in the cows' udders. Doddie just looked at me and
said: ``Is that ri
ght?''
Now, I know that Doddie is more at home these days with his mobile phone and
his brewery rep's motor, but you would have thought that he would recognise an
agricultural wind-up when he heard it. A case of ``pull the udder one!''
</TEXT>
