<HEADLINE>2000: a place odyssey</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635158</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As midnight on December 31, 1999, approaches STEPHEN McGINTY wants to party
into the new millennium.
FORGET this year, what about December 31 1999? On the night when the calendar
rolls over to reveal the big 2000, just where do you plan to witness the birth
of new millennium?
It's not such a daft question. Around the world hotels are being filled up with
folks anxious not to miss the night of not one, but one hundred lifetimes. The
London Savoy has been fully booked since 1990. Disney World in Orlando has sold
out nearly all i
ts 17,000 rooms.
If it's winter in New York you fancy, The Rainbow Room has already been able to
stop taking reservations for its New Year's Eve bash, priced at only $1000 per
person excluding drinks. While the Empire State Building could grow by feet
just using its peak
as a paper spike for hiring requests.
London has been swept up years ago, with the Albert Hall booked since 1975, the
Roof Gardens sagging under thousands of requests for the night's hire and
British Airways opening a requests department to work all through those
received.
Yet in Scotland, the one nation most entwined with Hogmanay - something which
we do so well - hotels, cities, even castles seem curiously laid back.
Historic Scotland, caretaker of Edinburgh Castle has said: ``not now'' to any
enquiries by Richard Branson's Virgin to hire Scotland's greatest monument for
a monumental millennium bash.
Edinburgh's Hogmanay, now in its third year, is building towards a climax in
1999. The five-day event, produced by Unique Events, is funded by Edinburgh
District Council, Lothian Regional Council and Edinburgh Enterprise. The
current plan is to draw media
attention away from American cities such as New York. Promoter Peter Irvine
believes Scotland already tops the world.
He said: ``No other city has a full programme of events like Edinburgh. We are
very aware of the approaching millennium celebrations and once we have come out
from under this one we will all be preparing ourselves for year 2000. But we
are already aware o
f the immense problems.''
``There is the problem of billing appropriate acts. Everyone will want
Pavarotti but will Wet Wet Wet still fit the bill, would they want to?''
This year the city's hotels and guest houses became fully booked by
mid-November with late enquirers being shunted out to Fife and the Borders in a
bid to secure accommodation. Yet some have already expressed an interest in
booking up for 1999.
A spokesperson for reservations at the Caledonian Hotel says that despite a
number of enquiries the hotel has not yet decided what it will be doing for a
millennium celebration.
Glasgow will be linking its millennium celebrations to its year as City of
Architecture. Leader of the council, Pat Lally says: ``The year 1999 will be a
major triumph for Glasgow as City of Architecture and I feel we will all be
entitled to celebrate.''
Anyone wishing a rare touch that only history can provide will have to run the
risk of having nowhere to go. Anyone wishing to hire a Scottish castle for the
night will have to wait until nearer the time.
A spokesman for Historic Scotland said: ``We can't set costs that far ahead and
because they are the Government's property, they might be using them in 1999.
We have had one or two approaches from people but we've had to say come back
nearer the time.''
Antonella Sacchero at Gleneagles says the hotel has received a steady stream of
enquiries stretching back over the past 10 years. But reservations for the
hotel will not actually open until next year, probably May.
Cameron House by Loch Lomond is in a similar situation with enquiries running
to figures double the room availability. A reservation list will be opened
during the next six months, with their capacity stretched nearer the time with
the building of a numbe
r of new lodges.
However, anyone wishing to try to suck the air from others' more billowing
plans, can point out that strictly speaking the millennium does not end until
the following year: December 31 2000. But this is unlikely to deter people such
as one British busines
sman who is organising simultaneous parties in Sydney, London and New York -
and will appear at all three.
The difference in attitudes is light-years from the last millennium's end when
thousands of northern Europeans expected the world to end at midnight.
In five year's time, even if Peter Irvine doesn't order one of the world's
biggest fireworks direct from China for Edinburgh's celebrations, the second
millennium is still sure to end with a bang.
</TEXT>
