<HEADLINE>Business leaders call for further interest rate cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635160</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the year draws to a close, business leaders are urging the Chancellor to cut
interest rates again early in the new year to sustain business growth.
The British Chambers of Commerce yesterday called for more interest rate cuts
throughout the year. This follows CBI president Sir Bryan Nicholson's
suggestion on Thursday that the time might soon be right for a further
reduction and that the CBI was keepi
ng a close check on the moderating pace of growth among manufacturers.
The BCC deputy director- general, Richard Brown, was more forceful, stating
that while the main priority for the Government of a stable economic
environment with low inflation looks like being maintained and will bring
increased prosperity to UK firms, ``
essential to this are more interest rate cuts throughout the year. Britain has
the highest interest rates in the G7 and these must be brought down as a matter
of priority''.
The Chancellor sliced a 0.25-point off rates after his meeting with the
Governor of the Bank of England on December 13. Their next two monetary
meetings are scheduled for January 17 and February 7. The Chancellor has
forecast 3% growth for the UK economy
next year but most economists believe this to be too ambitious unless there is
a further stimulus through another rate reduction. Most forecasts centre on
2.5%-2.75% growth.
In his annual message to the 200,000 members of the BCC, the deputy
director-general said that investment looks set to rise, which can only be good
for British firms, improving quality and competitiveness in overseas markets.
He stressed, though, that the Chancellor must keep a tight grip on Government
spending if the economy is to grow without overheating.
``Markets overseas, particularly in Europe, continue to present challenges to
British companies. These challenges are being seized upon, and 1996 looks set
to see an increase in the UK's share of markets as the drive for global
competitiveness continues.'
'
Mr Brown said that business is strongly committed to Europe, and Britain needs
to play a full and constructive role in its development, arguing for
competitiveness, deregulation and job creation. He warned that ``Europe must
not fetter its business and ci
tizens with unnecessary regulations'' and that it must be founded on the
principles of the free market.
n DR NEIL Blake, research director of economic forecaster Business Strategies,
expects economic growth of around 2.73% in 1996 with exports doing well. He
considers that the massive build-up in stocks will ensure home market demand
can be met without exce
ssive imports and, as a consequence, the balance of payments will not suffer
unduly.
Consumer spending itself is forecast to rise by 2.75%. In the absence of strong
growth in real earnings, the driving force will be personal tax cuts (and more
important the first year without tax increases since 1993); windfall gains of
#50 off householde
rs' electricity bills in England and Wales; the maturing of the first Tessa
accounts; and the prospect of gains to investors from building society mergers.
</TEXT>
