<HEADLINE>Blisters could have been made by belt, murder trial told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN accused of throttling prostitute Leona McGovern had injuries to the
inside of his hands, a court heard yesterday.
Mr George Walker, 31, claimed later the healed blisters were old rope burns.
However, a police surgeon, Dr Colin McKelvie, said the blisters could also have
been caused by Mr Walker pulling hard on a belt.
Ms McGovern, 22, was found murdered with a belt round her neck, the High Court
in Glasgow has heard.
She also had multiple bruises and stab wounds around her head and face. Her
ribs were broken and the impression of a boot was stamped on her chest.
Dr McKelvie said Ms McGovern was found lying behind the Art Centre in
Washington Street, Glasgow, on June 2.
He said: ``She was curled up behind a wall and a fence and her blood was still
flowing down a flight of stairs.''
An apple that Ms McGovern had been eating was found nearby.
Dr McKelvie said that, weeks later, on August 25, Mr Walker told him the healed
blisters to his palms and fingers had been caused when he was pulling on a rope.
Pathologist Dr Eleanor Murray said a star screwdriver or a piece of steel fence
could have been used to stab Ms McGovern.
Cause of death was strangulation, said Dr Murray.
Mr Walker denies punching, kicking, and stamping on, strangling, and stabbing
Ms McGovern. The trial continues next week.
</TEXT>
