<HEADLINE>The good, bad and the highly intelligent.  Nevin happy to promote the `A' level team</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635162</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLISH football would be entitled to mark the end of this year with unfettered
enthusiasm. The game in the south took a beating from allegations of bribery,
sickening acts of violence, and wretched cases of drug abuse. Some of the most
influential people
, George Graham and Eric Cantona, in particular, took centre stage at times
during the last 12 months and did no more than scythe the legs from football
which spent a lot of time prostrate in a mire of sleaze.
Fingers remain pointed at some players, but the game is recovering, and with
the European Championship finals to be played in various parts of England in
the summer, hopefully the stench of decaying morals will clear.
Many of the world's finest players will vie for our attention and football
could be a joyous occasion again, provided, of course, none of us allow the
finals to be hijacked and used as a platform for the unspeakable creatures sent
out by extreme right gro
ups. Football has been blighted by these contemptibles, but they are not a
product of the sport which often feels alone in trying to cope with the problem.
The return of Scotland to Wembley offers a platform for abuse, and society will
have to help to deal with the shameful organisations who have attached
themselves to a sport which has shown itself capable of creating its own
monsters. It would be a dreadfu
l shame if football is dragged further down at a time when the signs seem to be
suggesting that through the vigilance and concern of the Professional
Footballers' Association good might be triumphing over evil.
The PFA are conscious of the sport's need to project an acceptable image, and
as you would imagine, they are anxious to protect the rights of their members.
With 100% membership, they are a potent and influential union in these times
when the power of the
people has been eroded in most other professions.
The PFA also are a well financed body - since '92, when the players threatened
to strike, the PFA have been taking a percentage of money brought in through
deals with television companies, whose views are given credence within the
English game's administr
aton.
Indeed, the association are succeeding in pressing for changes within the
development programmes employed in England. For years, the Charles Hughes'
method has been the modus operandi, but the players' union - believing that
system to be outdated - have c
hallenged conventional thought and are trying to force their own psychology on
the authority.
The PFA's chief executive, Gordon Taylor, who also is chairman of the
federation of football unions throughout the world, FIFPRO, has emerged as a
formidable and respected leader, but he benefits from having around him a team
equally adept. Among them can
be found Scotland international winger Pat Nevin, who is in his third year as
chairman.
The 32-year-old Tranmere Rovers player has passed beyond feeling shocked by the
worst excesses of players unable to cope either with their fame or wealth, but
familiarity has not dulled his compassion and he remains supportive of the
members.
Nevertheless, the former Clyde, Chelsea, and Everton player, does wince
whenever a Vinny Jones speaks or allows a newspaper to use his name at the head
of a column. Nevin, though, was one of the first in the modern game whose
lifestyle challenged the wide
ly held belief that footballers had their brains in their feet.
Jones and Nevin, an incongruous pairing. Like Neanderthal Man meets Renaissance
Man, or blind rage and calm reason. However, Nevin, who would prefer to study
the classic line of the marble nose on Michelangelo's David, while Jones might
be unable to resis
t an urge to bite it, feels the denigration of the footballer has gone far
enough. It is time, he believes, to look at the positive.
Nevertheless, he did admit some players, who use their brains every day of the
week, and not just Saturdays, found life in the dressing room easier if they
disguised any academic prowess. This tendency to underplay intelligence perhaps
helped to perpetuat
e the myth that footballers are dullards. But Nevin claims the opposite, and
has statistics to back his call.
Two years ago, he says, the PFA did a check and found that more than half of
the YT kids coming into the game were capable of achieving `A' standard in four
or more levels. The PFA-driven youth training scheme - 93% of the young players
took exams which w
ere the equivalent of two A level passes - was hailed as the top one anywhere
in Britain.
All young players coming into the English game have to take national or general
national vocational qualifications which are accepted by universities, with the
PFA putting #500,000 into the scheme. Rightly, they are proud of their results.
``Hopefully we are smart enough to look at society and realise what is
happening,'' Nevin said, ``and we try to help players to avoid the various
dangers. For every nasty piece of work in our game who makes it on to the front
pages, there are dozens of go
od, honest, and decent players who work hard within their communities.
``The great majority of players carry their responsibilities well, some don't.
That is the reality, but I know the media are not generally interested in that
side of our game.''
While it is the PFA's priority to work for, and to protect, their members,
Nevin accepts the union must also be mindful of the game's needs and it could
be to everyone's benefit that there is a greater intelligence emerging within,
even if the behaviour o
f a very small minority attracts a disproportionate amount of attention.
That is a measure of the society in which we all live but, quietly and
effectively, Nevin and his people are working to strengthen the foundations.
``It might also be worth pointing out that while the problems of alcohol and
drug abuse grow in society, it seems that football is attracting fewer kids
with any of these difficulties,'' he said.
``We offer courses and try to educate players on the problems of drugs,
alcohol, gambling, and various other topics, because footballers do tend to
have a lot of time on their hands.
``It might not be ideal for clubs to have young players for a short spell each
day and then expect them to do the right things when they are away from the
ground, so we try to help in this respect. As a union we are concerned about
the dangers players fac
e.''
The PFA offer a wide range of courses, including business studies, chiropody,
langauges, arts, massage, the London taxi knowledge, politics, as well as
Christian ministry, and they have given 794 education grants costing #300,000
already this year.
With players willing to learn, the game in England seems healthy and is
enhanced by the willingness of European players to sign up and play before
increasing attendances.
The PFA know a certain level of intelligence is required to play the modern
game properly, and although no-one is suggesting that soon only nuclear
scientists might have the mental capacity to play, the fact is that footballers
capable of original thought
will prosper.
``I believe most players realise a gap has developed between them and the
Europeans,'' Nevin said, ``but when clubs are banned from Europe for five
years, as the English were, you must accept that game will fall 10 years behind.
``However, English clubs have had serious problems in dealing with the
three-foreigner rule while playing in Europe, but it is also true that, while
in exile, teams like Wimbledon, Crystal Palace, and Sheffield United came to
the fore and their style of p
lay did not help.
``English football did not grow in that period, but I think an increasing
awarensss of what is needed and the influx of European players is helping to
shatter the public perception that there is a lack of intelligence in football.
``That intelligence must also be evident in coaching, which is absolutely
essential.''
</TEXT>
