<HEADLINE>They're the ones to watch.</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635163</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Who will be the rising stars of the New Year, the up
and coming movers and shakers of arts, industry,
science and education? Here, and on the next two pages, Herald specialists
select their tips for the top.
POP/ROCK: DAVID BELCHER
FORD KIERNAN. Pasty-faced all-round Glaswegian comedy genius, whether in live
stand-up with partner John Paul Leach, as an impressionist on Radio Scotland's
On The Ball, or as an actor. See him as one of the stars of BBC Scotland's
forthcoming Pulp Video
series.
ONE DOVE. Most of their 1995 was written off following vocalist Dot being badly
injured in a car accident. Then their record company, London, dropped them.
When the band's long-delayed second album surfaces, however, you can be fairly
sure it will be one
of 1996's healing highlights.
LUNGLEG. Green Day? Don't talk to me about pretend-punk laddies from America
when Scotland's got the real thing in the form of raucous rrrumpus-burrrds
Lungleg.
EARTHLING. Trip-rapper Earthling is what the much-lauded Tricky would be like
if he possessed brains in his head and read books, ie thought-provokingly
propulsive.
GANGER. Hailing from Perth and Glasgow, Ganger are an intriguing blend of
old-time psychedelia and slightly less old-time Kraut-rock.
BIS. Soberingly young, this teenage male-female Scottish trio are vaguely
reminiscent of the Beastie Boys and sort of like Huggy Bear. But they're a lot
more pop-orientated than either.
DANCE: MARY BRENNAN
MARK BALDWIN. His background is essentially rooted in contemporary movement -
he danced with Rambert before beginning to choreograph for them - yet he has a
real feel for the lines and possibilities of classical ballet. the best news is
Scottish Ballet re
cently secured his talents as choreographer-in-residence.
MATTHEW BOURNE. In recent years, Bourne and his company - Adventures In Motion
Pictures - have staged radically fresh versions of such classics as The
Nutcracker and a La Sylphide set amidst Glasgow tenements.
NEVILLE CAMPBELL. As well as being a fine choreographer, he has an impressive
track record in getting projects off the ground - Phoenix Dance Company is just
one instance, more recently he was involved in new initiatives in South Africa
- so hopes are hig
h for the future of a revamped Dundee Rep Dance Company under his artistic
directorship.
DEIN PERRY. The Aussie wizard booted tap dance out of yesterday's top hat and
tails and slammed it bang up to date in denims and Blundstones. Choreographer
and leader of Tap Dogs, Perry looks set for international recognition in '96
when the company retur
ns - by popular demand - for a further stint in London.
DANCE BASE. Still located within Edinburgh's Assembly Rooms - though keen to
acquire its own premises - it represents an increasingly significant focal
point and support structure for dance-makers in the city and beyond.
ICE DANCE. The new year looks like being the year of the big ice spectacular.
Theatres across the country will hastily freeze their stages to accommodate
classic ballets and popular stories.
FASHION: JOHN DAVIDSON
NINA BOSCH. What's new in modelling? The ingenue.  In time for the
international shows last October, little Nina had her hair cut to an elfin
crop, perfectly complimentary her quirky features and gamine charm.
GUINEVERE VAN FEENUS. Who is that girl? This was the question on every fashion
editor's lips when this lass walked on to the runway at the Ghost show in New
York last November. Blonde and intriguingly hesitant, yet more curvey than
truly waiflike, Guinev
ere has the mystique of a true cover star.
JOHN GALLIANO. Time-served fashion maniac, and for the third time British
Designer of the Year, John Galliano is poised to disrupt the elegant calm of
Paris when he sends out his first Haute Couture collection for the house of
Givenchy at the later this m
onth.
JO GORDON. Every million years or so, Joan Burstein of Browns boutique in
London devotes her windows to some extraordinary fashion discovery. And right
now the low-voltage spotlights are being turned on the surreal headgear of Jo
Gordon, the hottest name
in millinery.
HARVEY NICHOLS. Is it opening? Is it not? Knightsbridge's most exclusive high
fashion store is absolutely, fabulously, definitely, maybe coming to Scotland.
Sites are all but secured in both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
TOM FORD. Suddenly Gucci is the name on the lips of every dedicated follower of
fashion. And it's all the doing of Tom Ford, the American who has in just two
seasons made Gucci the hottest, hippest thing in Italian fashion with skinny
satin shirts and vel
vet hipsters.
POLITICS: ROBBIE DINWOODIE
HELEN LIDDELL. Ms Liddell only entered Parliament in 1994. Expect her to
achieve spectacularly high office in 1996. The former newspaper industry
executive has shaken off links with doomed magnate Robert Maxwell to become the
most striking Scots talent on
the Shadow team.
NICOLA STURGEON. Absurdly young, 26, Parliamentary candidate, close friend of
by-election victor Roseanna Cunningham, and now adopted for the SNP in previous
Jim Sillars fiefdom of Govan. Irvine-born solicitor and senior party office
bearer - youth and en
ergy are her tautologous portfolios - she might not have much chance in normal
circumstances. But now that civil war has broken out in Labour ranks over the
Watson-Sarwar contest, who knows?
ADAM BRUCE. Tory high-flier of whom great things are expected. Also 26, he will
fight Liberal Democrat MP Menzies Campbell in North-East Fife at the next
General Election. Tories are calling this a target seat and predicting great
things for their man, th
e son of the Earl of Elgin.
MICHAEL MOORE. Inherits Sir David Steel's redoubt in Tweeddale. A gangling
financial wizard, he is Scottish Liberal Democrat spokesman on small business
and employment.
CATHERINE TAYLOR. Wishaw-born, this student of geography and international
relations at St Andrew's was marked out for political greatness when at the age
of 21 she was elected to the party's national executive. A definite career
high-flier. As soon as sh
e finishes her exams.
STEPHEN HENDRY. Fledgling politican, thanks to his manager embroiling him in
party politics by claiming that he would quit Scotland if Labour created a
tax-raising Parliament. Having achieved everything in snooker, Mr Hendry will
this year come out for Sc
ottish Independence and give a large proportion of his accumulated wealth to
Hearts . . . perhaps.
SCIENCE:  JOE DONNELLY
MARC ANDREESSEN. At 24, Andreessen is the founder of Netscape Communications
Corporation and developed the Mosaic Netscape Navigator. This coming year will
see a huge increase in the number of PCs and new entrants to the web. Most will
use the Andreessen
system.
BILL GATES. Last year his Microsoft Corporation's Windows 95 launch was a
world-wide event. A substantial proportion of PCs use the Windows system or its
predecessors.
DAN GOLDIN. Space is more accessible these days thanks to Goldin, whose job, as
head of NASA is to keep space missions going. In 1996, Goldin's team will
achieve a rendezvous with the giant asteroid Eros which passes close to the
earth in February. There
will also be two trips to survey and land on Mars.
TOM McEWAN. An engineer at Lawrence Livermore Labs in the US, McEwan developed
a tiny, cheap radar which uses hardly any power.
OLIVER PEEBLES. A recombinant DBNA specialist from Slammanan, he has developed
a new way of manufacturing plastic. He uses transgenic bacteria to manufacture
polymers which are quite easily turned into biodegradable plastic.
Dr DAVID FLINT. Dr Flint, of the Hannah Research Institute in Ayr, has
developed cells which manufacture antibodies to destroy fat. The cells work in
the same way as immunisation, and a single dose can reduce fat by up to 30% as
a treatment for obese peop
le
JAZZ: ALISON KERR
DIANA KRALL. Harry Connick Jr is old hat: Canadian Krall is the new pretender
to the young glam pianist-singer throne.
THE GLASGOW JAZZ CO-OP. This organisation was set up by members of the former
Glasgow Society of Musicians. In 1995 they put their money where their mouths
were with four successful concerts featuring out-of-town musicians, who would
otherwise not have ha
d a platform in Glasgow.
NATIONAL JAZZ INSTITUTE. This new venture, based at Jordanhill College is to be
Scotland's answer to the USA's celebrated Berklee College. Former Berklee
student Tommy Smith was instrumental in devising the course, and the support of
other big names like
the American vibes player Gary Burton has also been promised. The course begins
in January.
ZEPHYR. Retired businessman John Bune decided to use the money he'd made on the
Stock Market to invest in his favourite jazz pianist, the superb Brian Lemon.
He set up a record company called Zephyr, and gave Lemon carte blanche when it
came to choosing s
idemen and tunes.
NAIRN INTERNATIONAL JAZZ FESTIVAL. Inspired by the film Jazz on a Summer's Day,
local businessman Ken Ramage has been organising world class jazz concerts in
beautiful surroundings for two years now.
DAVE MILLIGAN. This piano-playing Borders boy has already impressed both the
jazz and folk communities; establishing himself on the Scottish music scene not
only as a soloist and an accompanist to such stars as Scott Hamilton, but also
as co-leader of the
folk group Bachue Cafe.
ART: CLARE HENRY
DAMIAN HIRST. The sheep and shark showman, who performs in the arena of
taxidermy, made his name and #20,000 at the Turner Prize. But is it art?
MATTHEW DALZIELL and LOUISE SCULLION. Scotland's answer to the Venice Biennale
this year presented a work called Sargassum which you can see at Glasgow's CCA
until January 28. Their next works will appear in Lyon, France, and beside the
M8.
DEJAN SUDJIC. The newly appointed director of Glasgow Capital of Architecture
and Design 1999, whose name we will all have to learn how to say and spell.
ADRIAN WISZNIEWSKI. He is a busy bee, currently juggling six - or is it seven?
- commissions, including two paintings for Liverpool Cathedral, a portrait of
the three Citizens' directors (on view in Glasgow's People Palace), the
restaurant walls of Glasgo
w's Gallery of Modern Art, and a book by George MacKay Brown.
JULIE ROBERT. Scotland's first winner of the SAC British School at Rome
scholarship, has left us for a year's dolce vita.
MONET. He took Chicago by storn, causing queues around the block by 8am. At
least 900,000 people visited his exhibition, the biggest and best America has
ever seen...... and perhaps the last of its kind ever.
THEATRE: MARK FISHER
DAVID HARROWER. This young playwright has wasted no time in making his mark.
His debut drama, the sparse, linguistically precise Knives in Hens, went down a
treat on a tour of the Highlands and Islands in the summer.
KATHRYN HOWDEN. Winner of a Herald Angel award for her role in the Traverse
Theatre's Bondagers, Howden has proved herself a tremendously versatile
performer.
STEWART LAING. One of the Citizens' Theatre's stable of
designers-turned-directors, Laing attracted attention for Strindberg's The
Father, followed by an unsettling version of the little-known Sicilian play The
She Wolf. But all of this is as nothing comp
ared to the $17m musical he is going to stage on Broadway in 1996.
NICOLA McCARTNEY. Her 1995 Mayfest production of her own play, Easy, about date
rape demonstrated an ear for everyday language as well as a readiness to
address sensitive issues. KENNY MILLER. The name may be familiar but the
occupation could change. The
Citizens' Theatre design boss flexed his directorial muscle for the first time
on a well-received studio production of Look Back in Anger in November and now
he's ready for more in the director's chair.
ANTHONY NEILSON. Son of actor/director Sandy, he has established a reputation
for writing tough, uncompromising and explicit scripts for the stage and
screen. His play Penetrator was recently revived at the Tron, which has also
commissioned a new one from
him.
</TEXT>
