<TEXT>
GET them away from the TV, put Barbie down, switch off the computer; we're in
the middle of the long haul from Christmas Day to January 2, when things get
back to normal, and it's time to get them out of the house.
Many of Scotland's normal attractions, parks, and centres stay open over the
holiday period, but check out some of the special events for kids.
The place to be is definitely Edinburgh, with the third Hogmanay celebrations
now under way to Tuesday, accompanied this year by the special Kids' Hogmanay
events. Details from 0891 881996 (39p per minute cheap rate, 49p all other
times), but in the city
centre you might like to try the carnival, Waterloo Place, 4pm to 11pm; the
coach and pony rides from the Tron, High Street, and the carousels on the Royal
Mile, noon to 5pm during the holiday; the free Ghosty Stories told at the Tron
Kirk, High Street, 4
pm to 6pm (book on 0131-557 4700), and the Readiscovery Book Bus on the High
Street, noon to 5pm. Or nip across the tracks to the dry ice rink on the roof
of the Waverley Shopping Centre (noon to 9pm). And on New Year's Day and
January 2 you could take in
the Hot Air Balloons at Arthur's Seat from 1pm.
Children's Hogmanay shows are the Happy Gang, Bedlam Theatre, Forrest Road, 2pm
and 4pm, #3.50; the Tales of Jemima Puddleduck, Netherbow Theatre, High Street,
11am and 2.30pm, #3 (concessions #2); and shows from Magic Bob (Bedlam Theatre,
Hogmanay, New Y
ear's Day, #3.50) and writer Aileen Paterson reading her own books in the
Maisie Story Hour today at the Netherbow Theatre, High Street, 1pm, #3 (#2).
Booking for the shows from Edinburgh and Scotland Information Centre, 0131-558
1072; Ticketline on 0131-
220 4349 or Netherbow Theatre, 0131-556 9579.
Sports-mad youngsters will be keen on the big events over the holiday period.
Edinburgh's Hogmanay gives us the Triathlon at Arthur's Seat, 11.30am and 1pm,
New Year's Day - or they could enter the Kids Duathlon which starts at 11.30am
and costs #3.
The Bank of Scotland Scottish Junior Open Squash Championships brings together
the world's top young players at Colinton Castle and National Squash Centre, 70
Katesmill Road, Edinburgh, today and tomorrow. Entry free. 0131-317 7343 for
details.
The traditional New Year Athletics Gala at the Meadowbank Stadium, Edinburgh,
is two days of track events with professional athletes, Scots footballers, and
rugby players taking part in fun runs, and the hard-training Scottish girls'
squad competing again
st male athletes in a gruelling series of races. From noon each day on
Saturday, December 30 and Sunday, December 31.
In Crieff, the Strathearn Harriers hold their annual New Year's Day fun run at
8am, mince pies and hot toddies in the Somerfield supermarket car park to get
everyone off to a good start.
There are pantos all over Scotland until well into the New Year; check with
your local theatre, but the pick of the other shows must include the Singing
Kettle Christmas Party at the SECC, Finnieston Quay, Glasgow today at 11am and
2pm; Tuesday and Wednes
day, January 2 and 3, at 2pm and 6pm; Thursday, January 4 at 2pm only. Tickets
#4-#7; family tickets #15-#21; information on 01337 831121.
Christmas is also a good time for a visit to the circus: try the Bobby Roberts
super circus at the SECC, Finnieston Quay, Glasgow, until Saturday, January 14;
performances most days 2.30pm and 7.30pm, tickets #9/#6 (concessions #6/#4),
0141-248 9999 for i
nformation. Or try the Christmas and New Year Carnival, also at the SECC,
1.45pm to 10.45pm until January 14: rides and fairground fun for #1.
In Aviemore, the Stathspey Steam Railway is running Mince Pie Specials from
tomorrow to January 2; 01479 810363 for details.
Or take the kids on a Festive Tree Trail at the Royal Museum of Scotland,
Chambers Street, Edinburgh; if you can spot all 10 trees you're up for prizes.
Today (10am-5pm), and then on Tuesday, January 2 (10am-8pm), entry free.
