<DOCID>GH951230-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sack for engineer who came up short on #4.5m building</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONSTRUCTION site engineer was sacked after the length of a #4.5m building
was found to be 14 millimetres short.
Mrs Michelle Morgan, who lost her claim of unfair diswmissal by Renfrew-based
Amec Construction Scotland Ltd, also failed to allow properly for the slope of
the site, an industrial tribunal in Glasgow heard.
She had been working on the Molecular Medicine Centre, a six-storey building at
Western General Hospital and Edinburgh University.
Mrs Morgan, who surveyed the site before construction work began, complained
about staff shortages. She was promoted from assistant site engineer to site
engineer during the project.
Three months later, the client's architect complained about engineering
standards. A meeting was held about lack of progress, poor workmanship, and
poor management.
Mrs Morgan accepted she was responsible for errors, including failing to make
sufficient compensation for the slope in setting out the original base line.
She claimed she had been expected to carry out too many duties when she had
first been allocated to
the contract.
Mrs Morgan was given a written warning but further investigation by the
company's senior engineers revealed the extent and consequences of these errors.
She was called to a disciplinary interview, where she accepted she had made
certain errors, including a mistake in the length of the building. She admitted
it was 14mm short. She said she had discussed the matter with the quality
assurance manager and the
y decided not to report it in the hope the error could be ``ironed out'' as the
construction proceeded.
She said some of the problems had been caused while she was on holiday and she
blamed inefficient contractors.
However, she was sacked for failing to carry out her duties as site engineer
competently and accurately, failing to report an error in the designed length
of the building, and colluding with a colleague to conceal the error.
The tribunal said it was satisfied that, faced with an extremely irate client
on a prestigious contract worth #4.5m, the company, having investigated the
issue thoroughly, was entitled reasonably to conclude there had been
significant failures on the part
of Mrs Morgan in the setting-out process and it was entitled to dismiss her.
The tribunal ruled that Mrs Morgan of Dumbarton Road, Old Kilpatrick, was not
unfairly dismissed and rejected her complaint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
