<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sayanora to the record</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN maxi yacht Sayonara won the Sydney-to-Hobart bluewater classic but
missed out on breaking the race record that has stood for 20 years.
Sayonara, owned and skippered by American computer billionaire Larry Ellison
and with media magnate Rupert Murdoch aboard as a crew member, arrived at
Hobart's Constitution Dock shortly before 3am yesterday.
The race record of 2days 14hr 36min 56sec for the 720-mile journey down the
east coast of Australia was set by American skipper Jim Kilroy in Kialoa III in
1975. The Bruce Farr-designed Sayonara missed it by almost 10 hours.
Light winds yesterday meant Sayonara advanced only 25 nautical miles in eight
hours. Ellison described the race as the ``most terrifying and frustrating'' of
his career.
Crossing turbulent Bass Strait when winds gusted at up to 45 knots was the
terrifying part, while ``looking at the lights of Tasmania for six hours and
not seeing them move'' was the most frustrating.
Australian maxi Brindabella was runner-up for the second successive year - two
hours behind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US Army in race to finish bridge.  Deadline set for key link</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Friday
US ARMY engineers are racing against a deadline of noon tomorrow to complete a
bridge over a flood-swollen river, the last link in a route for thousands of
American troops to enter Bosnia.
A double pontoon bridge spanning the 300yd-wide Sava river separating Croatia
and Bosnia is said to be their biggest such project since the Second World War.
After winter storms and floods turned military camps into a muddy quagmire, the
engineers' commander today ordered the bridge to be in place by midday tomorrow.
It will plug a gap in a military corridor to bring nearly 20,000 American
troops from bases in Germany to Bosnia to help implement the Dayton peace
accord.
The Americans will roll across the steel and aluminium floating bridge in
tanks, trucks, and armoured cars to their base at Tuzla in north Bosnia.
The US contingent will make up one-third of the Nato-led peace Implementation
Force (Ifor), whose commander, Admiral Leighton Smith, said today he was
convinced that Bosnians wanted an end to their savage 43-month  conflict.
In Banja Luka, the biggest town held by separatist Bosnian Serbs, he said: ``We
are extraordinarily encouraged by what we see. I am absolutely convinced that
the people of this country want peace.''
Banja Luka was once dubbed a ``heart of darkness'' because of heavy ``ethnic
cleansing'', the forcible expulsions by Serbs of Muslim and Croat civilians
from the area.
General William Nash, chief of the US contingent to Ifor, flew to the
bridgehead near Zupanja in Croatia today.
``The bridge is going to go in tomorrow,'' he said. ``Pat, we've gotta make it
happen now,'' he told rear commander General Pat O'Neal.
Work on the bridge - actually two, to allow traffic in both directions - ground
to a halt yesterday when the swollen Sava burst its banks.
Today, however, General Nash ordered four Chinook helicopters to start dropping
bridge sections into the fast-flowing river, which were then built up on both
sides for connecting together tomorrow.
Admiral Smith held two hours of talks with Mayor Predrag Radic and the vice
president of the so-called Bosnian Serb assembly, Nikola Koljevic.
He said the admiral had promised security for Serbs in Sarajevo and elsewhere,
who fear for their safety when the areas they occupy come under Muslim-led
government control under the peace pacts.
Serbs are already fleeing the capital, some taking their dead with them, and
many say they will set fire to their homes rather than let Muslims occupy them.
Koljevic told reporters he was confident there would be no return to
war.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sharp exit in style</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974635169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE'S chief constable, Leslie Sharp, jetted out of Glasgow eight days
ago for a pre-retirement break in the sun with his wife and stepped back on to
the tarmac yesterday as Sir Leslie, to face a posse of newsmen.
He obviously knew the honour was in the post but he was patently not prepared -
probably for the first time in the last four and a half years - for the media
reception. Within minutes he was relaxed and enjoying the limelight,
wisecracking with a press co
rps he had won to his cause.
``I did not think this would happen for me because for various reasons I have
never been president of the chief officers' association in Scotland and I am
retiring early. Having said that I am very pleased,'' he said.
``It is good to have your work recognised but people should remember there were
25,000 officers in the Met, 6000 in West Midlands, 1200 in Cumbria and 7000 in
Strathclyde, and chief constables get to the top on the backs of others. It is
the work of all t
hese people which is being recognised. The chief gets the sack if things go
wrong and the kudos if things go right. In the last four and a half years in
Strathclyde I think things have gone right.''
Sir Leslie, 59, said he and his wife Audrey had decided to snatch a last minute
holiday to become used to the idea of retirement after 40 years in the police.
He plans to leave office at midnight in George Square on Hogmanay ``with a
glass in my hand''.
``I believe that my time here has been a success,'' he added.
``I do believe Strathclyde is a better place to live now than it was when I
arrived.''
When asked if he had any advice for his successor, Mr John Orr, Sir Leslie
said: ``John Orr is a very experienced officer and needs no advice from me. I
would say to him that the key for the right hand top drawer is in the left hand
drawer because the rig
ht hand one does not lock.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
