<HEADLINE>Kjus is king of the downhill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORWAY'S Lasse Kjus yesterday won the men's World Cup downhill in Italy and
later claimed he tried not to think about the overall competition,
concentrating instead on each race as it came along.
Kjus won in a time of one minute 55.35 seconds from Andreas Schifferer, of
Austria, second in 1-55.66, with Canada's Ed Podivinsky third in 1-55.86.
The Canadian said that Kjus's downhill win was likely to force some of the top
racers in the discipline to change their training programmes over the summer.
``I think the future of downhilling is to be more technically proficient, like
the Norwegians are now,'' he said. ``I think a lot of skiers will be doing more
technical training over the summer.''
Podivinsky, only twenty-eighth fastest in Thursday's final training session,
said he had then exchanged his skis for ones more suitable to ice. ``I cared
more about remaining on the course than speed,'' said Podivinsky, the 1994
Olympic downhill bronze me
dallist.
``This was the most difficult course we have raced in the last two years,'' he
added. ``It's amazing Bormio could hold a race with no snow in the valley.''
Schifferer, just 21 and in his first World Cup season, seemed as surprised as
anyone to be on the podium after starting a distant thirty-fifth. He had been
sixth in Val d'Isere after a poor debut race in Vail and then was too tense in
Val Gardena.
Leading finishers: 1, L Kjus (Norway) 1min 55.35sec; 2, A Schifferer (Austria)
1-55.66; 3, E Podivinsky (Canada) 1-55.86. British: 30, G Bell 1-58.30; 50, A
Freshwater 2-01.59.
Leading overall standings: 1, Kjus 885pt; 2, M von Gruenigen (Switzerland) 498;
3, H Knaus (Austria) 390.
Downhill World Cup standings (after four races): 1, L Alphand (France) 263; 2,
Kjus 225; 3 (equal), P Ortlieb (Austria), X Gigandet (Switzerland) 175.
Nations Cup standings: 1, Austria 5089; 2, Switzerland 3040; 3, Italy 2227.
q SWEDEN'S Pernilla Wiberg yestrday picked up where she left off before
Christmas by winning her second consecutive World Cup slalom at Semmering in
Austria.
The 25-year-old Swede, after a frustrating start to her season, showed that she
has definitely found her form by powering her way down the Hirschenkogel course
in a two-run combined time of 1min 40.28sec. It was her thirteenth career
victory and her secon
d in a row.
Switzerland's Karin Roten used the fastest time of the second run to vault from
fifth to second, registering her first World Cup podium finish with 1-41.20.
Austria's Elfi Eder, winner of the first two slaloms of the season, took third
in 1-41.78, much to
the delight of the partisan crowd lining the sun-drenched course.
Leading finishers: 1, P Wiberg (Sweden) 1min 40.28sec; 2, K Roten (Switzerland)
1-41.20; 3, E Eder (Austria) 1-41.76. British: E Carrick-Anderson did not
qualify for second run.
Leading slalom standings: 1, Eder 260pt; 2, Wiberg 200; 3, U Hrovat (Slovenia)
192.
Overall World Cup standings: 1, A Meissnitzer (Austria) 488; 2, A Wachter
(Austria) 478; 3, M Ertl (Germany) 433.
