<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pilarski sets a tough schedule</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAL Pilarski is an increasingly rare phenomenon among his fellow members of
the British Alpine Ski Team.
While more skiers of his age graduate to the team from spells with academies in
the USA, Norway, Austria, or France, Pilarski - who has almost halved his world
ranking in only seven starts since joining the Hanson &amp; Robertson British FIS
team in the summe
r - is a truly home bred skier.
Personal bests in his most recent races in North America are the fruits of
tough summer training. Now he is hopeful of reaching the World's top 350 to
achieve Europa Cup qualification from his next series of European FIS races
early in the new year.
At just 18, he has a second tilt at the World Junior championships in
Switzerland in March in his sights, and believes he can achieve Britain's best
men's result of recent years, and a place in the top 15 in his preferred
discipline, the slalom.
His domestic targets include wins at the British Junior championships in Tignes
later that month, and to establish himself as one of Britain's top three men's
technical disciplines skiers.
Falkirk-based Pilarski took his first infant steps on skis on the local 100
metres or so of dry slope matting at Polmonthill.
If he has lacked the solid seasons on snow that schooling abroad offers, his
success to date and his impressive potential are a testament to elements of the
coaching set-up of Aberdeen Ski Club, who have pioneered long-term summer camps
on the Alpine glac
iers and a strong foundation in the most up-to-date techniques.
``I never let the fact that I have not been abroad to a ski academy bother
me,'' said Pilarski, who was tops in all three disciplines at last year's
British Junior championships. ``I knew it was always going to be the case.
``Now I have the opportunity to ski full time I'm not going to miss any
chances.''
Long term, his targets are the 1998, or realistically, the 2002 Olympics and a
place on the World Cup tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spring in call to Sinn Fein over killings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635172</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRELAND'S Deputy Prime Minister, Dick Spring, yesterday joined calls for Sinn
Fein to condemn terrorist-linked killings in Belfast.
He said the recent shootings - claimed to have been carried out by an
anti-drugs group with IRA connections - were ``a worrying feature in the whole
context of the Northern Ireland peace process''.
Mr Spring, who is Ireland's foreign minister and a key figure in political
developments surrounding the peace process, added: ``Reports from the security
forces would seem to point to paramilitary organisations.
``These incidents are obviously a worry. Whether or not they destabilise the
peace process remains to be seen. We would hope they would not continue.''
Asked in an Irish radio interview whether he would like to see the murders
condemned by Sinn Fein, Mr Spring said: ``I would like to see them condemned by
everybody.
``They are totally unacceptable, an affront to civilised society and, at the
end of the day, they are not going to contribute to what we all want to achieve
- the establishment of peace and democratic politics for the whole island.''
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams was under growing pressure yesterday to use his
influence to stop the killings and punishment beatings.
Alliance Party deputy leader Seamus Close said: ``As a leader, Gerry Adams must
lead and ensure that there are no more dead bodies or broken bones, no more
widows or orphans.''
The latest victim of the killer gangs, father-of-two Martin McCrory, 30, who
was shot in his Belfast home as he cradled his baby son in his arms on
Wednesday night, will be buried today.
</TEXT>
