<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let's drink to the survival of small taxation mercies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Aidan O"Carroll</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROM the National Insurance contribution (NIC) point of view, the Budget was
remarkable for what did not happen. In the run-up to the Chancellor's
pronouncement, rumours abounded that all taxable benefits in kind would become
subject to employers' NIC, cu
rrently 10%. As it turned out, the topic did not rear its ugly head at all, but
it may be a matter we will need to come back to.
The mis-match in treatment of NIC and PAYE on benefits in kind will not survive
what seems to be the inevitable closer working of the Inland Revenue and the
Contributions Agency. It is not only administratively inconvenient; it is a
revenue raising opport
unity going abegging. So if the Conservative Party does not cotton on to this,
Labour undoubtedly will.
Historically, benefits in kind are not included in pay for NIC purposes
because, when the legislation was first framed in the early sixties for the
graduated contributions scheme, they consisted of such things as free coal to
miners, the provision of boar
d and lodgings to farm workers and free canteen facilities for company staff.
There was no wish to impose an NIC liability on these and similar items.
There was also the problem of valuation. NIC liabilities traditionally arise at
the time of payment, and employers would have needed instant valuations and
that was simply impractical if not impossible.
This hurdle has been eliminated to some extent by the introduction of the class
1A system of collecting employer contributions on company cars and fuel after
the end of the relevant tax year.
Benefits are now a regular feature of remuneration packages and for a
considerable number of employees they are of a significant value. But since
they are taxable there is no real logic in leaving them NIC-free.
The payment of NICs was not an important or costly issue until October 1985
when the ceiling on employers' contributions was removed. Previously they did
not have to pay NIC on wages above a certain limit, but the Government raised
billions of pounds by r
emoving this.
Since then, a large number of schemes have been developed using more and more
exotic means to avoid paying employers' NIC - predominantly in relation to
bonus payments.
The Contributions Agency has always been one or two steps behind these so, for
example, it legislated against bonuses paid in gilts in 1988, and those paid
through unit trusts or by way of certain life assurance policies in 1991. More
recently, it acted o
n gold bullion in December 1993, and gemstones and fine wine from August 1994.
Finally, from April this year, no doubt suffering from a high degree of
frustration, it has attempted to make any assets for which trading arrangements
exist liable to NIC.
Each of these moves, of course, came about only after much use of each specific
scheme.
Very few ``fat cats'' who were receiving large bonuses tended to keep fine
wines, gemstones or gold bullion. Instead, they encashed these and not only
avoided NIC but also didn't have to account for tax on the value for some time
after the tax year.
It was thought the agency had tired of this cat-and-mouse game and that the
present schemes using increasingly complex arrangements might have rattled it.
It was strongly felt it would take back the initiative and state that all
benefits in kind were subj
ect to NIC with possibly one or two minor exceptions, such as luncheon and
healthcare vouchers.
It had the Inland Revenue legislation and well-established procedures relating
to the payment of tax on benefits to help it. A class 1A type of contribution
would not have placed too great an administrative burden on employers who are
already going to hav
e to provide a lot of the information required for self-assessment tax
purposes. However, we heard nothing.
Perhaps, politically, it was too difficult to introduce what would, in effect,
be an expansion of the tax system to cover these benefits in kind and would hit
middle and higher income earners.
However, this leaves the UK with one of the cheapest social security systems in
Europe and we are almost unique in not charging contributions on all payments,
including benefits in kind.
In that sense, the Budget lived up to the Chancellor's claim that Britain is
the ``enterprise centre of Europe''. It is a significant saving for companies
with employees moving around the continent if they have a 10% social security
cost on only cash item
s rather than, for examaple, around 40% on all emoluments which can be due in
France, Belgium and Italy. With that in mind, perhaps we should drink to small
mercies!
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
