<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A hat, a hug, and a roaring fire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Interviews: Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE most honest answer you can give to anyone who asks you how you're keeping
warm this winter is, simply, that you are not. Everybody is frozen. Frosted
panes and burst pipes plague a struggling nation. Some people are scared of
putting the heating off
in case the bath fills up. Others are scared to put it on because it costs.
Scotland, currently, is as cold as Moscow and just as carefree. From
warehousemen, farmers, and Big Issue vendors, to lawyers, politicians, and
housewives, all are equal in their
suffering. Here, a few members of the public give away their secrets for
combating lower temperatures. Needs must, it's time to pitch in together.
n What's the best way to keep warm? Body heat - David Ewing, Supervisor
n We've got a Calor gas heater in the back room, we take turns to run in and
get a heat - Janice, city centre shop assistant
n I've tried to keep wearing a suit to work, but it's just not warm enough. I
don't have any thermals, so I've got a jumper over my shirt and tie all the
time - John Lewis, office clerk
n When I was broke and couldn't afford to buy a Powercard to stick in my meter,
I burned newspapers in my kitchen sink to heat up the house. I'm thinking of
doing that again - Jim Meek, unemployed
n Exercise - Gillian Peters, trainer
n How do I keep warm? I've borrowed my boss's fan heater - she's on holiday -
and I've plugged it in under my desk - Sarah McPherson, secretary
n By not coming in to The Herald - Colleague David Belcher complaining about
the working temperature
n Eat a lot, keep yourself stoked up with fuel, lots of soup and stodge -
Michael Robb, barman
n Get a dog. Cats are no good unless you skin them - Kate Smart, manageress
n You lose 75% of body heat through your head, so always wear a hat. And wear
layers of clothing rather than one heavy outfit - Herald Fashion Editor John
Davidson
n Bring the duvet through from the bedroom and curl up in front of the fire -
Kirsty Wilson, hairdresser
n Have a hug - Steven Urquhart, romantic
n Stay off work - Jim McAlpine, bookie
n If you were out on exercise you would find a hollow, perhaps under a ridge,
or a natural dugout, and you would lie down there, out of the wind. It's the
wind that kills. On the other hand, in snow you must never lie down, or stop,
you must keep moving o
r you will freeze to death - Anonymous TA Officer
n A real log fire and a furry rug - Ailsa Cunninghame, nurse
n I always wear at least three pairs of woolly socks and a big pair of boots.
If your feet are warm the rest of you is too - Naseem Ahmad, grocer
n Stay in bed with someone you love - Margaret Norris, department store customer
n A plate of porridge in the morning - Sauchiehall Street pedestrian
n Well you could always go abroad someplace nice, like that Princess Di off to
Antigua, if you had the same money - Joe McNulty, fruiterer
</TEXT>
