<HEADLINE>Wealthy got wealthier in 1995.  Survey shows Stagecoach topping share performance league for second successive year</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN CALDER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S new breed of millionaires got even richer during 1995. A study of
the performance of the shares of top Scottish firms has revealed Stagecoach
heads the listing for the second year in a row.
The last 12 months have seen the brother and sister partnership of Brian Souter
and Ann Gloag add more than #80m to their personal wealth as shares in the
Perth-based company soared. That works out at a staggering #1.5m a week between
them, or #225,000 a
day.
And the Wiseman brothers will no doubt be toasting in 1996 with a pinta as
shares in their East Kilbride-based dairy business shot up to net the trio a
cool #25m.
But whisky firms will be glad to see the back of 1995. Producers of two of the
biggest brands - Famous Grouse and The Macallan - topped the list of
under-performers. The reduction in duty in the Chancellor's November Budget
should help in 1996.
The study, conducted by Edinburgh stockbroker Tilney &amp; Co, shows that shares in
Stagecoach accelerated from 225p at the beginning of January to 354p by the end
of the year. That rise out-performed the FTSE All-Share index by 27%. It also
took the market v
alue of Stagecoach, Britain's biggest bus operator, up by more than #190m to
nearly #530m.
Brian Souter, the firm's 41-year-old bus conductor turned executive chairman,
and his sister Ann Gloag, a nurse turned managing director, cashed in as they
are the two main shareholders. Mr Souter, who holds a 23.4% stake, added #44.8m
to his wealth takin
g the total value of his share in the business to #123.7m. Ms Gloag, who has
19.6%, gained #37m which took her stake to #103.6m.
``The shares analysis continues to prove that the wealthy can only get
wealthier,'' said Bill McCall, director with Tilney &amp; Co.
The stockbroking firm said most of the surge had come towards the end of the
year, following Stagecoach being awarded the contract to run Britain's largest
rail franchise - South West Trains.
The Royal Bank of Scotland was a close second in the performance stakes. Over
1995 its share price rose from 393p to 586p, out-performing the market by 23%.
Mr McCall said: ``This was mainly due to Scotland's biggest bank announcing
record profits earlier
in the year, and then becoming the subject of intense takeover speculation
towards the year-end.''
The Dundee-based food retailer Watson &amp; Philip shared second slot, with a 172p
rise in its shares over the year to 535p allowing it also to out-perform the
market by 23%.
Wiseman Dairies took fourth slot, with a 45p rise in its share price from 103p
to 148p. Its shares showed growth of 20% relative to the market. This rapid
rise added #35.2m to the value of the company - controlled by three brothers -
over 1995.
Alan Wiseman, the 44-year-old chairman who holds a 37% stake, gained #13m in
personal wealth, taking the total value of his share to #41m. Robert Wiseman,
aged 40, is managing director. He has a 31% share, which rose #10.9m over the
year to just under #35
m. Gavin Wiseman, the 38-year-old director who holds a 5.1% stake, saw his
share jump #1.8m to #5.6m.
Cairn Energy, the relatively unknown Edinburgh-based oil and gas exploration
company, was the fifth-best perfoming Scottish share. During 1995 its price
rose from 82p to 117p, allowing it to out-performed the market by 18%.
At the other end of the scale, 1995 was not a good year for whisky firms with
the price war squeezing margins as they battled desperately for market share.
Highland Distilleries which produces Famous Grouse, the second best selling UK
brand, has the unenviable record of being the biggest sinner. Its shares
plunged 120p to 323p - under-performing the market average by minus 38%.
Howden, based in Renfrew, reflected the pressures in the engineering sector as
it under-performed the market by minus 36% with a drop in share price over the
year from 93p to 67p.
Weir Group echoed its sector's slump as shares in Scotland's biggest
engineering firm dropped 67p from 213p.
Macallan-Glenlivet, which produces The Macallan also had a tough time. Its
shares tumbled from 211p to 190p.
Edinburgh Fund Managers was the fifth worst performer. Doubts over its future
ownership resulted in its shares falling 71p to 658p.
