<HEADLINE>RAVED BY THE BELLS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jonathon Wills</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635179</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jonathon Wills tries to pinpoint the best time to celebrate New Year and
decides any date can be a good excuse for a party
WHY is New Year when it is? Jews and Muslims don't celebrate it on January 1.
Nor do the Chinese. They pick more sensible dates, when there's some serious
evidence that the northern hemisphere really is recovering from winter. Until
1600.AD Scotland did t
he same. The civil and legal New Year was in March, when shoots of green were
re-appearing in more sheltered spots. In England they didn't change over to
January 1 until 1752.
Europe, ahead of the game as usual, had switched in the 16th century, when Pope
Gregory's men of science worked out that the old Julian calendar, drawn up by
one C.J Caesar (101-44 BC), had miscalculated the time it takes for the Sun to
complete one orbit
of the Earth. During a millenium and a half, this had put the clocks forward
by 10 days and a bit. Pope Gregory's boffins solved the problem by turning
October 5, 1582 into October 15, 1582. Bingo! They were back in sync with the
solar system.
Not us, though. Julius Caesar might once have united Europe, single currency
and all, but that had fallen to bits in 455.AD, when Rome was first-footed by
the Vandals. By 1582 even the Pope's writ no longer ran in England or Scotland,
what with the Reform
ation and all that.
Euro-sceptical Protestants were naturally a tad suspicious of some Italian
Godfather in a funny hat and a frock presuming to shorten their natural span by
10 days, which is what they assumed His Holiness intended.
Now, you can have a lot of fun in 10 days, getting rich, drunk, and begetting
heirs to the throne and what not. People over here didn't want to miss out on
10 whole days of that, especially with not having to go to Confession any more,
and who can blame t
hem? They might have missed New Year on March 1, for Heaven's sake!
Just as will happen with the new single currency, the offshore islanders
eventually fell into line and celebrated on the proper ``New Style'' date. On
Britain's own offshore islands, such as Shetland, resistance to changing the
calendar was even more mark
ed and prolonged.
On Foula (population 40), some people still celebrate Christmas and New Year on
the old style dates but, being Foula, they do it 12 days later, not 10. Until
the telephone and the Internet came along, it could take a while for messages
to reach Foula and
sometimes they were garbled.
Twenty years ago, when I lived in Unst, Britain's most northerly inhabited
island, we had it both ways. We celebrated Christmas, or Yule, on December 25,
New Year (or Newerdy) on January 1, ``Aald Yule'' on January 6 and ``Aald
Newerdy'' on January 11 or
12 or 13, depending on how well we'd recovered from Aald Christmas. The Unst
men liked a good celebration, although some of the womenfolk were less than
approving, and four opportunities to get a good dram in were better than two.
Lord knows there are few signs in a Shetland January, whatever date you pick,
that our sleet-blasted heath will ever sprout again. The worst of the winter is
still to come. There's no new grass until the middle of May and snow squalls
can hit us in the fi
rst week of June.
Until the men of science came along, priests, charlatans and mothers-in-law
were always propagating the dreadful fear that the Sun might not make another
orbit, if the Great Godfather in the Sky decided to punish the punters,
particularly the sons-in-law
, for their wickedness. True, it always had come back, but you never knew and
you never could tell, so you kept up the payments to the shamans who said they
knew how to make the necessary arrangements.
That's where Yule came in, long before the Christian shamans started up their
own fear-full racket, which shows no sign of waning despite over a century of
compulsory education.
My own theory is that Yule was nothing to do with New Year, particularly in the
far north. In pre-Christian times it was a time to light bonfires and torches
to scare off the evil ones, tempt the Sun back from the other side of the hill,
and also to sacri
fice stuff, say you're sorry and it won't happen again, and have a good
blowout. We are talking fertility rites and insurance policies here. People had
no idea whether it had worked until the spring - the real New Year - arrived.
Christmas, Hogmanay and the midwinter fire festivals which once were held all
over Scotland are basically the old Yule bolted onto new calendars and
religions. This is thoroughly confusing; some Eurocrat is probably working on a
scheme to standardise it a
ll. But there's no chance it can ever be sorted out at this late date, whatever
happens to British Summer Time. Just as well, because the duplicated,
overlapping celebrations make British winter time so much easier to bear.
Budget Day may have moved from March to November but the tax collectors still
follow their ancient, pagan calendar. Ever wondered why the income tax year
starts in early April? It's because by then they're pretty confident, as they
always have been, that
there actually will be a new crop of bannocks, salt beef, whisky, coal and salt
to get their dirty claws into. I must have been four and a half when first
woken up to bring in the New Year (New Style). My mother carried me to the
doorstep. It was cold, ev
en wrapped in a blanket. The sky was all stars. A church clock chimed down in
the village. I was grumpy, as I still am when roused from a deep sleep.
I couldn't see what all the fuss was about but at least my parents were both
being jolly at the same time, a pleasant change from the usual festive season
rows. Before I was put back to bed I had a symbolic slice of black bun, which
had arrived from Shetl
and in the post before Christmas. More importantly, my father gave me five bob,
a small fortune in 1952.
That was in Wheatley, Oxfordshire, where most people didn't even stay up for
The Bells. There were no first-footers. That was the trouble, as far as my
Lerwick-born mother was concerned. She liked living in England but around
Hogmanay she liked it less an
d pined for ``home''. That was the time of year when she indulged in what was
then a spectacular extravagance - long-distance telephone calls to Shetland.
At No 2 Russell Crescent, Lerwick, 600 miles away, there would be the usual
wild party in progress. A succession of jolly relatives came to the phone, to
bellow ``Happy New Year!'' and say things like ``Yus, yus, wir aa fine, foo's
du Caathie, an da man a
n da bairns?'' and ``Whit a terrible nicht o' wadder'' and then the three
minutes would be up for another 12 months.
It was another 11 years before my first Shetland Hogmanay, at the Lerwick
Market Cross. It was amazing: a huge street party with hundreds of people
roaring, kissing, cheering and swigging out of half bottles of each others' and
God knows who else's whisky
. In no time at all I was drunk for the first time in my life.
Our gang of teenagers ended up on the Orsk, a water tanker for the Soviet
fishing fleet, where we were obliged to eat a mess of cabbage, garlic custard
and onions, down glasses of the comrades' vodka in a wannie and, at the
commissar's insistence, watch a
two-hour, flickering film about the heroic shock workers of the Uzbekistan
cotton fields. That fairly sobered you up.
We escaped from the Orsk around four in the morning, pursued for some distance
along the docks by the second mate, a Kaliningrader who wanted ``jurst waan
moor keez'' from my pal's girlfriend. Then we went first-footing on shore. I
must have passed out so
me time after eight. I awoke behind a sofa in a strange house at teatime, with
no idea where I was, feeling hellish and deeply ashamed. But no-one seemed to
have noticed. They were getting ready for more first footing and, after ``a
peerie moothlifter'',
by golly, I went with them.
In England, Christmas had been the big deal. In Shetland, it was New Year. Or
so I thought, until I took part in my first Up Helly A'. It means, roughly
translated, ``The Mother of All Parties''. The famous torchlit procession and
burning of the replica N
orse galley (now with added fireworks in these affluent times) are but the
beginning of an all-nighter to end all-nighters.
Up Helly A' is Christmas and New Year rolled into one. In its modern form it is
only a century old but its origins pre-date Christianity. It was and remains
the final fling of the Yule carousing season which, at this high latitude,
lasts for over a month,
from Christmas Eve until the awful morning after the last Tuesday in January.
Up Helly A' is a sub-arctic Mardi Gras, an enormous booze-up organised with
military precision. It has been organised by worthy burghers, rightly and
tightly so, ever since serious Up Helly A' rioting in Lerwick was suppressed in
the late 19th century - w
hen drunken plebs used to pull blazing tar barrels on sledges through the
streets and leave them on the doorsteps of the previous year's least popular
worthy burgher, for Heavens' sake!
Up Helly A' purists like to think their festival is unique; in fact, it is just
a fiercely burning relic of a tradition whose smouldering embers encircle the
northern quarter of the globe. Other midwinter festivals are being revived as
the clammy hands of
57 varieties of kirk slip their grip and people rediscover older traditions.
Visitors who come to Shetland for Up Helly A' are often disappointed. The fiery
procession and the galley burning are sensational but the parties that follow
are strangely alienating, however welcoming the locals try to be. As 48 squads
of disguised men e
ach perform skits and costumed displays in a dozen halls in succession, the
incomer can feel a bit out of it. The jokes are in-jokes, the thousands of
jolly conversations between old friends intimate and local. The dialect is at
its most impenetrable on U
p Helly A' night.
Shetland has never seriously marketed Up Helly A' as a tourist attraction and
it probably never will. The halls are run as private parties by committees of
hosts and hostesses and the squads are their invited guests. Only a few tickets
are on sale to the
public. It is first-footing on a Viking scale but still very much a family
affair.
The trouble with Hogmanay first-footing is that etiquette demands you should
not stay too long. With all those other houses to visit in just one night, you
never have time to say everything you meant to say, which is probably just as
well, seeing the stat
e some of us get into after a dozen whiskies.
So throughout the Yule season, people all over Shetland still ``geng
hoosamilla'' (go between the houses), to visit their friends and relations at
other times and ``hae a richt nicht''. This means a proper gossip lasting well
into the small hours and prob
ably until daylight, some time after 9am. Next night they'll visit the next
neighbours. And even a month is never long enough. I knew one sociable old
crofter in Unst who first-footed a neighbour as late as September.
I have spent New Year in other places and nowadays usually do - but only
because my constitution is no longer capable of lying insensible in ditches
between the houses. I've taken a turn at the Tron in Edinburgh, partied in
Fulham, fallen about in Fife, a
nd even danced in the streets of Alloa (where there is sometimes a piper).
Why do so many of us ring in the New under the influence? Possibly because if
we were completely sober we wouldn't understand what all the fuss is about.
What are we celebrating, anyway, on this arbitrary midnight when nothing, apart
from our resolutions, really changes? Well, survival, I suppose, after another
year of Tory occupation. And defiance,in the face of Labour's flight from
principle. And making
a fresh start, wiping the personal slate clean - particularly important for
Protestants who haven't got Confession. And, like Dr Samuel Johnson, we
recognise that a triumph of hope over experience seems worth at least one toast.
I am resolved to spend this New Year quietly, as Hogmanay falls on the Sabbath.
A frugal meal, possibly a small glass of port to follow vespers, and then I
shall read an improving book as we complete yet another sorry orbit. Following
a decorous domestic
scene of mutual felicitation upon the stroke of the New Year, I shall perhaps
sip a nip of Crabbie's Green Ginger Wine before retiring, 10 minutes into 1996,
to enjoy a good night's sleep, so as not to be late for matins.
The hell I will. Happy New Year!
n.Jonathon Wills is a writer and broadcaster based in the Shetlands. He is
founding partner of the Shetlands News Agency, and a former Lord Rector of
Edinburgh University. In the summer he runs Bressaboats, a wildlife and
seabirds tourism business.
</TEXT>
