<HEADLINE>Yeltsin goes back to work after Kremlin walkabout</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From ALASTAIR MacDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Friday
RUSSIAN President Boris Yeltsin returned to the Kremlin today for the first
time since suffering acute heart trouble more than two months ago and recorded
a New Year's address to the nation.
Yeltsin, 64, strolled through the grounds of his headquarters in central Moscow
after arriving from a country residence at Barvikha, west of the capital.
Interfax said Yeltsin chatted with tourists and Muscovites in the Kremlin
grounds.
``I have come out for my first day at work in the Kremlin,'' he said when he
stopped to chat to sightseers beneath the onion domes on a snowy Cathedral
Square.
Later the presidential press service said he was in the studio recording his
New Year's message, to be broadcast on Sunday.
The president left a sanatorium at Barvikha earlier this week for his nearby
country residence, where his press service said he planned to spend the New
Year with his family.
Yeltsin was taken to hospital on October 26 suffering from what doctors
described as an ischaemic heart condition, a blood supply problem.
A month later he moved to the sanatorium where he gradually increased his
workload and received a stream of visitors.
Yeltsin's health problems have cast doubt on prospects for him standing for a
second term in a presidential election scheduled for June 16, although most
analysts expect him to run.
Today he gave few clues to his tactics for the New Year battle with a resurgent
communist opposition.
Final data released by the Central Electoral Commission today confirmed the
communists will be the strongest bloc in the new parliament which convenes on
January 16. They have 157 of 450 seats, over 100 more than their closest rivals.
Yeltsin vowed to stick to his reform course despite a strong showing by the
communists in the December 17 Duma election. However he kept the nation
guessing on whether he would stand for a second five-year term in the
presidential election next June 16.
``I am still thinking about it,'' he said, adding he would announce his
intentions at the beginning of February.
His wife Naina has voiced concern about the impact of a second term on
Yeltsin's condition. However the president has vowed to make a complete
recovery from his second bout of heart trouble in less than four months.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
