<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Food prices set to rise in 1996</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS should be prepared for higher food prices in 1996, according to Jim
Reed, director-general of the United Kingdom Agricultural Supply Trade
Association. He forecasts that eggs, chicken and pork - products where feed is
the main production costs -
will be dearer in the shops.
Mr Reed warned that livestock farmers, faced with higher costs for animal
feeds, would have to recover part of the increase from the market.
``We drew attention in November to the strong upward pressure on livestock
costs resulting from higher raw material prices on the international market,''
he said. ``Throughout Europe, feed manufacturers face spiralling costs which
they have no choice but
to pass on to farmer customers.
``The EU Commission recently imposed higher cereal export levies and allowed
some imports of sorghum in the southern member states of the EU on special
terms. Partly in response to these moves, quieter trading on north European
grain markets allowed price
s to slacken a little, he added.
Although such efforts were welcome, feed grains were still #15-#20 a tonne up
on the same time last year and UKASTA sees no evidence that the escalation in
prices of high-protein ingredients is over.
``Feed manufacturers are paying an extra #50 on every tonne of soya bean meal
and rapeseed meal above the cost in August,'' explained Mr Reed. ``For
fishmeal, where supplies are sharply down, the increase is #100 a tonne.
``Feed prices will move strongly upward for several months to come and
livestock producers must look to their outlets for higher prices in return. It
is hard to avoid the conclusion that sustained upward cost pressure will affect
the whole range of livest
ock products just at the time when higher vegetable and flour prices are also
coming through.'
</TEXT>
</DOC>
