<RECORDNO>974635184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brown Bros
goes East
DUMFRIESSHIRE-based meat processor Brown Brothers has doubled its turnover to
#4m this year, with the help of large sales of speciality pork to Russian
retailers.
Business at home is also booming for the family company, which has more than
doubled its workforce to nearly 50 since it moved from Biggar to larger
premises in Kelloholm 2!s years ago. Brown Brothers hopes to recruit another 30
employees next year.
During the latter part of this year, the company shipped 140 tons of cured
smoked shoulder pork to Russian retailers in 20-ton consignments. Moscow
supermarkets were among the buyers. Managing director Martyn Godfrey believes
Russia could develop into a s
ubstantial market for Brown Brothers, which also exports to Spain and Gibraltar.
Pork on menu
THE growth rate of newly-weaned pigs can be boosted by as much as 25% with
``menu'' feeding, according to Mike Baker, manager of the Meat and Livestock
Commission's pig development unit in Bedfordshire.
Rot bonus
ITALIAN potato growers, who normally deal with Dutch producers, have turned to
Britain for seed potato supplies in the wake of the outbreak of Brown Rot in
Holland. Initial supplies to the Italian market are expected to be limited but
a number of varietie
s will be going into trials in Italy next year for evaluation. The Potato
Marketing Board is considering a trade mission to Italy early in the New Year
and will also be advertising in the Italian trade press.
</TEXT>
