<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MLC plans initiative to stem market decline</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE beef industry, faced with the challenge of rebuilding its image because of
the BSE controversy, is planning an important event at the National
Agricultural Centre, Stoneleigh, in March.
Farmers attending Beef for the Market will be challenged to play their part in
arresting the decline in UK home consumption which has fallen from 20kg per
person in 1987 to less than 16kg.
The Meat and Livestock Commission - one of the sponsors - will demonstrate how
it perceives beef to be positioned in the market and how it can best be
promoted and sold. It will take up the MLC advertising theme of how little fat
there is in lean beef com
pared to products that are usually thought to be leaner.
Producers will be briefed on some of the issues which have to be faced by the
retailer, including the predominance of households comprising only one or two
people, which gives rise to a demand for smaller joints and retail packs.
Another sociological factor which has affected meat sales is the changing
lifestyles of families - resulting in fewer family meals and more eating out,
which accounts for 20% of beef consumption.
It is six years since supermarkets overtook independent butchers in the league
of retail beef sales. Since Sunday opening was extended to England and Wales,
the supermarkets' share of domestic beef sales has risen to 55%.
The recent BSE scare has dented that figure at least temporarily. Scottish
experience has shown that traditional High Street butchers have suffered much
less than supermarkets. The strength of the traditional butcher shop has been
that it has staff on han
d to explain the issues and to reassure the customer.
The supermarkets will not give up their hard-won share of the beef market
lightly. They are showing enthusiasm for farm assurance schemes that guarantee
cattle welfare and the wholesomeness of home-produced beef.
One aim of the beef event will be to involve producers in meeting the demands
which are increasingly being imposed by the market. Signet - the MLC and
Scottish Agricultural College joint venture - will demonstrate the main beef
systems and identify key pr
ofit factors.
Beef consultant Dr David Allen said: ``Picking a breed suited to the beef
system is extremely important. Signet will demonstrate how important estimated
breeding values (EBVs) are to the suckled calf producer and also to the dairy
farmer buying a bull for
natural service or AI organisations buying bulls for studs.''
n JOHN Ross, president of the National Farmers' Union of Scotland, is also
anxious that everything possible should be done to counter the effects of the
BSE scare on meat consumption. He has described 1996 as a year of challenge for
the meat industry in t
he battle to win back the confidence of customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
