<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Carter again on target</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635187</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BILLY McPherson, for so long one of the mainstays of Insights Menzieshill
indoor team, yesterday came back to haunt his old club when he guided English
title-holders Old Loughtonians to victory in the Menzieshill invitation
tournament at the Dick McTaggar
t Centre in Dundee.
Over the three days Old Loughtonians were that shade better than their rivals,
although it was not until the concluding two series of games that they
eventually sealed their triumph.
They began by beating Menzieshill 6-3 on a day when the Taysiders were well
below form. Uncharacteristically, they made elementary mistakes in defence and
were deservedly overcome.
Steve Carter, Old Loughtonians' Australian striker, did most to separate
Menzieshill from the trophy when he was one of the Englishmen's early
goal-scorers as they established a 2-0 lead.
Menzieshill fought back, but they could do nothing to stop the English side,
who completed their programme with a maximum record by beating Torbrex
Wanderers 7-5, with Carter winning the top goal-scorer award with 14 strikes in
the course of the tournamen
t.
The Dundee side, by beating Wanderers 7-2, finished second, but Wanderers had
the satisfaction of producing the highest score of the day, when they beat
Touche Ross Gordonians 9-1.
The Scottish Under-21s eventually came good and finished in fifth place, which
will undoubtedly give coach Malcolm Callaghan food for thought for the
forthcoming European Junior championship. Results:
Touche Ross Gordonians 8, Bett Inns 2; Torbrex Wanderers 2, Insights
Menzieshill 7; Scottish Under-21s 4, Dita Travellers 4; Gordonians 1, Wanderers
9; Scottish Under-21s 7, Bett Inns 2; Old Loughtonians 6, Menzieshill 3;
Gordonians 4, Scottish Under-21s
3; Old Loughtonians 7, Wanderers 5; Dita Travellers 1, Menzieshill 7.
Final placings: 1, Old Loughtonians, 12 points; 2, Menzieshill 10; 3, Wanderers
8; 4, Gordonians 6; 5, Scottish Under-21s 3; 6, Dita Travellers 3; 7, Bett Inns
0.
JOSEPH DILLON
</TEXT>
