Independent
guidance
GLASGOW-based independent financial adviser MGW is producing a guide to the new
Tessas. It will be available from January 4.
MGW's managing director Brian McKenna says: ``Unlike the guides available from
Tessa providers, it does not promote any single product. It's an independent
guide, presenting a much broader picture on Tessas, their performance and the
alternative options a
vailable to investors with maturing accounts.''
The guide goes back to basics, explaining what a Tessa is and then outlines
some of the investment options available. For a free copy telephone 0141 353
2239.
PEP advice
THE PEP Shop has issued a guide highlighting eight different investment
philosophies employed by PEP managers and recommending one PEP in each
category. A copy can be obtained free by telephoning 0115 982 5105.
BoS fixes it
BANK of Scotland has announced a new range of fixed-rate mortgages with rates
reduced by up to 1.2%. They vary from 5.95% to 8.75% depending on the length of
the fix and the loan to property value ratio.
Index option
KLEINWORT Benson private bank is issuing a Tessa with an optional link to the
FTSE-100 index, with a guarantee of no capital loss. Each year for the
five-year period the account holder chooses to receive either the bank's
standard Tessa interest rate or t
he link to the index. There is a minimum deposit of #3000 and it is available
to those with maturing existing Tessas.
Rate reduced
BRADFORD &amp; Bingley Building Society has reduced the interest rate on its
phone-based Mortgages Direct service (telephone 0800 554709) from 6.7% to 6.5%.
It claims this is the lowest rate on offer from a direct mortgage provider.
Loans are available up to
75% of valuation.
High returns
POLICY Portfolio suggests people with maturing Tessas consider investing the
proceeds in second-hand with-profits endowment policies which, it says, offer
returns equivalent to 11% to 13%. For more details call 0181 343 4567.
US guarantee
MANOR Park (telephone 01481 701108) has added the US stock market to its range
of guaranteed equity funds which provide a variety of risk/reward options. The
guarantees range from 95% of the amount invested to 100% per quarter.
The related exposure to the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index goes from 355% to 80%,
for investors who want to avoid currency risk. It is slightly different for
those willing to accept this. Switches between the guarantee/exposure levels
can be made. Charges ar
e 5% initial and 0.25% quarterly.
C&amp;G choices
CHELTENHAM &amp; Gloucester has lowered its mortgage base rate for new borrowers to
7.24% and has launched a new range of fixed-rate loans. Two-year fixes are
available at 6.29%, three years at 6.75% and five years at 7.69%. The last two
carry a six-month int
erest penalty on early redemption, with a reservation charge of #250. For the
two-year fix there is no early redemption fee but there is a reservation cost
of #500.
Interest cut
ABBEY National has reduced the rates on its personal loans by 1.5 percentage
points and they now range from 13.9% on #10,000 or more, to 20.5% on up to #950.
Royal revises
THE Royal Bank of Scotland has revised the interest rates on its fixed-rate
mortgages. These now vary from 5.75% for a one-year fix up to 7.75% for five
years and 8.5% for 10, for loans up to 95% of valuation. Higher loan to value
ratios carry a 1% premiu
m.
Halifax offer
HALIFAX Building Society has announced a guaranteed minimum fixed rate of 7%
(including bonuses) for customers with maturing Tessa accounts who re-invest in
a fixed rate Halifax Tessa 2 between January 1 and 31.
Christopher Sims
