<DOCNO>GH951230-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The English in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a Scot who worked for 16 years in England, has had two English wives, and
has four grown-up children who consider themselves to be English, I feel I have
the right to comment on Graeme Woolaston's article, Caught in the middle of a
conflict of identiti
es (December 28).
I sympathise with him. As he says, Scotland and England are very different
countries; ``divided by a common language'' like Britain and America, in the
words of George Bernard Shaw.
Yet in his detailed comments he contradicts that sensible judgment. There is no
point whatever in saying to the Scots, ``You lost your independence - get over
it!'' They can't. There's the rub.
For 50 years they've been driving towards greater autonomy and nothing is going
to stop them.
The fact that 350,000 inhabitants of Scotland were born in England makes the
Scottish people fear for their identity: 16% of the Borders, and 10% of the
Orkney and Western Isles populations are English.
Just the other day a charming 30-year-old Glasgow social worker told me how
shocked she and her husband had been when on Skye nearly everyone they spoke to
was English. She thought the bridge would finish off the local Gaelic culture.
Again Graeme Woolaston's judgment of the arts situation in Glasgow (and
Edinburgh) is misguided. Nothing would do Glasgow's arts infrastructure more
good than to be run by Scots. Metropolitan tastes and fashions ring false up
here.
At a conference in the Burrell I attended some time ago a great cultural
panjandrum up from Queen Anne Gate said this to an international audience:
``Glasgow has splendid museums and galleries because it has no history.'' The
Dutchman beside me was shocke
d.
At another international conference in Edinburgh run by the Scotch Whisky
Association no-one could have guessed from the British speakers that the
product was Scottish; they were all English.
Finally, at an important film conference in Ayrshire no-one would have known
that there were any film-makers in Scotland at all, though at the last Oscars
ceremony the only Oscar awarded to Britain was to a Tartan Short.
It is the same in most areas of Scottish life now, even in local government.
The majority of staff at our universities are English, though the system they
were educated in is quite different from ours, which they therefore cannot help
but distort.
When to all that is added the imposition of Westminster decisions by the
Scottish Office in defiance of Scottish opinion, I would have thought that
Graeme Woolaston would have had more understanding of Scottish resentment.
His condemnation of the TV programme, The Englishing of Scotland, shows that he
does not understand.
George Rosie is a highly regarded writer and playwright with a great respect
for the truth and empathy for the moods of the Scottish people.
Andrew Lockhart Walker,
7 Lovers' Loan,
Dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
