<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE has been recent media coverage of Lord Baden Powell, the founder of the
Scouts, regarding his sexual tendencies.
Indeed, the mass media at large appear to highlight the aspects of voluntary
organisations which the public may at first find hard to swallow. Sir William
Alexander Smith founded the Boys' Brigade in Glasgow in 1883, and greatly
influenced Lord Baden Powe
ll.
These two organisations, run by unpaid volunteeers, have helped to enrich the
lives of boys in every thinkable aspect of life for more than a century. Why
are the positive points of the Scouts and Boys' Brigade not highlighted? Why is
their grave need for
helpers not publicised?
Dr Graeme P Currie,
116/118 Main Street,
Muirkirk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christians and Christmas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEEKEND Extra made interesting reading as usual (December 23). However, I found
it sad that the Free Church member would not be celebrating Christmas.
Despite the fact that this time has become hijacked by commercialism, it can
still be used as a focal point for the Christian Church to remember the birth
of Jesus.
We focus on His death at communion (or mass). Of course we have no exact date
of birth. However, scholars do give a date of some time about winter 5/4.BC
from the Gospel chronologies.
If one wishes to use accuracy as a reason for the non-celebration of Christmas
then surely the principle should apply to all times in the church calendar.
However, living so explicitly creates problems.
For example, Sunday was not the date of the Sabbath. It was Saturday. Sunday
was used after Constantine's conversion in 325.AD. In fact all the names of the
days derive from the Roman calendar.
Furthermore, New Year's Day in a Scriptural context was based on the lunar
calendar. Therefore for the Bible writers it changed from year to year and
certainly did not correspond to our New Year's Day.
If one wishes to live only those things stated explicitly, then we would not,
for example, use toilets as they are not mentioned in the Bible.
This is one Evangelical Christian who enjoys Christmas.
John Montgomery,
86 Dundrennan Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dilemma of integration</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635193</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE review of David Donald's book, Lincoln, was immensely interesting.
In 1984 Gore Vidal's Lincoln, in which Donald assisted, caused a furore by
disclosing that the American President was in two minds whether to integrate
the coloureds into the many states or to colonise them.
That continent eventually decided on ``togetherness''. Similar dilemmas occur
100 years later in another continent, this time Europe. Integration of peoples
and their utterances, or robustly separate nations?
Plus ca change.
Ian R Jenkins,
7 Spruce Avenue,
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Compensation for Skye Bridge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHILE it may or may not be the case that Miller-DYWIDAG, the Skye Bridge
builders, may have a valid claim for compensation from the Scottish Office, the
public have also suffered financially and may also have a just claim to some
form of financial recompe
nse.
The return of monies spent by the Appellants in the Court of Session, Motion to
Suspend the Construction works in November 1992 would not have been necessary
if the construction had not started prematurely.
Following the local public inquiry in Kyle the Secretary of State considered
the evidence and published his decision letter on June 25, 1992.
The public then had a period of six weeks in which to appeal to the Court of
Session. On August 6, 1992, four members of the public appealed to the Court of
Session, but while the appeal was pending the construction works on the bridge
were proceeding.
The appellants were effectively forced to go to the Court of Session to request
a suspension of the construction works so that when the legal issues were
examined no irrevocable damage had been done. This Motion to Suspend was
refused on grounds of conven
ience; ie, because the construction work had already started it was deemed it
should continue.
The construction should not have started, at the earliest, before the statutory
public appeal period elapsed on August 7, 1992. Also since, in the event, four
appellants did appeal to the Court of Session, it is not unreasonable to expect
that bridge work
s would not start until after their lordships had had time to consider the
complex legal issues involving vulnerable species legislation.
This suspension request cost the appellants a great deal of money. Legal costs
wasted thousands of pounds in the Motion to Suspend basically because the
Secretary of State had allowed construction work to start before the public
appeal period had elapsed.
To add insult to injury, the appellants also had to pay for the Secretary of
State's legal costs. Two, Mr Peter Findlay and Dr Bruce Stevens, were both
personally liable and had to pay for Ian Lang's legal expenses of some #1365
for the hearing.
It seems that both Miller-DYWIDAG and the general public understood different
start-up dates from the information provided by the Scottish Office. How could
this ambiguity be possible?
One way this question can be resolved is for the Scottish Office to publish the
terms of the contract. If different dates were used for the public and for the
developer, no wonder confusion reigns.
The contract still remains secret under the cloak of commercial
confidentiality. However there can surely be no sensible reason, now that the
bridge is finished, to continue to keep this a secret. The public are
effectively a party to the contract, since
it was signed, on our behalf, by our own public officials. Those officials are
our public servants and are there first and foremost to safeguard our public
interest.
Veronica Munro Stevens,
Kinnaber,
Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tackling dental decay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a first step in a strategy for tackling dental decay in children, parents
will have to be educated about dental care before the children get to school
age, eg, not to give a child juice in a bottle as the sugary substance sucked
in will damage the fron
t teeth.
Making a game of teeth-cleaning, especially at bedtime, is good practice.
Parents will have to be educated on diets not only for the sake of their
children's teeth but for overall wellbeing. This could mean reopening clinics
which have been closed down.
Another step towards helping children to better dental health would be to
repeal the decision not to supply milk to school children.
Another method would be to supply fruit and vegetable vouchers (along the same
lines as milk vouchers) so that families on benefits, especially those living
in outlying schemes where fresh fruit and veg are harder and dearer to come by,
are not disadvanta
ged even more.
Visits by school dentists should be made more frequently and take in all
children.
Kay Allan,
76 Carnwath Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents can find the solution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING worked closely with parents as a headteacher may I suggest that the
solution to problems such as have arisen in Stirling and London lies firmly in
the hands of parents?
A child's attitude toward school and teachers comes in the main from that
engendered by parents in the home. In particular instances where I have been in
conflict with parents I have noticed a negative response from the pupil in the
classroom.
Parents must back teachers even in difficult decisions where the child comes
off worse and loses face in front of his or her classmates.
Parental attitudes which encourage the cult of embryonic ego gratification and
self-obsession do no favour to the child who will be unable to achieve
unrealistic goals set in later life.
At this early stage of life, to behave as though one has all the answers
commands little respect and is an almost insurmountable obstacle in allowing
one to adopt the worthy and gratifying role of learner.
If teachers are to respect children then children must be brought to understand
that respect is a double-edged blade.
If parents want secure, meaningful education they must respect the teachers'
professional judgment and indeed hand their children over totally to the
teacher during the school day and let their children know that parent and
teacher are uniting for the chi
ld's benefit.
The standard of teaching has improved since we parents were at school. No
longer are there malicious, vindictive, arrogant sadists beating children for
poor conjugation. The great majority of teachers now are open, caring
professionals who need the backin
g of parents to give them and the children what they want.
The alternative is a fortress mentality where money allows the more privileged
to have their children educated by those who care and, for the rest, an
underfunded battlefield of decaying buildings and overcrowded classrooms.
Martin H Jones,
Acting Headteacher,
Canna Primary School,
by Mallaig.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Minimum wage
I HAVE difficulty in understanding how political organisations and trade unions
can continually advocate the introduction of a national minimum wage while
simply ignoring valid questions as to the impact of its introduction.
In the construction industry there is an ever-increasing drive away from
employing individuals (earning wages) towards the use of labour-only
sub-contractors (LOSCs) with the latter, as they act as sub-contractors, not
receiving wages and being required t
o tender for the work.
Such LOSCs, unless I stand to be corrected by those who advocate the
introduction of a national minimum wage, will fall outwith any such legislation
and therefore defeat its objective.
Worse still, all bona fide employers, while still being required to meet the
costs of holiday pay, sick pay, National Insurance, travel expenses, etc, will
be faced with the need to pay a national minimum wage and yet compete in the
market-place against o
ther companies which neither meet the employment costs nor pay a national
minimum wage.
In order to survive employers will have to change their working practices
resulting in more and more operatives becoming LOSCs so further destabilising
the employment patterns in this country.
How this can be perceived to be a benefit for anyone defies logic.
Alan McKinney,
National Director, Scottish
Decorators Federation,
1 Grindlay Street Court,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
