<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Earning and learning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635199</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TRADE-UNION leader was reported as being critical of the policy of Asda
Stores Ltd, in using members of uniformed youth organisations in their stores.
The basis of the criticism seems to be that young people are being used instead
of staff.
As a Scout Leader in the East End of Glasgow I would like to point out several
facts.
My troop, involving around 25 boys and girls, have assisted in the Asda store
in The Forge, Parkhead, for many years. Our main duty is bag packing and the
rewards are earned by the generosity of the customers.
A bucket is left beside every Scout in which the customers, if they wish, can
leave a donation.
From the money raised my troop have fulfilled the following: brought a Romanian
paediatrician and a civil engineer for a three-week study tour in Scotland
costing around #4000; sent one of our 16-year-old Scouts to the World Jamboree
in South Korea, enabl
ed the troop to camp in Switzerland and Denmark, and raised funds to supplement
the generous donations that Asda make to local charities.
As well as such specific benefits the money raised enables opportunities of
education for all the Scouts, and it is interesting that I have no smokers or
young people involved with drugs.
Ian McCreadie,
44 Lochearnhead Road,
Stepps.
</TEXT>
