<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Midwinter nightmare for those in next century</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT a difference a degree makes, especially if it's a degree of temperature.
This week, as my body temperature soared, the air temperature plummeted.
I could see great lumps of ice floating down the Clyde from my bedroom window,
while in my throat were lodged something which felt like broken glass. Hell is
not a bonfire - it takes only a temperature rise of a couple of degrees
Centigrade to create one
inside you.
I shall spare you the details. You have probably had the ubiquitous virus
yourself, and don't need to be reminded of days when you were one of the undead.
It takes something different to create the spectacular fall in air temperature
we have experienced this week but we sure have had it and it has triggered off
several side-effects. Even the trusty method of clearing roads by the
application of salt to redu
ce the melting point has not worked. (The salt and water mixture freezes at a
lower temperature than water alone, but this week it was so cold that salt and
water froze.)
There was something awesome about the big freeze. Rentaquote politicians
indulged in ritual denunciation of the Government and the public utilities, but
the enormity of the problem seemed to go beyond anything that could reasonably
be foreseen.
Of course it didn't stop some from trying. It seems to be a particularly
Scottish characteristic that we need someone to blame for our failures. Surely
no power or water supplier can foresee temperatures of minus 20C, but that
didn't stop some having a tr
y to blame it all on them.
The tragic loss of life in the Yorkshire pond, in which a little girl trying to
rescue a dog perished along with the two men who tried to save her, is as cruel
an event as one can think of.
But we would find it impossible to apportion blame. Unless we want the kind of
theology which traces every single event to God's purposes.
Some religious people who have strong faith are tempted to take this attitude,
but I believe it leads to a terrible view of God. I have always believed that
as long as there is water, ice, and the laws of gravity, there will be some who
drown, others who
slip and break a leg, and we should not try to explain such events as if they
were part of a celestial puppet show.
My fascination with temperature balance in our bodies and in nature has led me
to realise that it is a paradigm for our ecology. There is a very small band of
temperatures (inside and outside us) within which human life is possible.
Although there are som
e places, eg Siberia, in which there are wider poles, the mean is still within
narrow limits. Likewise there are deserts which were once within the mean (back
in the days of the Romans versus the Carthaginians in the Sahara). Only the
north and south pole
s seem to lie permanently outwith habitable terrain.
In other words we tread fairly narrow limits. That is one of the reasons which
sees to it that life prospers on the planet. But let us suppose for a moment
that the balance is disrupted, and mean temperature begins to rise or fall.
That is what happened d
uring Ice Age 20,000 years ago (a mere blink in geological time). The earth's
temperature was then 4C less than it is today. Not much, is it? I learned this
fact from volcano expert Dr James Jackson, who is giving the Christmas lectures
at the Royal Insti
tution in London.
He also threw in this other fact: that a volcano which exploded on an island in
the Philippines a few years ago caused an increase in the earth's temperature
of one half a degree Centigrade.
In addition to aerosols, car exhausts, acid rain, nature seems to be doing its
own little bit to make sure life is less secure.
Meanwhile a survey undertaken by Friends of the Earth and published yesterday
suggests that Scots will be horribly underwhelmed by this news. One in five
Scots are ``not even slightly concerned'' about the environment.
One exception was my aunt Louisa who died this year aged 96 and kept a library
of cuttings on threats to the environment. She was sure the next century will
see a huge ecological catastrophe with tidal waves caused by melted icebergs.
I tended to discount her pessimism - after all the scientists could not agree
among themselves but now I not so sure.
Life on earth is sustained by a system of checks and balances. Disturbing this
produces a chain reaction which even the smartest scientist cannot predict
accurately. We saw what Chernobyl did - what price a few wee volcanoes added to
the firework display?
So far we find it impossible to feed, clothe, keep healthy, and shelter those
who share the planet with us. How can we possibly get anywhere near this with
spiralling birth rates and gross over-population?
Whether you compare it to a snowstorm or a volcano, it still spells a midwinter
nightmare for those who will live in the next century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
