<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dropped
linesman
to take
action
LINESMAN George McGuire is taking legal advice after having been demoted by the
SFA following an October 21 incident at Ibrox involving Alan Lawrence, of
Hearts, and Rangers defender Craig Moore.
McGuire, of Bonnyrigg, and Aberdeen referee Mike Pocock missed an alleged elbow
incident by Lawrence, who later received a one-match, SFA suspension on the
strength of a referee supervisor's report.
Earlier this month, the 41-year-old civil servant was told he can now officiate
in amateur football only after 14 years as a referee in Scotland.
``I am taking legal advice on the matter,'' said McGuire, who claims he was
told there was no right of appeal against the decision.
It is believed McGuire is angry that his explanation that he did not see the
incident involving Lawrence and Moore was not accepted by SFA officials.
FIFA-listed referee John Rowbotham and Jim McCluskey also have been carpeted by
the SFA, but look to have escaped the severe action taken against McGuire.
George Cumming, the SFA's Referee and Development Director, would not say
whether or not McGuire's demotion was due to the Lawrence incident. However, he
confirmed that Rowbotham and McCluskey were pulled up by the Referee
Supervisors' Executive committee
``at the same time'' as McGuire, although he would not reveal whether they had
been punished.
q JIM Duffy last night said that it could be the summer before he knows if he
will be part of a management buy-out at Dundee.
Canadian chairman, Ron Dixon, revealed at the start of the month that he had
lined up a #3m deal that would hand control of the Dens Park outfit to Duffy
and vice-chairman Malcolm Reid.
Duffy said, hours before the club's agm last night: ``We would not just be
buying a football team if this deal goes through. The structure of the club is
involved. Hopefully, Dundee are going to return to the premier division and I
personally back the vie
w expressed by people in the game that clubs in the top division should be
required to meet certain criteria.
``That means we have to consider issues like undersoil heating and increased
facilities for supporters.''
``As far as I am concerned these discussions could take months, but we are
certainly not backing out of the plan. We are keeping in touch with the
chairman now that he is no longer in the country, and he is keeping in touch
with us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Players must stand up and be counted</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON paper, five games in a row unbeaten by Dundee United, and only one loss in
five by Airdrie, would please most managers and football pundits, especially in
such a tight league as the first division.
Enter the three-points-for-a-win syndrome, and suddenly the icy blast comes
more from disgruntled coaches than the present spell of weather.
United have three draws in their run, with the loss of six points, while
Airdrie have dropped seven over the same hurdle.
Amazingly, as the two square up in the only surviving first-division fixture on
top of the Tannadice electric blanket today, Airdrie have played only twice
since drawing 1-1 with United at Broadwood on November 25.
Manager Billy Kirkwood's Christmas cheer was dented when the Taysiders could
not defeat bottom-club Dumbarton on Boxing Day.
And Scotland Under-21 winger Andy McLaren is left out of today's game as a
result as Kirkwood seeks the type of consistent performance that would take his
team back into the premier division.
``It is now time for players coming into the side to show the sort of form that
will mean them keeping their places,'' he said. ``Equally, anyone left out must
show they want to fight to get back in.''
Another Scotland Under-21 player, midfielder David Hannah, could make his first
start since the opening day of the season, after having been out with a groin
injury.
Airdrie, meanwhile, have defender Sean Sweeney and striker Steve Cooper
grinding through their long-term suspensions - Sweeney is out for six games,
and Cooper for five - and they should have had Paul Jack back, but a recurrence
of the injury that has kep
t him out for many weeks means he again will be sitting this one out.
Kirkwood, desperate for a victory that would take his side to the top of the
league, added: ``We shouldn't need any warnings at this stage of the season,
but they are certainly there if we want to look for them. This is a big game
for us.''
Meanwhile, Kirkwood released David Craig, the former Partick Thistle
midfielder, who was immediately signed by Hamilton Accies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>League has ball at its feet</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE English Football League have survived the latest threat to its future, when
the 24 first division clubs backed away from mass resignation.
Norwich, Crystal Palace, and Oldham had led the protests, after the League's
extraordinary general meeting in London had thrown out a proposal which would
have given the top-flight clubs a greater say in the running of League affairs.
All but three of the first division clubs had earlier abstained when chairmen
voted through cash split proposals relating to the new, five-year, #125m deal
with Sky TV.
That contract would have been worthless had Palace chairman Ron Noades and his
fellow hardliners persuaded the clubs to hand in their notice to quit the
League before tomorrow's deadline.
The first division clubs had gone into emergency session immediately after the
EGM, but after three hours, League president Gordon McKeag was summoned to be
told that the resignation threat had been removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Striker's short stay at Ibrox could end soon Majorca are set to move for Salenko</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPANISH second-division side is considering an audacious move to sign Oleg
Salenko, who is ready to make his first-team return in Rangers'
premier-division match against Hibernian this afternoon, in an attempt to
strengthen their hopes of promotion to t
he first division.
Real Majorca say that after having been approached by an agent asking them if
they would be interested in either of two players, one of them Salenko, they
are trying to put together a deal which would persuade Rangers to part with the
player they signed f
rom Valencia.
The Ibrox club paid around #2.5m for Salenko, but he has never looked at ease
in Scottish football. Indeed, it would not be a surprise if he had a notion to
return to Spanish football, where he has tended to start well with clubs and
then shade.
The player might say the coaches have never done him any favours, but in his
time with Rangers he has not appeared like the type willing to match the
determination and commitment of others around him.
In a Spanish radio interview yesterday, Dr Beltran, president of Majorca, who
were one of the favourites for promotion before the season started but who have
dropped to thirteenth place, suggested that Salenko and Rangers might be
interested in doing busi
ness.
He also said that if the deal went through it would be his club's biggest
signing. The Spanish transfer deadline runs out on January 15, and with it
could go Majorca's chance of winning a place among the country's elite.
Rangers would expect to get their money back for Salenko, and Dr Beltran said
it might be possible for his club to find the cash from various sources to
finance a deal. In particular, the television station, Antena Tres, with whom
the club president is sa
id to have connections, might be willing to assist financially.
Although in the wrong half of the table after 17 matches, Majorca are only
seven points away from a promotion place - two clubs are promoted automatically
- and with 21 games remaining, Beltran believes ground can be made up if the
team had a forward like
Salenko.
Another of Rangers' strikers Gordon Durie, who has struck a rich vein of
scoring form at the time when Rangers need him, is not certain to play against
Hibernian this afternoon, when the Ibrox side hope to widen the gap between
themselves and Celtic at th
e top of the premier division.
The striker is nursing a thigh injury and will report early this morning to
undergo a fitness check. Naturally, with Ally McCoist still injured, although
he might be available for the Old Firm game at Celtic Park on January 3, Walter
Smith, the Rangers ma
nager, is hoping Durie recovers and is able to play a part in the attempt to
exact revenge on Hibs.
The Edinburgh club are the only team to have beaten Rangers in the league this
season - Darren Jackson's penalty was enough to give Hibs all three points when
they last played at Ibrox in September - and although the defending champions
won 4-1 at Easter
Road last month, they want to erase the memory of the home defeat. Durie's
scoring form could help them achieve that small, but no less important,
ambition.
``I'm hoping he'll make it, yes, because he has been enjoying what is probably
his best spell since coming to Ibrox, although he did start his career here
pretty well,'' said Smith. ``It has been difficult for him over the period,
because I have used him
in various positions, but up front is where he is at his best.''
Alex Cleland is available again and likely to start the game, one of only three
matches which survived the sub-zero temperatures - the two others are the
contests between Dundee United and Airdrie, in the first division, and Queen's
Park and Ross County,
in Division 3 - and Oleg Salenko also is fit and ready to begin a two-game
period which could have a significant bearing on the championship pursuit.
Celtic's match against Hearts at Tynecastle was postponed, which means they
will have been inactive since
their game against Falkirk two weeks ago.
Then they were only two points behind Rangers, but they could go into the Old
Firm game on Wednesday eight points behind if Smith's players beat Hibs. Celtic
would be faced with the prospect of playing for the first time in
two-and-a-half weeks, and witho
ut the suspended Peter Grant and John Hughes while trying to prevent Rangers
from moving even further ahead.
However, Simon Donnelly believes that Celtic's enforced idleness will not
affect them in mid-week. ``Everyone at the club is looking forward to the
game,'' said Donnelly. ``We have been training hard, with a lot of us staying
back for extra sessions, so o
ur fitness level is good.''
If by the time the lights are doused on Wednesday night, Celtic are 11 points
behind, pressure would mount on them, but that is not to say Rangers are
without concern. ``It's being said that pressure is being placed on those teams
who are not getting game
s, but there is a pressure to win on those who are playing,'' said Smith.
``There is no point in having these games if you are going to lose them, just
as there would be little good in losing to Hibs but beating Celtic.''
In the past, while they were compiling their run of seven titles in a row,
Rangers usually set off on a run around this point, but this time it will be
extremely difficult for them to better their first half of this season. To do
so they would have to go
through the second half of the programme undefeated.
Hibs, whose recent form has been dreadful, were hoping to have Michael O'Neill
available again after suspension, but he must complete his ban this afternoon,
because the Boxing Day game against Partick Thistle was postponed. Manager Alex
Miller is also un
able to call on Willie Miller, Gareth Evans, Graeme Mitchell, and Darren Dods.
Concerned about the effects the weather is likely to have on the New Year's Day
schedule, the Scottish League intend checking on pitches this afternoon and
again there are likely to be early postponements. Indeed, the game between
Aberdeen and Raith Rover
s on Tuesday is already in serious doubt because of fears about the safety of
the supporters.
Pittodrie has undersoil heating, but Aberdeen's manager, Roy Aitken, explained:
``The police advise that they would not recommend the game goes on unless the
weather improves. We are experiencing freak conditions in the North East and
the roads are a prob
lem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flyers go for four</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIGEL DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIFE Flyers could climb to their highest premier division place so far this
season with victory over Humberside Hawks tonight.
A win treble has lifted the Kirkcaldy club into seventh spot, and a point
behind former league pace-setters Basingstoke Bison. Player-coach Mark
Morrison, just back in Scotland after a whirlwind holiday trip with his family
to Canada, said: ``I set the bo
ys a target of six points from the four games around Christmas and new year.
``They've done brilliantly to beat Slough Jets and Milton Keynes Kings on the
road and see off Newcastle Warriors at Kirkcaldy. It really would be the icing
on the cake if we could finish off with a win over Humberside in front of our
own fans.''
Flyers will be at full strength for the match.
NIGEL DUNCAN
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth drugs message Churchillian appeal over the top</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER else he has achieved since he returned to Scotland, and there have
been major achievements deserving of praise, Michael Forsyth has been
singularly misguided in that part of his new year message which dealt with his
``major new national initiativ
e against drugs''. Neither the substance nor the tone did the Scottish
Secretary any credit. The misuse of drugs is a serious problem, but to the
extent that: ``The drugs epidemic is a scourge as terrible as any medieval
plague. This country strove in uni
ty, as one nation, during the Second World War to defeat tyranny. We must find
that unity again to crush the drugs menace.'' The plague analogy is a gross
exaggeration and the Churchillian appeal to wartime unity is over the top.
When Mr Forsyth then talks of ``winning back Scotland from the drugs culture''
and ``liberating a generation'' he is quarrying the rich seam of drugs-war
rhetoric which swept America 10 years ago but which has been discredited there
as pandering to the fe
ars and prejudices of the right. He would have been better served had someone
told him that this has also been discredited here. It is the kind of talk
deliberately calculated to play on the fear of the rise of an underclass; a
seething mass of uneducated
, inadequate, housing-scheme dwellers - disenfranchised by self-imposed
unemployment - unwilling to break out of their poverty trap and rampant with
hatred and jealousy of the better-placed middle classes. It is the same kind of
talk which is used to marg
inalise single parents or to justify cuts in benefit to young people as if they
themselves were entirely to blame for being jobless, while the reality is
continuing large-scale unemployment. The Scottish Secretary was on safe ground
when he said he had en
listed the leaders of the other major parties to line up behind Scotland
Against Drugs because no party leader in his right mind could do other. There
is some evidence that the other parties were expecting a joint announcement but
instead the idea has bee
n turned into another soundbite for Mr Forsyth. There already exists a vast
literature on every aspect of drugs abuse, every parent in the country has been
exposed relentlessly to it in the past five years and we have had an endless
round in Scotland of s
eminars, conferences, and police initiatives discussing what should be done. A
very considerable industry, involving thousands of people in the social
services, has grown up around the apparent need to treat drug users as if they
were suffering from some
kind of pernicious illness which was not their fault. Brutal reality is
different, of course, and much more prosaic. The major drug of abuse in
Strathclyde, in Scotland, and in a growing area of England is a sleeping pill
called Temazepam, stronger contro
ls of which have met with bitter resistance from the pharmaceutical industry,
which enjoys most-favoured status along with the booze and tobacco industries
in the eyes of the Government. It remains unfashionable to point out that the
social damage done by
cigarettes, alcohol, and prescription drugs is far more pernicious and has
gone on for far longer than the present drugs scare.
The Government's own task force, an all-party body, has barely had time to sit
down in the wake of its exhaustive examination of drugs problems in Scotland,
an inquiry which focused thinking on multi-agency approaches and which led to
the creation of the
area drug task forces based on the health boards. These have just been set up
and are getting their act together, begging the question of just how much more
talking Mr Forsyth wants. His big idea of partnership to beat the dealers is
therefore only an exi
sting objective dressed up and recycled. The pragmatic approach of Strathclyde
Police - educating and informing, offering diversion for youngsters and then
actually driving at the users, and through them the dealers, with single-minded
purpose is the exam
ple the rest of Scotland should look to.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A toast to Burns No slow build-up to celebrations</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER an embarrassing bout of hiccups, the great Burns festivities are about to
begin. So let's raise a glass (or two) to the national bard. The kind of
publicity gained by the organisation set up to run the official Burns
bicentenary festival may not hav
e been quite what it wanted, but it has achieved something after all. If you
didn't know it before, you know it now - 1996 marks the 200th anniversary of
the death of Robert Burns. And celebrations will start with a bang - there will
be no slow build-up t
o the climax. It was ``a blast o Janwar win'' that hanselled the infant Burns
on his entry into the world, and January has always been the big month in the
Burns calendar. This year there will be an extra dash of spice in the haggis
and champit tatties at
a multitude of Burns' suppers. True, these bizarre occasions usually celebrate
the poet's supposed excesses in the way of boozing and womanising rather than
his literary achievement, but at least they show he is not forgotten. The
memory is immortal, eve
n if many of us at table are a little hazy about just what it is we are
remembering. But Burns suppers are only the start. There will be a fireworks
show at Alloway where he was born, and a procession in Dumfries where he died.
Massed choirs, country danc
ers, fiddle bands, and television stars - ``a cast of over 600'', in the words
of the programme - will provide a spectacular in Glasgow Royal Concert Hall.
And there is more serious fare. Students of the man and his works will gather
for a three-day inter
national conference at Strathclyde University, and a major exhibition will open
this summer at the National Museum of Scotland. All that seems to be missing is
the film epic. After Rob Roy and Braveheart, the biopic Rabbie would have
rounded off the tarta
n trilogy nicely.
So the year will provide plenty of spectacle and entertainment. It will be fun,
and doubtless it will do wonders for tourism. Dare we hope that it may even
help to create a new readership for the poet, who after all lives best in his
works. Though Burns i
s a national icon, it's doubtful if many Scots today know the poems at all
well. It used to be said that even the humblest family could boast two books
its possession, one being the Bible and the other a copy of the poems and songs
of Robert Burns. Those
days are gone. Burns's gift was to speak directly to the heart, and it is this
which won him his unique place in the popular mind. Whether he is Scotland's
greatest literary figure is a matter of debate. Walter Scott long ago laid a
fair claim to that tit
le. Scotland has produced other writers of genius, both before and after Burns.
Robert Burns stands not alone, but as a leading figure among a host of bright
talents. Perhaps they merit at least a few grace notes in the fanfare.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Step out in classic style</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lesley Duncan tunes in to a Merry Widow and a
fiddler on the airwaves
ESCAPE to Vienna this Hogmanay weekend. Michael Bevis says Happy Birthday
Hanna! on Radio 2 at 5.03pm today as he traces the history of Franz Lehar's The
Merry Widow, first performed in the Austrian capital exactly 90 years ago. ``I
want to write music fo
r and around human beings, their hearts, their souls, their emotions and
passions, their joy and sadness,'' wrote Lehar. The unabated popularity of his
operetta suggests that he succeeded.
Darker operatic fare is offered by Radio 3 (6.30-10.25pm) when Tchaikovsky's
The Queen of Spades is broadcast Live from the Met. Still more music from
Lesley Garrett and Friends at 7.33pm on Radio 2 in a gala concert from the
Barbican, London.
Meanwhile Radio 4 listeners with a taste for ``the terrible and menacing, like
an unopened door in a bad dream'' may have shivered away the afternoon with the
Playhouse adaptation of Walter de la Mare's short story Seaton's Aunt
(2.30-4pm).
The play's the thing tomorrow, too. Radio 4 continues its Trollope
dramatisations with the start of Barchester Towers. The plot takes up the story
of the Harding family, first met in The Warden, broadcast in November. Alec
MacCowen and Juliet Aubrey resum
e their roles as Septimus and and his widowed daughter Eleanor while Simon
Russell Beale impersonates the odious curate Slope. Will he get his
comeuppance? The plot unfolds in three episodes. (2.30-3.30pm).
This being the time of year for reflection and retrospection, Radio 3 is
appropriately hosting a Memory Night: subtitled Remembering and Forgetting. The
evening opens with a collage of music, poems, and readings from the
photographic memory of childhood.
But as the theme is pursued, darker issues are confronted, including - by the
end of the evening (and year) - the nature of false memory with its
implications for child abuse and claims of abduction by aliens. In the course
of the evening, playwright and
actor Harold Pinter himself stars in the first production of The Proust
Screenplay, his film script for an unmade version of A la Recherche du Temps
Perdu (8.20-10.20pm).
Radio Scotland listeners will have a less taxing time with Cape Breton Island
Revisited (8pm), in which master fiddler Aly Bain traces the footsteps of the
early Scottish settlers of the Canadian island and swaps chat and tunes with
friends old and new.
Radio Scotland Be-Bops to Hip-Hops its way into the New Year with David Sillars
as host of a Hogmanay Special jazz party. Then, from 12.30am, the command is to
Party On! with John Cavanagh and Mark Percival.
Monday morning sees Radio 3 make its customary relay from The New Year's Day
Concert in Vienna (10.15am-12.30pm). Alternatively, at 10.15 on Radio 4, Long
Wave, youngsters may hear the first of five winning stories for children to
emerge from a recent Rad
io 4/Good Housekeeping Magazine competition. Joanna Lumley offers her choice of
music (Glenn Miller to Elton John) in a New Year's Day special (Radio 2,
10.03am-1pm).
Robert Burns, Hugh MacDiarmid, and Stuart Conn - as you've probably never heard
them before - feature in Cover Stories: Scots to Esperanto on Radio Scotland at
12.05pm. But can the true meaning and idiom of poetry really be translated? A
fascinating quest
ion for presenter David Stenhouse.
If you're an Archers fan rather than the kind of person (me) who feels queasy
at the first note of the signature tune, you'll not miss Monday's visit to
Ambridge at 7.05pm on Radio 4. It's 45 years to the day (gosh) since the
country saga was first broadc
ast. In episode 11,721, Ambridge folk look forward to another year. Will Shula
find love again in 1996? The nation awaits the answers.
The main - and sombre - listening for New Year's Day is The Nuremberg Trial, a
dramatised reconstruction of the Nazi war crimes trial after the defeat of
Germany in 1945. (Radio 4, 7.20-10pm).
Radio 3's year-long celebration of British music was a joy to tune in to
randomly over the past year. On Tuesday (5.30-7.30pm), Fairest Isle
Retrospective offers listeners a second chance to hear poet and award-winning
biographer Andrew Morton describe wh
at makes English music and poetry so quintessentially English. Now, keep that
Scotch touchiness at bay!
</TEXT>
