<DOCNO>GH951230-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Last dance for golden girl</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Maecella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635209</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RATHER good timing of Radio 2 to broadcast its celebration of Ginger Rogers on
Boxing Day with her sung encouragement that we should dust ourselves down, pick
ourselves up, and start all over again. Though Katharine Hepburn defined the
famous dancing team
thus - ``He gave her class, and she gave him sex'' - the bitchiness nearly
lost beneath presenter Wayne Sleep's appalling mimicry - the relationship of
the mythical partnership was neither the illicit affair of popular fantasy nor
the passionate feud con
cocted by the studio's publicity machine.
They were both obviously bound by their shared obsessive perfectionism.
Rogers's cream-coloured shoes darkened after one gruelling take, and the fact
she was being filmed in black and white meant the blood did not read as blood.
In Top Hat, Rogers remembe
red Astaire's annoyance that her unforgettable feathered dress left
unforgivable fluff all over his perfect tuxedo. Though she said it didn't. A
minor tiff between major hoofers.
Ginger, seemingly, was fond of quoting a sassier description than Hepburn's
about themselves: ``Ginger Rogers did everything that Fred did, only she did it
backwards and in high heels.'' Even Sleep's pretty banal commentary did not
trip up the programme t
oo much, but did he have to say - after mentioning The Gay Divorcee - ``that
title would have to go today''? Was that his idea of something modern-sounding?
During the filming of Follow the Fleet Astaire was walking down the street when
he heard the sound of a cement mixer and proceeded to improvise a dance to its
rhythm. The noise became part of Irving Berlin's score and was incorporated
into a scene in the
machine room of the boat. This anecdote would have delighted the brilliant
composer, Simon Jeffes, whose Penguin Cafe Orchestra (R3) similarly marries the
arbitrary with rigorous musicality.
Like Rogers and Astaire, Jeffes's work dissolves hierarchical snobberies. They
include ukuleles, jukeboxes, dripping taps, and penny whistles as well as
classic chamber orchestra instruments, and the results are gloriously tuneful,
moving, and original.
Like the serendipity of Astaire's cement-mixer sound, Jeffes once made a phone
call and heard the simultaneous sound of ringing and engaged tones.
He accompanied the rhythm with an elastic band, which he twanged with a handy
screwdriver, and from this grew an extraordinarily beautiful piece.
Accessible and melodious, Telephone and Rubber Band had my seven-year-old
daughter dancing around the room and she laughed when I told her the story.
Whereas The Laughing Policeman song, before it was binned, had her running and
screaming out the door.
Maybe I should tell Roy Hudd about this. He implied in Roy Hudd's Extremely
Amusing History of the Comic Song (R2) that this number could make anyone
smile. I think it's best suited to a English murder movie, all end-of-the-pier
creepiness, with gruesome
landladies and nightmarish ventriloquists' dummies.
And while I would love to have seen Vesta Tilley and Marie Lloyd strut their
stuff, this really should have included the word English in the title.
Jake Thackeray got a mention and Victoria Wood got an accolade.
Her song was a trifle hypocritical, I thought, being about a performer urged by
a cynical agent to push the Northern England ticket.
Mention of Billy Dainty but none of Billy Connolly - Victor and Barry would
have choked on their Kelvinside quiche.
I don't know who decided to call Radio Scotland's Chomsky interview Noam's Ark
but I wish they hadn't. Still, it could have been worse. Could have been Eighth
Choice Chomsky, for according to the Arts and Humanities Citation Index the
American linguist an
d radical is number eight in the top 10 of the world's most-quoted writer, the
only one still living - and talking excellent sense.
His belief that rule of law is used when applied to the less powerful states
and the rule of force comes into play when the superpower is threatened was
given ample detailed examples. Reagan, Thatcher, and now Newt Gingrich fighting
their war against the
welfare of family and children while preaching homey values, show us how
carefully we must protect the true language of democracy against its distorters.
</TEXT>
