<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gurusinha saves Sri Lanka from humiliation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA gradually wore down Sri Lanka's spirited resistance yesterday to move
within sight of victory in the second Test in Melbourne, despite a tenacious
century by Asanka Gurusinha.
The left-hander frustrated Australia for seven minutes short of six hours in
compiling his highest Test score of 143 to save Sri Lanka from the humiliation
of a second successive innings defeat against the Aussies.
But with only four wickets in hand and a lead of just 17, the tourists' fate
appears certain.
At the close, Sri Lanka were 284 for six from 103 overs, with captain Arjuna
Ranatunga, their last recognised batsman, on six alongside pace bowler Chaminda
Vaas on five.
Resuming on 33 for one, Sri Lanka batted with determination to ensure Australia
must at least bat again to take a winning 2-0 lead in the three-Test series.
Gurusinha, who began the day on eight, hammered one six and 15 fours during an
innings lasting 274 balls, eclipsing his 137 against the same opponents in
Colombo in 1992-93.
He eventually lost his wicket after tea when he was trapped leg before wicket
by pace bowler Paul Reiffel.
Gurusinha said he was delighted with his century given the circumstances,
adding: ``That was the best of my seven hundreds in Test cricket.'' Scores:
Australia - 500 for six (Steve Waugh 131 not out, David Boon 110). Sri Lanka -
233 (Arjuna Ranatunga 51, Glenn McGrath five for 40) and 284 for six (Asanka
Gurusinha 143).
q WEST Indies captain Richie Richardson steered his side to the first win of
their Australian tour with a seven-wicket defeat of a Queensland XI yesterday
in a one-day match in Toowoomba, 100km west of Brisbane. Richardson scored 75
not out from 84 delive
ries as the West Indies chased, and passed, the young Queenslanders' total of
237 for eight from 50 overs.
The West Indians reached 241 for the loss of three wickets when Richardson
stroked the winning runs from the first ball of the forty-ninth over.
</TEXT>
