<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appalling weather puts linesmen and support teams to the test All in the line of duty</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Graeme Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635211</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS THEY awoke on Christmas morning to the news that Scotland had been swept by
snowstorms the men who maintain the power lines which light up one-quarter of
the UK knew that their turkey and plum pudding would have to wait.
Some of the linesmen who work for Hydro-Electric have yet to enjoy their
Christmas lunch. In the most remote and hostile corners of Scotland they have
been working in appalling conditions to try to ensure that their 600,000
customers enjoy the power which
they take for granted at the flick of a switch.
When the television goes off and the lights go out it will mean a relatively
short spell of inconvenience for the majority of the population but for the
linesmen it may mean several days of working in conditions which most would
find difficult to tolerate
for even hours.
They cope with biting winds, driving snow and rain, and often the hardest task
is reaching the area where the fault has occurred.
In the summer, as they walk the countryside checking the power lines amid
picture postcard terrain, they are the envy of those kept indoors by work. In
the past week that same countryside has taken on a Christmas-card appearance -
but the workers are the
envy of few.
Typical of the 500 linesmen and the 300 fitters, labourers, and drivers who
support them in Hydro-Electric's area are Gordon Leslie and Ronnie Milne who
were looking forward to Christmas Day with their families.
The excitement of Santa's visit for Gordon's four young children had the family
up just after 6am, but even as he had gone to bed on Christmas Eve, having
heard late news reports of the weather, he suspected it would be his workmates
rather than his wife
and children with whom he would spend the following day.
The presents were opened and the first call was from his mother-in-law, the
second from Hydro-Electric and he was off, as was Ronnie who was also looking
forward to a day with the family.
It was disappointing to have to leave the festive celebrations almost before
they had begun and Gordon had to miss the excitement experienced by
14-month-old Hayley enjoying her first meaningful Christmas, but neither
hesitated.
``We would not have liked to be without power on Christmas Day, unable to get
dinner, so it was easy to imagine how those affected must have felt,'' they
said.
``If there is a big fault you just have to go for it! There isn't really any
choice.''
As they moved all over North-east Scotland locating and repairing faults,
similar teams were attempting the same all over Hydro-Electric's territory
which includes everything north of a line roughly from Dunoon to Dundee and
covers 25% of the land mass of
the UK but is occupied by only 2% of its population.
Some from Aberdeen boarded the boat to Shetland to lend support to their
colleagues on the Islands who were facing unprecedented conditions. However,
Hydro-Electric had to be careful not to send too many out of the area in case
the already bad weather aro
und Aberdeen deteriorated, causing further problems.
There are a variety of problems which the linesmen face, from blown fuses,
caused when the conductor cables clash because they sag under the weight of ice
and sway with the wind, to poles snapping or burning down.
If whole communities are blacked out the linesmen head first for the
high-voltage cables and divide them into sections for checking. In situations
like that they send as many crews as possible to the fault to reduce the burden
on individual linesmen and s
peed up the restoration of supplies.
Once the large-scale problems have been repaired they think about individual
consumers, some of whom, it appears, are less well equipped to cope than they
once were.
``It can take as long to restore the supply to one consumer as it can to repair
a fault which has blacked out hundreds of consumers so obviously we do the
high-voltage lines which run from village to village first.
``Then we prioritise, deciding where to go next, either at the Aberdeen office
or out in the country using our local knowledge.''
There was a time when rural dwellers were born and brought up in the country,
knew how to look after themselves, and were prepared for the times when the
power went down.
Now many of those who live in isolated dwellings or communities are
``incomers'' who are less well versed in country matters and do not expect to
have to do anything other than flick a switch to keep warm.
The linesmen are, on the whole, welcomed. They have, however, detected a change
in atmosphere since privatisation. An intolerance has crept in which was seldom
around in the nationalised days.
``It used to be a case of `the Hydro Board will be here as soon as they can',
but since privatisation they expect us to arrive almost immediately,'' said
one. ``No matter how quickly we are there some people seem to expect us to have
arrived earlier. Some
seem to think it is their duty to hurry us up.''
Even when the fault is identified it does not necessarily mean an instant
repair. Because of the equipment they require they have to get fairly close to
the location and, as happened over Christmas at numerous sites, local
contractors had to be called out
to clear a path through the snow for the familiar blue and white Land Rovers
which are ``home'' for the linesmen when they are working. The heaters provide
some comfort for the linesman as they travel from job to job and prepare
themselves to hike throug
h the snow.
Normally in winter they try to find somewhere for a hot lunch to help them cope
with the conditions but for many on Christmas Day that proved impossible and it
was evening before they could eat.
Out in the wilds one day this week Gordon was looking forward to making a cup
of soup to heat his bones on the small stove he carries in his vehicle - but
his water had turned to ice in its plastic container and he had to do without
until he returned to h
is Aberdeen home at night.
In bygone days they would have tried to work through the night, and although
there are some occasions when they still do, the linesmen normally stop
mid-evening to allow them a good night's sleep, a hot meal, and a chance to get
warm dry clothing on for a
n early morning start.
Keeping warm is a challenge for the linesmen in conditions like the past week
and Hydro-Electric is constantly re-assessing their requirements to try to find
the best possible balance between being warm and having the manoeuvrability to
carry out their wo
rk while perched 20ft off the ground held only by a strap and two spikes in the
insteps of their boots.
Special kit includes woollen gloves with grips which allow them to cling to the
ice which inevitably forms on the windward side of the poles.
They are in no doubt about the job they hate most, replacing broken poles. The
poles often snap when the icy ground prevents them from swaying in the wind.
Some of the poles are more than 30 years old but most in vulnerable areas have
been replaced as part of a multi-million refurbishment by Hydro-Electric.
The linesmen, who have been responsible for replacing hundreds of miles of
cable and scores of poles during spells of less inclement weather, believe that
had the storm struck a few years ago the scale of the problem would have been
considerably greater.
When the fir poles do break the linesmen have to summon an excavator to the
location to dig out the old pole.
Poles apart, the challenge of restoring brightness to hundreds of homes is
rewarding for the linesmen.
``I quite like working on faults,'' said Ronnie. ``Sometimes trying to find the
fault can be a challenge and you learn a lot about the system, switching
sections on and off. Trying to solve why someone is receiving strange voltage
can be interesting.''
However, most of the linesmen have been challenged enough over Christmas and
are hoping that the bad weather holds off so they can enjoy New Year with their
families in the warmth of their own homes.
GRAEME SMITH
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Battle to retrieve life from beyond the pale</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635212</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Following a vain five-hour bid by doctors to save three lives, Kirsty Scott
asks if resuscitation really can work
TO UNTRAINED eyes it seemed like a futile task. As the limp, waterlogged bodies
of three people were pulled from a frozen lake in Yorkshire on Thursday there
appeared to be no hope of saving any of them.
Yet rescuers and a team of doctors worked relentlessly for more than five hours
to try to resuscitate them, because there is often a small, slim chance that
victims of such accidents can literally be brought back to life.
``Basically, the cold affects the body by slowing down the system,'' says David
Campbell, a survival expert with the Survival Centre at Robert Gordon
University in Aberdeen. ``It shuts down parts of the body which are not
required to sustain life - the sk
in, the legs, the arms. What you have then is blood going into the core of the
body to maintain the vital organs.
``The body's way of reacting is to slow everything down. The heart can slow
down to somewhere in the region of six beats per minute or even slower.
Sometimes you also have a gagging reflex which closes off the airways and the
water doesn't get into the lu
ngs.''
Much of the original data on the effect on the human body of extreme cold comes
from Nazi experimentation, but there are more recent well-documented cases of
people being successfully resuscitated after long periods in icy water or
outdoor conditions. Mos
t recently, a man was brought round at Edinburgh Royal Infirmary after falling
through ice as he tried to rescue his dog.
In Aberdeen several years ago, a girl who had decided to commit suicide went
into a churchyard, took pills and alcohol and lay down on a bench. She suffered
extreme hypothermia and her body core temperature fell to 18C, the same as the
people in Yorkshir
e, yet she was successfully rewarmed and revived. The normal body temperature
is 36C.
And in one of the most astonishing cases, a two-year-old Canadian girl who was
stuck outdoors for six hours in temperatures of -22 was later revived. The
child's heart had stopped and her body temperature had dropped to 14C, but
doctors hooked her up to
a heart bypass machine and spent five hours slowly bringing her body
temperature up.
Mr David Steedman, a consultant in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary's Accident and
Emergency Department, says it should never be assumed that people who have been
immersed in the cold for long periods have no chance of survival.
``I think in a scenario where major hypothermia is involved you should never,
unless the elements are so dangerous, declare death at the scene. Someone can
look as though they are dead but can be revived successfully.''
Steedman says the longest period someone's heart had stopped and been
successfully revived was three hours and 40 minutes.
Heart bypass, like that used on the young Canadian girl, is the method often
chosen in tandem with gentle warming techniques.
``It is not an infrequent occurrence in Canada and a lot of their resuscitation
units are set up to put these patients on to cardiac bypass,'' says Steedman.
``That's what we did for a patient we had in recently. We managed to transfer
him immediately fro
m Accident and Emergency to a unit which routinely carries out cardiac bypass.''
Steedman says it had originally been thought that children survived cold water
immersion better than adults because they experienced a reflex reaction when
cold water hit their faces, which slowed their heart.
``More recently, people believe that young children have cardiac arrest at a
very much lower temperature than adults. Their hearts keep pumping to a much
lower level, maybe 22 to 23. In an adult, cardicac arrest may be precipitated
at 27 to 28. We now
believe that's the reason why children may survive neurologically intact. In
Canada, young children have survived from extremely low temperatures, even
below 20.
Campbell says the rescuers in Yorkshire would not have attempted resuscitation
on the three victims unless it was possible there was still some life there. He
says there are many factors which affect a person's chances of survival and
some cases which def
y all logic.
``For example, there was an Icelandic trawler which got into difficulties and
the three crewmen went overboard, swam to shore then walked a few miles for
help and they survived. They shouldn't have.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Who watches the watchdogs?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635213</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With regulators paid big sums to make companies the centre of their attention,
Christopher Sims turns the spotlight on the new breed of industry watchdog
PETER Davis, the National Lottery regulator in trouble for accepting free
flights from a major shareholder in Camelot, the company running the Lottery,
is not the first industry regulator to be accused of being nave.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, who oversees the electricity industry, caused an
enormous rumpus in March when he announced a new review of power prices just
after investors had bought a further tranche of electricity shares from the
Government.
The shares immediately fell in value, leaving buyers complaining bitterly that
they had paid too much and that they had been sold them under false pretences.
Labour accused the Government of ``conning'' people into buying the shares.
Professor Littlechild was accused of being nave in not appreciating the impact
his pronouncement would have on share prices. There were mutterings to the
effect that, as he came from an academic background with no experience of
business, he would not app
reciate how the stock market would react to a simple statement that he was
reconsidering the electricity price cap.
The regulators must have a thick skin because by their very nature they are
bound to offend almost everyone. Indeed they are not doing their job well if
all is sweetness and light with those they police.
Their brief is not really to be the consumers' champion, rather they are there
to hold the ring between the consumer and the supplier. So consumers always
think that they are being too soft on the companies and the companies feel they
are not allowing the
m to make a large enough return on their capital.
However, it is clear that companies have been much more profitable than
necessary so shareholders have been massively rewarded. The downward move of
the electricity shares in March was only a temporary blip in an onward march.
Regulators are essential when there are monopoly providers of services,
otherwise consumers would have little protection. But as Don Cruickshank, the
Scot who runs the telephone watchdog Oftel, believes, regulators should be
aiming to make themselves redu
ndant by promoting competition. Once consumers have a genuine choice,
competition will do a better job than a regulator.
But he is finding British Telecom's grip on the domestic market hard to loosen
and the small companies which try to get past the BT colossus would no doubt
accuse him of being nave in his hopes of cracking BT without drastic action.
Cruickshank certainly has experience of the private sector - for several years
he worked for Richard Branson's Virgin Group - but most regulators don't.
However, there is no doubting their intellectual ability, despite their
relatively low pay.
Peter Davis will lose #64,000 a year if he is sacked. Cruickshank is the
highest paid regulator at #124,000 which may seem a lot, but pales beside the
#530,000 plus share options earned by his chief protagonist Sir Iain Vallance,
chairman of BT. Yet he ha
s a job every bit as difficult and responsible. Sir Iain is batting just for
BT, Cruickshank is laying the ground rules for a whole industry.
On the other hand, Clare Spottiswoode appears to have a relatively simple task
as director general of Ofgas, regulating a single straightforward business,
British Gas. At least it seemed so when she took the job in 1993. Since then
the Government has deci
ded to bring forward the date when householders can choose their gas supply
company - now the regulator and British Gas have a more complicated task as a
result.
This was the reason why Michael Heseltine, then Secretary of State for Trade
and Industry, increased her salary by 22% to #90,000 earlier this year. In
contrast, Cedric Brown, the head of British Gas, received a 75% increase to
#475,000 - though he did re
fuse the latest company share options which could have netted him #2.4m. All
the regulators are paid much less than the heads of the companies they oversee.
Professor Littlechild's #102,000 a year compares unfavourably with the #148,000
earned by Murray S
tuart, non-executive chairman of ScottishPower, for example.
Spottiswoode was the successor to Sir James McKinnon, the Scot who was one of
the first of the regulators, and who established a reputation for abrasiveness.
She pursued a gentler path, though she too had to show a thick skin when
denying unfounded rumour
s she had had an affair with the civil servant who recommended her for the job.
Davis is a classic case of the regulator getting too close to the regulated,
something which watchdogs always need to guard against. The regulator and his
staff may have dealings with the same people over several years and it would be
no surprise if a cer
tain camaraderie develops.
It no doubt seemed perfectly reasonable for Davis at the time to accept
``lifts'' from GTECH, he may even have thought he was saving the taxpayer the
cost of several fares. But the warning bells should have rung as soon as the
invitation was made.
The relationship between the regulated and regulator should surely be such that
the former would not dream of offering hospitality to the person who indirectly
controls his profits and thereby the value of the directors' share options.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Africans may be left in the cold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Doug Gillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635214</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DURHAM CROSS-COUNTRY
OUT of Africa there is always something new to confound prospects of a British
cross-country revival. For years it was the Kenyan nemesis, John Ngugi,
collecting a record five world titles. A procession followed him out of the
Rift Valley, and Ethiopia no
w helps fuel our winters of discontent.
The BUPA-backed Durham Worldcross Challenge has done little to treat the
wounds, monopolised successively by James Kariuki (Kenya), Fita Bayesa and
Haile Gebrselassie (both Ethiopia), then Ismael Kirui (Kenya), but today
presents a chance for Andrew Pears
on and Rob Denmark.
Ngugi, now 33 and shedding pounds as he attempts a comeback for the world
championships, should surely be vulnerable, while young compatriot Simeon Rono
is not yet ready to pick up his spear. Assefa Mezgebu, who won the world junior
title at Durham this y
ear, is the one likely to thwart the Brits this time.
This may be the highest quality meeting of Scots on the country this winter -
perhaps even surpassing their own national championships. Men making the trip
south for the 9.4km event include world championship team members Tommy Murray,
Robert Quinn, and C
hris Robison, plus Ken Chapman, Peter Dymoke, Phil Mowbray, Glen Stewart,
Graeme Wight, and Stephen Wylie.
There is also a 2000m race including Clydesdale trio Des Roache, Kheredine
Idessane, and Euan Calvert, plus Frank McGowan (Racing Club).
The women's event, which features City of Glasgow pair Vikki McPherson and
Sheila Fairweather, plus marathon internationalists Allison Rose and Trudi
Thomson, will be a stern test for the Scots.
The opposition includes former world junior champion Paula Radcliffe, Geta Wami
(Ethiopia) fifth in the world cross-country this year, Elena Fidatov (Romania)
third and fourth in the last two European cross-country championships, Lyudmila
Borisova (Russia
) fifth over 1500m at the Gothenburg World Championships, and Zohra Ouaziz
(Morocco) bronze medallist at 5000m in Sweden.
DOUG GILLON
</TEXT>
