<DOCNO>GH951230-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Atherton called on to defy the odds again Another epic script for Captain Fantastic</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE spotlight is on Mike Atherton again as England try to stage a sequel to
their Great Escape in Johannesburg. This time there is an outside chance of
bettering even that blockbuster, with victory a distant but none the less
lingering possibility.
They have 90 overs to survive against Allan Donald, Paul Adams and co - or one
day to score the 308 runs that would result in a remarkable fourth Test victory.
So much, as ever it seems, rests on the slim shoulders of Atherton. He was
Captain Fantastic at the Wanderers after an undefeated 185 enabled England to
draw the second Test against all odds. Now the New Year Honours List may have
to be rewritten if he ca
n produce another epic innings.
Atherton and Alec Stewart - long overdue a meaningful contribution after 16
Test innings as an opener without so much as a half-century - gave England a
solid start tonight by surviving nine overs.
But there is no doubt whose wicket South Africa want most this morning - or
which batsman England can least afford to lose.
``They've got a lot of other good players, but Atherton is their trump card,''
said home opener Gary Kirsten, whose rock-solid contribution of 69 prevented a
full-scale Springbok collapse yeterday ``If we can get him out early, it might
make a difference.
''
Atherton never needs an incentive to fight as though his life depends on the
outcome of every ball, but the performance of a depleted England attack during
South Africa's second innings will make him even more determined, if that is
possible.
Just about everything that could go wrong did go wrong during the first hour of
the fourth day at St George's Park. Far from squeezing out every last run, the
tourists lost their final three first innings wickets in 40 minutes while
adding only 13 to an o
vernight total of 250 for seven.
Then Mark Ilott's attempts to shake off a thigh strain failed before he had
sent down a single delivery. Ilott hobbled away and England were left with
three front-line bowlers.
Dominic Cork, Peter Martin and Richard Illingworth could hardly have done any
more for their side, however.
Cork, meanwhile, was at the centre of a new controversy yesterday. Having
plunged South Africa to the brink of collapse at 69 for six, he resorted to
bowling down the legside while Gary Kirsten and Shaun Pollock tried to set up a
declaration.
Cyril Mitchley eventually called Cork for a wide - and that sparked a debate
between the 57-year-old umpire and captain Mike Atherton.
Twenty-four hours earlier, Mitchley had angered England by giving Atherton out
for a non-existent catch behind. Yesterday, the pair looked close to clashing
over the umpire's interpretation of unfair play.
Mitchley said that he signalled ``wide'' simply because he thought it was out
of Pollock's reach. But the decision had been coming for some time - and that
one delivery looked no further down legside than several others.
The umpire made a point of speaking to Atherton after two balls during Cork's
previous over had given Kirsten little chance of making contact.
South Africa's left-handed opener went on to make 69, keeping alive his side's
chance of victory at St George's Park. ``Maybe it's a good idea but it just
seems like negative cricket to me,'' said Kirsten when asked about England's
tactics.
``I haven't seen it happen too often. You would think maybe they would have
wanted to bowl us out.''
South African coach Bob Woolmer added: ``It's not the greatest part of the game
of cricket but, given the situation, I can understand why it was being done.''
Asked whether his team would resort to the same tactics, Woolmer said: ``I hope
not, no.''
South Africa had recovered from their grim position by the time Cork switched
from striving for wickets to making economy his No.1 priority. ``We had to try
not to give them boundaries,'' said the all-rounder.
