<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Model stars break the season's mould</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635216</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BY my reckoning it was Wallace and Gromit (BBC2, Sunday) by a lumpy Plasticine
head. Weeks of hype, hour after hour of ``blockbusters'', ``star-studded''
specials, and celebrity-ridden ``classics'' - in the end it came down to 30
minutes of stop-motion sl
apstick from one little man and his mutt.
Granted, even Nick Park's animated duo have become a ``tradition'' in three
years, heaven help their squishy little bodies. Granted, too, this year's A
Close Shave bore more than a passing resemblance to the prize-winning The Wrong
Trousers (itself repeat
ed last week). But for genuine invention, observation, and comic timing, the
wee chap and his canine sidekick had no competition.
Ken Russell's execrable ``musical'' Treasure Island (Channel 4, Sunday),
camping it up in that thumpingly heavy-handed style the nation has come to know
and loathe, can be passed over in silence (if only its maker had done the
same). P G Wodehouse's Heavy
Weather (BBC1, Sunday) was forgettable heritage comedy, rich in production
values and ageing actors disappearing over the top. Keeping Up Appearances and
One Foot in the Grave (both BBC1, Monday) were both dog-tired formats, as
wearying as the festival i
tself.
It's the usual debate, in other words: why is Christmas TV quite so bad?
There's plenty of it, no expense has been spared, you look forward to it for
days - but when it comes it's about as welcome as a gift-wrapped packet of
cheap cigars.
The sense of occasion that once attached itself to the TV premiere of a hit
picture has now almost disappeared and the sense of fun once to be had from
something seasonally corny, like Miracle on 34th Street (Channel 4, Sunday),
has been eroded by repetit
ion.
That said, the networks themselves are culpable. In their hands the TV
Christmas, always a delicate thing, has become a faux festival. It wouldn't be
Christmas without Eric and Ernie (BBC1, Sunday), would it? The Wind in the
Willows (ITV, Monday) is tradi
tional - God knows how - is it not?
There has to be Noel Edmonds (BBC1, Monday), surely? And Top of the Pops? And
carols? And the Queen? Tradition, that much-insulted word, is being
manufactured and used as a substitute for imagination. To be charitable, there
were good things, but only a f
ew, and they had little to do with the season. After his ``world tour of
Scotland'' Billy Connolly showed again,  A Scot in the Arctic (BBC1, Thursday),
that he might be on to something with this documentary game. Camping alone on
the roof of the world wh
ile living in fear of polar bears and frozen extremities, he was fluent and
funny, exhibiting unself-consciously his God-given, unstoppable gift of the gab.
STV's McCallum (also Thursday) had the makings of the series it doubtless aims
to become, and not just because John Hannah is as hot at the moment as young
actors get. Overcoming its own predictability, McCallum was a forensic
pathologist (ho hum) investi
gating the death of a colleague. It managed to grip for most of 90 minutes,
largely because the hero appeared to have an interior life at least as
interesting as his action-packed exterior one.
Some actors have conviction on tap, no matter how unpromising the material, and
Hannah is one. He invested the part of McCallum with more complexity than the
script alone could have allowed. He is a star in waiting.
For this column's money only Northern Exposure (Channel 4, Wednesday), making
its last appearance for this season, could touch Wallace and Gromit. The
religious event in question here was Passover, not Christmas, but it was the
best drama of the week none
the less.
The show's vice is its knowingness, its virtue the absolute self-confidence
with which the ensemble move from the real and normal to the surreal,
supernatural, and plain wacky. No matter how comic the plot there is always a
steel thread of real emotions r
unning through it all. I shall miss it.
</TEXT>
