<HEADLINE>Soldiering on as time goes by</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Phil Penfold</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974635217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Phil Penfold speaks to Valerie Singleton who has left the old firm behind to
host a new quiz show and add more than a touch of nostalgia  to her life
HAS it been hard to shake off the ``Aunty Val'' image? Valerie Singleton
visibly shudders and says: ``I really don't know why they called me that . . .
I mean, you never heard of `Uncle John and Uncle Peter' did you?''
However, to a generation of youngsters glued to their teatime TV sets between
1962 and 1972, Singleton will always be a slight authority, strong nostalgia
figure. ``I always thought of myself,'' she says reflectively, ``as a sort of .
. . elder sister.''
A friend of mine observed that every time he saw Singleton, he wanted to sit up
straight and look tidy. She giggles when I tell her this, and says that might
reflect rather more on the standards of television for young people today
rather than on her own
style of presentation. But there we are. Today, Singleton bounces into the room
wearing a fuschia-purple two-piece suit with a black halter-type top. The hair
is short and neatly coiffed, and she has a pair of rimless spectacles to
balance off two enormou
s silver-globe earrings and a gold rope around her neck.
Singleton may be in her mid-fifties, but she looks a good 10 years younger.
She's fit (``I try to walk everywhere - it's not unknown for me to cross London
on the way to work, as long as I'm wearing a pair of sensible shoes''), she's
busy, and she's back
on our TV screens from January 1, hosting a Channel 4 afternoon quiz show
called Backdate.
Channel 4? Isn't this a bit of a departure for the woman who was Mrs BBC for
more than two decades? Why isn't she still with the ``old firm''?
``I don't know, you'd better ask them,'' she says firmly. The truth is perhaps,
that the current state of the Corporation isn't particularly to Singleton's
taste. ``In the old days, I'd know the person at the head of a department, or
the one who was makin
g the particular programme, and we'd talk, or they'd call me, and - perhaps -
they'd think `Oh, Val can do that . . .' and I'd get the offer and away we'd
go. Now, the BBC is dependent on so many independent production companies, all
making their own pitc
h for a particular slot with a particular idea. I might be involved with just
one of those projects, and while it might get shortlisted, it won't be the
final choice. So I don't get the work. It's as simple as that.''
But let's not assume, says Singleton, that she is forever doomed to making
pilot shows that never see the light of day. No way. ``I've been doing an awful
lot of writing, some more travelling, a lot of videos, and quite a lot of
corporate presentation for
various firms,'' she explains. ``I haven't been sitting twiddling my thumbs.''
Single, she lives in South London (``with a cat called Daisy. She's very old,
so we get on well together'') and if there is anyone in her life, she's not
saying so. Her mother died not so long ago, so she tends to see her father
quite a bit. Indeed, the p
air of them spent Christmas together, ``with a few friends''. Other than that,
there is a brother and two nieces to make up the Singleton clan, and that's it.
From what she reveals, it seems that Singleton doesn't mind doing things alone.
``I like going to galleries, and museums, travelling, and if I have any
ambition at all, it's to become proficient in something,'' she says. ``I've
been doing some pretty inte
resting evening classes in architecture, art, and archaeology recently, and
they've been terrifically absorbing. In an ideal world, I'd like to win the
Lottery, go to Italy for a year and learn the language while discovering all I
can about their art and
history.''
She gives the distinct impression that she thinks herself to be the Jill of all
trades and - arguably - the mistress of none. ``I started out at Rada and
dancing school,'' she says, ``and then I went into television presentation and
did all sorts of thing
s before someone spotted me at the BBC and thought I might do rather well with
a new programme called Blue Peter.
``I'd done TV advertising programmes, which were allowed in those days, I'd
been a stage ingenue, and I'd been a hoofer. I'd never been really out of work,
but I don't think I'd ever really found my niche until Blue Peter came along.
``I even did a stage tour of Britain supporting Jessie Matthews and Sonnie Hale
in a show called Nest of Robins. By then, they'd got divorced and the
atmosphere on stage was . . er, well, sometimes rather `strained'. She was a
great trooper, however, and
I suppose I learned a lot of stage craft from her. Oh, I'd do anything back
then. Anything they offered. I even appeared in Emergency, Ward 10!''
And it seems that Singleton will do just about anything today. ``Not just
because it's offered,'' she says, ``don't make it out that I'm desperate. I'm
not. It's got to be something with a touch of originality to it. Something that
stimulates me. Hence Ba
ckdate, which I do think has the potential of a shelf-life as long as
Blockbusters or Countdown if we're lucky. The feel-good thing about this new
show is that the contestants are all such nice people. And meeting people is
very important to me. Keeping i
n touch, you see.''
People still think that she's presenting The Money Programme, PM and - even -
Tonight. ``The fact that I haven't, and for several years, doesn't seem to
matter,'' she says, ``so I just thank them for the compliment. I think that you
become such a familiar
face that it takes a long time to sink in.'' I very much enjoyed The Money
Programme in the beginning. PM had a very broad remit to begin with, we'd
review books, talk to authors, visiting artists. Then it swung entirely to news
and current affairs, and
perhaps that wasn't entirely what I wanted to do."
Backdate will ask questions about ``sport, the arts, politics, films . . .
anything. It's all to do with a particular date selected from the last 50 years
by our computer at random. It combines nostalgia and tactical skills and I
think it's great fun.''
Singleton admits that she has always kept a diary "even if it was a selection
of thoughts scribbled on hotel notepaper and it's always been a source of
amazement to me that, even when I've been working hard all day, I've seemed to
write so much.''
Life today, reflects Singleton, ``is much more uncertain. You're a freelance,
available for hire. But I think that it makes it rather more fun. I'm
deliberately trying to shift direction. I don't see me still presenting TV
shows when I'm 70 - heaven forfe
nd! By then, I think - I hope - I'll be writing full-time.''
So how does she relax? ``I'm not very good at that, I admit. But I can never
spend enough money on books,'' she says, ``and I tend to eat out a lot, because
I'm not a great cook.''
She must, I assume, be a pretty rotten person to buy for, should anyone want to
get her a gift or a Christmas present. The woman who has everything?
``I'd far rather get something practical, like a pair of tights,'' she says,
``or a #5 pocket art guide. Simple things mean so much more to me. The sad
thing about growing old is realising how little you actually need - and also
how little time you've got
left to learn about what you actually want to.''
One thing she has recently enjoyed, she reflects, was the shopping for a whole
series of new outfits for Backdate. ``I went out with a very nice lady from the
wardrobe department, and the result is that I've got some lovely frocks to
wear. This (she smoot
hs the skirt of the suit) is one of them.''
And only today, she admits, the tables have been turned as far as remembering
one particular date is concerned. ``Geoff Hurst is doing a celebrity book on
the anniversary of England winning the World Cup, so he's written to me asking
where I was on that p
articular day . . . it'll mean a trip to the diaries, I know!''
And no-one could resist asking the million-dollar question of Singleton. Has
she still got a coveted Blue Peter badge? ``I used to have two,'' she
confesses, ``but the floor manager on Backdate told me how his ambition all his
life was to get one, so I ga
ve him one of them.
"Yes, I still hold on to and treasure that little piece of personal nostalgia.
You can't escape it - ever.''
</TEXT>
