<HEADLINE>Good year for the roses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Liz Taylor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNDER THE HAMMER
THE last Saturday of 1995 seems a good day from which to survey the activities
of the past year in the saleroom and look for possible future trends. On the
whole, buyers took a canny approach to their purchases, resolutely turning
their backs on things wh
ich had been over-enthusiastically estimated by auctioneers. As a result,
specialities which have been much vaunted in the past settled down to a far
less hysterical pace.
A good example can be found in teddy bears, which have lost a lot of their
steam. Now a decent Steiff bear can change hands at around #3000, not the five
and six figure sums they were making a couple of years ago. I'm always fairly
sceptical about astonis
hing prices unfailingly publicised by auction houses in an effort to drum up
business and enthusiasm. Are all those prices really genuine indicators? I
doubt it, for what's to stop unscrupulous collectors being under-bidders for
their own treasures? If th
ey're stuck with the goods in the end, they're paying themselves with only the
saleroom commission to find.
An example of an over-estimated bear coming unstuck occurred earlier this month
when Donald Campbell's Merrythought teddy bear, Mr Whoppit, went home unsold
after Christie's put him up for sale with a price of between #50,000 and
#60,000. Poor Whoppit is
a survivor though, his ordeal by water on Lake Coniston proves that, so we'll
probably be seeing him again.
If bears are in the doldrums, however, other toys have done reasonably well
during the year and there is a big collecting enthusiasm for everything from
Dinky cars to models of Lady Penelope. Among the notable prices were #11,375
for a pair of Japanese do
lls in silk kimonos which Christie's in London sold in June. The month before,
a Minic toy car, a Bentley Sunshine Saloon, was sold by the same auctioneers
for #3600.
Like bears however, Rock and Pop memorabilia is another area showing signs of
coming to the end of an inflationary period - things like Jimi Hendrix's
jacket, or George Harrison's spare guitar. There seems to be too much material
of meagre quality around,
but during the year there have been a few highlights such as when Cynthia
Lennon sold John's Japanese Airlines ``Happi Coat'' at Christie's in London.
She must have been as surprised as everyone else when it made #18,000, for
these coats were free gifts
from airlines for their first class passengers in the 60s and Lennon probably
left it behind with Cynthia when he went off with Yoko Ono - he himself
couldn't have set much store by it.
Another pop world surprise was a 1961 recording made by a classmate at Dartford
Grammar School of Keith Richards and Mike Jagger - the earliest known recording
of the soon-to-be famous Rolling Stones. A collector paid #50,250 for it last
May.
Specialist sales always raise good audiences with money to spend. Golf sales,
football sales and whisky sales did well in 1995 for Christie's in Glasgow. I
wonder if the buyer who paid #3900 for a bottle of Macallan Glenlivet in March
has drunk it by now?
In July, one of the stars of Christie's golf sale was an Austrian bronze figure
of a golfer wearing plus-fours which sold for #2,185, and their November
football sale realised #224,733, double the expected total. Top lot was the
Sheriff London Shield whic
h sold for an astonishing #39,000. Phillips in Edinburgh also returned very
good figures from their golf sale in July when a selection of old golf balls
made spectacular improvements on their estimates - one going as high as #19,995
when estimated at betw
een #7000 and #10,000.
As far as paintings are concerned, the Scottish Colourists spent the year
recording prices well below their previous highs, but on December 1 there was a
glimmer of hope for better days when Phillips in Edinburgh sold a Peploe
still-life of fruit and rose
s to a London dealer for #50,580. This painting had an interesting history
because it was saved from a house fire five years ago.
Another Scottish artist who never seems to have been awarded the honour she
deserves is Phoebe Anna Traquair; in October, Phillips of Edinburgh sold a
lovely copper casket made by her for the very good price of #2350 though they
had estimated at between #
500-700.
A trend for the future is the recent escalation in prices in the field of
Decorative Arts, especially William Morris style pieces dating from the turn of
the century. They have been doing very well and some very interesting things
are appearing on the mar
ket, like the embroidered table mats Phillips sold in Edinburgh for #4470
(estimated at #600), and the set of framed Morris tiles representing the
seasons of the year which made an astonishing #32,000 (estimate #12,000).
Another area that has been quietly booming is jewellery. Perhaps canny
investors are putting their cash into diamonds instead of securities.
Christie's in Glasgow reports its jewellery sales have done particularly well
over the year and among the highligh
ts were a diamond brooch sold in June for #27,600, and an emerald and diamond
ring sold for #20,700. In November they also auctioned a Hamilton and Inches
diamond tiara/necklace for #16,675.
The saleroom always throws up interesting oddities and one-offs that amuse
rather than give guidelines about where to go in the future. One such was Ian
Fleming's gold plated typewriter that Christie's sold in London for #55,750,
and a rare Kangaroo bicyc
le of 1885 that Phillips sold in Edinburgh for #8000 in August. Of course,
there's not many gold plated typewriters or Kangaroo bicycles around, so don't
waste time looking for them.
Anyone who is cleaning out old drawers or an attic over the holiday period
should keep an eye open for a few special things - like glass Christmas tree
decorations made in Germany in the 1950s. These irridescent glass balls are now
making very respectable
money, at least a couple of hundred for a good selection.
The second little money spinner might be an old fountain pen. Japanese Dunhill
Namiki's are making big money now, but don't despise your old Parker Vacumatic
because one sold last year for #220 and a mixed lot of a Swan Eternal self
filler, two Parker 51'
s, a Waterman and a Swan made #300. They were sold at Sotheby's in
Billingshurst.
Finally, don't disregard Susie Cooper's cheap and cheerful pottery. She died
this year and there's nothing like dying for raising an artist's price up.
Susie's crockery is now set to chase Clarice Cliff pottery into the high price
range.
</TEXT>
