<TEXT>
BEAUTY BOX
ENLIGHTENED capitalism has caught on. The Body Shop is no longer the only
cosmetic company which aligns profit with principle. The Aveda Corporation,
too, are concerned with trading fairly with the environment, minority groups
and indigenous tribes under
threat from pollution or poverty. It's hard to say what's going on here.
Aveda promote a lifestyle. The premier magazine issue of Aveda, The Beauty of a
Balanced Life, is essentially a catalogue of products which range from the
Eco-Spun Mandarin-Collar Sherpa Cardigan to Volumising Dandruff Tonic. It lists
recipes for organic
produce, and features articles on modern living which draw moral conclusions -
well, produce guilt really. Cheery quotations, such as ``the end of the human
race will be that it will eventually die of civilisation'' (Ralph Waldo
Emerson), litter the pages
. Beauty advice borrows from the ancient Indian Ayurvedic tradition; Aveda say
ageing well is a matter of eating simply and being at peace with oneself.
There is no way any company would bother preaching green politics to the public
if there wasn't money to be made by consumer conversion. The environmental
evangelists don't want their account in the red. If they are scoring profit
then there is a consiste
nt and serious demand for cosmetics which also supply a philosophy of life.
This has a novelty value. If only that for centuries, the personal and touchy
area of how someone looks has been abused and ridiculed by fashion. Being
downtrodden with low-self e
steem is anti-life and anti-social. Buying goods without regard to their source
is passe . The new breed of female (and male) consumer, equates health with
beauty, beauty with contentedness, happiness with confidence.
There will come a time, where anyone who copies the anodyne images punted by
cynical women's magazines and misogynist designers, will be treated with the
same sartorial derision as those who wear shell-suits. The pursuit of
individuality, of personal evol
ution is on its way, but it will ultimately be ignored for the right-wing
discipline and intellectual rigour of convention. But each step forward, even
cancelled by two steps back, is still a way of forging a path ahead. And I
suspect Aveda are the flagsh
ip of a shift of public opinion.
They bang on about environmental issues, the way Cosmopolitan cries out rules
on how to have great sex. But Aveda's range is intended to come on as more
cerebral. There aren't chapters, there are ``domains''; there isn't perfume,
there is Pure-Fume design
ed to complement the seven Chakras.
It has to be said, that Aveda's essential-oil based essences are crackingly
exotic. Their comprehensive range of cosmetics comes in what look like real
colours, deep, strong, and free from petrochemicals. Think about it. On
average, a woman will swallow a
tube and a half of synthetic lipstick a year, which her system will never
digest. Aveda's lipstick shades are derived from plant pigment - they use
beeswax and essential oils, Vitamin E, jojoba and basil.
The company says that plants are the much-maligned saviours of the planet.
Approximately 25 per cent of commercially available prescription drugs contain
plant-derived compounds, at an annual market value of $10 million. These
natural drugs include some o
f the most important medicines in the physician's cabinet, yet less than 10 per
cent of the world's 450,000 to 750,000 plant species have been investigated as
potential sources of new drugs.
In the sixties, an effective treatment for Hodgkins Disease was found in the
rosy periwinkle from the rainforest. The drug taxol, important in treating
ovarian and breast cancer, was distilled from extracts from the Pacific Yew, a
tree found in the Pacifi
c Northwest and British Columbia. Now the National Cancer Institute in America
spends a half million dollars a year taking samples from tropical regions.
Richard Schultes PhD, of Harvard University, says: ``The caveman must have been
an Ethnobotanist, bec
ause he had to learn which plants could kill him or possibly cure some disease
or feed him.'' Like I said, sometimes you need to get into reverse gear to go
foward.
n Aveda are based in America but have an outlet in Frasers, Buchanan Street,
Glasgow. Call Direct: 0141 221 7313
n Beauty Box has 50 Aveda vouchers worth #10 each, and which can be used at any
time, to give away to the first 50 readers who write in. The voucher enables
you to a free Aveda treatment at the Glasgow branch: of Frasers. You can choose
from 1) A stress r
elieving treatment, which involves the massage of the scalp using essential
oils, 2) an aromatherapy facial 3) a personalised make-up session with skincare
analysis and colour photo, or 4) a hand treatment. Please write to Anvar Khan,
The Herald, 195 Albi
on Street, Glasgow G1 1QP. You must include an address.
