<TEXT>
LADY CLAIRE'S KITCHEN
OH dear, another 51 weeks before it's Christmas again - I imagine some of you
must think I am quite mad! But now we look forward to the New Year. If, like
me, you have a house full of family and friends and have done so for many days
now, you may be wonde
ring about a special dish for dinner on New Year's Eve.
And you may be racking your brains to think of a dish which is special but
which doesn't take ages to make - a party type of main course made in minutes
rather than hours spent in preparation, then more in washing up; after all,
life is too short.
I thought that today we would discuss dishes suitable for entertaining when the
host or hostess is short on time, and quite possibly slightly weary. I never
get sick of having guests for Christmas and New Year, in fact I love them and I
love having the ho
use full of family and friends, but there is no escaping the fact it is quite
tiring.
We tend to have a fairly formal dinner on New Year's Eve. If you haven't
thought about the menu, start by planning the main course and arrange the first
course and pudding around that.
In an ideal world, and if I have remembered to get them and freeze them, we
would have venison fillets. They are so quick to cook - I like them undercooked
to the point of pinkness, but I do not like venison fillet cooked so rare that
the meat is red.
A simple sauce is made by cooking sliced mushrooms in butter with a dash of
sunflower oil till they are almost crisp, which improves the natural taste of
the mushrooms, then reducing Madeira and venison stock (you can substitute a
Game consomme, bought in
a can) till it has a syrupy texture - it should reduce by half to reach this
texture.
I leave the ratio of Madeira and stock to you, but half and half I find about
right. Serve with homemade redcurrant or rowan jelly. You may not have access
to venison fillet, but if you can get beef fillet there is always the classic
Beef Stroganoff, wher
e the meat is cut into little finger-thick strips, stir-fried over high heat,
then served in a reduced cream and brandy sauce.
But the recipe today is very simple and quick to make. To a certain extent it
can be prepared in the morning, needing only no more than five minutes cooking
that evening before dinner. Its great plus point is that it is versatile in its
main ingredient. I
have made this dish using monkfish, chicken breasts, or pheasant breasts: it
would be equally good with turkey breasts or pork fillet.
It has a simple and attainable collection of ingredients - leeks, ginger,
garlic, mustard and creme fraiche. One of the most helpful things to use for
this dish is a large saute pan.
What you serve with it depends to a certain extent on the main ingredient. For
instance, if you are using a firm-fleshed fish such as monkfish, or prawns,
then I would choose rice to accompany it. On the other hand, with a meat or
fowl version you could j
ust as well have potatoes cut in large chunks and roasted in olive oil, with or
without garlic, and with a good dusting of paprika in the roasting tin, and any
steamed or microwaved vegetable, such as sprouts - if you haven't had them too
often recently -
spinach, or sugar snap peas.
For a first course you could have smoked fish, either smoked trout, salmon, or
eel. Or, if you have the time and inclination, you could make a smoked fish
mousse or pate.
For pudding anything lemony is a good contrast to the first two courses,
possibly a straightforward lemon mousse, or a baked lemon pudding, or lemon
sorbet. If you happen to have any egg whites in your fridge, it takes very few
minutes to make a vanilla p
avlova, on which you could spread lemon curd and whipped cream.
If you use bought lemon curd sharpen it up with grated lemon rind and just
enough lemon juice, taking care not to let it become too runny. Making your own
lemon curd takes six minutes cooking in the microwave, giving the ingredients
two minutes on high, t
hen a good whisk, and repeating twice more. Assembling the ingredients for
lemon curd doesn't take long either. I use the grated rind and juice of two
lemons to one whole egg, plus two yolks, from large eggs, 3 oz butter cut in
bits, and 3oz caster sugar.
This has a sharp taste and would cover a pavlova which would feed eight.
NEW YEAR FILLET
n Monkfish, or Prawns, or Chicken, or Pork Fillet, or Pheasant in mustard and
creme fraiche sauce.
Serves 6-8
2lbs of whatever meat you use, sliced neatly into even pieces - about one inch
thick for fish, smaller for pheasant, pork fillet or chicken - or into
finger-thick strips
2 tablespoons of sunflower oil or olive oil
1oz butter
3 good sized leeks, washed, trimmed and sliced thinly
one inch of fresh ginger, pared of its skin and finely chopped
1 clove of garlic, skinned and finely chopped (optional)
1 tablespoon good grainy mustard, though use less if vinegary
1 teaspoon flour
2 pots (200ml) creme fraiche
Salt, pepper to taste.
Heat the oil and melt the butter together in a saute pan. Cook the sliced
leeks, ginger, and garlic together till the leeks are soft. You can do this in
the morning. Cut up the fish or fowl or pork in the morning. Scoop the cooked
leeks out of the saute p
an into a warm dish, and cook the fish or meat over a fairly high heat,
stirring all the time. As the pieces turn opaque they are cooked - that is why
it is so important to cut the pieces so small.
Replace the cooked leeks and ginger in with the fish or meat, stir in the
flour, let it cook for a few seconds then stir in the creme fraiche and
mustard. Let the sauce bubble for a minute, taste and season with salt pepper.
You can keep this warm, in a c
overed dish at low temperature in the oven, but not for too long.
</TEXT>
