<TEXT>
A SLICE OF LIFE
n.Jimmie Macgregor talks to Leila Farrah about a typical day's eating
LEFT to my own devices I would treat food as something to be done quickly
before getting back to work, but I appreciate the skill and patience that goes
into preparing a good meal.
For donkey's years I could never face breakfast so I'd go out on three or four
cups of tea. On tour you'd come off stage, it's party time and you're up half
the night, so you don't get up for 7.30 breakfast the next day but use room
service instead.
Quite often I'd go through the whole day without food, but by drinking the
worst kind of tea that's bad for your nervous system and sex life, full of
tannin, lots of sugar. There was a fair alcohol intake as well - bad stuff
this, but I'm being honest - a
nd you got high calories from that. And I'd have my main meal of the day at
11pm - never before going on stage because it slows you down. Absolutely stupid.
Just recently I realised the difference between my waist and chest measurements
was diminishing. So now I eat - and I hate the word - a little muesli in the
morning, tea with less sugar, and I enjoy peppermint tea.
I won't have lunch unless I'm at a function and they always give you salmon
which I find rather boring. I prefer Gravadlax or even tinned salmon - I love
the texture of the wee bones when you crunch them. A good herring has 20 times
the flavour of most sa
lmon I come across at functions. You used to be able to walk across Loch Fyne
over the herring, it would teem with them. Fish stocks are being raided now.
If I cook for myself it's haddock or monkfish from McCallums, that lovely fish
shop on Kelvinbridge, and potatoes. I'll eat a little fruit if I'm hungry
during the day. And when I'm filming and out walking, we carry food like
chicken legs and sandwiches.
Cakes and biscuits bore me, especially chocolate cake.
I like to eat Asian: at the Ashoka, the Shish Mahal and the Creme de la creme
but I eat nothing to hot because that kills the flavour. It's like drinking
high octane whisky with no water - you only get the burn. I'm getting bored
with Chinese food, but I'
m fond of Indonesian.
I appreciate the delicacy and aesthetics of Japanese food which is out of
character with me because I'm dead coarse and just grab stuff. When I was a
little kid, a local grocer used to make a gigantic, absolutely delicious
clootie dumpling - three feet ac
ross and 18 inches high. I'd buy a slice with my pocket money, take it home and
fry it. My father told me once he'd seen the wee shop cleaner washing the
windows and standing on the dumpling in her stockinged feet...... that didn't
stop me.
n.JIMMIE Macgregor MBE has worked as a schoolteacher, labourer, potter,
mortuary attendant, folk musician, illustrator and radio and television
presenter deeply involved in the folk music revival in Britain. He has made
more than 20 records and has perfor
med all over the world.
</TEXT>
