<HEADLINE>Canvassing ideas for a different holiday</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John McCalman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT can cost as much as a package holdiday in Spain; in fact it may even cost
more, given the spectacular deals currently offered by travel companies.
Nevertheless, a camping holiday in Brittany can provide a welcome change of
pace and culture for those wh
o are becoming disenchanted with the increasingly grotesque features of some
Mediterranean resorts.
Camping is a quality business in France and facilities are invariably of a
higher standard than can be found in Britain. Serious campers from Germany, the
Netherlands, Scandinavia, and France itself have fastidious tastes and high
standards must be mainta
ined.
Having camped in various parts of the United Kingdom, the sites provided by
Eurocamp along the stunning and unspoiled coastline of Brittany offer a series
of pleasant surprises.
As regular visitors to Brittany will testify, the beaches are magnificent -
clean, uncrowded, and yet easily accessible by car.
Sites are well managed and, in turn, owners expect responsible behaviour. No
lager louts here. Staff are unobtrusively helpful and locals are unfailingly
courteous and kind.
There is always a bonjour and au revoir from shop assistants and cafe and bar
staff. No-one is ignored. One longs for a similar civilised attitude here in
the UK.
This particular Eurocamp holiday begins with a memorable Brittany Ferries
crossing to Cherbourg from Poole in Dorest - surely one of the most spectacular
harbours anywhere.
As the gorgeous Dorset coastline unfolds to starboard, from the the Old Harry
Rocks at Studland and sweeping on past Swanage to Weymouth in the far distance,
we wonder why we should be leaving.
However, the memory of incredibly busy roads, parking pressures, and the sheer
vulgarity of some of the holiday areas turns our thoughts to the promised
quality and quietude of the Brittany camping holiday.
A two-day stopover in a handsomely-appointed Eurocamp mobile home at Chateau de
Galinee yields a first taste of North Brittany which has some of the most
spectacular coastline in France, along with a wealth of splendid, uncrowded
sandy beaches.
The inland site is barely ten minutes from the Cote d'Emeraude, a beautiful
stretch of jagged coastline, west of the smart modern resort of Dinard.
However, our interest was focused on the smaller, but popular resort of St Cast
whose Grand Plage is one of
the largest sandy beaches in the region.
It is also incredibly scenic. From the northern tip of Pointe de St Cast there
are stunning views of the Emerald Coast. The rugged Fort La Latte can be seen
brooding to the north west. Strengthened in the 17th century, it has stood on
its rocky promontory
for over one thousand years.
Of equal interest is Cap Frehel, one of the most outstanding features of the
Emerald Coast. The great lighthouse, whose beacon can be seen for nearly 100
miles in good weather, dominates the landscape. The cliffs here are 100 metres
high and their dull pi
nk colouring provides a startling contrast on a fine day with the emerald sea
and white surf.
Sprinkled liberally among the cliff formations are delightful, smaller sandy
beaches which we had a closer look at while sampling another Eurocamp Mobile at
nearby Le Chatelet. This is a larger, family-orientated site, in a dream site
overlooking the bay.
Despite being much busier with many more camping pitches, our stay was
nethertheless enjoyable, with campers affording each other mutual respect and
consideration.
For a day trip, the spectacular Mont-St-Michel, the 13th Century Benedictine
Abbey 40 miles to the north, is de rigueur. Built on a rock surrounded by sand
flats, the abbey and town has been described as ``the wonder of the western
world''.
On the day of our visit it seemed the rest of the western world was there to
share the experience. It was a veritable ant hill of tourists, with barely room
to squeeze past each other in the narrow, winding streets. Still, it should be
seen.
Even more family-orientated was our third Eurocamp site, 90 miles further south
at La Trinite-sur-Mer, the internationally-acclaimed yachting centre in the
heart of Quiberon Bay where ocean racers dominate the huge town-centre marina.
A mile out of town, Camping de La Plage offers a family holiday with direct
access to a fine sandy beach and, like the other two sites, a swimming pool
with play facilities.
The number of campers is high, but again the considerate behaviour of the
hundreds of campers meant a high activity family holiday and peacful, relaxing
break, were not incompatible.
Amazingly for such a crowded site, things get very quiet after 10pm. Is
everyone in bed? Not likley. A stroll around the site reveals almost every
family gathered around their anti-insect candles and bottles of wine, topping
off the late meal with some ci
vilised conversation. Children were tremendously well behaved and, again, no
lager louts.
Perhaps the only negative feature was the five o'clock alarm call provided by a
demented, and seemingly lonely, cockerel on a neighbouring property. Not
everyone on site appreciated this service.
``Lovely site, but I could choke that cockrel,'' a fellow camper declared.
Eurocamp mobile homes sleep up to six and are equipped with cooker, barbeque,
fridge, toilet and shower facilities. Tents, also with cooker and fridge
facilities, are also available. In addition, the camp sites visited had superb
toilet and washing facili
ties.
Special basins are set aside for washing clothes and dishes, and baby baths are
provided. The site washing machines and ironing rooms may be a harsh reminder
of home but are a Godsend for those who don't want to pack too many cases.
South Brittany offers the visitor a charming blend of old and new. It is an
area rich in local traditions and culture, yet its vibrant coastal resorts
attract visitors from all over Europe.
The coastline ranges from the ``cote sauvage'' of Quiberon to small sheltered
coves and ports offering boat trips to off-shore islands.
Generally, the region is relatively unspoilt and the picturesque villages and
old quarters of towns, such as Auray, Vannes and Nantes, are well worth
visiting, especially on markets days.
While there is an ample spread of supermarkets and hyper-markets to meet the
routine supply needs of campers, local markets provide a fascinating insight
into local culinary and craft traditions. The one at La Trinite sure Mer was
set up once a week in th
e car park of the local supermarket - a situation we couldn't imagine being
replicated in this country.
An astonishing range of strange-looking potted meats, pates, and bakery
products was being vigorously marketed, with stallholders proffering samples to
hesitant tourists. Fresher than fresh fish from the bay were being gutted and
sold on the spot.
Animal rights zealots would perhaps have have frowned on the cages of Breton
Spaniels being offered for sale.
This is cider-producing country, and so the wine connoisseur has to consider a
day trip to the Loire Valley to access the nearest local vintage. However, the
cider, either flat or sparkling, is an excellent accompaniment to savoury
crepes and the wide ran
ge of sea food that is available almost straight from the harbour.
Poultry, mainly free-range, is of excellent quality, and may be supplemented if
action is taken against that demented cockerel at La Trinite-sur-Mer.
n.A 14-night stay in a Eurocamp mobile home for two adults and four children
during the high season will cost around #1200. All under-18s are free but each
additional adult requires a supplement of #95.
</TEXT>
