<TEXT>
TO get away with naming a Glasgow restaurant Froggies, you would surely have to
be French. The British more tactfully or more pretentiously would call it Les
Grenouilles. At any rate, Froggies is indeed that rarity in Scotland, a French
restaurant which i
s genuinely French, yet which is not, apparently, just another offshoot of
Pierre Victoire.
It is French enough, moreover, to have a chef from Marseilles and a proprietor
from Toulouse, though after that the resemblance between Froggies and a French
restaurant - a French French restaurant of the sort you find in France - begins
to falter.
The decor, though Frenchified with posters, atmospheric photographs, and lots
of global lighting, cannot conceal the fact that the personality of this large,
lofty space in Glasgow's business centre is basically lounge-bar or possibly
steak-house British.
The colour gamut ranging from beige to brown with a patterned red carpet is no
more than marginally cheered up by tricolour pennants dangling above your head.
On a quiet day, the mood is glum.
But the staff at least seem pleased to see you, even if nobody bothers to bring
you that fundamental French restaurant requisite, a basket of bread. About the
Frenchness of the menu, however, there can be no doubt, even if - or
particularly as - the three
-course set lunch at #9.95 and dinner at #12.95 are of the brusque ``menu
touristique'' type. But if poulet chasseur is not to your taste, the  la carte
menu provides an escape route, with its emphasis on regional dishes and the
promise, you may hope, of
a dash more flair.
The fish soup which comes at the incredibly low price of #2.15, with bowls of
cheese, crispy toast, and a passable rouille, certainly has the tang of
authenticity you would expect of a restaurant that has someone from Marseilles
at the helm. This is good
enough to make you consider escalating another time to the bouillabaisse at the
more predictable price of #16.95. Choucroute and cassoulet, rather less
expensive, are among the options, but the confit de canard last week proved a
depressingly dim represen
tation of the real thing.
A limp piece of duck, with slithery skin and stringy flesh, seemed a poor shot
at a dish which the Auberge, Edinburgh's leading French restaurant, gets
absolutely right, and the accompanying omni-purpose vegetables - potatoes,
carrots, mange-touts - were
no compensation. The wine list is uninvitingly perfunctory, and the house white
much too sweet.
In self-tribute, Froggies does incorporate frog's legs among its starters. But
what is to be expected of Duck's at the Marche Noir? The fractured name is a
clumsy extension of what used to be, more simply and snappily, the Marche Noir.
As for the restaura
nt itself, on the northern fringe of Edinburgh's New Town, this, too, has been
extended, so that what was once a somewhat forlorn entrance bar has been
renovated to form a section of the restaurant itself.
Unfortunately, none of the changes quite works. What used to look forlorn still
looks rather forlorn, and what used to be a neat name now seems guaranteed to
puzzle newcomers who might arrive expecting duck (if not ducks or duck's) to be
the restaurant's
theme, along the lines of the famous duck restaurant in Warsaw which, when it
runs out of duck, has to close its doors.
But no, though the menu includes a token duck dish, the name is that of the
proprietor, Malcolm Duck, and the aim is at least partly to degallicise what
never has been a genuinely French restaurant anyway. So now we are greeted with
such printed absurditi
es as ``Le Lunch'', ``Le Dinner'', ``Le Desert'', and ``Le Coffee'', and the
menu, though listed as ever in elaborate French, now incorporates an English
translation on a separate page.
Perhaps because the cooking falls into that zone where the ingredients are
Scottish but the style French, the hybrid menu -  la carte at lunchtime,
#19.50, three-course prix fixe in the evening - can be claimed to justify
itself. But except for the fact
it saves the staff from having to explain the dishes to the customers, it does
all seem rather a waste of effort. The food produced by the young Scottish
chef, if you are not by then too exasperated to eat it, is, rather good.
True, my pheasant last week came with tiny shallots rather than with the more
interesting caramelised apples that were promised both in French and English,
but the meat was nicely moist. The preceeding timbale of prawns and crab was
sabotaged by its vineg
ary artichoke accompaniment but there was a good crme brulee to finish with,
even if it was overwhelmed by the gigantic plate it was served on.
The wine list - a battleground between France and the New World - is skillfully
assembled and not overpriced. This is a restaurant whose intentions could be
said to conquer its pretensions, and whose smart service makes up for its
mishaps. But at times on
ly just.
n Froggies, 53 West Regent Street, Glasgow (Tel: 0141 332 8790). Set
three-course lunch for two with a modest bottle of wine, about #30. Set
three-course dinner with a modest bottle of wine, about #36,  la carte about
#50.
n Duck's at the Marche Noir, 2/4 Eyre Place, Edinburgh (Tel: 0131 558 1608).
Three-course lunch for two with a modest bottle of wine, about #36. Set
three-course dinner with a modest bottle of wine, about #50.
</TEXT>
