<TEXT>
Pests are food
for thought
KNOW your enemy. Pond Cottage on a pale winter afternoon sets a deceptively
peaceful scene. Sheep are grazing in a field across the road. Two deer,
startled by the car, leap the fence and run for the trees. Buzzards cry
overhead on their lunchtime flight
above the open ground we haven't got round to planting. A small grey vole
scarpers in fright as I'm digging the last of the potatoes. At dusk rabbits
help themselves to what's left of the vegetable garden.
Like the gardeners in the last two articles in this series we want a garden
full of wildlife. Our pond is big but dying from silt and nitrate suffocation,
so I envy Matt Smith's lively haven for frogs and newts in the middle of
Glasgow. Our plot, sliced f
rom farmland, is too exposed to welcome many birds yet, and I know we will have
to wait a long time to create anything like the sheltered intimacy of Rosemary
Wilkes' mature garden in East Lothian.
In the meantime, we are learning that not all wildlife is welcome. Especially
if it is not really wild. Deer, voles, even rabbits, still cause an involuntary
pleasure but only the buzzard is on our side. Buzzards eat rabbits and knowing
who eats what is t
he secret of survival for any future trees and shrubs we intend to plant.
The gardener is at the top of the food chain but who would know it looking at
the havoc caused in my garden after a day or two of hungry visitors? Stray
sheep have devoured the best part of #100 worth of healthy new stock planted in
early November when th
e soil was still warm enough to get the roots off to a good start. On the
advice of the nursery, I did not bother with tree shelters as rabbits and deer
have not caused much damage to the hedgerow established two years ago. In the
ideal world trees grow s
tronger and fitter without shelters which can create a microclimate for weeds,
voles and all manner of leaf-eating insects.
But in the ideal world there are no marauding sheep to crop the silver birch
plantation, munch the sweet briar hedge and polish off the guelder rose and
cotoneaster. They left the mint but that is no compensation for the loss of
time, effort - and expecta
tions. At least half of the pleasure of planting is the picture you see in your
mind's eye as you dig. Instead of this weedy, wind-swept bank there is the
future tree-lined footpath where local people walk on their way to the village:
silver birch mixed w
ith holly and juniper to shelter the garden from the prevailing wind and frame
the view from the kitchen window.
The holly and juniper suffered only a mild nibbling but I will have to start
again with the silver birch and it will be spring before I know whether the
rose hedge will send up new shoots. I chose roses to separate the newly sown
lawn from the path leadin
g to the pond and wood. Rosa rubiginosa grows fast, produces pink roses in
summer and big, cheerful hips in winter. It seemed suited to a cottage garden
and at #45 for 15 metres it was a third of the price of yew. But yew is deadly
poisonous to livestock
which now makes it seem an excellent investment.
Revenge is meat. I've been eating a lot of lamb lately but maybe it is not a
good idea to increase demand and stimulate supply. Over-production is what
causes most of our problems in the first place, according to the botanist
Oliver Rackham in the History
of the British Countryside. As Rackham tells it, rabbits, introduced in the
12th century to produce meat on poor grazing land, were once delicate things
which could hardly dig their own burrows. They did not become a pest until the
19th century when tast
es changed and since then a combination of myxomatosis and evolution have
produced a robust, anti-social, surface-living brute.
Likewise deer, the greatest threat to the future of Scottish woodlands, have
increased to unnaturally large populations limited only by starvation and
poaching. ``It is hardly good even for deer themselves,'' says Rackham, ``that
so much excellent meat sh
ould be running round the countryside not properly used.'' And as for ravaging
sheep: ``The simplest conservation measure of all is three strands of barbed
wire.'' Presumably, he doesn't mean around the neck.
IN fact, we have good strong stock fencing round most of the site except for an
unnoticed weak spot along the roadside where only two strands of wire run along
the top of a stone wall. But all this is a timely lesson as we are applying for
a Woodland Gran
t Scheme grant to plant another 2000 native trees - without shelters. I'm sure
Rackham is right about the barbed wire but he has equally uncompromising views
on ``automatic and unintelligent'' tree planting which he says is mistakenly
confused with conser
vation on the basis of advice limited to ``native trees good, exotic bad with
inaccurate lists of native species''. The best trees for wildlife are ancient,
coppiced - or dead if people can be persuaded not to tidy them away.
Woods are not the same as gardens however. Our plantation is an attempt to
create a sheltered corridor between ``unnatural'' farmland and the remnants of
an old woodland with a lot of garden along the way. The selection includes wild
cherry (because it lo
oks nice and attracts birds) alder, willow and downy birch for damp ground, and
silver birch and Scots Pine for drier more exposed areas. We lose eco-points
because the trees are not grown from locally collected seeds so they are not
genetically programme
d for survival in our area (we have not yet found a local source although the
pressure group Reforesting Scotland is working on a register of such nurseries).
Halfway through a Scotvec course in conservation management, one of the
valuable lessons I have learned is that in conservation there are no simple
definitions, easy solutions or firm conclusions to be drawn about the outcome
of our actions. Despite exoti
c species, town gardens have become a richer source of wildlife than much of
our countryside - most of Britain's amphibeans live in garden ponds and the
despised Leyland Cyprus can make a wonderful home for spiders and nesting birds.
As far as our garden is concerned we won't be around to see ancient trees but
we have plenty of dead wood and much of it is going to stay, (festooned,
perhaps, with climbing roses and clematis). A large dead ash above the pond
drums to the sound of tappin
g woodpeckers. Coppicing ash is part of the future plan to produce timber for
the garden and firewood for the house as well as a thriving habitat for birds
and insects.
But existing trees are on the wrong side to prevent the prevailing wind
sweeping across the grass and battering at the windows. That's where the silver
birch comes in. Birch provides a beautiful, fast growing shelter which filters
the wind more effectivel
y than a solid barrier and (according to the conservation group Highland
Birchwoods) is just about as native as you can get.
I also fancy an exotic evergreen or two, along with yews and junipers, to
create that comforting sense of security near the house. Pass the mint sauce.
</TEXT>
