<HEADLINE>H is for Hoots, mon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A  is, of course, for Auld Lang Syne, sung out of time and tune at any Hogmany
bash.
B  is for Black Bun, that Scottish delicacy without which no Hogmany buffet
table is quite complete. Or Bad Behaviour? There's always sure to be plenty of
that.
C  could be for Ceilidh. Or as readily for Carry-oot or coal - the two
essentials for first-footing.
D  is for Debris, of which there will be plenty come the cold light of Ne'erday.
E  is for Endless, the perfect adjective to describe revelry uniquely without
time limits.
F  is for First Foot, who should be a tall, dark, handsome stranger - but more
often is just plain strange.
G  is Ghastly and Grim. Two adjectives which describe many, many Hogmany
parties. (Make a note in your diary of doors to avoid next time around).
H  is much more likely to stand for Hangover than Haggis - usually reserved for
next month's Burns Night bonanza.
I  is for Inebriated, a posh-ish word used by men in uniform to describe the
condition of Hogmany's most committed revellers.
J  must surely stand for Jimmy Shand, without whose lovely music no New Year
celebration can be considered complete.
K  is for Kissing. Yes; there's always plenty of that.
L  could stand for Liver Failure (if you overdose on the W). Do try to make it
stand instead for Life Assessment; Hogmany is a great time for con-templation.
M  is for those same old Marvelous Memories which gush from old Uncle Arthur's
mind whenever his mouth is in constant contact with a glass.
N  stands for Neighbours, to whom you may very well never normally speak. But,
hey . . . isn't New Year the time to break the ice.
O  is for Open House. The problem with hosting any Hogmany party is that you
really don't get to choose the guests.
P  stands for Pipers. As the old year slips into the new, anyone who has ever
pressed a chanter to their lips feels an inexplicable desire to mark the
moment. Discordantly.
Q  is for Queasy (lethal mixtures of B, S and W do take their toll).
R  is, of course, for Rikki Fulton. Like the Reverend I. M Jolly, make New Year
a time for Reflection and Resolution too.
S  stands for Shortbread and Stovies. And, if you're very lucky, maybe just a
little Smoked Salmon.
T  is for tartan. Absolutely the only thing to wear.
U  is for Ulcer. Oh dear. Overdone it again, haven't you?
V  will neither stand for Violence nor Vandalism. Hopefully.
W  must be for Whisky, the essential libation of the great celebration.
X  denotes that drinking and driving is an absolute No, No, No.
Y  is for Year-end. Oh, just remembered what all this nonsence is actually
about.
Z? Well, Zzzzzzzzzzzz is the only sound heard as Scotland sleeps right through
Ne'erday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
