<HEADLINE>Two societies in an  uneasy microcosm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lorn McIntyre</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOCIOLOGY
St. MARY'S HAMILTON: A Social History, 1846 - 1996
John Donald, #9.95
HOW fared these immigrants from Ireland and Italy who arrived at ports and
railway stations with rosaries in their battered suitcases and the hope in
their hearts that they would find prosperity and religious tolerance in
Scotland?
The answers may be found in Hamilton, according to Thomas Devine, which is why
the deputy principal and professor of Scottish history at Strathclyde
University, hailed as one of the best historians of his generation, devoted
precious time to editing a soc
ial history (from 1846 to 1996) of St Mary's Church, Hamilton. He also happens
to be a parishioner of St Mary's.
As far as Devine knows, there has never been a local in-depth study done for
any Presbyterian, Episcopalian or Roman Catholic community in Scotland, or
indeed in England.
``Normally when you get a 150th anniversary of such places you're going to get
a parish pump history which emphasises the clergy and talks about great names
and is all uncritical, based on people's recollections and deeply nostalgic and
sentimental. This
is a full-scale scholarly study done by people who are historically trained and
they are looking at it in a critical way.
``They are also locking it into issues of modern historiographical concern,
such as sectarianism, such as the issue of assimilation. What happens to Irish
immigrants and their second, third and fourth generation descendants in
relation to attitudes to Sco
tland and to Ireland? Another issue is the enormous changes that have occurred
in Catholicism over the past 20 or 30 years.''
In the book, Martin J Mitchell points out that the immigration of Irish
Catholics to the west of Scotland from the mid-1790s placed the Catholic Church
under immense pressure. ``The church was not wealthy and could only send
priests to the region when the
y became available. Chapels were erected only when sufficient funds had been
collected to begin construction, and where there was a congregation large
enough to be able, through its weekly contributions, to help repay the money
borrowed to complete the bu
ilding.''
In September 1843, John Scanlan, an Irish priest who had come to Scotland the
previous year, arrived in Hamilton to establish a mission.
There was ground available, but no money to begin building. Scanlan began
fund-raising, but in April 1845 absconded with the money, ``leaving a great
deal of debt in Hamilton''. His successor, James Purcell, also an Irishman,
began a new collection, and a
600-seat chapel and a priest's house opened in November 1846. Soon it would
not be big enough.
There were 746 Catholics in Hamilton in 1851; by 1857 there were 1411. The
Glasgow Free Press of November 1852 claimed that ``whilst a few live as
brokers, the great majority support life by vending delph, fish, whiting, or
exchanging them to the country
people for rags, bones, old iron, etc''. But the massive increase of Catholics
in and around Hamilton and at Quarter between 1851 and 1857 was almost
certainly caused by the growth of coal mining in these areas.
Gradually, over a hundred years, Irish immigrants to Hamilton and other
industrial areas emerged from the claustrophobia of the pits and the din of the
factories into the light of opportunity and social mobility.
Devine says: ``The other reason why this is a very interesting study is that
this is the first- ever time anyone has come to grips with that very
fascinating phenomenon, the rise of the Catholic middle class, essentially
created by the post-1945 education
al changes. Hardly any of these individuals who belonged to that class are
involved in business. An enormous number of them are involved in education,
particularly school teaching, and there are elements inevitably in areas like
accountancy, law and medic
ine.
``This is probably the first generation where you can actually say: we do have
a middle class Catholic population, and there are probably only about four or
five parishes left in Scotland to which this description can be applied.''
What are the politics of a parish like St Mary's? Joseph M Bradley, who
contributes three chapters to the book, conducted a general survey of Catholic
church-attenders in 1990 which showed that almost 60% of St Mary's parishioners
were Labour supporters.
How did they view the prospect of an independent Scotland? ``About a fifth of
St Mary's respondents either believed that a Northern Ireland situation would
be created where the Protestant population dominated the Catholics, and
excluded them from many are
as of social, economic and political life. A number of respondents also feared
for Catholic schools,'' Bradley writes. However, 68% of St Mary's respondents
believed Scotland should be understood  better or have an Assembly.
Italians as well as Irish emigrated in significant numbers to Scotland,
bringing recipes for ice cream, a veneration for the sanctity of the family,
and a dedication to hard work. The Di Mambro family arrived here around 1919
and went to St Mary's Parish
about 1926/27 where they rented a local cafe and eventually involved themselves
in ice-cream wholesale.
As Bradley records: ``The grandchildren of the original Di Mambros prove an
interesting case in assessing contemporary Italian identity. A sense of their
heritage is maintained by way of their forenames: all have Italian names, and
all are conscious of th
eir `Italianness'. The Italians, like the Irish, sometimes found themselves
discriminated against in Scotland because of their religious beliefs. A St
Mary's parishioner recalled: ``In the past it was atrocious. If there was a job
vacant, no Catholic need
apply.'' And Bradley records that ``almost half of St Mary's church-attenders
believe discrimination in favour of Protestants is a social reality in
Scotland''.
What is the state of the Catholic religion in Scotland after the long struggle
to establish itself here? ``Every church in Scotland is losing support, and
statistically the Catholic Church is losing support in terms of the people
attending mass,'' Devine
says. ``But it's losing support at a lesser rate of knots than other
denominations.''
After Hamilton there will be more in-depth studies of the Irish in Scotland,
because Devine has helped to establish the Irish-Scottish Academic Initiative,
which links Aberdeen and Strathclyde Universities, and Trinity College, Dublin.
Devine is negotiati
ng a separate connection through his research centre at Strathclyde with the
Londonderry campus of the University of Ulster. ``The idea is to try to
understand the two societies in terms of this long historical connection.''
LORN MacINTYRE
</TEXT>
