<HEADLINE>Days in the rose city n Images of Morocco: A father and son share an unguarded moment of happiness in Marakesh and, below, mist-shrouded mountains dominate the land.  Pictures by ANGELA CATLIN, from a sequence commended in the Scottish Press Photographers' Competition this yea r. Daisies at the seaside</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE moon hung in the night sky like a great orange pumpkin, brushed by spindly
palm trees. We drove through the city outskirts, glimpsing, here, djellaba'd
figures and camels, there, the frontages of modern hotels. My Moroccan
neighbour stretched my resid
ual French to breaking point, probing my views on astrology.
Soon we seemed to have left the city entirely behind. There were mud walls to
our right and the low buildings of a traditional village. We swung into the
grounds of the Hotel Tikida and out of the bus into the scented midnight air.
So this was Marrakesh (
or Marrakech as the French have it).
The journey from humdrum London to this fabled place had taken eight hours or
so and two hops by Royal Air Maroc: first from London to Casablanca - where
travellers automatically scan each other for the lineaments of Bergman and
Bogart, such is the potenc
y of cinematic legend - and thence to the city beside the Atlas Mountains.
The mountains would prove totally elusive in the next three days, lost
somewhere in the haze. They must be startlingly beautiful. Daylight revealed
much else to admire close at hand. The hotel itself - just one of Marrakesh's
choice of sybaritic berths -
has the air of a palace, built as it is in traditional colonnaded style round
gardens overflowing with flowering shrubs, reflected in a pool. It seemed
almost crass to use the last for mere swimming. A fountain played in the main
reception hall, an indoor
water hazard for the clumsy-footed. Carpets, wallhangings, the great vases of
fresh roses all spoke of a culture confident in its own standards and vitality.
The occasion for our visit was Marrakesh's thirty-fourth National Festival of
Popular Art. Each summer it draws a cosmopolitan audience, attracted this year
also by an international tourism fair. The fair centre milled with visitors,
sipping sweet mint te
a and munching sweetmeats in the many trade booths. The Minister of Tourism
announced to the throng (in French, naturally) that ``tourism is the locomotive
of development''. The traditional befezzed band played. Soft drinks flowed. We
exited under giant p
ictures of Morocco's monarch, Hassan II, and his two sons.
It would be a long night. For we were heading for the El-Badi Palace in the
heart of the old medina. Floodlit, the palace's walls seemed out of some
Brobdingnagian film set. The storks' nests on the battlements strengthened the
impression of unreality. Un
der a starry, moonlit sky we were ushered into our tiered places, each
clutching a prickly, long-stemmed rose. The moon swung across the sky in the
next three hours as a dazzling succession of dancers, musicians, and actors
from Morocco's varied kingdom o
f some 26 to 28 million people, performed a series of tableaux.
Tableaux should not suggest something static. Gorgeously arrayed women dancers,
with multicoloured silks billowing, and curious back strappings, swayed and
gyrated. The singing was mesmeric, though the sound is produced back in the
throat in a way very di
fferent from western techniques. Princely figures on white horses and camels
came and went. Rifles were fired. Blanks no doubt, but the audience of
thousands jumped communally. A French commentary of impenetrable eloquence
accompanied the action. We stumb
led out, overwhelmed by the sheer exoticism of the scene.
A second evening's entertainment saw hundreds of people feast on lamb and
Moroccan wine under giant awnings leading down to a little lake. It had a
backdrop of traditional buildings and palm trees. In this oasis under the North
African sky, reality again
proved elusive. The palm trees and buildings moved as on casters. Gauzy figures
glided over the lake in boats like Arabic ladies of Shalott. We learned why
Marrakesh children don't eat doves. It's because of the saintly Fatima who was
a legend by day, a d
ove by night. The city's great twelfth-century Koutoubia mosque - the city's
outstanding landmark - was built near her tomb.
Red is the official colour of Marrakesh (a city of some 1.4 million people) but
really it should be the warm rose of its old walled town - a contrast to the
wide boulevards the French bequeathed from the decades of their protectorate,
from 1912 to 1956.
A sortie to the city's souks is mandatory. - though for someone brought up in
the proprieties of resale price maintenance, the obligation to bargain is
irksome.In the narrow lanes, crammed with locals and tourists, the contents of
the little shops and boo
ths spill onto the minimal walking space. Men turn wood with curious little
foot implements. Gorgeous carpets in abstract patterns (designed as wall
hangings rather than for pedestrian use), brasswear and pottery, ornate silver
jewellery, traditional robe
s for men and women, and pointed-toed
leather slippers out of The Arabian Nights - these were just some of the things
to catch the eye in the melee.
``Ecosaisse! Ecosaisse!'' some small boys shouted after me. ``How observant of
them,'' I thought, till I realised my straw hat sported the motto ``Bell's
Scottish Open.'' Another urchin stroked a lizard and demanded payment for
posing for a picture. Be pr
epared to be importuned.
The snake charmer exercises his slippery charges in the Djemaa-el-Fna, the
great main square in the old part of town. No temptation to linger here. As on
the streets of modern Marrakesh - where young women in western dress ride past
on Vespas while contem
poraries hide behind veils on the pavements nearby - one is aware of the clash
of cultures. It is not necessarily a comfortable feeling.
So many sights of Marrakesh remain to be explored. There is the legendary Hotel
La Mamounia with its art deco mirrors and furnishings and acres of gardens.
Churchill used to escape here during the Second World War. It's certainly beats
10 Downing Street.
The Jardin Menara, with its large, still pool among olive groves, is the most
easily reached of Marrakesh's green spaces.
Morocco's monarch is a golf enthusiast - which may help account for two
impressive courses boasted by the city. The Palmeraie Golf Palace has a new
course built by Robert Trent Jones junior. Its clubhouse and hotel have opulent
interiors in traditional Mo
roccan style. The complex looks like the stamping ground of multi-millionaires
but in fact tariffs are surprisingly reasonable.
The course is green and seems to stretch to the horizon, punctuated by palm
trees and water hazards. The Royal Golf Club is in total contrast. Built in the
1920s, it has narrow fairways enclosed by trees and shrubs. Eisenhower played
on it. So, apparently
did Churchill, with the fabled Pasha of Marrakesh, El Glaoui, as his opponent.
Players tee off to a profusion of bird song.
It would take a long time to tire of Marrakesh - which has, among its numerous
other charms, a dry healthy climate with no tormenting mosquitoes. However, we
took a hurl to the seaside - to the Atlantic town of Essaouira (formerly
Mogador). Journeying thr
ough the western Sahara was almost as good as arriving. No featureless desert
this but a place of shrubby hills and valleys and strange little forts and
sudden patches of cultivation. Goats might be spied up trees eating foliage.
Enigmatic swathed figures
(shepherds?) stalked the middle distance or squatted by the roadside. In one
little oasis town I bought a wooden box of dominoes from a shy teenage boy. The
price pleased us both.
Essaouira had all the breeziness of a Troon or Ardrossan - though the
Livingstone daisies in the flowerbeds are the outsize variety that grow round
Portuguese lighthouses. In fact, the Portuguese built a fort here, there was a
flourishing Jewish community
as late as the 1960s (it evaporated in the wake of the Six Days' War), and
Orson Welles filmed part of Othello against one of its old gateways.
The bleaching sunlight was lovely to walk in; the harbour full of bustle and
the smell of cooking fish. A shop full of locally crafted woodwork yielded
various gifts, including a dodecahedron for a mathematical relative. And I
found the ideal place to sta
y - the modest little Villa Maroc, built and furnished with charm and greenery
on several floors round a central well in a back street.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
