<TEXT>
INNOVATIONS
THERE have been many mind machines but, so far, most have featured in science
fiction movies. Here's a mind machine for our time. It's a gadget which links
light, sound, and the brain. It's a method for getting away from it all which
costs about the same
as a cancellation to Majorca.
Produced by Lifetools, the Mindlab is promoted as a way of attaining the full
benefits of meditation without any of its tedium. The Mindlab is a compact box
of electronics linked to a set of goggles and stereo headphones.
For up to an hour, the wearer can be tuned into a blend of sound waves and
swirling light pulses of colour. Lifetools says the synchronised patterns slow
down beta-wave patterns in the brain to a state of relaxation, while alpha
waves are boosted to a str
ong focus.
As the spiralling light patterns slow down, the mind is supposed to follow
suit. The equipment can be programmed for different levels and times, with a
rechargeable battery for reaching states of meditation for up to forty years.
It's small enough to use on a plane where the swirling lights are possibly the
equivalent of two gins and an in-flight movie.
The system is also reprogrammable from tapes and the material includes
specially designed sound and light concerts, and multi-sensory hypnotic tapes.
A colour-sync option lets external sounds trigger the light intensity, which
might add a further dimensio
n to Sergeant Pepper if we ever needed one. A sound generator allows the wearer
to pick exactly the right tone to suit any taste.
At #269, one would probably need several sessions to get over the blow to the
wallet, but that's still #80 less than the upmarket PolySync pro version which
is a little more sophisticated and allows the user to specify the frequency of
lights, sound pitch
, and has 50 built-in programmes.
After the hustle and bustle of the festivities, a personal show of light and
sound has its attractions. It might just beat watching re-runs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
