<TEXT>
n.HOLD everything for a second at the bells on Hogmanay. But only for a second.
That's what will happen to the world's atomic clocks just before the stroke of
midnight marks the border between this year and 1996.
The keepers of the primary standard of time and frequency will be adding a leap
second on December 31. This is the 20th such adjustment to the world's time
scale, as decreed by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures in Paris.
Such seconds are ne
eded to keep our clocks - the best of which are now so accurate they lose or
gain less than a millionth of a second per year - in step with the spinning
Earth, which varies several thousandths of a second per day.
Since we can't speed up the Earth, we have to slow down the clocks every one to
two years to keep them ``in synch''. This is done by stopping them for exactly
one second so the Earth can catch up.
This year's leap second will be inserted at 23:59:60 Co-ordinated Universal
Time. That means the official last minute of 1995 will actually be 61 seconds
long. But who's counting? Happy New Year from Frontiers!
n.IF you are considering first footing tomorrow night, it's best to put your
best foot forward...... and make sure you keep your balance, especially if
you're in high heels.
Fortunately, assistance in keeping one's feet may be at hand from a team of
Dundee researchers who've been doing some fancy footwork to save us from the
follies of fashion. It has developed an electronic insole which doesn't take
the weight off one's feet
, but spreads it around to where it's most beneficial.
The team, led by Rami Abboud, a biomedical and rehabilitation engineer, aims to
help patients with problem feet without their having to undergo surgery. The
new insole has a set of transducers which redistributes the weight of a
shoe-wearer to ease pressu
re on delicate joints, thus helping to reduce foot deformities.
n.NEW research shows a recently discovered gene cold be a major factor in what
determines a person's skin type - and be a clue to potential risk of skin
cancer. The melanocyte-stimulating hormone receptor gene is the focus of
research by the Human Genetic
s Unit in Edinburgh and the Department of dermatology at Newcastle.
Skin cancers are on the increase for a number of reasons. Susceptibility varies
and it's long been known fair-skinned people are at risk. Those with dark,
pigmented skin face a vastly reduced threat. According to the researchers, the
ability to tan is rel
ated to the type of pigment produced, either dark eumelanin or red
phaeomelanin. The Mels tan easily but the redskin-palefaces don't have this
protection.
The researchers have been looking at what regulates the relative proportions of
the two pigments and found it's all connected with the MSH receptor gene. The
work, funded by the Medical Research Council, is likely to have serious
implications for not only
the understanding of the tanning response, but, more importantly, in helping
to determine the risk factor associated with skin cancers and skin ageing.
Further research is planned to examine the changes in the MSH receptor gene in
different populations.
n.THE connection between Beethoven's music and heavy metal may soon be
discovered. A team of scientific and anthropological experts from Arizona
Univeristy has bought a small oval frame with a lock of hair reportedly from
Ludwig von Beethoven. The lock wi
ll be compared to other known samples of the composer's hair to help establish
its authenticity, and then tested to determine whether the maestro had heavy
metals, such as lead, arsenic, or mercury in his system.
These could act as clues to his medical condition for traces of such elements
may be the result of medicinal compounds. Urologist Alfredo Guevara bought the
lock of hair a year ago at Sothebys London auction house in conjunction with
Ira F. Brilliant, who
has established a centre for Beethoven Studies in California.
If the investigators manage to determine the locks are genuine, they should be
able to give a picture of his condition and possibly the influences on his life
and work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
