<TEXT>
ONE of the world's leading teams involved in the investigation of marine
mammals' biology will soon be based in St Andrews. The Natural Environment
research Council's Sea Mammal Research Unit will be flitting from Cambridge to
operate from the Gatty Marin
e Laboratory in February.
It will have the opportunity to study seals in controlled conditions, in a new
40-metre tank in a new extension to the Gatty which will open next year to
coincide with the laboratory's centenary.
The Sea Mammal Research Unit has pioneered the development of satellite-linked
loggers which follow diving behaviour, feeding, and physiology of marine
animals and allow their status and travels to be studied in the open ocean.
Beluga whales in the Arctic, elephant seals in the Antarctic, and grey seals
around Scotland are just some of the sea creatures it has focused on. On the
Isle of May, in the Forth, the team has studied the grey seal population -
their breeding success, su
sceptibility to disease, and levels of pollutants in their bodies.
The SMRU will work closely with the Wildlife Population Assessment research
group in St Andrews University in a bid to estimate the population sizes of
whales, dolphins, and porpoises.
Dr Philip Hammond, who has moved to St Andrews in advance of the team's flit
says: ``The excellent new facilities and the active research environment of the
Gatty will enable the Unit to realise its full potential as a world-class
centre of excellence.''
Over at Stirling Uniersity, the Natural Environment Research Council has
awarded almost #170,000 for a fish reproduction study. The grant has been won
by Professor Niall Bromage and Dr Clive Randall of the Institute of Aquaculture
and will support a study
of the ways in which fish use seasonal patterns of changing day length to time
their reproductive activity.
Professor Bromage says: ``This should have considerable interest to the fish
farming industry, which is worth #400.million a year.''
The results of the research should allow trout and salmon farmers to enable
their fish to produce eggs and milt on demand in any month of the year and not
just for the short autumnal period when the fish begin to breed.
The all-year supply will help the trout and salmon industry to maintain a
continuity of production of market-sized fish of consistent quality throughout
the year, thus avoiding gluts and shortages of current production. It will
probably stabilise prices t
oo.
</TEXT>
