<HEADLINE>A LOOK BACK IN ANGST</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Linklater</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974635234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JANUARY
n THE year opened under the grim shadow of Frederick West as he hanged himself
in Winston Green Prison, Birmingham. He left his wife Rosemary to face 10
murder charges in what would become the ``House of Horrors'' trial.
On the other side of the Atlantic, chief prosecutor Marcia Clark was getting
her hair cut and selecting demure rather than figure-hugging suits to adjust
her image for America's ``Trial of the Century'' as the O J Simpson court soap
opened.
In Britain and America, security and justice were in the dock. The Home
Secretary faced resignation calls as three dangerous inmates gained a copy of a
master key to escape from Parkhurst, Isle of Wight, and tried to take off in a
Cessna aircraft at Sando
wn Airport. News was also coming through of rioting at Everthorpe Prison, North
Humberside.
Eric Cantona leapt a barrier at Selhurst Park and planted a kung-fu kick in the
ribs of a taunting Crystal Palace fan to set the tone for a year of living
dangerously for football. Necrotising fasciitis posed another scary form of
attack, except it couldn
't be suspended for the rest of the season or ordered to carry out community
service.
Neither was it going to be a tranquil time for Royals. The announcement of
divorce proceedings for the Parker Bowles prompted a new spate of Prince
Charles and Camilla revelations. A poll suggested Prince William, and not
Charles, was the popular choice f
or the next king. The Princess of Wales gelled back her hair. Lord Charteris,
the Queen's former private secretary, offered a testimonial for the Duchess of
York: ``She is vulgar, vulgar, vulgar, and that is it''.
A year of 50th anniversaries and somber reflection began with events to mark
the half-centenary of the liberation of Auschwitz. Farewells to
satirist/comedian Peter Cook, conducter Sir Alexander Gibson, writer/naturalist
Gerald Durrell, entertainer Larry
Grayson.
Quote of the Month: ``In the early days, privatisation signalled liberty,
equity, prosperity. Now it's just a bunch of slobs stinging the consumer and
putting each other's salaries up over a heavy lunch.'' (Former Cabinet Minister
Alan Clark).
FEBRUARY
n IT was a strange month. Long after it ceased to be fashionable, Britain had a
man walking in space. ``Golly, it's high, isn't it?'', reported Dr Mike Foale
from the US space shuttle Discovery. Equally long after it could possibly
matter, Leith had a sus
pected ex-KGB agent. ``The only time I could be called an agent was when I was
a collector for Littlewood's Pools,'' responded former Labour MP Ron Brown.
A parrot called Barney was restored to the custody of his owner after
identifying Georgina Morgans in the Crown Court, London, with two affectionate
wolf whistles. A Scottish Industry Minister called Allan Stewart resigned after
a fracas with protesters a
gainst the proposed M77 in which he was alleged to have brandished a pick-axe.
A separate assembly was promised Northern Ireland in the historic UK-Irish
Peace Framework initiative launched in Belfast, but devolution for Scotland
would cost #2845m, according to converted unionist Ian Lang, the Scottish
Secretary. British Gas emphasi
sed his point by declaring profits of #1.25m, or #40 a second. Barings,
Britain's oldest merchant bank, tried to match this in reverse with a collapse
that sent the pound plunging.
Farewells to actor Donald Pleasence, Tory MP/wit/bon viveur Sir Nicholas
Fairbairn, writer/vet James Herriot, and former tennis champion Fred Perry.
Quote of the Month: ``I'm a silly old fool.'' (Stephen Fry, after stage-fright
and bad reviews led him to walk out on his West End show).
MARCH
n NICK LEESON, the missing financial trader involved in the Barings disaster,
was detained by police at Frankfurt Airport. ``I'm the fall guy,'' he said
classically. ``I only blew #200 million.''
It became a month for trading places. Gerry Adams visited New York. The Queen
visited Belfast. Grand Prix star Damon Hill visited the Bicester Magistrates to
face a speeding ban. His time, 102.7mph on the M40 at Adderbury, Oxfordshire,
was reckoned the fa
stest of the year he recorded without bumping into Michael Schumacher.
The Beatles launched a revival, and discovered that All You Need Is John. The
Kray Twins lost Ronnie. But Tom Hanks proved you could continue solo as a
complete dork, when he won his (second successive) Oscar for Forrest Gump.
Football's year of kung-fu, bungs, banged-up stars, and drugs continued with
Hampshire Police detaining Bruce Grobbelaar, John Fashanu, and Hans Seegers for
questioning on match-fixing allegations. Tragedy struck down the incomparable
Davie Cooper, who di
ed at 39 after suffering a subarachnoid haemorrhage of the brain.
Other farewells: journalist/broadcaster Hugh Cochrane, pop star/eccentric Viv
Stanshall, and actor Robert Urquhart.
Quote of the Month: ``And who are you?'' (Joan Rivers interviewing Elizabeth
Hurley at the Oscar Awards ceremony).
APRIL n IT was a month for politicians to shoot themselves in the foot. The
Commons pulled the plug on Tory MPs David Tredinnick and Graham Riddick in the
``cash for questions'' row. The Labour Party pulled the plug on Clause Four, in
its public seduction
of the English middle-class vote. Three Scottish judges pulled the plug on
Panorama's interview with John Major, but it would have taken more than BBC
partiality to save the Tories from being wiped out in the Scottish local
elections. They were left with
out control of a single authority.
There were two ways to hit the National Lottery jackpot. Two people shared a
#22m ``rolled-over'' prize by getting the numbers right. The Churchill family
scored #12.5m by selling state papers to the nation and getting the Lottery to
cough up.
Two atrocities shocked the world. In Rwanda the agony continued with the
slaughter of thousands of Hutu men, women, and children in the Kibeho refugee
camp. At Oklahoma City more than 130 adults and children were killed by the
bombing of a federal governm
ent building. Neo-Nazi Timothy McVeigh was arrested as President Clinton
promised the death penalty for the cuprits.
Farewells to friend of the arts George Singleton (Mr Cosmo), DJ/comedian Kenny
Everett, singer/actor Burl Ives, and film star Ginger Rogers.
Quote of the Month: ``When seagulls follow a trawler, it is because they think
sardines will be thrown into the sea.'' (Eric Cantona, on receiving 120 hours'
community service order).
MAY
n IT was an unhappy time for Scottish domestic productions. Actor Tom McGovern
protested over the withdrawal of the film role of Robert Bruce after seeing Rob
Roy go to Liam Neeson, William Wallace go to Mel           Gibson, and the Loch
Ness Monster go
to Ted Danson.
We weren't even allowed to make and enjoy our own cheese. A ton of Lanark Blue
was seized by environmental health officers as a listeria monocytogenes claim
grated on.
The only victory was for the Fort William sleeper service. The Court of Session
found against ScotRail, who had tried to derail statutory consultation by
calling one-way empty trains a ``passenger service''. This confirmed that for
years ScotRail services
had little to do with passengers, and it prompted a great rail debate.
Inspired, perhaps, by VE-Day anniversary celebrations, Nato committed to air
strike action against Bosnian-Serbs. In a tragic escalation, 71 were killed in
retaliatory shelling of Tuzla and 350 UN peace-keepers (including 33 Britons)
were taken hostage as
``human shields''.
Farewells to former prime minister Lord (Harold) Wilson, fashion designer Jean
Muir, and Bet Gilroy (who announced she was pulling her last pint in Coronation
Street).
Quote of the Month: ``If I had been a surgeon I would have been a super
surgeon. If I had been an architect I would have been a super architect. If I
had been Frank Sinatra I wouldn't have made much of a living.'' (Bosnian-Serb
General Ratko Mladic).
JUNE
n IT became official that rats outnumbered people in the United Kingdom. The
estimate was of a 30% population increase to bring the tail count of Rattus
Norvegicus to 60 million. ``Rats are reliable,'' commented Rob Ollason, head of
the education section
of Edinburgh Zoo. ``I've never known one to bite a member of the public.''
John Major offered to make way for one by resigning the Tory leadership and
opening it to election. ``It is time to put up or shut up,'' he challenged.
Welsh secretary John Redwood, a Thatcherite hard-liner, duly obliged. His
resignation from the Cabinet
was celebrated in the valleys. ``He will go down like a rat sandwich,''
predicted Ieuan Wyn Jones, Plaid Cymru whip, accurately.
Hugh Grant tried to play rat to revise a thoroughly boring image as Mr Squeaky
Clean by consulting Ms Divine Brown in a BMW convertible on Sunset Boulevard.
An act of lewd conduct was the police interpretation. Publicity for Grant's
forthcoming film, Nine
Months, was guaranteed and his girlfriend Liz Hurley didn't have to tell
anyone who she was any more.
Mike Tyson wanted it known that if he wasn't a new rat, at least he had a new
name. It was as Abdul Malik Aziz that he emerged from prison after three years
for a rape conviction, and he was a more commercial proposition than ever.
Curiously, it was as Mi
ke Tyson that he climbed back into the ring.
Farewells to film critic Dilys Powell and film star Lana Turner.
Quote of the Month: ``It doesn't matter who you are, I would ticket my own
father or even my husband.'' (Traffic warden Angela Hallam, receiving police
award for 4071 parking tickets issued in a year).
JULY
n MICHAEL FORSYTH was appointed Scottish Secretary in the cabinet reshuffle
after John Major's sweeping ballot victory in the Tory leadership fight. Ian
Lang went to Trade Secretary. ``It's Reservoir Dogs II,'' commented a senior
Scottish Conservative.
Gazza arrived. Gazza endorsements, Gazza haircuts, Gazza mania. He was not the
only manifestion of ``weather rage'' in one of the hottest Julys on record.
Average temperatures for Glasgow were 16.3 C, about 1.6 degrees hotter than
normal. William Hills dr
opped the odds to 10-1 for temperatures topping 100F on the British mainland.
France, which had gone belatedly bellicose since VE-Day, suspended nuclear
tests on Muroroa Atoll temporarily to storm the Greenpeace ship Rainbow Warrior
II in the South Pacific - a rare naval triumph.
The release of Private Lee Clegg was met with rioting in Belfast. Arsenal
manager George Graham was found guilty of misconduct and banned by the Football
Association.
Farewells to DJ Wolfman Jack, former motor racing champion Juan Manuel Fangio,
poet Sir Stephen Spender, and country singer Charlie Rich.
Quote of the Month: ``You don't negotiate with prime ministers. There isn't a
deal.'' (Michael Heseltine, rewarded with the new post of deputy prime minister
after supporting Major in the leadership election).
AUGUST n FOR the anniversaries of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagaskai,
and VJ-Day, Japanese prime minister Murayama expressed ``profound remorse'' for
his nation's wartime atrocities. This sparked a row. Was it an apology? Was he
speaking only fo
r himself? Veterans said it wasn't enough.
An epidemic of wasps (of the yellow and black variety) was the latest product
of the long hot summer, the driest since records began in 1659. ``I've been
chased up the Royal Mile wearing a floral tie,'' boasted Edinburgh
environmental health director Rich
ard Carson. This became an occupational hazard in an Edinburgh Festival in
which bottoms were an official theme with the arrival of Canova's Three Graces.
Croatia launched an all-out offensive in Krajina, capturing Knin as the
fighting spread into Bosnia, as the Serbs accused each other of treachery.
Sarajevo market was mortar-shelled by Bosnian-Serbs, killing 37, injuring 85.
Serb-held positions were bombe
d by Nato jets, as the misery turned another circle.
Old Labour accused Tony Blair's New Labour of abandoning grassroots, as union
sponsorship of MPs was abandoned, and a battle for the soul of the party
ensued. ``It is not our responsibility to be lobotomised foot soldiers for the
New Blair Army,'' said Hi
llhead MP George Galloway.
Farewells to film star Ida Lupino, writer/campaigner Bridget Brophy,
mountaineer Alison Hargreaves and amateur rugby.
Quote of the Month: ``How do you keep the natives off the booze long enough to
get them past the test?'' (Duke of Edinburgh, talking to driving instructor
Robert Drummond during a visit to Oban).
SEPTEMBER n IT was a month for posing. The island of Skye claimed to be part of
the British mainland (despite the misgivings of a Bradford firm later in the
year who would charge Euro postage rates), but it was announced it would cost
#5.20 for a passenge
r car to demonstrate it.
Posing as a 32-year-old, Liz Taylor announced that her eighth marriage, to
construction worker Larry Fortensky, 20 years her junior, was on the rocks.
Posing as 17-year-old Brandon Lee, the 32-year-old star of the Bearsden Academy
production of South Paci
fic was revealed as none other than Brian MacKinnon. Posing as pupil William
Windsor, Charles and Diana's eldest son began humble school-days at Eton
College. Posing as a pair of adults, Will and Julia Carling announced that they
would need time and space
alone.
Bosnian Serbs were withdrawing from Sarajevo and driven to a peace deal
brokered by President Clinton in Geneva. France's continuation of nuclear
testing in the South Pacific was internationally condemned, and protest riots
brought the Tahitian capital to
flames.
Farewell to poet Donald Davie, Labour Party treasurer Sam McCluskey, and
actress Susan Fleetwood.
Quote Of The Month: ``Cash is vulgar.'' (Naomi Campbell on why she carries only
plastic for those rare occasions when she actually has to pay for anything).
OCTOBER
n TRAGEDY in the ring. James Murray died of brain injuries after his British
title bout in Glasgow with Drew Docherty. Renewed calls for a ban on the sport
were met by brave words from the dead boxer's father, who said the fight must
continue.
After an interminable nine-month trial, 120 witnesses, 45,000 pages of
transcript and 1100 exhibits, O J Simpson got the not guilty verdict that had
begun to appear as an inevitable guilty verdict when he was arrested 16 months
before. the Rosemary West t
rial began.
Derek Lewis, head of the prison service, was given the finger after a damning
inquiry into the Parkhurst breakout, but tried to stay at the wicket. Duncan
Ferguson's appeal against jail failed. The Faldos marriage broke, Michael
Howarth divorced the Tory
Party, but Canada and Quebec stayed hitched, just. Boris Yeltsin survived a
second heart scare, and a political power struggle. Cliff Richard received a
knighthood for pop survival.
Farewell to former prime minister Lord (Douglas) Home of the Hirsel, writer
Kingsley Amis, astrologer Patrick Walker and legendary Grand national winner
Red Rum.
Quote Of The Month: ``This prosecution team did not lose today. I deeply
believe that this country lost today.'' (Fred Goldman, father of one of the two
victims, on the O J Simpson verdict).
NOVEMBER
n TWO political murders. Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin was assassinated
by a right-wing Jewish extremist while leaving a rally in Tel Aviv. His role in
the Middle East peace process had earned him the name of ``traitor'', but he
refused to wear a b
ullet-proof vest. In Nigeria, international pressure was ignored with the
execution of dissident writer Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight others following a farce
of a trial. John Major called it judicial murder. The Commonwealth conference
took the unprecedented s
tep of suspending Nigeria.
Rosemary West was jailed for life 10 times over, after her husband gave taped
evidence from the grave, and admitted burying 20 more victims. The Barclay
Brothers bought The Scotsman. The Princess of Wales shocked the Palace with her
Dianorama confessions.
Newsreader Julia Sommerville and her boyfriend were questioned by police after
a roll of film containing exposures of her seven-year-old daughter posing in
the bath with shaving foam was reported. Police said no action would be taken.
The Queen Mother, a
ged 92, had hip replacement surgery. Pat Barker won the Booker Prize with The
Ghost Road. Rangers and Celtic were humbled in European competition with 4-goal
and 3-goal defeats on consecutive nights against Juventus and Paris St Germain.
Farewell to comedian Marti Caine, actor Paul Eddington, soul musician Junior
Walker, film director Louis Malle, DJ Stuart Henry and Today newspaper.
Quote of the Month: ``It's left us with a huge hole to fill.'' (Arsenal Ladies'
soccer coach Vik Akers on the news the star striker was out for the rest of the
season because she was pregnant).
DECEMBER
n MAD cow disease paranoia catching. Schools across Britain took beef dishes
off the dinners' menu. The Duchess of York sent a #250,000 diamond necklace and
bracelet, a wedding present from her mother-in-law, through baggage at Kennedy
Airport, New York.
Astonishingly, they went missing. Even more astonishingly, they were recovered.
Also in New York, the Princess of Wales won an award for humanitarian work.
Former secretary of state, Dr Henry Kissinger, declared her ``luminous''
personality was a benefit to the world. HM Government said it was okay to
drink, so long as it was your ro
und. Drinking 21 units (male) and 15 units (female) was now safer than sex or
eating steak, though all three were more fun.
Headmaster Philip Lawrence was fatally stabbed outside his school, trying to
break-up an attack on pupils. Brixton rioted. Nick Leeson was jailed for six
years for trading bad futures. Scotland drew England at Wembley in the European
Football Championship
s. Hampden scored #23 million from the lottery.
Farewell to comedians Jimmy Jewel and Arthur Mullard.
Quote of the Month: ``Another interview, another yard of rope.'' (Sir Bernard
Ingham on the Princess of Wales).
The year ended as it began: trouble at the Palace. This time the Queen says
it's over for Charles and Diana. The divorce is set. Who will be king? Who will
be queen? Read on...
QUOTE OF THE YEAR
``If adultery disqualified a monarch from reigning we would have had a
republic long ago.''
Tory Peer Lord Deedes
</TEXT>
