<HEADLINE>Blair to go public in push for power</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair plans a series of nationwide meetings with members of
the public during 1996 - a year in which, he said yesterday, Labour would try
to bring down the Government before Parliament runs its full span.
Mr Blair has developed a taste for ``meet the people '' gatherings following
the successful ones he conducted first with party members during the Clause
Four debate and then with different sections of the business community.
Now he plans that he and his shadow Cabinet colleagues will speak at a series
of public meetings open to voters who are not Labour supporters. In his New
Year message, he said he believed Labour had now built up a relationship of
trust with the people. Ne
xt year he wants to move beyond that ``to form a genuine partnership with the
people''.
Mr Blair said: ``I do not want the public to elect a Labour Government simply
because they despise the Conservatives for what they have done to the country.
I want them to elect a Labour Government because they know us and understand
our policies and they
believe these policies can make them better off in a better Britain.''
He added: ``If we can get an early election, we will be delighted and we will
be prepared for it. We believe essentially that the Government has lost all
purpose and direction. There is no vision and no leadership.''
He said Labour had the opportunity to rise to the challenge of providing that
leadership, giving a sense of direction, and justifying the hope people had
placed in them.
Despite his party's huge opinion poll lead, running at more than 30%, Mr Blair
said complacency remained ``a constant enemy'' and the party must be
``determined and disciplined''.
Recognising cynicism among the electorate as a second enemy, he said: ``We must
restore faith in politics by being honest with the people and by making only
those promises we know can be kept.''
The travelling campaign to sell this message to the voters would enable people
to test him and his team.
Britain had declined as an economic power and been marginalised in Europe where
the Government's decisions were taken not in the national interest but ``to
hold together a fundamentally divided party''.
</TEXT>
