<HEADLINE>Coach ban for outside lane</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW MULLINS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COACHES and larger mini-buses will be banned from the outside lane of motorways
for a two-year trial period, the Scottish Office announced yesterday.
The new legislation was immediately condemned by National Express spokesman
Stuart Render as ``a knee-jerk reaction to a number of accidents not at all
related to the third lane or to speeding coaches.''
The ban comes into effect on January 1, in response to an EC directive that
will permanently limit coach speeds to 65mph, which operators say will increase
the Aberdeen-London travelling time by half an hour.
Mr Andrew Howard, head of road safety for the Automobile Association, said the
new legislation would prove whether imposing further restrictions on coaches
would improve road safety.
RAC spokeswoman Ms Sue Nicholson said the organisation was concerned that
coaches fitted with the new limiters would cause ``bunching'' on motorways.
The spokeswoman also called for more training for drivers, pointing out that
``the most effective speed limiter is the driver's right foot''.
No comment was available from either the Department of Transport or the
Scottish Office.
</TEXT>
