<HEADLINE>Cool heads, brave hearts, and General Election fever for party leaders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH political leaders are squaring up for a General Election battle in
1996.
New Year messages from the Conservatives, the Scottish National Party, and the
Liberal Democrats set the scene for a political dogfight next year.
Scottish Conservative chairman, Sir Michael Hirst, in his message to party
members, recognised that a General Election could soon be called.
He said the party was preparing for a contest but could only offer a ``good
fighting chance of securing a fifth term of Government''. In a New Year message
last year, Prime Minister John Major was more positive. He said the party was
``invincible'' if it
was united.
Sir Michael admitted the party, which has suffered electoral defeats and a
continued decline in popularity, had ``weathered quite a storm'' during 1995.
However, he added that the ``listening party'' was in a positive and buoyant
mood.
He said: ``Scottish Tories have plenty of spine and I believe we have rallied
and the fightback is well under way. We have started to turn the tide and we
are now setting the political agenda for Scotland.''
He said the appointment of Michael Forsyth as Scottish Secretary had un-nerved
political opponents.
He repeated claims that tax cuts would be introduced when prudent and launched
a bitter attack on Labour's devolution plans. He accused the Liberal Democrats
of slavishly supporting ``ill-conceived and dangerous'' plans for
constitutional change.
Sir Michael added that the party guns would be trained on the SNP.
He concluded: ``There is no doubt that much effort and hard work is still
needed to reassure many of our supporters. It would be foolish and naive to
suggest otherwise.
``But I am confident that many of our long-term policies to secure Britain's
ever-improving economy will afford us the opportunity of more tax cuts.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond put his party on full election alert and said the
Tories were ``running out of political rope at Westminster and face the
prospect of being run out of office''.
In a reference to the Mel Gibson blockbuster, he said 1996 was the year for
``brave hearts and wise heads'' in Scotland.
Despite a recent downturn in SNP support following a summer high, Mr Salmond
added that Scotland could dictate the political agenda over the next 12 months.
He said Conservative leaders had effectively admitted that the status quo was
not working in Scotland.
He repeated claims in last year's message that Labour was a ``Mark.II Tory
party'' scrambling for votes in Middle England at the expense of Scots.
Mr Salmond said: ``This is the time for brave hearts and wise heads in Scotland
- brave hearts to power through Tory scaremongering and secure the best future
for Scotland, and wise heads to see through Labour's pretence of promoting
Scottish interests.''
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said success in the local
government elections north of the Border, which saw the party win 123 seats,
provided a solid base on which to build. He also claimed his party would set
the political agenda and added
that they were the only true guarantors of a Scottish parliament.
He further pledged support for a Scottish Office anti-drugs initiative.
Mr Wallace said the Liberal Democrats aimed to become the second largest party
in Scotland after the General Election.
He said: ``We shall go forward committed to the effort needed for a major
electoral battle but in the sure knowledge that our message will find a
receptive audience.''
q.Meanwhile, the Scottish Tourist Board (STB) in its 1996 message revealed a
#5m project to link the network of computers in STB offices around Scotland,
which serve some nine million visitors.
</TEXT>
