<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heating system explodes at Highland bar Five hurt in hotel blast</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE people were injured, three seriously, in a Highland hotel at lunchtime
yesterday when part of the building's heating system, a back boiler behind an
open fire in the lounge bar, exploded.
Temperatures in Newtonmore village, in the Badenoch area, had been around -20C
and there had been a 14-hour power cut in the previous days, leading many to
speculate that frozen pipes were at fault.
The explosion rocked the lounge bar of Braeriach Hotel on Main Street. One of
the most seriously injured was the hotel owners' son, Mr Duncan Harper, 27, who
had been tending bar at the time.
The force of the blast sent furniture and fittings flying across the room, some
of which were thought to have caught Mr Harper in the face, knocking him
unconscious. He was flown by air ambulance helicopter to Raigmore Hospital,
Inverness, where he remain
ed under observation in the intensive therapy unit last night. His condition is
stable and comfortable.
The helicopter then flew back to link up with a road ambulance that earlier had
picked up an elderly couple, the only customers in the lounge bar at the time
of the explosion. They were airlifted to Raigmore but no information was
available on their condi
tion last night.
The hotel has been owned by Mr John Harper and his wife Anne for the past 12
years. Mrs Harper was one of the other people slightly hurt when glass from the
bar was sent flying in to the street.
A fire service spokesman said a frozen water inlet or outlet pipe had almost
certainly caused the blast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S local authorities remained unimpressed yesterday with Scottish
Secretary Michael Forsyth's latest bid to decentralise power from Government to
councils.
Publishing his consultation paper, Devolution of Power to Councils, Mr Forsyth
said he would be seeking views over the next three months on the scrapping of a
range of regulatory burdens hanging round the necks of local authorities.
The proposals in the consultation paper are designed to give councils more
freedom and include powers to councils to draw up their own by-laws and limited
powers over traffic regulations.
However, the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities said that while Mr
Forsyth claimed to be pro local government, the proposals revealed a different
story. The organisation accused Mr Forsyth of refusing to give an inch on key
issues which would give c
ouncils more democratic accountability.
Cosla submitted a list of 52 proposals in November. Later in the month, Mr
Forsyth announced a wide-ranging review of all Scottish Office controls over
local government and trailed many of the proposals announced yesterday.
Crucially, he rejected nine of
Cosla's key proposals.
The convention's president, Ms Rosemary McKenna, pointed out that, from April,
councils would have to use a quarter of capital receipts to repay debts and in
the following years half the total of cash raised.
``In reality, councils will have very little cash left. The Scottish Secretary
is just tinkering. If Cosla's discussions with the Scottish Office on
relaxation of controls of local government are to have any credibility, then
the issue of general competen
ce must be on the table.''
</TEXT>
