<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six new knights in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND gains six new knights in today's New Year's honours list, which also
features awards for show-business and sporting celebrities and a number of
previously unsung heroes.
The retiring chief constable of Strathclyde Police, Mr Leslie Sharp, receives a
knighthood, as do Professor David Carter, chairman of the Scottish Liver
Transplantation Unit, and the principal of Glasgow University, Professor Graeme
Davies.
They are joined by Professor Donald Mackay, chairman of Scottish Enterprise; Dr
Kenneth Calman, the Government's chief medical officer; and leading Scottish
Tory, Mr Adrian Shinwell.
One of the saddest entries on the list is the CBE for Mr Archie Gillespie,
Strathclyde region's director of finance, who collapsed and died at his home on
Christmas Day.
A Scottish Office spokeswoman yesterday confirmed that the medal would be
presented to Mr Gillespie's widow, Alice, although official protocol meant the
ceremony would not involve an investiture at Buckingham Palace.
Scottish golfer Bernard Gallacher, who captained this year's European Ryder Cup
team to victory over the US, receives an OBE.
In total, 1036 people are honoured, with 40% of all awards recommended by
members of the public.
One third of those honoured are women, including Stella Rimington, head of
Britain's security services, who becomes a dame, and agony aunt Claire Rayner,
who gets an OBE.
The list contains stars from the pop scene, TV, and the stage. Actress Julie
Goodyear, the former Coronation Street landlady Bet Gilroy, is made an MBE,
while Elton John becomes a CBE. Cameron Mackintosh, the successful stage
impresario, becomes a knight,
while actress Peggy Mount, 78, gets an OBE.
In the world of politics, an unexpected knighthood goes to Tory back-bencher
Michael Spicer (South Worcestershire), one of the ringleaders of the back-bench
rebellion against the Maastricht legislation.
Last week, the former Minister contributed to the Government's humiliating
defeat over Euro-fisheries by arriving too late to vote.
Labour's deputy shadow Scottish Secretary John McFall last night attacked the
award of a knighthood to Professor Donald MacKay, chairman of Scottish
Enterprise. He said he could only presume that Professor MacKay had been
honoured for political services.
Another row concerned the knighthood given to furniture tycoon Graham Kirkham,
who is reported to have bailed out the Tory Party with a #4m loan.
Labour's deputy leader John Prescott called it ``the crudest example yet of
honours being given for financial services to the Conservative Party''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother's devotion rewarded</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WIDOWED mother who took a night porter's job in a hotel to provide for her
three infant children is rewarded for her devotion with an MBE in the list.
Mrs Jean McGlashan, 54, has done the night shift at the Buchanan Arms Hotel at
Drymen for 20 years following the death of her first husband.
She only took the job because she was allowed to bring her three young children
to the hotel with her while she worked throughout the night.
Mrs McGlashan, now head night porter at the hotel, said: ``I am absolutely
thrilled. The award is for everyone at the hotel, not just myself, because they
have all been so kind to me.''
Her first husband, Alistair, died 20 years ago, leaving her to bring up sons
Stuart and Alan, and daughter Gail, on her own.
Mrs McGlashan, who married second husband Donald 10 years ago, said the job
still was great fun, despite having to work from 10pm to 8am five nights a week.
She said: ``The hotel is really my life. I love it, and you meet a lot of nice
people who become friends, not just guests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leading Scots  knighted</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON, CALUM MACDONALD, CHRIS REEKIE and SARAH URQUHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND gains new knights in today's New Year Honours List.
Sir David Carter has been the driving force behind the campaign that helped set
up Scotland's first-ever special liver transplant unit.
Professor Carter, 55, who is the Queen's surgeon in Scotland, is currently
chairman of the Scottish Liver Transplantation Unit, which is based at
Edinburgh Royal Infirmary.
In a long and distinguished career, Professor Carter has operated on victims of
the genocide in Uganda and been to Nepal to teach and examine patients at
hospitals in the Himalayas.
The first successful liver transplant was carried out at the unit in Edinburgh
Royal Infirmary in 1992 by a team which included Professor Carter. Since then,
110 transplants have taken place
Sir Graeme Davies, the principal of Glasgow University, is honoured for his
services to higher education as a former chief executive of the Higher
Education Funding Council for England and Wales.
He was born and brought up in New Zealand and held academic posts in Auckland
and Cambridge and visiting professorships in Brazil, Israel, Argentina and
China before being appointed professor of metallurgy at Sheffield University in
1978.
Professor Davies became vice-chancellor of Liverpool University in 1986, and
served as chief executive of the Universities Funding Council and the
Polytechnics and Colleges Funding council before taking up his HEFC role in
1992.
Sir Donald Mackay, the chairman of Scottish Enterprise and the economic
consultancy group Pieda, is a graduate of Aberdeen University, and held
academic posts there and at Heriot-Watt University.
He has been economic consultant to the Scottish Secretary since 1971, is a
member of the Scottish Economic Council and a governor of the National
Institute of Economic and Social Research, and a director of Grampian Holdings.
Sir Kenneth Calman, who has been the Government's chief medical officer since
1991, was born in Glasgow and educated at Allan Glen's school and Glasgow
University.
Professor Calman, 54, was a lecturer in surgery at the city's Western Infirmary
from 1968 to 1972, and served for 10 years as professor of oncology at Glasgow
University from 1974.
Sir Adrian Shinwell, who is knighted for political service, is a past president
of the Scottish Conservative and Unionist Association. He is a partner in the
Glasgow law firm Kerr, Barrie and Duncan.
q.The man who has provided the music for some of the most important events in
Scotland has been honoured.
Mr Herrick Bunney, 80, the organist and master of music at St Giles' Cathedral
in Edinburgh, has been appointed a Commander of the Royal Victorian Order.
Mr Bunney said: ``I am thrilled by the honour particularly as it is a personal
order from the Queen who has heard me play on many occasions.''
The founder of the Edinburgh Youth Orchestra and the former organist for
Edinburgh University, he is believed to be only the third organist at St Giles'.
He moved to Edinburgh in 1946 from London after hearing of a job at St Giles'.
He said:``I never regretted moving to Edinburgh. It has been marvellous.''
Mr Bunney still plays the organ three times every Sunday and at other major
events. He has not decided on retiring yet, but says it is something he will
have to think about some day.
q.Mr Nisbet Gallacher, HM Senior Chief Inspector of Schools in Scotland, is
made a Companion of the Order of the Bath. Educated at Kilmarnock Academy,
Glasgow University and Jordanhill College of Education, Mr Gallacher, 59, was a
national specialist in r
emedial education and a district inspector before being appointed to his
current role in 1987.
q.Professor John Howie, CBE, has been professor of general practice at
Edinburgh University since 1980. Professor Howie, who is 58, was a general
practitioner in Glasgow from 1966-70 and lectured in general practice at
Aberdeen University 1970-80. He is t
he son of Sir James Howie, who was director of the Public Health Laboratory
Service from 1963-73.
q.Mr Nelson Robertson, CBE, the group chief executive of Perth-based General
Accident, retires tomorrow, aged 60. Born in Berwick-on-Tweed he was educated
at Berwick Grammar School and gained an MA at Edinburgh University. He joined
the company's Newcastl
e branch in 1958 before moving to the head office. In 1984 he became a director
of the company and was appointed deputy Chief General Manager in 1989 and Chief
General Manager in 1990.
q.Mr Iain Harrison, CBE, the chairman of Harrisons (Clyde), has spent 46 years
in the shipping industry in Scotland. He began in 1949 as a junior clerk with
Lyle Shipping and established his current company in 1955, managing vessels for
other companies.
q.Mr James Wyness, CBE, has been Lord Provost and Lord Lieutenant of Aberdeen
since 1992. The son of a plasterer, he started his working life as a shipyard
electrician but that career was curtailed when he fell from a mast. In 1968 he
went to Aberdeen Uni
versity as a mature student and graduated to become a history teacher. Mr
Wyness retired as a teacher at Hazlehead Academy earlier this year shortly
before his election to the new Aberdeen City Council. He will be convener of
the education committee of th
e new authority.
q.Professor Struther Arnott, CBE, the principal of St Andrews University, has
held the post since 1986 and is now Scotland's longest serving principal.
Professor Arnott has generated much debate about the funding and organisation
of higher education in Sc
otland and floated the controversial idea of a University of Scotland.
q.Mrs Alison Davies, OBE, is Scottish divisional director for the Save the
Children charity. She is also an office bearer for Children in Scotland, an
umbrella organisation for groups caring for needy young people, and serves on
the Scottish Forum on Pris
oners' Families.
q.Professor Dorothy Geddes, OBE, professor of oral biology at Glasgow
University, was the first woman to be appointed to a chair of dentistry in the
UK. Educated at Edinburgh and Newcastle universities, she held various posts in
practising dentistry befor
e taking a lecturing post at Glasgow in 1975.
q.Mrs Patricia Greenhill, OBE, has been a Conservative councillor for Dunblane
East on Stirling District Council since 1984. In the local elections of 1992,
the council split with 10 Conservative and 10 Labour seats. The Conservatives
took control when Mr
s Greenhill won a cut of the cards for the position of provost.
q.The Rev. David Laing, OBE, minister of the Congregational Church in
Easterhouse, has held the post since 1968. Prior to this, he was a professional
speedway rider, and still maintains links with the sport as chaplain of Glasgow
Tigers Speedway Team. In
1986, he became chairman of Strathclyde Region Council's social work committee.
He left the position in July to become secretary of the World Mission of the
Scottish Congregational Church.
q.Mr Archibald Gilchrist, OBE, a director of Caledonian MacBrayne since 1990,
was one of the founding members of the Scottish Legal Aid Board in 1986.
q.Mr Henry Heaney, OBE, is Librarian and Keeper of Hunterian Books and
Manuscripts at the University of Glasgow. He has served for six years as a
member of the British Library Board and has also been as a trustee of the
National Library of Scotland.
q.Mr Hugh MacLean, OBE, chairman of the Crofters' Commission, was educated at
Oban, Tiree and at Glasgow University. He worked for 10 years in the Zambian
ministry of agriculture and, since 1968, for the Highlands and Islands
Development Board, latterly a
s director of project development for the board. A native Gaelic speaker, he
has been closely involved in its promotion and culture.
q.Dr Ernest Robinson, OBE, is chairman of the council of the St Andrew's
Ambulance Association, and has been involved in community health care for more
than 30 years. A retired GP who now lives in Milngavie, he practised at various
posts in Glasgow.
q.Mr John Neil, OBE, has served the Boys' Brigade in Glasgow for 34 years. His
first association with the movement came in 1949, when he was a volunteer
officer with a Coatbridge company. In 1961, he took up a full-time appointment
as a national training
officer, and in 1978 became secretary of the BB's Glasgow battalion, the
largest in the world with 8500 boys in 116 companies.
q.Mr Robert Campbell, MBE, an MoD police Officer at Brechin, has been a charity
fund-raiser through sponsored walks since 1977, raising over #20,000 for a
variety of charities. He has covered long distances in short periods, in one
case 125 miles in 35 ho
urs, and in 1992 undertook the longest beat in Britain by walking from RAF
Wethersfield in Essex to his home in Angus, some 600 miles.
q.Miss Sheila Cant, MBE, organises and runs weekly classes for a group of
mentally handicapped young people and is involved in fund-raising, not just for
her own group but for mentally handicapped people in the wider community. She
is currently employed a
s a nurse manager in the Accident and Emergency/Orthopaedic Directorate of the
West Glasgow University NHS Trust Hospitals, and has been a nurse for more than
30 years.
q.Mrs Agnes Henderson, MBE, has been a volunteer in Airdrie Citizens' Advice
Bureau since the day the bureau opened, 24 years ago, and at age 75 is still
going strong. Over the years she has helped thousands of people in the local
community, and has helpe
d to train hundreds of volunteers
q.Mrs Margaret Webb-Bowen, MBE, began a 34-year commitment to the Women's Royal
Voluntary Service in Edinburgh. when she started to help out at the WRVS shop
at Edinburgh's Princess Margaret Rose Hospital in 1962. Mrs Webb-Bowen, 70, is
one of 125 volunte
ers at the hospital who provide a shop and canteen for patients and relatives.
</TEXT>
