<HEADLINE>Losing the fingertip grip on power</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH Emma Nicholson's decision to leave the Conservative Party, Mr Major's
prospects of hanging on to power until the last possible moment of April or
May, 1997, now look dim.
By March at the latest the two outstanding by-elections should result in his
overall Commons majority disappearing.
He will then be at the not-so-tender mercies of any small group of Conservative
rebels.
It is doubtful if another threat of a confidence vote, followed by a General
Election if he loses, will deter them again as it did when he came to the brink
of losing the Maastricht Treaty Bill.
Most Conservative MPs in marginal seats are convinced they will not be coming
back whenever the election is held and for those with still-safe seats, the
threat may have lost its potency.
There is, in the Tory ranks, a widespread feeling that not only can the
Government not be saved, it may not be worth saving.
Mr Clarke's cautious approach last month exploded the final dreams of some that
a striking Budget might put them back on course for recovery.
The Government has attempted more relaunches than the combined American and
Russian space programmes and none has managed to get the party off the ground
or its opinion-poll ratings off the floor.
Miss Nicholson's departing words are all the more wounding because they come
from someone whose family background is stuffed with political Tories, two of
them Cabinet Ministers.
Very much a ``One Nation'' Tory, her judgment that the Government ``does not
care'' will wound as well as anger Mr Major especially as, though
independent-minded, she was a loyalist who forebore to criticise publicly.
Equally, her judgment that the Government, and she probably means the Prime
Minister especially, has been weak on Europe indicates that Mr Major's attempt
to fence-sit on the issue no longer carries conviction even in his own ranks,
although it is difficu
lt to see what else he can do.
She is not the only pro-European who believes he has been forced to sell-out to
the Euro-sceptics and she may not be the last to abandon his party. Others were
rumoured to be considering defection at the time Mr Alan Howarth crossed the
floor to Labour la
st October.
The divisions on Europe are slowly tearing the Conservative Party apart as
those on Ireland did the Liberals last century. Nor is it a sordid squabble.
The stakes could hardly be higher for the future of Britain.
Both Tory camps are probably unfair to the Prime Minister. Miss Nicholson in
her exasperation has made too little of Mr Major's stubborn refusal to rule out
Britain joining a single currency, which has in turn exasperated the sceptics.
With several economic indicators like inflation, interest rates and even,
relatively, unemployment performing in a way that would have been regarded as a
triumph for earlier prime ministers, Mr Major's unlucky Government is reaping
no reward while being c
onstantly buffeted by policy or personal mishaps which lend conviction to
Opposition claims that this is a dying administration.
Mr Major is famously stubborn and may still try to struggle or, in Mr Blair's
word, ``stumble'' on. He will be increasingly dependent on the nine Ulster
Unionists.
They are highly suspicious of the Northern Ireland peace settlement which they
cannot see having an outcome agreeable to them but they are highly suspicious
of a Labour Government as well.
They are, however, unlikely to demand a price for their support which would
clearly sink the ``peace process'' for, like Sinn Fein and all the Province's
political groups, they do not want to be fingered as the ones who brought the
gun and the bomb back o
n to the streets.
But Mr Major's options look increasingly restricted. There are Tory MPs unhappy
about parts of the Asylum and Immigration Bill, others about the impending
divorce legislation. The Government could find its two main Bills receiving
unwelcome amendment in t
he early part of next year. It could also face losing snap votes on a variety
of issues - one of them Europe.
Three or four months of that might convince even Mr Major that a Government
which is almost impotent in the Commons has no moral right to continue.
</TEXT>
