<HEADLINE>Record day for the Royal Bank</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Bank of Scotland had its busiest day yet on a Friday before
Christmas, with more than #26m being withdrawn. The bank also expects December
to show a record figure for any month, with more than #400m withdrawn from its
network of 1000 cash machin
es.
Barclaycard, which has nine million credit card holders, reported an 11% jump
in business this Christmas.
Shopping rage
BARGAIN-HUNTERS in the frenzied New Year sales were warned yesterday by the
British Retail Consortium to be wary of ``shopping rage'' after the jailing
this week of a south London woman who smashed a bottle of wine over another
shopper's head in a row ove
r queue-jumping.
Street assault
AN Edinburgh man head-butted a Dutch tourist on Thursday in the city's Lothian
Road, breaking his nose. Sentence was deferred yesterday at Edinburgh Sheriff
Court until January 19 for reports on Craig Forrest, 20, of Clovenstone Park,
Edinburgh.
World's end
THE BBC's final World Service programme in French is being withdrawn at
midnight tomorrow, to save money. BBC Infos offered a 24-hour feed of news and
music via satellite from London to 100 French radio stations.
Nelson touch
BURGLARS have escaped with ``priceless'' heirlooms - including the diaries of a
chief gunner in Admiral Nelson's fleet - in a raid on businessman Gordon
Scullard's home in Whickham, Tyne and Wear.
Pools jackpot
THREE women from Larne, Country Antrim, who work in a tissue factory, yesterday
scooped Northern Ireland's biggest pools win - #1,454,804. They cleaned up on
Boxing Day when their Littlewoods bet of just 60p each hit the jackpot.
Death inquiry
A MAN and a woman were being questioned by police yesterday after the death of
their baby boy, who was admitted to hospital at Hartlepool, County Durham, on
Thursday.
Clerical passion
THE Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George Carey, has told the Football
Association's official magazine, FC, that he was so keen on the game that he
carried on playing until the age of 38.
Murder charge
A SCHOOLBOY appeared in court at Oxford yesterday, accused of the knife murder
of publican's son Mark Bye, 23, in the city on Wednesday. The 15-year-old was
remanded into the care of Oxfordshire County Council until January 3.
Granny's anger
MRS Pauline Kay, 61, of Marlow, Buckinghamshire, is angry because her local
vicar, the Rev.Nick Molony, of All Saint's Church, blessed rock star Rod
Stewart's wedding - despite refusing to baptise her grandchildren because their
parents did not live in th
e parish.
</TEXT>
