<HEADLINE>Nationalists target Labour's man as the Tory `tartan tax' campaign hits home Robertson faces SNP onslaught</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE political battle in Scotland will intensify in the New Year with the
decision by the SNP to launch a highly personalised onslaught on Shadow Scots
Secretary George Robertson.
SNP chief executive Michael Russell has written to all the party's senior
office bearers describing Mr Robertson as ``the weak link in Labour's profile
in Scotland'' and seeking lines of attack in their different portfolios to step
up the pressure on him.
The memo also concedes that Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth is ``hitting
home'' with his tartan tax offensive and claims that, because Labour under Mr
Robertson is failing to mount a robust defence, the ``myth of the subsidised
Scot'' is spilling over
and hurting the SNP.
To combat this, SNP leader Alex Salmond will seek opportunities for
head-to-head confrontations with Mr Forsyth on economic issues over the next
three months.
However, the most striking features of the communication is its focus on Mr
Robertson, who is described as ``weak'' and is said to have had to be rescued
over the tartan tax issue by Labour leader Tony Blair during his recent visit
to Scotland.
Mr Robertson said last night that he regarded such an attack as a compliment
and said it was to be expected, given Labour strength at present.
``They have a serious problem at the moment and, whenever the nationalists are
desperate, they turn personal. I am neither surprised nor worried. Labour
support has held up consistently.
``The SNP tried the same tactics before the unitary elections and were
trounced. They seem to be obsessed with me at present but it is a wee bit
pathetic for a party that aspires to take Scotland out of the Union to indulge
in this.''
The memo claims that Mr Robertson's alleged weakness was ``emphasised for the
whole of Scotland by the fact that Blair had to rescue him from Forsyth during
Blair's last visit.''
Mr Russell's memo claims there has been internal Labour discussion of ``Mr
Robertson's weak performance, lack of cutting edge, and recourse to bluster
under pressure - which, according to our private information, is shared across
the parties and even with
in `New' Labour in Scotland and at Westminster, where Helen Liddell is being
talked up as a successor''.
He calls on members of the party's Scottish cabinet to come up with issues on
which implications of the Scottish Constitutional Convention's scheme have not
been seriously or correctly considered, adding: ``During the first part of
1996, we intend to put
Robertson under increased pressure.''
The SNP chief executive concedes on the Government's tartan tax offensive:
``There is no doubt that Forsyth is hitting home on Labour with this.
``Some of the attacks, however, are probably spilling over on to us, partly
because Robertson is failing to deflect anything back on the Tories and
allowing the general myth of the `subsidised Scot' to prevail, against all the
real evidence.''
The SNP, he argues, must take the economic case directly to the Tories because
the convention's plans - described as ``the assembly proposals'' - are said to
be hedged about by fears of a backlash from the south of England.
The memo seeks ideas and details for use as ammunition for Mr Salmond in
seeking direct debates with Mr Forsyth on economic issues ``in whatever forums
are available''.
``Forsyth's case is weak,'' claims Mr Russell, ``and is only getting currency
because Labour's plans are weaker still.''
Mr Russell, speaking from his home in Cowal, Strathclyde, said last night:
``One of the things I am trying to do is help the party consider strategy as we
enter the New Year, but I am not going to comment further on what is an
internal party document.''
</TEXT>
