<HEADLINE>Tory in vote defeat honoured</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TORY MP who helped precipitate a humiliating Government defeat in the Commons
this month by turning up too late to vote receives a knighthood in the New
Year's Honours List.......for political service.
Michael Spicer (above) who - according to Tory sources - arrived at the Commons
at 10pm rather than 7pm to find Labour had already won a debate on Euro fishing
policy by two votes, was one of three Tory back benchers to be knighted.
The 52-year-old Euro-sceptic former Minister was one of the ringleaders of the
Maastricht revolt and voted consistently against the Government until the Bill
was passed.
However, since then, as leader of the Fresh Start group of sceptics, he has
sought to influence Tory European policy from the inside. It was he who
conducted peace moves with whipless Conservative MPs in a bid to bring them
back into the party fold.
All have since returned, except Sir Richard Body, MP for Holland-with-Boston.
The Government was severely embarrassed when it emerged it could have won the
fishing vote this month, but for two of its MPs, Mr Spicer and Sir Michael
Marshall, who turned up too late.
Sources claimed Mr Spicer and Sir Michael had mistaken the timing of the vote,
despite a three-line whip, but friends of Mr Spicer insisted that he had ``made
an arrangement'' with the Whips' Office. Although he is a Euro-sceptic, they
said he had not del
iberately abstained and would have voted with the Government.
</TEXT>
