<HEADLINE>Tribunal strikes off one solicitor and fines another #2000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE lawyer has been struck off and another fined #2000 after being found guilty
of professional misconduct by the Scottish Solicitors Discipline Tribunal.
The tribunal ruled that Mr Alexander Hastings of Inverroy, Roy Bridge,
Inverness-shire, was no longer a fit and proper person to remain on the roll of
practising solicitors.
In a separate case, the tribunal imposed a #2000 fine on Bernard Hill, of
Pollokshaws Road, Glasgow, for breaches of the solicitors' accounts rules.
Mr Hill has lodged an appeal at the Court of Session both against the finding
of professional misconduct made against him and the fine.
Mr Hastings, 49, has been a solicitor since 1973 and practised in Fort William,
at first on his own and latterly as a consultant with another firm.
In March 1993, he was instructed by a building society in connection with a
loan of #102,500 which was to be secured over Fiddich Lodge at Fiddich View,
Craigellachie, Banffshire.
Standard securities, giving security over the property, had already been
recorded in favour of the Royal Bank of Scotland and Barclay's Bank.
The tribunal stated that, before cashing the loan cheque and dealing with the
funds, Mr Hastings had a professional duty to ensure that he was in a position
to record a standard security in favour of the building society. It was also
necessary to discharg
e the prior securities.
However, Mr Hastings cashed the loan cheque on March 9, 1993, but failed to
record the necessary deeds.
The tribunal found him guilty of professional misconduct for cashing the
building society cheque when he was not in a position to record a clear title
in favour of the borrower or an effective standard security in favour of the
lender.
The tribunal stated that the gravity of Mr Hastings's failure to record the
necessary deeds was clearly demonstrated by subsequent events.
He left the building society without security and the borrower defaulted on the
loan repayments from an early date. It soon became apparent that Mr Hastings
had also failed to obtain a discharge for the borrower's previous loan over the
same property and
that the borrower was insolvent.
The tribunal also found that Mr Hastings had provided inadequate professional
services in winding up a woman's estate and reduced his fee for the work by
#700.
Mr Hill, 56, a former fiscal who has been a solicitor since 1967, set up on his
own account in 1987 as Hills in Pollokshaws Road, Glasgow.
The tribunal ruled that he had breached the accounts rules by having three
separate shortages on his client account, amounting in total to #590.
The rules state that solicitors must ensure at all times that cash in their
client account shall not be less than the total of clients' money held by the
solicitor.
The purpose of the rule is to ensure that the lawyer has enough funds in the
account to meet the total of all sums due by him to individual clients.
</TEXT>
