<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951230-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951230-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951230</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wallace welcomes party's newest member</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974635254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace last night welcomed Miss
Nicholson's defection from the Tory ranks and put her move firmly in the
context of a controversy over Europe involving Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth.
The Scottish Secretary, it emerged last night, has abandoned the practice of
predecessors Ian Lang and Malcolm Rifkind by refusing to accept an invitation
to become a patron of the European Movement - in what has been seen as part of
the Tory leadership's
change of tack to the Right.
Welcoming Ms Nicholson to the Liberal Democrat fold, Mr Wallace said: ``We
welcome our newest member to the Parliamentary party and this underlines how
far John Major and his Government have moved from the centre ground and their
principles on European po
licy.
``The Conservative Party is running away from Britain's destiny in Europe. We
have always known that fault-lines were there in the Conservative Party. Now
they have become all too apparent.''
Mr Wallace said an example of this was Mr Forsyth's rejection of the invitation
to become a patron of the all-party European Movement. ``I think it is very
regrettable and it calls into question his commitment to Scotland's future as
part of the European
Union,'' he said.
Others invited, including all the heads of all the Scottish parties, had
accepted ``more or less by return post'', but Mr Forsyth put up a series of
questions and held off, before telling them in November that he was declining.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson last night called the rejection a
``calculated political snub'', caused by Mr Forsyth's extreme anti-European
views and another move to distance himself from Labour's more mainstream
approach in Scotland.
SNP chief executive Michael Russell said: ``A Secretary of State who is a
Euro-sceptic runs against the interests of Scotland in Europe and against the
feelings of the Scottish people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
